<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>Why HVDC? - Lower Investment Cost</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Lower investment cost
</H2>
<H3>
  Overhead line transmissions
</H3>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="2">
  <TR VALIGN="Top">
    <TD>
      <IMG SRC="sk6167.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
    </TD>
    <TD>
      <H4>
	A DC transmission line costs less than an AC line for the same transmission
	capacity. However, the terminal stations are more expensive in the HVDC case
	due to the fact that they must perform the conversion from AC to DC and vice
	versa. But above a certain distance, the so called "break-even distance",
	the HVDC alternative will always give the lowest cost. The break-even-distance
	depends on several factors and an analysis must be made for each individual
	case. The importance of the break-even-distance concept should not be
	overstressed, since several other factors are important in the selection
	between AC or DC.
      </H4>
      <P>
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
<CENTER>
</CENTER>
<H3>
  Cable transmissions
</H3>
<H4>
  The above relationships apply also for submarine or underground cables. This
  is because AC needs three cables and DC only one. (The sea water or the ground
  is an excellent conductor for DC and can be used as the return conductor.)
  But cables are much more expensive than overhead lines, and therefore HVDC
  becomes economically attractive already for distances above about 50 km.
</H4>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="abbhand.gif" ALIGN=TOP> | <A HREF="home.htm">ABB Power Systems
  Home Page</A> | <A HREF="http://www.abb.se">ABB Sweden</A> |
