<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>ABB HVDC projects - Highgate</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Highgate back-to-back station, Vermont
</H2>
<P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="2">
  <TR>
    <TD ROWSPAN=2>
      <IMG SRC="l35400t.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
    </TD>
    <TD>
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD VALIGN="Bottom">
      <A HREF="l1322.htm"><IMG BORDER="0" SRC="l32767i.jpg" ALT="Photos" WIDTH="80"
	  HEIGHT="52"></A>
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
<H4>
  In April 1984 ABB received a contract for the supply of a 200 MW back-to-back
  HVDC converter station to Vermont Electric Power Company (VELCO). An extremely
  short delivery time of 17 months was required, and the station was taken
  into service in September 1985. The reason for the short delivery time was
  that in the late autumn of 1983 an agreement was reached between the State
  of Vermont (USA) and the Canadian utility Hydro Quebec about the import of
  electric power to Vermont. Under the terms of this agreement Hydro Quebec
  was to export 150 MW as soon as the necessary facilities had been built and
  then increase this by a further 50 MW in 1987.
</H4>
<H4>
  It became particularly urgent to start the import of electricity from Canada
  as soon as possible, since it was planned to shut down the Vermont Yankee
  Nuclear Power Station for maintenance from mid-September 1985 for a period
  of at least 8 months. During this period it was felt that imported power
  from Hydro Quebec would be profitable compared to other sources for the
  replacement power. This lead to the shortest delivery time for any HVDC project
  in the world.
</H4>
<H4>
  Technical Data:
</H4>
<P>
<TABLE border>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      Commissioning year:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      1985
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      Power rating:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      200 MW
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      DC voltage:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      57 kV
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      Back to back station
    </TD>
    <TD>
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      Main reasons for choosing HVDC system:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      Asynchronous link
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
