<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>ABB HVDC projects - Kontek</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Kontek
</H2>
<P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="2">
  <TR>
    <TD ROWSPAN=2>
      <IMG SRC="kontek.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
    </TD>
    <TD>
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD VALIGN="Bottom">
      <A HREF="l1402.htm"><IMG BORDER="0" SRC="kontek2i.jpg" ALT="Photos" ></A>
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
<H4>
  In December 1995 the Kontek Interconnection was handed over for commercial
  operation to the owners SEAS of Denmark and VEAG of Germany. Even before
  that, the link proved to be a vital part to secure the power supply to Zealand,
  Denmark, when, in late October 1995, an anchor of a ship broke the 400 kV
  AC cable between Sweden and Denmark.
</H4>
<H4>
  The capacity is 600 MW at 400 kV DC. The strongest motivation for the project
  was the possibility to optimally operate the highly efficient thermal power
  generating units of Zealand, combined with the beneficial environmental aspects
  of low Nox and Sox of these units. In addition both interconnected areas
  will gain from higher security of operation as well as increased possibilities
  for power exchange and trading. The converter stations were delivered by
  ABB and the land and sea cable by the Danish company NKT.
</H4>
<H4>
  Technical Data:
</H4>
<P>
<TABLE border>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      Commissioning year:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      1995
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      Power Rating:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      600 MW
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      DC Voltage:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      400 kV
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      Length of underground DC cable:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      120 km
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD>
      Length of submarine cable:
    </TD>
    <TD>
      50 km
    </TD>
  </TR>
  <TR>
    <TD VALIGN="Top">
      Main reason for choosing HVDC system:
    </TD>
    <TD VALIGN="Top">
      Asynchronous connection, long sea crossing &nbsp;
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
