<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>Outdoor Valves</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<A NAME="DDE_LINK2"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif"
    alt=""> <IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A>
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Outdoor valves
</H2>
<H4>
  ABB has built an air-insulated outdoor prototype valve, which has been in
  service since June 1992 in the Swedish station of the Konti-Skan 1 transmission
  link. The operation has been very succesful, and has proven the adequacy
  of the concept for further installations.
</H4>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="l36596.jpg">
</CENTER>
<P ALIGN=Center>
<I>Prototype outdoor valve</I>
<H4>
  Outdoor thyristor valves give full flexibility in station layout, reduce
  delivery times, reduce equipment size and make it easier to upgrade an existing
  station.
</H4>
<H4>
  The outdoor valve unit contains a single valve function. Consequently, 12
  units are needed for a 12-pulse converter. Inside the outdoor valve unit,
  the electrical configuration is of traditional design with thyristor modules
  and reactor modules as for present indoor valves built by ABB. Therefore,
  valve maintenance is as easy to perform as for the ABB indoor valves.
</H4>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="sk6560.jpg">
</CENTER>
<P ALIGN=Center>
<I>12-pulse converter with outdoor valves</I> 
  <HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="abbhand.gif" ALIGN=TOP> | <A HREF="home.htm">ABB Power Systems
  Home Page</A> | <A HREF="http://www.abb.se">ABB Sweden</A> |
</CENTER>
