<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>Active DC Filter</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<A NAME="DDE_LINK2"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif"
    alt=""> <IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A>
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Active DC filter
</H2>
<H4>
  Demands regarding permitted interference levels from DC lines have become
  increasingly stringent in recent years. ABB has therefore developed an active
  DC filter that enables efficient filtering using a small-size filter.
</H4>
<H3>
  Operating principles
</H3>
<H4>
  The principle of the active DC filter is to inject a current generated by
  a power amplifier into the DC circuit cancelling the DC side harmonics coming
  from the converter. The amplifier is controlled by a high speed digital signal
  processor controller.
</H4>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="sk6558.gif">
</CENTER>
<P ALIGN=Center>
<I>Circuit diagram of active DC filter</I>
<H3>
  Experience
</H3>
<H4>
  A prototype active DC filter was installed in December 1991 in the Konti-Skan
  2 transmission.
</H4>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="sk6559.gif">
</CENTER>
<P ALIGN=Center>
<I>Harmonic current content on the DC line</I>
<H4>
  The ABB active DC filter has already become a standard solution in HVDC
  transmissions with stringent DC filtering requirements. It is in commercial
  operation in recently commissioned HVDC transmissions and will be included
  in ongoing deliveries as well.
</H4>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="l36917.jpg">
</CENTER>
<P ALIGN=Center>
<I>Active DC filter at the Swedish terminal of the Baltic Cable Link</I>
  <HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="abbhand.gif" ALIGN=TOP> | <A HREF="home.htm">ABB Power Systems
  Home Page</A> | <A HREF="http://www.abb.se">ABB Sweden</A> |
