  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>Deep hole ground electrode</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<A NAME="DDE_LINK2"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif"
    alt=""> <IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A>
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Deep hole ground electrode
</H2>
<H4>
</H4>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="2">
  <TR VALIGN="Top">
    <TD>
      <IMG SRC="l36922.jpg">
      <CENTER>
	<I>Deep hole electrode testing</I>
      </CENTER>
    </TD>
    <TD>
      <H4>
	Traditional land electrodes, generally require a large are and must be located
	where the earth resistivity is low. The geological conditions for effective
	grounding at greater depths are often favourable due to a lower earth resistivity
	resulting from a higher salt content. In cooperation with other interested
	parties, ABB is therefore in the process of long-term testing a deep hole
	ground electrode at the Swedish station of the <A HREF="l131.htm">Baltic
	Cable </A>HVDC transmission link.
      </H4>
      <P>
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="sk4957.gif"> 
  <P>
  <I>Principle design of deep hole ground electrode</I> <BR>
</CENTER>
