</DOCHDR>
<!doctype html public "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>CCC - Dynamic Stability Improved</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<A NAME="DDE_LINK2"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif"
    alt=""> <IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A>
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Dynamic stability improved
</H2>
<H4>
  The dynamic stability of a CCC HVDC transmission is greatly improved due
  to the contribution to the commutation voltage from the capacitors resulting
  in a positive inverter operating characteristic. A conventional inverter
  has a negative operating characteristic, which is destabilizing, and if the
  AC network has a low short-circuit capacity, this could cause problems.
</H4>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="sk6552.gif">
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <I>U<FONT SIZE="-2">d</FONT> /I<FONT SIZE="-2">d</FONT> chracteristics</I>
</CENTER>
<H4>
  The improved stability is demonstrated by the curves for maximum available
  power, (MAP). The important consequence is that the CCC is far less sensitive
  to such circumstances and can be connected to networks having a much lower
  short-circuit capacity than a conventional converter.
</H4>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="sk6553.gif">
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <I>MAP curves for CCC and conventional HVDC</I>
</CENTER>
<H3>
  <A NAME="Bottom">Reduced load rejection overvoltage</A>
</H3>
<H4>
  The MAP curves also demonstrate that the load rejection overvoltage (AC voltage
  at Id=0) is much lower with a CCC. This is because of lower reactive power
  generation in the small shunt filters.
</H4>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="abbhand.gif" ALIGN=TOP> | <A HREF="home.htm">ABB Power Systems
  Home Page</A> | <A HREF="http://www.abb.se">ABB Sweden</A> |
</CENTER>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
<A HREF="copyrajt.htm">Copyright </A>ABB Power Systems Sweden 1996
</BODY></HTML>
