<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>CCC - Commutation Capacitor</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<A NAME="DDE_LINK2"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif"
    alt=""> <IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A>
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  The commutation capacitor
</H2>
<P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="2">
  <TR>
    <TD>
      <IMG SRC="sk6554.gif">
      <P>
      <I>Commutation capacitor</I>
    </TD>
    <TD>
      A key component in a CCC is the commutation capacitor. The steady state operating
      voltage of the capacitor is defined by the direct current. The capacitor
      is protected against overvoltage by parallel ZnO varistors. Since both the
      voltage stresses on the capacitor and the energy requirements for the varistor
      are relatively low compared to the installed capacity, the commutation capacitors
      can be made very compact.
      <P>
      <P ALIGN=Center>
      <IMG SRC="sk6555.gif">
      <P ALIGN=Center>
      <I>Commutation capacitor voltage</I>
      <P>
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="abbhand.gif" ALIGN=TOP> | <A HREF="home.htm">ABB Power Systems
  Home Page</A> | <A HREF="http://www.abb.se">ABB Sweden</A> |
</CENTER>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
<A HREF="copyrajt.htm">Copyright </A>ABB Power Systems Sweden 1996
