<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>ABB Power Systems-Application of CSC</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">

<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">.
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" "> 
<P>
<B>Applications of Controllable Series Compensation</B> 
<P>
Series compensation is a well-established technology for increasing
the power carrying capability of transmission lines. Series capacitors
act by inserting a voltage in series with the transmission line
whose polarity is opposite to the voltage drop across the line.
The net effect is the decrease of the apparent reactance of the
transmission line. The different control methods for series capacitors
can be an appropriate solution for following system challenges.
<HR>

<P>
<B>High series compensation level</B> 
<P>
Series Capacitors increase the power carrying capability of transmission
lines and thus allow a higher utilization level of transmission-limited
power plants. The level of allowable compensation in transmission
networks has traditionally been limited due to the potential interactions
between the series capacitors and the shafts of nearby turbine-generator
units. This phenomena is known as subsynchronous resonance (SSR).
Some forms of controlled series capacitors permit a high level
of compensation without the fear of SSR.<HR>

<P>
<B>Power oscillation damping</B> 
<P>
Many large power system experience undamped power oscillations
in the frequency range of 0.2-2.0 Hz across critical tie-lines
when a high level of power, relative to the transmission capacity,
is transmitted over a long distance. Controlled series capacitors
can provide an active damping for these oscillations and therefor
permit the transfer of larger levels of power for longer distances.
Furthermore, controlled series capacitors can provide critical
support to the power system following major disturbances and enable
the system to remain in synchronous operation.<HR>

<P>
<B>Interconnections</B> 
<P>
Two power systems are usually interconnected in order to either
transfer economical power from one system to the other, or to
share the spinning reserve resources of both systems and thus
enhance the overall reliability of both systems. Controlled series
capacitors are an effective means of interconnecting two power
systems in order to utilize the economic interchange of power
even when the interconnection points are electrically weak.<HR>

<P>
<B>Power flow control</B> 
<P>
Controlled series capacitors allow the operator to control the
level of power flow on a transmission line. This is especially
beneficial following a line-outage contingency where the uneven
distribution of power between various transmission circuits might
lead to overloading and force the operator to reduce the capacity
usage of many lines.<HR>

<P>
<B>Loadability control</B>
<P>
Controlled series capacitors are an effective means of increasing
the power carrying capability of transmission lines. The level
of compensation can be controlled in order to minimize system
losses during normal operation, while increasing the power transfer
on lower voltage circuits during contingencies on the higher voltage
transmission system.<HR>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="abbhand.gif" ALIGN=TOP> | <A HREF="home.htm">ABB Power Systems Home Page</A>
| <A HREF="http://www.abb.se">ABB Sweden</A> | </CENTER><HR>

<P>
<A HREF="copyrajt.htm">Copyright </A>ABB Power Systems Sweden 1995. <BR>
<B>Latest updated 18-Mars-1996</B> 
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT12-B38-83</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA063-000363-B035-183</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.abb.se:80/pow/r32.htm 138.221.250.99 19970112024006 text/html 5943
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Sunday, 12-Jan-97 09:47:34 GMT
