<DOCHDR>
http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us:80/plan.html 198.174.235.51 19970121013409 text/html 13830
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Tue, 21 Jan 1997 01:35:57 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 13658
Last-modified: Thu, 16 Jan 1997 01:59:05 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Put Yourself Into the Plan - Fight Crime in Minneapolis</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#0b002f" BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H1>Put Yourself Into the Plan<BR>
Fight Crime in Minneapolis</H1>
<H3><BR>
Enforcement</H3>
The City of Minneapolis will fairly and vigorously enforce the law. <BR>
 
<H3>Intervention</H3>
When society intervenes,<BR>
 lives of crime are prevented.
<H3><BR>
Prevention</H3>
A crime prevented is a crime <BR>
that never happens. <BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
Minneapolis is a great city. We refuse to let crime -- or the fear of crime
-- diminish it in any way. We will not allow criminal activity -- serious
or petty -- to destroy the beautiful city that is our home.<BR>
<BR>
Minneapolis has a plan to fight crime. Every citizen can be a part of this
plan. It is based on four proven and effective strategies.<BR>
<H2>Zero-Tolerance Enforcement</H2>
 The Minneapolis Police Department enforces zero-tolerance for serious crime.
Our new Gang Strike Task Force has taken the offensive. Thugs, bullies and
gang members who commit crimes of violence and other major crimes will be
arrested.<BR>
 The Minneapolis Police Department is also preparing to enforce zero-tolerance
for &quot;gateway&quot; misdemeanors such as street-level drug-dealing,
prostitution, playing loud music, public consumption of alcohol and littering.
We will not allow irresponsible people to destroy our neighborhoods.<BR>
<H2>Saturation Enforcement</H2>
 The Minneapolis Police Department concentrates zero-tolerance enforcement
on high-crime neighborhoods and addresses.  Anyone who thinks any place
in Minneapolis is &quot;safe for crime&quot; will find out differently.<BR>
 The Minneapolis Police Department - working with the Public Schools and
the Park and Recreation Board - will ensure that our schools and parks are
safe. The Safe Schools/Safe Parks initiative will create safe walking routes,
and use &quot;McGruff&quot; vehicles, school safety assessments and other
tools to protect children and families. The citizens of Minneapolis will
do whatever is necessary to protect our children.<BR>
<H2>Zero-Tolerance Prosecution</H2>
 The City of Minneapolis aggressively prosecutes criminals, including those
who commit the &quot;gateway&quot; misdemeanors that can destroy the livability
of our city. The City will work with the Hennepin County District Court
to create a calendar to target chronic misdemeanants. We will stop the &quot;revolving
door&quot; that frustrates the good work of our Minneapolis police officers.<BR>
<H2>Smart Prevention and Intervention</H2>
 Minneapolis citizens take responsibility for our own safety. We develop
good safety habits. We look out for each other's well being. United, we
can prevent crime.<BR>
 An important part of crime prevention is providing education, recreation
and employment opportunities for youth. We must also remember to teach our
children, by word and by example, our family and community values. We will
never turn our backs on our children. They are our future.<BR>
<BR>
Take a few minutes to read this brochure. It will update you on how the
Minneapolis Police Department enforces the law. It also suggests how you
can put yourself into the plan to fight crime and build community in Minneapolis.<BR>
<BR>
The citizens of Minneapolis lead law-abiding and productive lives. We will
not permit criminals to define the kind of community we live in, or the
kind of community we will pass on to our children.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H1>Fighting Crime </H1>
<H3><I>Straight Talk from Police Chief Robert K. Olson</I></H3>
<H2>The Minneapolis Police Department</H2>
Minneapolis citizens can be proud of their professional law enforcement
organization. It continues to be on the cutting edge of policing in America.
We are currently authorized to hire the highest number of officers in Department
history - 914 sworn positions. In addition, we have put almost $2.5 million
worth of vehicles and equipment into service in 1996. <BR>
<H2>Community Policing</H2>
In the last year we &quot;civilianized&quot; many office positions in order
to put more officers into community policing. We decentralized the Department,
giving precinct commanders additional resources, and empowering them to
be responsible for crime fighting in their precincts. We now have 66 more
officer positions in the precincts than we did a year ago. They do much
more than answer 911 calls. They are part of the new Community Response
Teams that solve problems identified jointly by precinct commanders and
citizen precinct advisory committees.  <BR>
<BR>
We have decentralized School Liaison, DARE, and some property crimes functions.
This frees up officers to work in the precincts, on the streets. It also
means the commanders - rather than distant headquarters personnel - are
responsible for solving problems in their own precincts. Last year we created
a Downtown Command which includes our Mounted Patrol, K-9, Traffic and other
units. That freed up resources in the Fourth Precinct, which had previously
been responsible for downtown, and ensured that downtown will remain one
of the safest places in the city.<BR>
<BR>
Minneapolis has been on the cutting edge of community policing in establishing
CCP/SAFE units across the city. In 1996 we expanded this very successful
program by 50 percent.<BR>
<H2>The Minneapolis Gang Strike Force</H2>
We have assigned 12 experienced officers to the Minneapolis Gang Strike
Force. We know the &quot;blueprint&quot; of how gangs operate. We know who
the members are, who the leaders are, where they live and their daily routines.
We know their motivations and the types of crimes they commit. This  intelligence
resulted in the arrest in August and September of 14 gang members. Three
are murder suspects and charges against the others include attempted murder,
soliciting a minor for prostitution, and drug and gun felonies. We are now
working our way through a list of the 50 most dangerous gangsters. Minneapolis
will be rid of them. <BR>
<H2>Safe Schools/Safe Parks</H2>
The Department is working with the Minneapolis Public Schools and Park and
Recreation Board to improve safety in and around schools and make them a
better environment for learning. A number of measures are proposed as part
of this Safe Schools/Safe Parks initiative, including I.D. cards, security
training for school personnel, and security evaluations for all public schools.
We are working with the Park Board and Park Police to increase park safety
and enhance summer activities for youth, and have launched a Police Athletic
League.<BR>
<H2>Homicides </H2>
Minneapolis has experienced a tragic increase in homicides. Most are committed
by persons known to the victim. Often one or both parties are engaged in
criminal activity. Sadly, over 40 percent involve youth, either as victims
or perpetrators. We are combating this problem with police intelligence,
saturation enforcement and a focus on top criminals and gang activity.<BR>
<BR>
Overall, other crime in the city has not been increasing. The MPD will continue
to focus on violent crime, and the crimes that most disrupt the quality
of life in our neighborhoods.<BR>
<BR>
As proud as I am of our Department, I want every citizen to understand that
good police work is only part of the answer to crime. No matter how many
officers are on the street or how many arrests are made, our work needs
to be backed up by a cooperative criminal justice system, and by county,
state and federal governments. <BR>
<H2>Be Part of the Solution</H2>
Most importantly, we need to work with cooperative and active citizens.
We need you to be our partner. We must all rededicate ourselves to strengthening
our community and fighting crime, each of us in our own way. Together, we
can make sure that Minneapolis continues to be one of the great cities of
America.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H1>Defusing <BR>
Drugs, Guns and Gangs</H1>
<I>by Sergeant Mike Martin</I><BR>
<BR>
When you watch the news or read the newspaper, it's hard to avoid stories
about gangs, gun violence and drug-related crime across the country.  Unfortunately,
we in Minneapolis are not immune to the negative impact of street gangs
and narcotics, but we are taking new steps to curb gang activity and violence
in our neighborhoods. We understand that preventing violence requires not
only suppression, but prevention and intervention.  <BR>
<BR>
The Minneapolis Gang Strike Force is responsible for tracking gang intelligence
and making arrests for gang-related crimes.  Our goal is to insure that
there are serious legal consequences for anyone wanting to traffic in guns
or narcotics in our city. <BR>
<BR>
We also work closely with the precinct Community Response Teams to target
street-level drug dealers and remove illegal guns from our neighborhoods.
 In addition, we train school personnel and youth-serving agencies on how
to identify and deal with gang activity.  <BR>
<BR>
We also train community organizations, church groups and other organizations
that provide early intervention with kids who are at risk of becoming involved
in gangs.  We recognize that issues like poverty, lack of parental supervision
and inadequate recreation can put a child at risk.  This is why we need
the help of community members to  provide positive role models for our youth.
 <BR>
<BR>
Some of the best programs I have seen for gang intervention have been community-based
groups that stress cultural issues and provide positive mentors for our
youth.  Programs like The Lao Assistance Center and the American Indian
Center's Golden Eagles Program are excellent examples of the power of early
intervention to prevent youth violence.<BR>
<BR>
As a gang investigator and a resident of Minneapolis, I am excited about
the opportunities we have to provide a positive future for our kids, but
we can't do it alone.  We need your help to identify issues, suggest solutions
and work with our kids.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H1>Confronting<BR>
Domestic Violence</H1>
<BR>
<I>by Fourth Precinct Commander Chris Morris</I><BR>
<BR>
Before commanding North Minneapolis' 4th Precinct, I served in the Domestic
Violence unit. Verilea Howard and I are members of a team that has developed
a more effective way to confront domestic violence. It's made up of the
Minneapolis Police Department, the City Attorney's Office, the Domestic
Abuse Project and other community agencies. We've called it The Minneapolis
Model.<BR>
<BR>
In the past, victims/survivors of domestic violence often shut themselves
off from family, friends, police and social service agencies. Families and
neighbors usually looked the other way. Perhaps the most distressing fact
was that, even when cases were prosecuted, 60 percent were dismissed.<BR>
<BR>
Things have changed. Victims are more willing to report violence and society
recognizes that domestic violence is a crime that radiates outward to include
children and neighbors among its victims. When domestic abuse is reported,
police officers have always intervened immediately - often in highly dangerous
situations. What is new is that police investigators and the City Attorney's
Office are more aggressively following up to gain evidence for prosecution.
It goes without saying that our concern for victims/survivors continues.
The Domestic Abuse Project helps them find safe places to live and connects
them with the support networks that are so vital to recovery.<BR>
<BR>
By taking an aggressive, zero-tolerance stand on domestic violence, we've
been able to reverse the apathy of the past. Police and prosecutors - rather
than victims - are taking responsibility for making sure that abuse stops
and offenders are brought to justice. Our conviction rate is now 60 percent;
offenders are paying for their crimes through  jail time, probation and
intensive counseling.<BR>
<BR>
Victims of domestic violence can call the Metro Area Shelter Crisis Line,
<BR>
646-0994. It is answered 24 hours a day. They can be certain that we will
help.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H1>Put Yourself Into the Plan</H1>
<H3>We know what causes crime and violence.<BR>
We also know how to prevent it.</H3>
<H2>Know the Issues</H2>
Crime is the result of personal, family and community failures. The best
way to prevent crime is to build a strong community. Good parenting and
quality education, employment training and jobs, community policing and
neighborhood conflict resolution -- all prevent crime. These have nothing
to do with government. How we conduct our lives on the job and in our homes
and neighborhoods is the most important factor in determining our safety.<BR>
<H2>Get Involved</H2>
What's most important is for each of us to put ourselves into the plan to
fight crime. We don't need to do something big or momentous to be effective.
Small things can make a big difference - learning the name of the child
next door, welcoming the new people on the block, or helping a young adult
improve his or her job skills. Decide what you can do. That's crime prevention.
It's everybody's job.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H2>Minneapolis will stop crime and build community.<BR>
You can put yourself into the plan.</H2>
<PRE>Youth Coordinating Board	                                 673-2060
Mentoring, literacy and other youth programs and activities. 

Minneapolis Human Resources	                                 673-2282
Law enforcement career opportunities with Minneapolis.

First Call for Help	                                        335-5000
Information on family and other social services.

CCP/SAFE	                                                  673-3015
Block clubs and personal safety and home security workshops.</PRE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
