<html><head><TITLE>Recycling Collection</TITLE></head><body>City of Minneapolis, Division of Solid Waste & Recycling<p><H2>RECYCLING COLLECTION</H2><HR width=100%><p><b>COLLECTION BEGINS AT...</b><p>Recyclables are collected every other week on your garbage day. Please have your recyclables at the curb or alley-line by 7:00 am.<p>For calendar of recycling collection dates, call Solid Waste & Recycling at 673-2917.<HR width=100%><p><b>ITEMS COLLECTED</b><p>Click on any of the items below for what we collect and how to prepare it.<ul><a HREF=#Boxboard>Boxboard</a><br><a HREF=#Cans>Cans</a><br><a HREF=#Corrugated>Corrugated Cardboard</a><br><a HREF=#Glass>Glass</a><br><a HREF=#Battery>Household Batteries</a><br><a HREF=#Mags>Magazines</a><br><a HREF=#News>Newspapers</a><br><a HREF=#Office>Office Paper & Mail</a><br><a HREF=#Phone Books>Phone Books</a><br><a HREF="#Plastic">Plastic Bottles</a></ul><p>Please remember, mixed recyclables are not collected. Do not mix cans with glass, newspaper with magazines...etc.<p><HR width=100%><p><b>RECYCLING CONTAINER OPTIONS</b><ul>Small waste baskets, pails and corrugated boxes less than 10 gallons in size may be used instead of paper bags to hold cans, glass, or plastic. Do not use 12 or 24 pack pop boxes.<p>Large containers less 30 gallons in size can be used, but recyclables must be in separate paper bags in the container.<p>Call Solid Waste & Recycling at 673-2917 for official recycling stickers for labelling your small waste baskets, pails, and large containers.</ul><HR width=100%><p><b>RECYCLING CREDIT</b> $$$<p>The City of Minneapolis offers a recycling credit of $7 per dwelling unit per month for registered buildings whose residents participate in the Minneapolis Recycling Program. If you have questions or would like to register your building for recycling credit, call Minneapolis Solid Waste & Recycling at 673-2917.<p><HR width=100%><p><b><a name=Boxboard>Boxboard</a></b><p><ul><li>Cereal boxes are the best example of boxboard. Include any dry food box such as:<ul>Cake mix boxes<br>Cookie boxes<br>Cracker boxes<br>Hamburger Helper boxes<br>Jell-O mix boxes<br>Macaroni & cheese boxes<br>Pasta boxes<br>Potato chip boxes<br>Pretzel boxes<br>Pudding mix boxes<br>Rice boxes<br>Tea boxes</ul></ul><ul><li>Please do not include:<ul>Refrigerated or frozen food boxes -- have a plastic coating<br>Doughnut and movie popcorn boxes -- are food contaminated<br>6, 12, & 24-pack beverage boxes -- have a wet strength additive</ul><li>Remove and throw away any plastic bags, such as those used to hold potato chips and cereal.<li>Flatten boxboard boxes and place in the same paper bag as your office paper and mail.</ul><p><b><a name=Cans>Cans</a></b>  <br>Food and beverage cans, and aluminum foil. <ul><p><li>Rinse clean. Must be in paper bags.</ul><p><b><a name=Corrugated>Corrugated Cardboard</a></b><ul><li>No pizza boxes.<li>Flatten and bundle with string or twine. Each bundle must be smaller than 3'x 3' and weigh less than 20 lbs. Small flat pieces of corrugated cardboard may be placed in paper bags.</ul><p><b><a name=Glass>Glass</a></b><br>Clear, green, blue or brown food and beverage bottles and jars only. <ul><li>No broken glass, dishes, mirrors or windows.<li>Rinse clean. Throw away caps, lids, and rings.<li>Must be in paper bags.</ul><p><b><a name=Battery>Household Batteries</a></b><ul><li>No auto batteries.<li>Must be in a clear plastic bag. Place in recycling bin next to other recyclables.</ul><p><b><a name=Mags>Magazines & Catalogs</a></b><br>Any thickness - as long as the pages are glossy. <ul><li>No magazines or catalogs with newsprint pages.<li>Must be in paper bags or bundled with string or twine. Each bundle must weigh less than 20 lbs.</ul><p><b><a name=News>Newspaper</a></b><br>Also include any ads that come with the newspaper<ul><li>Must be in paper bags, or bundled with string or twine.</ul><p><b><a name=Office>Office Paper & Mail</a></b><ul><li>Includes all office papers and junk mail such as:<ul>Brochures<br>Construction paper<br>Copier paper<br>Envelopes<br>File Folders<br>Greeting Cards<br>Letters<br>Mail<br>Notebook paper<br>Post-It Notes</ul></ul><ul><li>Do not include brown envelopes, product samples, or plastic bags.<li>Labels and windows do not need to be removed from envelopes.<li>Place in the same paper bag as your boxboard.</ul><p><b><a name=Phone Books>Phone Books</a></b><br>Any phone directory.<ul><li>Place in or on your recycling bin. Do not bag.</ul><b><a name=Plastic>Plastic Bottles</a></b><p><ul><b>Please Note:</b> We no longer collect food jars (like peanut butter), colored food tubs (like butter and yogurt), and single-use microwave containers (like plates for frozen microwave dinners).</ul><ul><li>A plastic bottle is a plastic container with a neck. Examples include:<ul><br>Antifreeze<br>Bleach<br>Conditioner<br>Cooking oil<br>Dish detergent<br>Distilled Water<br>Fabric Softener<br>Ketchup<br>Laundry detergent<br>Lotion<br>Milk<br>Pop<br>Syrup<br>Windshield Washer Fluid</ul></ul><ul><li>No motor oil, hazardous waste or prescription bottles.<li>Remove and throw away all caps and pumps. Rinse clean.<li>Must be in paper bags.</ul><p><HR width=100%><p>Updated 3/20/96</body></html>
</DOC>
