Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5759
Last-modified: Thu, 16 Jan 1997 01:58:58 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><TITLE>Overview</TITLE></head><body>City of Minneapolis, Division of Solid Waste & Recycling <H2>OVERVIEW</H2><HR width=100%>The Division of Solid Waste & Recycling provides service to approximately 290,000 residents in 114,000 dwelling units. This includes all 1-4 unit residential buildings, and any buildings with five or more units that contract with the City for solid waste services. Crews also collect garbage and recyclables from an additional 100 City buildings, and from 1,200 litter containers placed throughout the city.<p>Service is comprehensive and includes garbage, recycling, large item, and yard waste collections. Collection is provided by City of Minneapolis collection crews, and a consortium of private garbage haulers, Minneapolis Refuse Incorporated (MRI). The City and MRI each collect from approximately half of the dwelling units in the city. In addition, neighborhood clean sweeps and drop-offs for excess garbage, construction and paving materials and tires are also provided as a part of City service.<p>The City of Minneapolis, Division of Solid Waste & Recycling, has received numerous national awards:<ul><li>1992 Best Recycling Program - National Recycling Association<li>1992 Systems Excellence Award - Solid Waste Association of North America<li>1991 Best Recycling Program - US Conference of Mayors</ul>The following is a brief overview of the different aspects of the Division of Solid Waste and Recycling.<p><HR width=100%><p><b>FUNDING</b><p>The primary source of funding is the Solid Waste Base Fee and Disposal Fees charged on the Public Works Utility Bill. The Solid Waste Base fee is $19 unit/month. The Large Cart Disposal fee is $4 cart/month and the Small Cart Disposal fee is $2 cart/month. The Recycling Credit, for participating households, is $7/unit/month.<p><HR width=100%><p><b>GARBAGE COLLECTION</b><p>Residential garbage, including carpet and large items less than 50% metal, is collected weekly. Each building may set out two large items per week. The Division of Solid Waste & Recycling also collects garbage from 1,200 litter containers, and City buildings including fire and police stations.<p><HR width=100%><p><b>LARGE ITEMS COLLECTION</b><p>Major appliances, such as air conditioners and refrigerators, are collected every other week on recycling day. After collection, PCB-laden capacitors and fluorescent light ballasts are removed for disposal at a hazardous waste facility. Mercury switches are removed for recycling. Freon is removed, filtered and reused in city air-conditioning equipment. The appliances are then sent to a scrap metal dealer to be recycled.<p>Large items that are at least 50% metal, such as aluminum storm doors and filing cabinets, are collected every other week on recycling day and delivered to a scrap metal dealer for recycling.<p><HR width=100%><p><b>RECYCLING COLLECTION</b><p>Minneapolis began its recycling program at a time when legal requirements or statutes mandating recycling were nonexistent. The program was originally supported by a strong environmental ethic and a concern about rising garbage disposal costs. A pilot curbside program in 1982 served 32,000 households and collected just over 1,000 tons of newspapers, clear glass and aluminum cans. In 1995, over 22,000 tons of recyclables were collected.<p>Newspapers, metal cans, glass bottles and jars, plastic bottles, magazines, household batteries, phone books, milk/juice cartons, drink boxes, office paper, dry-food boxboard, and corrugated cardboard are collected bi-weekly for recycling. Approximately 90% of the households served by Minneapolis Solid Waste & Recycling participate.<p>In October 1990, household batteries were added to materials collected by recycling crews. In addition, battery drop-off locations were made available at community centers, and fire and police stations for residents who do not have City recycling collection. Mercury and silver oxide, gel cells and nickel-cadmium batteries are recycled. Alkaline batteries are disposed of at a hazardous waste landfill and lithium batteries at a hazardous waste incinerator.<p><HR width=100%><p><b>YARD WASTE COLLECTION</b><p>Grass clippings, leaves, and brush are collected weekly from April through November. Yard waste is composted within the city limits by a contractor.<p>The City Street Division cleans leaves from streets during the fall. These leaves are composted, mulched or landspread.<p>Christmas trees are collected for one week each January. The trees are then chipped and used in landscaping and composting.<p><HR width=100%><p><b>DROPOFF PROGRAMS</b><p>The Division of Solid Waste & Recycling offers vouchers to drop off building and paving materials, excess garbage, and up to eight tires at no additional charge. Two vouchers of each type are available per year for each building with City Solid Waste & Recycling service.<p>The concrete and asphalt collected are both reused. Concrete is stockpiled during the winter months, and then crushed and used as a granular road bed. Asphalt is also crushed and used in varying amounts for new paving projects.<p><HR width=100%><p><b>NEIGHBORHOOD CLEANSWEEPS</b><p>Cleansweeps are one-day, neighborhood clean-up events organized by registered neighborhood groups. The neighborhood provides a coordinator, promotion, and volunteers to help load materials. Minneapolis Solid Waste & Recycling provides trucks, drivers, and disposal. Cleansweeps are a popular City program especially with elderly residents who get assistance from their neighbors with garbage removal. In 1994, 29 neighborhoods organized Cleansweeps.<p><HR width=100%>Updated Monday, 20 May 1996.</body></html>
</DOC>
