<html><head></head><body>City of Minneapolis, Division of Solid Waste & Recycling  <H2>TECHNICAL DETAILS</H2><p><HR width=100% .><p><b>GARBAGE COLLECTION</b><p>Service provided:<ul><li>Garbage is collected weekly.<li>Carts provided are either a 24-gallon Schaffer garbage cart, or a 90-gallon Otto garbage cart(s)</ul><p>Garbage trucks used by City crews:<br><ul><li>Low entry, Crane Carrier chassis with 20-cubic yard Leach 2RII compactors and Zoeller semi-automated lifters.<li>19 garbage trucks service 650 dwelling units per route per day.  Two crew members per truck.<li>For downtown litter containers, a 6-cubic yard, side-loading packer is used.  This truck has one crew member.</ul><p>Processing Garbage:<ul><li>Garbage is delivered to the Hennepin County Waste-to-Energy facility in Minneapolis.  Of the garbage, 93% is incinerated, and 7%is landfilled.<li>Waste disposal is procured through a five year contract with Hennepin County that expires January 1, 2001. The disposal price for 1996 is $45/ton</ul><HR width=100%><p><b>LARGE ITEM COLLECTION</b><p>Service provided:<ul><li>Large items (major appliances, items more than 50% metal, and hide-a-beds) are collected every other week on the next business day after recycling day.</ul><p>Large item trucks used by City crew:<ul><li>Low entry, Crane Carrier chassis with a custom designed stakebed box and hydraulic tailgate is used to collect these materials.<li>Two trucks during the winter, and three trucks during the summer months, service 57,000 households bi-weekly, approximately 2900 dwelling units per route per day in the winter, and 1900 dwelling units per route per day in the summer.<li>One to two crew members per route.</ul><p>Processing Large items:<ul><li>PCB laden capacitors and fluorescent light ballasts are removed for disposal at a hazardous waste facility.<li>Mercury switches are removed for recycling.<li>Freon is removed, filtered and reused in City air-conditioning equipment.<li>Scrap metal is recycled.</ul><HR width=100%><p><b>RECYCLING COLLECTION</b><p>Service provided:<ul><li>Recyclables are collected every other week on garbage day.<li>One Shamrock 23 gallon recycling bin is provided to each household.  Residents may purchase additional containers at local stores.<li>A recycling calendar with collection information is mailed yearly to each home.</ul><p>Recycling trucks used by City crews:<ul><li>Dual-side drive, low-entry, Crane Carrier chassis with a custom Kann 24 cubic yard box and 19 cubic yard gooseneck trailer.  Separate compartments are provided for each item.  Crew separate glass into clear, green and brown compartments.  A five gallon bucket is used for household batteries.<li>12 recycling trucks service 57,000 households bi-weekly, approximately 500 dwelling units per route per day.<li>3 to 6 tons per day.<li>One crew member per truck.</ul><p>Processing Recyclables:<ul><li>Recyclables, except batteries, are processed and marketed through BFI. As of April  30, 1996 proposals were still being evaluated to determine which firm will process and market the City's recyclables.<li>Batteries are taken to a Hennepin County facility, where they are sorted by type.  Mercury and nickel-cadmium batteries are recycled; lithium batteries are disposed of at a hazardous waste incinerator; and alkaline batteries are disposed of at a hazardous waste landfill.</ul><HR width=100%><p><b>YARD WASTE COLLECTION</b><p>Service Provided:<ul><li>Yard waste is collected weekly on the garbage day, from approximately April 15 through November 30, weather permitting.<li>Customers are asked to place yard waste in bundles, plastic bags or paper bags designed for yard waste.<li>Christmas trees are collected for one week in mid-January.</ul><p>Yard waste trucks used by City crews:<ul><li>A variety of tandem axle trucks are used which have been retired from garbage routes.  All have 20 yard Leach 2RII compactors.<li>Seven trucks service 57,000 households weekly, approximately 1600 dwelling units per route per day.<li>One or two crew members per route.</ul><p>Processing Yard Waste:<ul><li>Yard waste is debagged and composted at a private composting facility located inside the city limits. SKB operates the facility and has a contract with the City that began October 1, 1995, and continues through February 28, 1998.</ul><p><HR width=100%>Updated Monday, 1 May 1996.</body></html>
