<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Household Hazardous Waste</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body>
City of Minneapolis, Division of Solid Waste & Recycling
<H2>HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE</H2>
<HR width=100%>
<p>
<b>MOBILE DROP-OFFS</b>
<p>
The mobile collection events are over for 1996.
<p>
Minneapolis residents can bring household hazardous wastes to the permanent Hennepin County Citizen Waste Drop-offs:
<UL><LI>Hennepin County Recycling Center Transfer Station, Brooklyn Park<BR>
<LI>South Hennepin Recycling & Problem Waste Drop Off Center, Bloomington </UL>
<P>
Drop-off site hours, locations and maps are available at the Hennepin County, <a HREF=http://www.co.hennepin.mn.us/wrecycle.html>Environmental Management Division</a> web page.
<p>
<HR width=100%>
<p>
<b>HOW TO PREPARE</b>
<p>
For your safety and county employee safety, please keep these guidelines in mind.
<ul><li>To avoid spillage, bring in household hazardous wastes in tightly sealed containers, in plastic-lined boxes, in your car trunk. 
<li>Containers must be no larger than 5 gallons in size. 
<li>Container contents should be labeled if not in the original packaging. 
<li>NEVER mix or pour household hazardous wastes together!
</ul>
<p>
<HR width=100%>
<p>
<a name=examples><b>EXAMPLES OF ITEMS COLLECTED AT MOBILE DROP-OFFS</b></a>
<p>
<ul><li><b>Consumer Electronics</b>
<p>
Camcorders, computers, radios, stereos, tape players, televisions, telephones, and vcr's.
<p>
<li><b>Mercury Products</b></a>
<p>
Mercury barometers, switches, thermometers, and thermostats
<br>Fluorescent light tubes, and HID (high intensity discharge) lamps.
<p>
<li><b>Rechargeable Products</b></a>
<p>
Cordless telephones, hand vacuums, radios, radio controlled toys, power tools.
<p>
<li><b>Household Hazardous Wastes </b></a>
<p>
Household hazardous wastes are usually identified by words such as:
<p>
<ul>Caution! Caustic! Corrosive! Danger! 
<br>Flammable! Poison! Volatile! Warning!</ul>
<p>
Here are some specific examples:
<p>
<b>Car Products</b> -- Brake and transmission fluids, gasoline, gasoline mixed with oil.
<p>
<b>Cleaning Products</b> -- Disinfectants, drain cleaners and oven cleaners
<br>Solvent based floor products, metal polishes, and spot removers.
<p>
<b>Painting Supplies</b> -- Paints,  paint strippers, primers, thinners, turpentines, varnishes/oils, wood finishes, wood preservatives and stains.
<p>
<b>Pesticides</b> -- bug sprays, poisons, and weed killers.
<p>
<b>Other Products</b> -- Adhesives and glues (solvent based), aerosol cans - if any contents remain inside, alcohols, household batteries (any size or type), kerosene, lye, photographic chemicals.</ul>
<p>
<b>ITEMS NOT COLLECTED AT MOBILE DROP-OFFS</b></a>
<p>
<ul>Asbestos
<br>Auto batteries
<br>Compressed gas cylinders/tanks
<br>Explosives
<br>Large appliances (ovens, refrigerators...etc)
<br>Medical or infectious waste
<br>Motor oil, motor oil filters
<br>Radioactive waste (smoke detectors...etc)
<br>Tires
</ul>
<p>
<HR width=100%>
Updated Monday, 28 October 1996.
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
