<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Budget &amp; Evaluation</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Budget &amp; Evaluation"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Budget &amp; Evaluation</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P>The Office of Budget &amp; Evaluation administers a financial planning,
budgeting, and program evaluation system that provides the information that
allows policy officials to determine the appropriate level of government services
to be provided by City departments and agencies, and allows them to allocate
public funds needed to provide these services in the most efficient and effective
manner possible. The City budget is made up of several parts. Of particular
interest to citizens are the Operating, Community Development Block Grant,
Capital, and Year of the City budgets.

<H3><BR>City of Minneapolis Budget Process</H3>

<P>The City of Minneapolis has a budget review process which integrates
departmental performance with budget review in a year-round continuum of
events.

<P>The Office of Budget &amp; Evaluation prepares a budget calendar, which includes
a process for reviewing each department's operational performance from the
previous year. City departments appear before their appropriate City Council
policy committee to report on their accomplishments in the previous year as well
as to indicate anticipated changes in their current year activities that were not
reflected in the performance information reviewed during their budget
hearings.

<P>Departments with capital improvement or Community Development Block Grant
(CDBG) programs, as well as community service organizations seeking CDBG funds,
submit all those requests in April and May. By mid-June, all <A
HREF="/departments/index.html">City departments</A>, the <A
HREF="/departments/other/library.html">Library Board</A>, the <A
HREF="/departments/other/parks.html">Park &amp; Recreation Board</A>, the Municipal
Building Commission and the <A HREF="/departments/other/mcda.html">Community
Development Agency</A> submit their operating budget requests. Decision packages
are prepared which describe policy changes or alternatives requested by
departments or proposed by the budget staff. In July, these decision packages
form the basis for the Mayor's budget hearing with department heads.

<P>The Mayor's budget includes recommendations for the <A
HREF="/departments/other/parks.html">Park Board</A> and <A
HREF="/departments/other/library.html">Library Board</A>, <A
HREF="/departments/other/mcda.html">Community Development Agency</A>, <A
HREF="/departments/other/mpha.html">Public Housing Authority</A> and Municipal
Building Commission. State law requires local governments to establish maximum
tax levies for the coming year by September 15. Next year's budget will be
presented a few weeks prior to this deadline in order for the City's independent
boards and commissions to react to this proposal before the <A
HREF="/departments/other/taxation.html">Board of Estimate &amp; Taxation</A> sets
the maximum levy amounts.

<P><A HREF="/departments/city-council/index.html">City Council</A> hearings on
the proposed budget occur in mid-October. State law now requires that city
budgets be adopted at a public hearing. Like the maximum tax levy, this date must
also be established by September 15 although the hearing cannot be held before
November 29. The independent boards and commissions adopt their own operating
budgets, although the <A HREF="/departments/city-council/index.html">City
Council</A> and <A HREF="/departments/mayor/index.html">Mayor</A> decide what
level of local government aid and bonding authority they will receive in most
instances.

<P>Once the final budget resolutions are adopted, all requests from <A
HREF="/departments/index.html">City departments</A> for additional funds or
positions made throughout the year are brought before the <A
HREF="/departments/city-council/index.html">City Council</A> for approval as
amendments to the original budget resolutions.

<P>

<HR>

<ADDRESS>
<P><B>Budget &amp; Evaluation</B><BR>
City Hall, Room 325M<BR>
350 5 St S<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1315
</ADDRESS>

<P><B>Phone Number</B><BR>
(612) 673-3007<BR>


