| <A HREF="../../../../related.html">Other Sites</A> <HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="top"></A>All About Elections</H2>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>Read below for answers to many of your election questions,
like: <BR>
<TABLE WIDTH="457" BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING="2" HEIGHT="152">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP" HEIGHT="21"><UL>
  <LI><A HREF="#dates">When and where</A> to vote
</UL>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP"><UL>
  <LI>How to <A HREF="#prereg">pre-register</A>
</UL>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP" HEIGHT="21"><UL>
  <LI>Voting by <A HREF="#absentee">absentee ballot</A>
</UL>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP"><UL>
  <LI>How to be an <A HREF="#judge">election judge</A>
</UL>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP" HEIGHT="20"><UL>
  <LI><A HREF="#nonpartisan">How the 1997 elections work</A>
</UL>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP"><UL>
  <LI><A HREF="#assistance">Assistance</A> for people with disabilities
</UL>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD HEIGHT="33" VALIGN="TOP"><UL>
  <LI>Offices on the ballot &amp; how to <A HREF="#filing">file for office</A>
</UL>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP"><UL>
  <LI>Important <A HREF="#phones">elections phone numbers</A>
</UL>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP"><UL>
  <LI><A HREF="#ballots">Petitions</A> to change the City Charter
</UL>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP"><UL>
  <LI>Election <A HREF="order_form.html">materials</A> available
</UL>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP" HEIGHT="21"><UL>
  <LI>Who's running? <I>Available mid-July, 1997</I>
</UL>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP"><UL>
  <LI>What's on the ballot? <I>Available in mid-September, 1997</I>
</UL>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</P>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><HR></H2>

<H2><A NAME="dates"></A>1997 Election dates</H2>

<P>Primary election: Tuesday, September 9, 1997 <BR>
General election: Tuesday, November 4, 1997<BR>
Polls open 7:00 a.m. -- 8:00 p.m.</P>

<P>Primary absentee balloting begins: Friday, August 8, 1997<BR>
General absentee balloting begins: Friday, October 3, 1997</P>

<P>Deadline to pre-register to vote in the Primary election: Tuesday, August
19, 1997<BR>
Deadline to pre-register to vote in the General election: Tuesday, October
14, 1997</P>

<H3><A NAME="Maps"></A>Where do I vote?</H3>

<P>You must vote in the precinct in which you live. Each precinct has a
polling place. In Minneapolis, there are 145 polling places, all of which
are handicapped accessible.</P>

<P>1997 Minneapolis polling places will be approved by the Minneapolis City
Council on Friday, August 8, 1997. Please do not refer to any past-year
lists. If a polling place is changed from last year, registered voters of
that precinct will be notified by postcard in mid-August.</P>

<P><B>Check back again.</B> By mid-August, you will be able to click a map
and find your polling place.</P>

<H3>How do I vote?</H3>

<P>Voting is easy. You can <A HREF="#prereg">pre-register</A>, <A HREF=
"#dayreg">register on Election Day</A>, or <A HREF="#absentee">vote by absentee
ballot</A>. Check the regulations carefully; it will help reduce delays.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<H2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><A NAME="prereg"></A>Pre-Registering to Vote</H2>

<P>No ID is needed to pre-register. You may preregister any time up to 20
days prior to an election.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Eligibility of voters</B></P>

<P>A person IS eligible to vote, if at the time of the election he/she:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>Is 18 years of age or older
  <LI>Is a citizen of the United States and
  <LI>Has resided in Minnesota for at least 20 days.
</UL>

<P><BR>
<B>Who needs to register </B></P>

<UL>
  <LI>Individuals who have never registered to vote
  <LI>Individuals who have moved or changed their name since they last registered
  <LI>Individuals who have not voted at least once in the last 4 years
</UL>

<P><BR>
<B>Where to pre-register </B></P>

<UL>
  <LI>Minneapolis City Hall, Room 1B
  <LI>Minneapolis Public Libraries
  <LI>Minneapolis Park Buildings
  <LI>Minneapolis Fire Stations
  <LI>Minneapolis Police Stations
  <LI>Hennepin County Service Centers (Brookdale, Ridgedale, Southdale &amp;
  Maple Grove)
  <LI>Hennepin County Government Center, Room A600
</UL>

<P><BR>
<B>Deadline to pre-register </B><BR>
Individuals must register by:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>August 19, 5 P.M. for the Primary election
  <LI>October 14, 5 P.M. for the General election
</UL>

<P><BR>
<B>Notice to voters </B><BR>
Newly registered voters will receive a postcard notice indicating their
<A HREF="#Maps">polling place location</A>.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3>

<H2><A NAME="dayreg"></A>Election Day Registration Requirements</H2>

<P>Voters may register on election day if the following conditions are met.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Eligibility of voters </B><BR>
A person IS eligible to vote, if at the time of the election he/she: <BR>
- Is 18 years of age or older <BR>
- Is a citizen of the United States and <BR>
- Has resided in Minnesota for 20 days.</P>

<P>The following are NOT eligible to vote: <BR>
- Anyone convicted of treason or any felony whose civil rights have not
been restored <BR>
- Anyone under guardianship of the person<BR>
- Anyone found by a court of law to be legally incompetent <BR>
<BR>
<B>Proof of residence </B><BR>
Voters registering to vote on election day must provide proof of residence
within the precinct. Any one of the following is authorized:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>Valid Minnesota driver's license or learner's permit (or receipt for
  either) showing correct/current address in the precinct
  <LI>Valid Minnesota identification card (or receipt) showing correct/current
  address in precinct
  <LI>College students may use any of the following: current student fee
  statement showing address in the precinct, current student picture ID card
  showing address in the precinct, or current student registration card showing
  address in the precinct
  <LI>Notice of Ineffective Registration card mailed by election headquarters
  within the two weeks prior to election day, showing address of voter in
  the precinct
  <LI>Valid registration in the same precinct (applies if voter has moved
  within the same precinct or changed their name)
  <LI>Voucher -- oath of a pre-registered voter in the same precinct or of
  a voter who registers on election day with one of the above five ID's.
  A voter who is vouched for cannot vouch for another voter.
</UL>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3>

<H2><A NAME="absentee"></A>Voting by Absentee Ballot</H2>

<P>Request an absentee ballot with <A HREF="abform.html">this form</A>.</P>

<P>Absentee balloting occurs within the 30 days before each election. Eligible
Minneapolis voters may vote by absentee ballot for any of the following
reasons:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>Absent from the precinct on election day
  <LI>Illness or disability
  <LI>Religious discipline or observance of religious holiday
  <LI>Service as an election judge in another precinct
</UL>

<P><BR>
Absentee Voters may:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>Vote in person at Minneapolis City Hall during regular business hours.
  <LI>Complete the entire process by mail.
</UL>

<P><BR>
An official absentee ballot application may be obtained from Minneapolis
City Hall. You can also print <A HREF="/abform.html">this one</A>. An application
need not be on an official or standard form. It is accepted if it contains
the following information: your name and residence address, the address
to which you wish ballot(s) sent, date of application, reason for the request,
and your signature. <BR>
<BR>
Please allow at least seven days to complete the process. Additional absentee
voting hours:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>Saturday (prior to election day) 1 P.M. - 3 P.M.
  <LI>Monday (prior to election day) 5 P.M. - 7 P.M.
</UL>

<P><BR>
Special absentee balloting procedures are available to voters in hospital
or health-care facilities. <A HREF="/departments/city-council/clerk/elections/index.html#phones">Call</A>
the Minneapolis Elections Department for additional information.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>How to Be an Election Judge</H2>

<P>Are efficient, fair elections important to you? You can help protect
voters' rights, serve your community... and get paid to do it.</P>

<P><B>Election Judge requirements</B></P>

<UL>
  <LI>eligible to vote
  <LI>able to read, write and speak English
  <LI>attend a training class
</UL>

<P><B>Election Judge responsibilities</B></P>

<UL>
  <LI>open and close the polls
  <LI>register and sign in voters
  <LI>distribute and collect ballots
  <LI>operate voting equipment
  <LI>record and certify the vote totals
</UL>

<P><B>Election Judge pay</B></P>

<P>Minneapolis Election Judges are paid $6.00 per hour to attend a training
class and for service on Election Day. State law allows for time off from
work <B><I>without loss of wages</I></B> to serve as an Election Judge with
20 days prior written notice to the employer.</P>

<P><B>Scheduling</B></P>

<P>Full-day (6 a.m. to approximately 9 p.m.) or part-time shifts are available.
Election Judge assignments are made by the Elections Department. Each precinct
uses four to 12 judges, depending on the needs of the election.</P>

<P>For further information, call 673-3871.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>&nbsp;</H2>

<H2><A NAME="assistance"></A>Assistance to Persons with Disabilities</H2>

<P>All polling places meet state and federal accessibility standards. All
polling places have a booth accessible for persons with disabilities. Voters
unable to enter a polling place may, with the assistance of two election
judges of different political parties, register and vote without leaving
their vehicle.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2><A NAME="nonpartisan"></A>Elections for City Offices Are Non-Partisan</H2>

<P>Party preference or political principle will appear with the candidate
name only for the offices of Mayor and Council Member. Voters may select
candidates regardless of the listed party or principle.<BR>
<BR>
If more than two candidates file for an office, there is a Primary contest.
The top two vote-getters for each office from the Primary election will
run in the General election.<BR>
<BR>
There are no write-ins in a primary.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2><A NAME="ballots"></A>Petitions to Change the City Charter</H2>

<P><B>Time Frame to Place a Question on the November 4, 1997, General Election
Ballot</B></P>

<P>There are three available methods to place a Charter question on the
ballot:</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Citizen-initiated petition process<BR>
  Charter Commission recommendation<BR>
  City Council recommendation</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>All three are incorporated into this schedule.</P>

<P><TABLE WIDTH="450" BORDER="1" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="29%" BGCOLOR="#d9d9d9" VALIGN="TOP"><B>Date</B></TD>
<TD WIDTH="71%" BGCOLOR="#d9d9d9" VALIGN="TOP"><B>Event</B></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">August 14, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">Last <I>regularly</I> scheduled Charter Commission meeting to recommend
Charter change for referral to the Intergovernmental Relations (IGR) Committee.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">September 4, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP"><P>Last <I>regularly</I> scheduled IGR Committee meeting to propose ballot
language and refer to full City Council:</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>from petition submission<BR>
  from Charter Commission recommendation<BR>
  from City Council recommendation</BLOCKQUOTE>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">September 12, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">Last <I>regularly</I> scheduled City Council meeting to approve ballot language.
Mayor approves Council action.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">September 12, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">Ballot layout submitted to printer. <BR>
<I>(NOTE: Primary election, September 9, 1997)</I></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">October 3, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">Absentee balloting begins for November 4 election.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">November 4, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">GENERAL ELECTION</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">November 7, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">Amendment results certified by City Council.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD COLSPAN="2"><I>NOTE: This time frame does not preclude the Charter Commission, Intergovernmental
Relations Committee or City Council from scheduling special meetings.</I></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</P>

<P><B>Citizen-Initiated Petition Process</B></P>

<P>Number of registered voter signatures required to present a petition:
8,155 signatures <BR>
<I>(5% of total votes cast at previous State general election, November
5, 1996; 163,110 voting) </I><BR>
<TABLE WIDTH="450" BORDER="1" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="29%" BGCOLOR="#d9d9d9" VALIGN="TOP"><B>Date</B></TD>
<TD WIDTH="71%" BGCOLOR="#d9d9d9" VALIGN="TOP"><B>Event</B></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">May 8, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">Earliest date a <I>petition</I> may be submitted to place a Charter question
on the General Election ballot.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">August 28, 1997</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">Latest date a <I>petition</I> may be submitted to place a Charter question
on the General Election ballot. Special Charter Commission, IGR Committee
and City Council meetings must be scheduled.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</P>

<P>The <I>petition</I> verification process however can take up to 25 days
-- Elections Department has 10 days to verify initial submission of signatures;
petitioners have 10 more days to obtain additional signatures if needed;
Elections Department has 5 more days to verify additional signatures.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2><A NAME="filing"></A>Eligibility to Run for Office</H2>

<P>Per Article VII, Section 6 of the Constitution of the State of Minnesota:
Every person who by the provisions of this article is entitled to vote at
any election and is twenty-one (21) years of age is eligible for any office
elective by the people in the district wherein he has resided thirty days
previous to the election, except as otherwise provided in this Constitution
and law of the United States.</P>

<P>Candidates file in the Office of Elections, Room 1B City Hall. Each candidate
receives a packet of financial and campaign information at the time of filing.</P>

<P>The following dates are in accordance with the provisions of Chapter
Two of the City Charter of Minneapolis and Minnesota Statutes.</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Opening date for candidate filing for office: Tues, July 1, 1997<BR>
  Closing date for candidate filing for office: Tues, July 15, 1997 <FONT
   SIZE=-1>(5:00 p.m.) </FONT><BR>
  Withdrawal by noon Wednesday, July 16, 1997</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>Filing fee</B> (all candidates): $20.00, or petition in lieu of filing
fee per M.S. 205.121.</P>

<UL>
  <P><I>A nominating petition filed on behalf of a candidate for municipal
  office in a city of the first class shall be signed by eligible voters
  who maintain residence in the election district from which the candidate
  is to be elected. The number of signers shall equal 500, or two percent
  of the total number of individuals who voted in the municipality, ward,
  or other election district at the last preceding municipal general election,
  whichever is greater.</I>
  <P>November 4, 1993, Number Voting City-wide: 104,626
  <P>Petition Signatures Required for City-wide offices: 2,093 signatures
  <P>Ward and park district petition information, contact the Office of Elections
  (673-2070)
</UL>

<P><B>Note</B>: Minneapolis City Charter, Chapter 2, Section 5 states:</P>

<UL>
  <P>For the offices of Mayor and Council Member, the top two vote-getters
  for each office from the Primary election will run in the General election.
  <P>Party preference or political principle will appear with the candidate
  name for the offices of Mayor and Council Member.
  <P>Primary election ballot format will be set up according to the non-partisan
  candidate format with no party columns.
</UL>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Back to <A HREF="#top">top</A></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

