<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Fire</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Fire"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Fire</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P>The Minneapolis Fire Department has five main areas of service responsibility:
fighting fires, fire investigations, fire safety inspections, fire prevention,
and emergency medical service.

<H3><BR>Fighting Fires</H3>

<P>The Fire Department has about 430 firefighters assigned to 20 stations located
throughout the City, with at least 109 firefighters working every day. Each
station responds to calls within its own response zone and may assist in
responding to calls within a larger district (there are four districts in the
City). The department's typical response to an alarm is three engine companies
(smaller trucks), two ladder companies (larger trucks), and a battalion chief.
Additional resources may be called in for multiple alarm fires. The first company
out of a station attempts to respond to an alarm within six minutes (the average
response time is 3.5 minutes).

<H3><BR>Fire Investigations</H3>

<P>The Fire Department has four investigators who examine every reported fire to
determine its cause/origin and the extent of loss. If the department determines
that arson is the cause of a fire, the <A
HREF="/departments/police/index.html">Minneapolis Police Department</A> conducts
the ensuing investigation.

<H3><BR>Fire Safety Inspections</H3>

<P>The Fire Department has six inspectors who strive to carry out annual fire
safety inspections of existing properties in the following categories: apartment,
condominium, commercial, office, service, storage and school. Auditoriums and
churches are inspected on a seasonal basis. Inspections are also carried out for
new construction and for any other properties requiring a City permit, license,
or certificate. Other inspections are carried out in response to a complaint or
referral. If a code violation is noted, a follow-up inspection is made to check
for compliance with departmental regulations.

<H3><BR>Fire Safety Education</H3>

<P>The Fire Department has two full-time employees involved in fire-safety
education and planning: in schools, day-care centers and hospitals; with block
and neighborhood groups; and in response to requests for information from
individual Minneapolis residents. The department's Junior Fire Program, for
instance, involved 3,659 fifth-grade children at 49 public elementary schools
during the 1992-93 school year. The &quot;Safe Escape House&quot; (a mobile,
fire-safety instruction unit) is frequently used at block and neighborhood
gatherings to teach children how to safely escape from a building that is on
fire.

<H3><BR>Emergency Medical Service</H3>

<P>Fire Department personnel stationed at the 20 Minneapolis fire stations are
also trained Emergency Medical Technicians. Technicians at each station respond
to calls within their fire-fighting response zone. The average response time is
3.5 minutes.

<P>

<HR>

<ADDRESS>
<P><B>Minneapolis Fire Department</B><BR>
City Hall, Room 230<BR>
350 5 St S<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1387
</ADDRESS>

