<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Health</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Health"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Health</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P>The Minneapolis Department of Health has three main areas of service
responsibility: personal health, public health nursing, and environmental
health.

<H3><BR>Personal Health</H3>
<P>The Health Department offers a variety of direct-care services to
income-eligible people at a downtown clinic and at satellite community and
high-school clinics. These clinics offer health care to mothers, teens, and
children; dental care; family planning services; and laboratory tests (e.g.,
blood, urine) for health problems and marriage licenses.

<P>The Health Department also provides general health information and encourages
health and wellness activities. Most of these services are free. Examples
include: worksite and school programs on AIDS; radio and TV public-service
announcements; brochures and posters; and health films, videos and literature.
Health educators are also available to speak about health-related topics.

<H3><BR>Public Health Nursing</H3>
<P>The Health Department provides home visits by nurses, home health aides, and
other specialists for residents who are unable to visit a clinic or who require
special assistance. Other services include training for care givers and
self-care; consultations for child-care programs; and organizing group
activities, especially for developing parenting skills.

<H3><BR>Environmental Health</H3>

<DL>
	<DT><B>Housing Hygiene</B>
	<DD>This program's task is to investigate sanitation and pest-related
	complaints in multiple family dwellings and single-family homes. The
	sanitarians are also involved in &quot;neighborhood sweeps,&quot; in which
	all properties in a neighborhood are inspected for compliance with a variety
	of City regulations: health, fire, building, etc. If a violation is noted, a
	follow-up inspection is made to check for compliance with City regulations.

	<DT><BR><B>Food Protection</B>
	<DD>The Health Department has sanitarians who strive to make regular
	inspections of food-oriented businesses and institutions. Sanitarians also
	make inspections in response to complaints from patrons or employees of such
	businesses. If a violation is noted, a follow-up inspection is made to check
	for compliance with City regulations.

	<DT><BR><B>Animal Control</B>
	<DD>The Health Department has animal-control wardens who minimize the risk of
	bites and rabies for residents by picking up stray animals. The department
	makes periodic patrols in neighborhoods that are prone to stray-animal and
	other violations of animal-control ordinances, sells animal licenses, and
	operates the animal shelter. Wardens are also available for group
	presentations.

	<DT><BR><B>Other</B>
	<DD>Other environmental health services include periodic monitoring of water
	quality (wells, lakes, rivers, and public and commercial swimming pools);
	inspecting tattoo parlors, dry-cleaning establishments and tanning parlors;
	and responding to complaints of carbon monoxide, asbestos, lead, and
	violations of the Clean Indoor Air Act.
</DL>

<P>

<HR>

<ADDRESS>
<P><B>Health</B><BR>
Public Health Center, Room 510<BR>
250 4 St S<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1372
</ADDRESS>

<P><BR><B>Phone Numbers</B>
<PRE>
