<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Inspections</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Inspections"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Inspections</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P>Minneapolis Inspections, a division of <A
HREF="/departments/city-coordinator/operations/index.html">Operations and
Regulatory Services</A>, has the following main areas of enforcement
responsibility:

<UL>
	<LI><A HREF="#insp-env">Environmental Review</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#insp-haz">Hazardous Boarded Buildings/Truth-In-Housing</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#insp-zon">Zoning Administration</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#insp-pln">Plan Review</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#insp-per">Permit Issuance</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#insp-con">Construction Inspections</A>
	<LI><A HREF="housing.html">Housing Inspections/Rental Licensing</A>
</UL>

<HR>

<A NAME="insp-env">
<H3>Environmental Review</H3>

<P>The Environmental Review section is responsible for the pollution prevention,
control, and cleanup activities of the City of Minneapolis. The section works to
assure the continued high quality of Minneapolis' air, water, and soil resources.
In addition to handling citizen environmental complaints involving air, odor,
noise, water pollution, illegal dumping, and hazardous spills, the section helps
coordinate City environmental policy with other local, county, regional, state,
and federal agencies.

<A NAME="insp-haz">
<H3><BR>Hazardous Boarded Buildings/Truth-In-Housing</H3>

<P>The Hazardous Boarded Buildings section secures and boards vacant and open
buildings deemed to be public nuisances and initiates the demolition process. The
City cannot issue any permits for repairs or alterations to a vacant, boarded,
and condemned building until the following steps have been taken:

<OL TYPE="1">
	<P><LI>The owner must make application for, and obtain, a code compliance
	inspection. If the entire building is to be gutted and brought up to code,
	the code compliance inspection may be waived by the Director of Inspections.
	To apply for a code compliance inspection, call the Hazardous Buildings
	section, (612) 673-5805.

	<P><LI>A cash deposit is required before any permits can be issued, and may
	be refunded.

	<P><LI>A licensed contractor must obtain permits to do any electrical,
	plumbing, or mechanical work.

	<P><LI>Vacant boarded and condemned buildings may not be occupied until a
	certificate of code compliance has been obtained.
</OL>

<P>The Truth-In-Sale of Housing section enforced the Truth-In-Sale of Housing
ordinance. The section administers tests and certification of TIH evaluators and
sets guidelines for their performance. For more information, call the
Truth-In-Housing Information Service, (612) 673-5849.

<A NAME="insp-zon">
<H3><BR>Zoning Administration</H3>

<P>The Zoning section is the first stop for anyone who wants to know if their
proposed use of a particular parcel of land is allowable. If the proposed use is
consistent with existing zoning ordinances, the next step is submission of
construction plans to the Plan Review section. If the proposed use is not
consistent with existing zoning ordinances, the applicant will be scheduled for a
public hearing by the Planning Commission for a rezoning or a conditional use
permit, or by the Board of Adjustment for a variation or an appeal.

<A NAME="insp-pln">
<H3><BR>Plan Review</H3>

<P>After Zoning has approved the proposed land use, two sets of construction
plans are submitted to the Plan Review section in order to secure a permit for
new construction, expansion or remodeling. The Plan Review section determines
compliance with local ordinances and applicable state building and mechanical
codes.

<A NAME="insp-per">
<H3><BR>Permit Issuance</H3>

<P>The Permit Issuance section issue permits for most work regarding building,
electrical, plumbing, and heating for contractors and the general public. This
includes the collection and handling of all permit fees. The section also
provides information about which projects require a permit, how to go about
getting a permit, and how much the permit costs.

<A NAME="insp-con">
<H3><BR>Construction Inspection</H3>

<P>The inspectors who make up the Construction Inspections section are
categorized by their areas of expertise: building, electrical, elevator,
mechanical, and plumbing. As part of the construction permit process, inspectors
are required to ensure that the work being done meets code and follows the
approved plan. More than one inspection may be performed during construction if
work does not meet code requirements, if the job is particularly complex, or if
it involves more than one area of expertise. Inspections can be scheduled by
calling the inspector's mobile phone number directly. To obtain an inspector's
phone number, please call the appropriate section listed below:

<PRE>
Building Inspections    (612) 673-5841
Electrical Inspections  (612) 673-5843
Elevator Inspections    (612) 673-5839
Mechanical Inspections  (612) 673-5847
Plumbing Inspections    (612) 673-5845
</PRE>

<P>

<HR>

<ADDRESS>
<P><B>Inspections</B><BR>
Public Health Center, Room 300<BR>
250 4 St S<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1373
</ADDRESS>

<P><BR><B>Phone Numbers</B>
<PRE>
Environmental Review         (612) 673-5897
Hazardous Boarded Buildings  (612) 673-5828
Permit Issuance              (612) 673-5890 or (612) 673-5895
Plan Review                  (612) 673-5831
Truth-In-Housing             (612) 673-5849
Zoning Administration        (612) 673-5836
</PRE>


