<HEAD>

<TITLE>Inspections -- Housing</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Inspections -- Housing"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Inspections -- Housing</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P>Each of the field inspectors in the Housing Inspection section of the <A
HREF="index.html">Inspections</A> division is assigned a district within the
City. Housing inspectors respond to referrals from <A
HREF="/departments/city-council/index.html">City Council</A> members, other City
agencies, and interested citizens that a particular property in their district is
in violation of the <CITE>Housing Maintenance Code</CITE>. A copy of the
Maintenance Code is available for &#36;5 from the Inspections Office, (612)
673-5890, or is free to view at the <A
HREF="/departments/other/library.html#lib-mil">Municipal Information Library</A>,
City Hall, or the <A HREF="/departments/other/library.html#lib-ctr">Central
Public Library</A> downtown.

<P>Owners of properties found to be in violation of the code will be issued a
letter describing the violation(s), specifying a timeline for correction of the
problem and a date for reinspection. This letter is called an &#34;order.&#34; If
the problem is not corrected in the specified time, a binding final notice will
be issued. Nuisance orders have short due dates. Major repairs are given more
time. The next step could be a violation tag with court action and fine to gain
compliance. In most cases, owners correct the problem upon receipt of the first
notice, or set a timetable for completion.

<P>Housing Inspectors look for:

<DL>
	<DT><B>Alley/sidewalk</B>
	<DD>Growth and vegetation that hangs over the edge of the public alley or
	public sidewalk must be cut and removed. A clearance of seven feet over
	public sidewalks and 14 feet over public alleys is required.

	<DT><BR><B>Garbage and litter</B>
	<DD>Each property should have adequate trash containers, and the property
	should be free of trash, garbage and debris. If a nuisance condition exists
	and is not corrected in the time allotted, inspectors will order proper
	disposal and may authorize a contractor to correct the problem and assess the
	costs to the owner.

	<DT><BR><B>General disrepair</B>
	<DD>Buildings that lack paint, have broken windows and rotting wood, broken
	steps or guardrails, and missing bricks in walls and chimneys will be issued
	orders.

	<DT><BR><B>Graffiti</B>
	<DD>Owners will be asked to paint over or remove graffiti marks painted on
	their property. For information on graffiti removal, call the Graffiti
	Hotline, (612) 673-2090.

	<DT><BR><B>Grass/weeds</B>
	<DD>All tall grass and weeds over eight inches in height must be cut and
	removed from your property. This includes all boulevards, side yards, and
	along alleys.

	<DT><BR><B>Inoperable vehicles</B>
	<DD>Inoperable or junk vehicles that have missing wheels or engines, broken
	windows, or out-of-date registrations will be tagged and towed.

	<DT><BR><B>Missing or unreadable addresses</B>
	<DD>Visible and readable house numbers are required for identification by
	emergency vehicles. Numbers must be on the front of the home or in the rear
	if there is an alley access.

	<DT><BR><B>Parking in yard</B>
	<DD>Vehicles may not be parked in yards or on unpaved surfaces; vehicles must
	be parked within the garage or on a hard-surfaced driveway. The number of
	vehicles outside a garage is also limited.

	<DT><BR><B>Poor housing hygiene</B>
	<DD>Inspectors will refer homes which may have extremely unhealthy conditions
	-- such as excessive or improperly stored garbage, rats, roaches, or other
	situations that may cause a health hazard -- to the <A
	HREF="/departments/city-coordinator/operations/health.html">Health
	Department</A>.

	<DT><BR><B>Storage of Large Items</B>
	<DD>Property owners who store large appliances, tires, or used motor oils and
	petroleum products on their property may be issued an order. Owners who have
	City service are advised to call <A
	HREF="/departments/public-works/solid-waste/index.html">Public Works/Solid
	Waste & Recycling</A>, (612) 522-6644, to inquire about (1) a special pick-up
	of large items such as refrigerators and freezers; and/or (2) a dumping
	voucher for tires (limit of one voucher per property per year and a maximum
	of four tires per voucher). Oil products must be disposed of properly and not
	in garbage containers or on streets, alleys or lawns. Free oil disposal is
	available at these City garages from 7 a.m. to 6 p.m. Monday through Friday:
	3607 44 St E; 2710 Pacific St N; 1308 Currie Av N; 1809 Washington St NE;
	6036 Harriet Av S; and 1911 26 St E (24 hours).

	<DT><BR><B>Unlicensed businesses</B>
	<DD>Illegal businesses will be reported to the proper authorities.
</DL>

<P>Other departments respond to health hazards such as rats, mice, roaches, and
lead paint (<A HREF="/departments/city-coordinator/operations/health.html">Health
Department</A>, (612) 673-2301) or asbestos (State Abatement, (612) 627-2170).

<H3><BR>CONDEMNATIONS</H3>

<P>When one or more of the following conditions exist, a condemnation may take
place:

<UL>
	<LI>A building is vacant and boarded.
	<LI>A building is determined to be unsafe; an inspector cites specific
	hazards.
	<LI>A building is dilapidated; no specific hazards are cited but the
	inspector has assigned the property a score qualifying it for condemnation.
	<LI>Utilities to a building have been discontinued.
	<LI>There is a housing hygiene problem (conducted by the <A
	HREF="/departments/city-coordinator/operations/health.html">Health
	Department</A>).
</UL>

<P>In rare situations, an individual dwelling unit in a multi-unit building may
be condemned if it does not endanger the remaining structure.

<H3><BR>REINSPECTION FEE ORDINANCE (Minneapolis Ordinance 244.190)</H3>

<P>The reinspection fee ordinance was passed on December 10, 1992. The intent of
this ordinance is to gain compliance of housing orders and to save resources. For
information on the ordinance, call (612) 673-3701; for information on
reinspection fee billing, call (612) 673-5864.

<H3><BR>RENTAL HOUSING</H3>

<P>Effective January 1, 1991, rental housing units with the City became subject
to a rental license ordinance. The intent of the ordinance is to:

<UL>
	<LI>Promote the health, safety, and welfare of the general public.
	<LI>Assure preservation of the existing housing supply.
	<LI>Help maintain property values.
	<LI>Work toward eliminating substandard and deteriorating rental housing.
	<LI>Maintain a living environment that contributes to healthful individual
	and family living.
</UL>

<P>The ordinance requires that every rental dwelling, including single-family
rental dwellings and rental units in owner-occupied duplexes, and rooming and
shared-bath units (unless they are in a licensed lodging house) must have a
license. For information on the licensing process, call (612) 673-3701.

<H3><BR>HOUSING INSPECTIONS GLOSSARY</H3>

<DL>
	<DT><B>Abated</B>
	<DD>The violation has been corrected by the owner and/or tenants.

	<DT><BR><B>Authorized</B>
	<DD>The Inspections Division has authorized a contracted company to correct
	the violation(s), and the fees/expenses for this service will be assessed
	against the property.

	<DT><BR><B>Boarded up/secured</B>
	<DD>Occurs when a vacant building, which may be open to trespassers and
	conducive to problems with fires, vagrants, and children, is sealed at all
	entrances on the first floor.

	<DT><BR><B>Condemned</B>
	<DD>The City designates a property unsafe or unsanitary and has it vacated.

	<DT><BR><B>Order</B>
	<DD>The letter notifying a property owner of specific violations of the
	<CITE>Housing Maintenance Code</CITE>. In this letter, a time limit for
	correction is set, and a reinspection is scheduled. Property owners are urged
	to call the inspector who issued the order if they have any questions.

	<DT><BR><B>Tagged</B>
	<DD>When a violation is not corrected, and/or the inspector feels the
	violation needs to be strongly addressed, the owner may be required to pay a
	fine. If the fine is not paid, the owner may be taken to court.
</DL>

<P>

<HR>

<ADDRESS>
<P><B>Inspections -- Housing</B><BR>
Public Health Center, Room 300<BR>
250 4 St S<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1373
</ADDRESS>

<P><BR><B>Phone Numbers</B>
<PRE>
Fax                                                  (612) 673-5819
General Information                                  (612) 673-5800
Graffiti Hotline                                     (612) 673-2090
Housing information and complaints                   (612) 673-5858
Information on safe removal of lead paint            (612) 673-2170
Information on licensing fees, units to be licensed,
  and the licensing process                          (612) 673-3701
Information on the licensing ordinance and program   (612) 673-3715
Seniors needing help to maintain their property      (612) 673-3004
Truth-In-Sale of Housing Information Service         (612) 673-5849
Zoning/Signs                                         (612) 673-5836
</PRE>


