<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Library</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Library"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Library</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P>The Minneapolis Public Library, as the city's pivotal information, education,
and cultural resource, is a source of community pride and economic stimulation.
The library selects, organizes, preserves, and makes accessible books and other
materials of current interest and permanent value, upholding the public's right
to know by providing people of all ages access to information and collections
that reflect all points of view. In a democratic society that depends on the free
flow of information, the library system, with its central facility and community
locations, is the key public institution and most visible symbol of democracy and
the importance of education, lifelong learning and intellectual freedom in the
City of Minneapolis.

<P>The library is governed by an independent board of trustees. Six are elected
at large for four-year terms and two are appointed for two-year terms by the <A
HREF="/departments/mayor/index.html">Mayor</A> and <A
HREF="/departments/city-council/index.html">City Council</A>. The board is
responsible for overseeing the establishment, management, and maintenance of
public libraries in the City of Minneapolis and has the authority to levy a tax
for the support of the library system. The board also appoints the director, who
administers and coordinates the operation of the library within the basic goals,
objectives, policies and principles approved by the Library Board. Anyone
interested in contacting a member of the Library Board may call the director's
office, (612) 372-6611.

<P>The Minneapolis library system consists of the Central Library at Fourth
Street and Nicollet Mall, 14 community libraries and a municipal reference
library at City Hall. The library's collection numbers over two million books
plus over 800,000 government documents and 150,000 nonprint items. During 1993,
there were 3,226,596 borrower transactions in the library system, and librarians
responded to 3,275,728 requests for information (2,074,921 requests were made in
person; 1,200,808 were made by telephone).

<P>Services offered by the Minneapolis Public Library include:
<UL>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-ctr">Central Library</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-mil">Municipal Information Library</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-com">Community Libraries</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-flc">Franklin Learning Center</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-kid">Children's Programs and Bookmobile</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-mat">Borrowing of Library Materials</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-cat">On-line Catalog and Remote Access</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-ref">Computerized Reference Services</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-cpy">Copy Services and Equipment</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-mtg">Meeting Rooms</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#lib-plt">Planetarium, Bookshop, and Homebound Service</A>
	<LI>General Information
</UL>

<A NAME="lib-ctr"><H3><BR>Central Library</H3></A>

<P>With more than 1.5 million books, over 2,700 magazine subscriptions and 75
different newspapers, the Central Library is the largest public library in the
state. Only about 16 percent of these materials are visible on open shelves. The
rest are shelved in nonpublic areas and may be requested at the service desks.
Special Collections, housed on the upper floors of the building, include rare
books and materials about Minneapolis. The Central Library collection is
organized by subject department. Each department provides books, magazines, and
other materials in its subject area.

<P><EM>Hours for the Central Library are 9 a.m.-9 p.m. Monday through Thursday, 9
a.m.-5:30 p.m. Friday, and 10 a.m.-5:30 p.m. Saturday.</EM>

<P><B>Telephone numbers for the subject departments are:</B>
<PRE>
Art and Music           (612) 372-6520
Business and Economics  (612) 372-6552
Business Directories    (612) 372-6526
Children's              (612) 372-6532
Film and Video          (612) 372-6558
Government Documents    (612) 372-6534
</PRE>

<A NAME="lib-mil"><H3><BR>Municipal Information Library</H3></A>

<P>A reference collection emphasizing urban affairs is housed at City Hall, Room
300. Hours for this Municipal Information Library are 8 a.m.-4:30 p.m. Monday
through Friday. For more information, call (612) 673-3029.

<A NAME="lib-com"><H3><BR>Community Libraries</H3></A>

<P>Community libraries serve as neighborhood information hubs, providing popular
reading for people of all ages, promoting literacy and love of reading among
children, and offering materials in a variety of formats for learning and
leisure-time activities.

<P><B>Community Library locations in Minneapolis</B>
<PRE>
East Lake         2727 Lake St E      (612) 724-4561
Franklin          1314 Franklin Av E  (612) 874-1667
Hosmer             347 36 St E        (612) 824-4848
Linden Hills      2900 43 St W        (612) 922-2600
Nokomis           5100 34 Av S        (612) 729-5989
North Regional    1315 Lowry Av N     (612) 522-3333
Northeast         2200 Central Av NE  (612) 789-1800
Pierre Bottineau  1224 2 St NE        (612) 379-2609
Roosevelt         4026 28 Av S        (612) 724-1298
Southeast         1222 4 St SE        (612) 378-1816
Sumner             611 Emerson Av N   (612) 374-5642
Walker            2880 Hennepin Av    (612) 823-8688
Washburn          5244 Lyndale Av S   (612) 825-4863
Webber Park       4310 Webber Pkwy    (612) 522-3182
</PRE>

<P>Contact community libraries for information about special collections and
services and individual hours.

<A NAME="lib-flc"><H3><BR>Franklin Learning Center</H3></A>

<P>A family literacy center helping adults and children improve their basic
skills in reading, writing, and math is located at Franklin Community Library.
Hours for the Franklin Learning Center are Mondays and Thursdays, 1 p.m. to 8:30
p.m.; Tuesdays and Wednesdays, 10 a.m. to 5:15 p.m. For more information, call
(612) 874-0951.

<PRE>
History and Travel       (612) 372-6537
Literature and Language  (612) 372-6540
Sociology                (612) 372-6555
Special Collections      (612) 372-6648
Technology and Science   (612) 372-6570
</PRE>

<A NAME="lib-kid"><H3><BR>Children's Programs</H3></A>

<P>Free programs for kids include storytime for young children, films for
children and families, and special events. Library Kids, a summer program for
readers and pre-readers, features performances by clowns, puppeteers,
storytellers, magicians, mimes, and musicians. A monthly &quot;Events&quot;
calendar listing library programs for kids and adults is available at all
Minneapolis Public Libraries.

<A NAME="lib-mat"><H3><BR>Borrowing of Library Materials</H3></A>

<P>Anyone who lives in the City of Minneapolis may apply for a free library card
at any Minneapolis Public Library. Anyone with a valid card from any
participating public library in Minnesota may borrow Minneapolis Public Library
materials including: current and classic videos, compact discs and LPs, computer
software, books in foreign languages, large-print books, books on tape, best
sellers, and children's books. For books and most other library materials
borrowed from the Minneapolis Public Library, there are three weeks between the
date of issue and the date due. Exceptions are 16mm films (loaned for one or two
nights), videocassettes (loaned for one week), and items borrowed on Special
Permit (loaned for a limited time by special permission). Minneapolis Public
Library materials (except videocassettes, 16mm films, compact discs, computer
software, interlibrary loans and Special Permit items) may be renewed one time if
there is no hold waiting and there is no unpaid fine due (touch tone renewal line
(612) 341-3848). Fines on most overdue items are 25 cents per item per day
(higher for videocassettes, 16mm films and Special Permit items). There are no
fines on juvenile materials. Materials borrowed from the Minneapolis Public
Library (except videocassettes, 16mm films, interlibrary loans and Special Permit
items) may be returned to any public library in the Twin Cities metropolitan
area.

<A NAME="lib-cat"><H3><BR>Online Catalog and Remote Access</H3></A>

<P>The library's online catalog provides access to the two million books and
nonprint items in the Central Library and the 14 community libraries. The catalog
provides instant information on each item's location and availability. Items may
be located by title, author or subject, as well as by combinations of key words
from the author, title and subject indexes. Users interact with the online
catalog through a terminal equipped with keyboard and screen; the screen provides
choices and instructions on how to proceed through a search. Each library
location has several terminals for public use.

<P>Anyone having a personal computer and modem at their home, school or office
may use the library catalog through online remote access. Call (612) 332-5135
(1200 bps) or (612) 332-5223 (2400 bps), or pick up a brochure at any Minneapolis
Public Library that tells how to connect to the library's catalog from a remote
location. You can now
<A HREF="telnet://mpls.lib.mn.us">access the library catalog</A>
via the Internet.

<A NAME="lib-ref"><H3><BR>Computerized Reference Services</H3></A>

<P>For use in finding magazine articles on a topic of interest, computerized
indexes such as InfoTrac and Newsbank are available at the Central Library and at
North Regional, Walker, and Washburn libraries. When appropriate, staff will
conduct a computer database search to find information on your topic. The service
is free for up to eight minutes of computer time. Ask at a service desk if
interested in this service. To request that the Library staff do more extensive
reference work for you, inquire about <STRONG>INFORM</STRONG>, the Library's
fee-based research service.

<A NAME="lib-cpy"><H3><BR>Copy Services and Equipment</H3></A>

<P>Photocopying and fax services are provided by the Copy Center at the Central
Library. Self-service, coin-operated copiers are also available at the Central
Library and at all community libraries. Coin-operated typewriters are available
at the Central Library and East Lake, Franklin, North Regional, Northeast,
Sumner, and Walker Libraries. An IBM compatible personal computer for word
processing is available at the Central Library (&#36;1.50 per 15 minutes of use).
Free public access to Apple IIgs computers is available at Sumner and Hosmer.

<A NAME="lib-mtg"><H3><BR>Meeting Rooms</H3></A>

<P>Meeting rooms are available on a rental basis at most Minneapolis Public
Libraries. Call the nearest library for more information. For meeting rooms at
the Central Library, call (612) 372-6610.

<A NAME="lib-plt"><H3><BR>Planetarium, Bookshop and Homebound Service</H3></A>

<P>In addition to regular library services at the Central Library, patrons can
see a show at the Minneapolis Planetarium or purchase used books at the Friends
of the Minneapolis Public Library Book Shop. The Book Shop hours are 10-3 Monday,
Tuesday, Wednesday, and Friday; 10-7 Thursday; and 10-3:30 on Saturdays. For
Planetarium show times and ticket information, call (612) 372-6644.

<P>The Friends of the Minneapolis Public Library is a volunteer, nonprofit
organization with more than 900 members. The Friends organization operates the
Planetarium and book shop at the Central Library, provides volunteers for library
programs including service to the homebound, sponsors book and author events, and
raises funds for the library's collections and programs.

<P>Minneapolis residents who are homebound due to age, illness or disability can
request to have books delivered to them once every three weeks by a volunteer. To
receive this service, or to become a volunteer, call (612) 372-6667.

<P>

<HR>

<ADDRESS>
<P><B>Central Library</B><BR>
300 Nicollet Mall<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1992
</ADDRESS>

<P><BR><B>Phone numbers</B>
<PRE>
