<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Neighborhood Services</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Neighborhood Services"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Neighborhood Services</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P>Neighborhood Services oversees a variety of human-service programs. Most of
the human services are funded by non-City resources, such as state and federal
government and private foundations. Neighborhood Services works with <A
HREF="/departments/other/nrp.html">Neighborhood Revitalization (NRP)</A>
neighborhoods and represents the City on task forces and committees involving
human service issues.

<P>The main programs and support provided by Neighborhood Services are:

<UL>
	<LI>Chamber of Commerce's Regional Economic Development Plan
	<LI>Community Resource Program
	<LI>Community Development Block Grant
	<LI><A HREF="contract-mgmt.html">Contract Management</A>
	<LI><A HREF="housing.html">Housing Services</A>
	<LI>Jump Start
	<LI><A HREF="metp.html">Minneapolis Employment and Training</A>
	<LI>New Work Force (facilitated through the Youth Trust)
	<LI>School Human Services Redesign Initiative 
</UL>

<H3><BR>Community Resource Program</H3>

<P>The Community Resource Program (CRP) is funded by the State of Minnesota. The
City will receive approximately &#36;2 million for 1994 and 1995. Funded programs
fit into the following categories: crime, employment and training, economic
development, early intervention, and community self-help initiatives. Crime,
economic development, and community self-help initiatives are funded through an
RFP process.

<H3><BR>Jump Start</H3>

<P>Jump Start is a volunteer program offered to youth ages 11-14 to become
involved in community projects during the summer and fall. Volunteer receive
&#36;1.00 per hour for every hour they volunteer. Jump Start projects are carried
out by schools, libraries, parks, and non-profit organizations.

<P><EM><B>NOTE:</B> The Community Crime Prevention program became part of the
Police Department's Division of Community Services on January 1, 1991. See the <A
HREF="/departments/police/index.html">Police Department</A> Community Services
section for more information about CCP activities.</EM>

<P>The Minneapolis Community Action Agency became a non-profit organization,
called Community Action of Minneapolis, on January 1, 1994. For information on
Community Action of Minneapolis' services, call (612) 348-8858.

<P>

<HR>

<ADDRESS>
<P><B>Neighborhood Services</B><BR>
City Hall, Room 310 1/2<BR>
350 5 St S<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1315
</ADDRESS>

<P><BR><B>Phone Numbers</B>
<PRE>
Neighborhood Services Administration  (612) 673-2885 or
                                      (612) 673-2598
</PRE>


