<HEAD>

<TITLE>Park &amp; Recreation</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Park &amp; Recreation"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Park &amp; Recreation</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P>The Minneapolis Park and Recreation Board has six main areas of service
responsibility: planning and engineering, maintenance, forestry, horticulture,
police, and recreation.

<H3><BR>Planning and Engineering</H3>

<P>Plans, builds and maintains a system of safe, functional and aesthetically
pleasing parks, parkways and bike and foot trails. The board also owns and
maintains 44 neighborhood and community centers and other special facilities
(golf courses; indoor ice arenas; outdoor swimming pools; indoor tennis courts;
boat, buoy and canoe rack rentals; a downhill ski and tubing facility;
refreshments refectories; bird sanctuaries; a rose garden; a Japanese garden; a
wildflower garden; and a sculpture garden).

<H3><BR>Maintenance</H3>

<P>Maintains park facilities and grounds as environments that are clean, safe,
functional and aesthetically pleasing. Some examples of maintenance tasks
include: swimming pool repair, retaining wall installation, turf reseeding,
control of Eurasian milfoil and Purple Loosestrife (lake weeds), and lawn mower
maintenance.

<H3><BR>Forestry</H3>

<P>Preserves, protects, and perpetuates trees along boulevards and in parks. Some
examples of forestry tasks include: planting a variety of new trees, tree
maintenance (watering and trimming young trees), disease control, tree and stump
removal, and clean-up after storm damage.

<H3><BR>Horticulture</H3>

<P>Plants, maintains, and enhances floral gardens in neighborhood and regional
parks and along parkways; in the Lyndale Park gardens; the J.D. Rivers' 4H
Children's Garden; the Daylily/Lily Display Garden in Theodore Wirth Park; the
Minneapolis Sculpture Garden and the Eloise Butler Wildflower and Bird Sanctuary.
Provides horticultural programming (i.e. educational programs, volunteer
opportunities, naturalist programs) at many of these garden sites.

<H3><BR>Park Police</H3> 

<P>Maintain order in City parks by enforcing park rules and regulations and lend
assistance to park users. Some examples of police activities include regular
patrol of all areas of the park system, investigation of park-related offenses,
regulation and control of park-sponsored events, and presentational programs
related to park safety.

<H3><BR>Recreation</H3>

<P>Provides recreational programs and activities on a neighborhood and city-wide
basis. Programs are developed with citizen input for people of all ages,
interests, and abilities. Some examples of programs and activities include:
swimming lessons, concerts, softball leagues, neighborhood festivals, bike safety
clinics, 10K runs, day care, family weekend camp, and arts and crafts.

<P>

<HR>

<ADDRESS>
<P><B>Park and Recreation</B><BR>
Grain Exchange, Suite 200<BR>
400 4 St S<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1400
</ADDRESS>

<P><BR><B>Phone Numbers</B>
<PRE>
General Information  (612) 661-4800
Fax                  (612) 661-4777
</PRE>


