<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>Police</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Police"
-->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<P><TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP"><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" ALT="logo" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="CENTER"><H1 ALIGN=RIGHT>City of Minneapolis</H1>

<H2 ALIGN=RIGHT>Police</H2>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<!-- end include --><!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" --></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/index.html">Home</A> | <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's
Hot</A> | <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A> | <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A> | <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A> <HR ALIGN=LEFT><!-- end include --></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>Jump to <A HREF="#phones">police phone numbers</A><BR>
Looking for a <A HREF="police_patch.html">Minneapolis Police Patch</A>?</P>

<P>The Minneapolis Police Department is organized into four bureaus: the
Patrol Bureau, the Investigative Bureau, the Internal Services Bureau, and
the Community Services Bureau.</P>

<H2><BR>
Police Bureaus</H2>

<DL>
  <DT><B>Patrol Bureau</B>
  <DD>The Patrol Bureau provides general patrol and traffic law enforcement
  services. Most of the Patrol Bureau personnel are assigned to one of the
  four Minneapolis Police precinct stations, each of which is responsible
  for a sector (or precinct) of the city. Patrol duties include response
  to emergency and non-emergency requests for police service, prevention
  and deterrence of crime, offender apprehension, initial investigation and
  evidence gathering, and maintenance of order in the community. Twenty-five
  Patrol Bureau personnel are assigned exclusively to traffic law enforcement.
  Their duties include response to personal injury vehicular accidents, maintenance
  of proper traffic control and flow throughout the city, and the issuance
  of traffic violation citations to encourage compliance with existing traffic
  laws.
  <DT><BR>
  <B>Investigative Bureau</B>
  <DD>The Investigative Bureau is comprised of approximately 200 employees
  who are divided into four specific divisions: CID I, Crimes Against Persons;
  CID II, Crimes Against Property; Special Investigations Division, e.g.,
  Narcotics, Vice, Intelligence, Gang, License; and the Juvenile Division.
  <DT><BR>
  <B>Internal Services Bureau</B>
  <DD>The Internal Services Bureau is comprised of work specialists who perform
  various internal support functions for the department such as:
  <UL>
    <LI>Selection and training of personnel
    <LI>Fiscal control of departmental operations
    <LI>Maintenance of central police records
    <LI>Provision of criminal identification information
    <LI>Statistical analysis of crime trends
    <LI>Crime laboratory/criminologistics support
  </UL>
  <DT><BR>
  <B>Community Services Bureau</B>
  <DD>The Community Services Bureau includes SAFE, Crime Prevention, and
  RECAP (Repeat Complaint Address Policy). SAFE/CCP provides teams of police
  officers and crime prevention specialists to work in neighborhoods to:
  <UL>
    <LI>Strengthen community by organizing networks of residents such as block
    clubs, apartment networks, and other resident connections.
    <LI>Develop and implement crime prevention strategies with residents.
    <LI>Work with residents to solve neighborhood problems such as drug houses,
    loud parties, unsupervised problem youth, graffiti, vandalism, and problem
    families.
  </UL>
  <P>The Bureau works cooperatively with other City departments to solve
  problems at both the team level and through the Coordinated Neighborhood
  Action Plan (CNAP). A youth coordinator implements youth crime-prevention
  programs and assists teams in problem solving.
  <P>Other strategies and projects include:
  <UL>
    <LI>Personal safety workshops
    <LI>Home security demonstrations
    <LI>McGruff Safe Houses
    <LI>Mediation
    <LI>Leader training
    <LI>Crime Alert Bulletins
    <LI>Providing neighborhood-level crime statistics
  </UL>
  <P>Additionally, the bureau works with rental property owners to ensure
  well managed, problem-free buildings.
</DL>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<ADDRESS><B>Minneapolis Police Department</B><BR>
City Hall, Room 130<BR>
350 5 St S<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55415-1389</ADDRESS>

<P><BR>
<A NAME="phones"></A><B>Phone Numbers</B></P>

<PRE>To report a crime or request police assistance           <B>9-1-1</B>

Downtown Command                                         (612) 673-2655
For information, 2nd Precinct (Northeast Minneapolis)    (612) 673-5702
For information, 3rd Precinct (South Minneapolis)        (612) 673-5703
For information, 4th Precinct (North Minneapolis)        (612) 673-5704
For information, 5th Precinct (Southwest Minneapolis)    (612) 673-5705

