<H1><I><FONT COLOR="#000000">ON THE AGENDA</FONT></I></H1>

<H2><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
City of Minneapolis Actions &amp; Issues January 17, 1997</FONT></H2>

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
<BR>
<I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions of
the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. This
is Issue 8, Volume 13. Next issue will be January 31. ON THE AGENDA and
other City documents are available in alternative formats, call 673-2009.
The City provides sign language interpreting for its programs; call TTY
673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity Affirmative Action
Employer.</I></FONT></P>

<H2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
<BR>
City Clears Snow, Residents Asked to Help</FONT></H2>

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000">Minneapolis Public Works crews are working hard
to clean up after the recent snowfalls. Crews continue to clear snow from
street corners, bus stops and alleys. <BR>
<BR>
City residents are also encouraged to help. Keeping key areas of the City
clear of snow and ice helps make winter bearable.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Sidewalks</B> Remember that sidewalks around homes and businesses should
be fully cleared. This helps people move about and decreases the risk of
injury. Keep in mind that people with mobility impairments need enough space
to get around. To report unsafe sidewalks, call 673-2420.<BR>
<BR>
Community organizations provide shoveling assistance for a fee. Seniors
and persons physically unable to keep their sidewalks and garbage cart paths
in good winter condition can call 673-3004 for a referral.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Free Sand </B>City residents can pick up free sand to help them keep
sidewalks safe. The sand is available at four street maintenance yards.
They are at 18th and Jefferson St. NE, 121 Glenwood Av N, 6036 Harriet Av
S, and 4444 Snelling Av S. The sand is furnished for the private use of
residents only, not for commercial use. It is accessible outside the yard
gates 24 hours a day seven days a week. Residents must bring their own shovel
and bucket.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Garbage Carts and Fire Hydrants </B>Please help clear snow from around
fire hydrants and shovel a three-foot path around garbage carts and recycling
bins so that City crews can get to them when needed.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Potholes</B> This winter's severe weather has caused some streets to
break up. City crews are making temporary repairs to the worst potholes
and are encouraging people to drive with caution. To report dangerous potholes,
call 673-5720.</FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</P>

<H2><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
Home Tour Update</FONT></H2>

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
The 10th Minneapolis/Saint Paul Home Tour will be Saturday, May 3, and Sunday,
May 4.<BR>
<BR>
The deadline for home nominations is Friday, February 14. Owner-occupied
homes of all kinds are needed. In particular, the tour seeks nominations
from owners who are people of color or persons with disabilities, and from
owner occupants of two-, three- and four-unit structures. Although new kitchens,
baths and other renovation projects are regularly featured, homes do not
need to be extensively remodeled. Homes will be selected by mid-March. Call
673-2491 for nomination materials.<BR>
<BR>
The tour invites organizations to conduct neighborhood tours on the Home
Tour weekend. Last year's neighborhood tours of Bancroft and Old Highland
were very successful. Organizations that would like to use the Home Tour
to promote themselves to new buyers and to build neighborhood identity should
call soon. Go/no go decisions must be made by February 14. The number is
673-2009.<BR>
<BR>
Become a Friend of the Home Tour. Friends of the Home Tour is new this year.
It recognizes that REALTORS&reg;, contractors and many retail businesses
need a cost-effective way of advertising their services to Home Tour visitors.
The $200 fee covers a business-card-size ad in a flyer handed to Home Tour
visitors, a listing in a quarter-page ad in the Home Tour Guide, 100 words
on the Home Tour website and other benefits. Reservations must be made by
February 14. Call 673-3821 for more information.</FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</P>

<H2><FONT COLOR="#000000">Selected Janaury 10 City Council Actions</FONT></H2>

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
<B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT</B><BR>
- Appropriated funds for relocation of the Northern Clay Center to 2424
East Franklin and for the renovation the Free Store at 1510 East Franklin.<BR>
- Approved NRP First Step plan and funds for Folwell neighborhood and Folwell's
Early Access request for Home Improvement Program.<BR>
- Approved modifications to the Bancroft NRP Action Plan.<BR>
- Approved School Board NRP funds for the Seward neighborhood.<BR>
- Appropriated funds for the Minneapolis Youth Coordinating Board.<BR>
- Directed staff to prepare redevelopment contract with Heritage Renovation
Limited Liability Co. for redevelopment along North First Street.<BR>
<B>PUBLIC SAFETY &amp; REGULATORY SERVICES</B><BR>
- Authorized contract amendment with the Metropolitan Visiting Nurses Association
for community nursing and home health services.<BR>
- Authorized proceeding with an application for a Community-Oriented Policing
Services (COPS) More Grant that will increase department efficiency and
effectiveness with computer technology.<BR>
- Accepted $3,750,000 Federal and $750,000 State grants to be used for hiring
police officers.<BR>
- Authorized contract with Minneapolis Public Schools to provide Drug Abuse
Resistance Education (DARE) services to each 5th grade classroom with costs
to be paid by the schools.<BR>
<B>TRANSPORTATION &amp; PUBLIC WORKS</B><BR>
- Executed cooperative agreement with Hennepin County Regional Railroad
Authority and Urban Ventures Leadership Foundation for removal of 3rd Av
S and 4th Av S bridges over 29th Street railroad corridor.<BR>
- Authorized purchase and distribution of wheel kits for recycling containers
in a manner that recovers all costs from customers that order kits.<BR>
<B>WAYS &amp; MEANS/BUDGET</B><BR>
- Authorized consultant agreement to provide facilitator services to the
Convention Center Employee/Management Work Team.<BR>
- Approved homestead classification for the Chicago Avenue Co-op, 1500-02,
1504 &amp; 1508-10 Chicago Av.<BR>
- Accept funds bequeathed to the City through the estate of Marion V. Sherva
to the Organ Trust Fund.<BR>
- Accepted grant from the Minneapolis Foundation to be used to conduct management
study of Minneapolis Employment &amp; Training Program, authorized contract
University's Center for Urban &amp; Regional Affairs to conduct the study.
<BR>
- Authorized application to the National Park Service through the Metropolitan
Council for funding to be used to review area plans for conformance with
the Mississippi National River and Recreation Area Comprehensive Management
Plan.<BR>
<BR>
<I>This is partial list of Council actions. For a full list, or for details
on any action, call 673-3130. The minutes of Council meetings can be found
at http://www.finance-commerce.com. The next Council meeting begins at 9:30
a.m. January 24. Watch live on City Cable 34 or repeats Mondays, Wednesdays
and Fridays at 6 p.m.</I></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</P>

<H2><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
Open Appointments</FONT></H2>

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
Two positions are now open on the <B>Housing Board of Appeals</B>. The board
acts upon all appeals of the housing maintenance code. The board may modify,
sustain, or quash all or any portion of any order, interpretation, requirement,
decision or other determination in matters of enforcement of the housing
maintenance code and all other codes affecting existing buildings; but can
make no determination that would endanger health or safety. The board meets
the second Wednesday of January, March, May, July, September and November.
For more information call Connie Fournier, 673-5824. Application deadline
is February 7.<BR>
<BR>
The <B>Rental Dwelling License Board of Appeals</B> decides all appeals
from the Director of Inspections' recommendation to deny, not renew, revoke,
or suspend a rental dwelling license or provisional license. Members of
the seven-member board serve two-year terms. The board meets monthly or
more frequently at the call of the chair. For information call Connie Fournier,
673-5824. One position is currently vacant to fill an unexpired term of
a representative of the residential building Industry. Application deadline
is February 7.<BR>
<BR>
The <B>Metropolitan Aircraft Sound Abatement Council </B>studies aircraft
noise issues and advises on problems. The council has 33 members who serve
two-year terms. For more information, call Perry Thorvig at 673-2036. There
are six regular and two alternate positions vacant. Applications are due
January 24.<BR>
<BR>
<I>Call the City Clerk, 673-2735, for application materials. Appointees
must be residents unless otherwise noted or unless exempted by Council action.</I></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<BR>
</P>

<H2><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
Charter Commission Requests Proposals</FONT></H2>

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
<BR>
January 17, 1997<BR>
<BR>
Dear Citizens,<BR>
<BR>
The Minneapolis Charter Commission is the body charged with making structural
changes and improvements in how City government works. The commission has
the power to recommend that such changes, in the form of proposed charter
amendments, be placed on the ballot. Proposals can come from citizens, from
Charter Commission members themselves, and from elected officials and their
staffs.<BR>
<BR>
The Charter Commission would like to have your input in determining what
changes should be put to the voters. We encourage you to submit your proposals
and ideas for making city government work better to the Charter Commission
in care of the City Clerk, 350 South 5th St, Room 304, Minneapolis, MN 55415-1382,
or fax to 673-3812. We ask that you submit your proposal in writing no later
than May 23, 1997, accompanied by specific language for the proposed change(s)
to the Charter. The Charter Commission will then review the proposals at
its regular monthly meetings, hold public hearings and decidein August whether
to place proposals on the ballot.<BR>
<BR>
If you are an officer or staff person for a community organization, please
take the time to present this letter at your next community meeting. If
you have questions about the charter or the process outlined in this letter,
please contact me at 521-7840 (home phone), 2514 Vincent Av N, Minneapolis,
MN 55411-1715.<BR>
<BR>
Sincerely,<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Mark Masica<BR>
Chair, Minneapolis Charter Commission</FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</P>

<H2><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
<BR>
City Cable 34 Highlights</FONT></H2>

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
- On the current edition of City Beat, host Kent Robbins talks with Fred
Neet of the Planning Department about riverfront development and Ken Dahl
of Employment and Training about summer youth employment. City Beat airs
Tuesdays at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 8:30 p.m., and Saturdays at 7:30 p.m.<BR>
<BR>
- The Department of Civil Rights' 1997 Dr. Martin Luther King ceremony will
air at 5 p.m. Tuesday, January 21, and at 5 p.m. Monday, January 27. </FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</P>

<H2><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
Planning Commission</FONT></H2>

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
The Minneapolis Planning Commission will hold a public hearing at 4:30 p.m.
Wednesday, January 22, in room 317 City Hall to consider a rezoning at 4821-23
Chicago Av S to allow use as office space.<BR>
<BR>
The Commission will hold a public hearing at 4:30 p.m. Wednesday, February
5, in room 317 City Hall to consider the following items:<BR>
- Minor subdivision at 3741 and 3751 17th Av S by St. Luke's Evangelical
Lutheran Congregation<BR>
- Conditional use permit to permit a wholesale food processor selling fresh
fruits and vegetables to food service venders at 1505 W Broadway.<BR>
- Conditional use permit for a 24-hour child care facility serving 40 children
in the day and up to 40 children in the evening 2304 at Emerson Av N.<BR>
- Change of a nonconforming use at 4255 3rd Av S to permit an increase in
the maximum number of children from 18 to 21 in the existing crisis nursery
providing overnight shelter for children from infants to 6 years of age.<BR>
- Change of nonconforming use at 616 3rd St S to permit assembly of materials
and warehousing.<BR>
For information call 673-5836.</FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</P>

