<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN"><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>MIAR Fall 1995 Newsletter</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#ffffff"><H1 ALIGN=center><IMG SRC="miar.gif" ALT="MIAR logo" ALIGN="bottom"><BR>City of Minneapolis<BR><I>Fall 1995 Newsletter</I></H1><H3><A NAME="TOC">Table of Contents</A></H3><H4><A HREF="#HARMONY">A Year of Harmony in a World of Difference</A><BR><A HREF="#ISMAILI">The Ismaili Muslim Community Responds to The Year of Harmony</A><BR><A HREF="#UPDATES">Task Force Updates</A><BR><A HREF="#KICKOFF">Year of Harmony-Diversity in a World of Difference Kick Off</A><BR><A HREF="#MOREACTIVITIES">Additional Diversity Month Activities</A><BR><A HREF="#URBANINIT">The Urban Initiative Program</A><BR><A HREF="#VOTEREG">Voting as an Initiative Against Racism</A><BR><A HREF="#TOJOIN">To Join a Task Force...</A></H4><HR><H3></H3><H1><A NAME="HARMONY">A Year Of Harmony in a World of Difference</A></H1><P><B>with The Honorable Emanuel Cleaver, II, Mayor, Kansas City Missouri</B><P><I>by Rev. Barbara Fountain Mason, Interfaith Task Force Co-Chair</I><P>There is an incredible gong to the tune of destruction, devastation anddiscord in the cities of our Nation. Nights are filled with pain,misunderstanding and uncertainty while people of good will work towards a bettertomorrow. Consequences of the discord are senseless acts of violence, echoingdissonance in our communities. We listen for peace and harmony only to hear andsee more discontent, deaths of our young, violent acts against the elderly, anddissolution of family structure.<P>Well, be of good cheer! There is good news! Discord can be turned to harmony.The Interfaith Task Force has accepted the challenge of Mayor Sayles Belton towork toward eliminating negative acts of violence in the City of Minneapolis. Wehave chosen to do this by celebrating the year 1995 as A Year Of Harmony withspecial guests and challenging workshops during our Diversity Month, October 22ndto November 22nd.<P>Our kick-off speaker for this month is a well known peacemaker and prophet. Heis the Honorable Emanuel Cleaver, II, Mayor of Kansas City, Missouri, co-founderof Harmony in a World of Difference, and pastor of St. James United MethodistChurch in Kansas City.<P>All too often, in our quest to seek peace and pursue it, we need skills andresources to accomplish our desires. Harmony, Shalom, Peace is desirable to mosthuman beings, though our interpretations of these words may differ, our goal isthe same.<P>We are not the only city that has struggled with the hard issues of violence,racism and conflict. The City of Kansas City faced these issues. Mayor Cleaverwas inspired to organize Harmony, a program which is aimed at improving racerelations, reducing prejudice and increasing cultural awareness.<P>Harmony in a World of Difference had its roots in the City Council in KansasCity, as does the Minneapolis Initiative Against Racism (MIAR) has its roots inthe Minneapolis City Council. Founders were Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton andCommissioner Sandra Hilary when they were City Council members.<P>The Kansas City Council ranked race relations as a top priority and set out toaddress this problem through the leadership of then Councilman Cleaver. Hedeveloped the Harmony covenants/voluntary agreement concept. The City endorsed itand provided seed money. Community leaders worked with the Anti-Defamation Leagueeducation program which began in Boston called A World of Difference. The twoconcepts were combined and the idea of Harmony in a world of difference emerged.<P>The initial project had four components: alliance, education, media, and taskforces. The task forces, like ours, covered a variety of sectors of the city suchas: financial, labor, real estate, economic development, media, education, lawand justice, religion, and intergroup dialogue. The project has grown andcontinues to work diligently to meet community needs.<P>The Honorable Emanuel Cleaver is the 51st Mayor of Kansas City and in 1991,became the first African American elected to the Citys highest office. He has along history of civic and community activism. Some of his accomplishments are ineconomic development, public safety (spearheading the community policing concept,and other neighborhood innovative programs), along with capital improvement.Since being elected Mayor, he has received many outstanding awards andrecognition. He and his wife Dianne have four children.<P>We cordially and very enthusiastically invite the community, civic andbusiness leaders, the faith community, one and all to come hear this greatspeaker and help us in Celebrating a Year Of Harmony in a World of DifferenceParticipate in the Kick Off Interfaith Celebration on October 24 and theConference on October 25th. Look for more details in this newsletter.<P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table of Contents)</A><HR><H3><A NAME="ISMAILI">The Ismaili Muslim Community Responds to The Year of Harmony</A></H3><P><I>by Naseem Kassim, Interfaith Task Force Member</I><P>The Ismaili Muslim Community of the Twin Cities had planned to organize andimplement some community service projects as part of their contribution for theYear of Harmony using volunteers from the Ismaili communities as well as otherfaith communities.<P>The objectives were to get the community to become actively involved inprojects whereby they would get to know other communities, aware of the needs ofthe less advantaged and less fortunate in the community at large, and to get thevolunteers to realize the importance and worth of their contribution.<P>The goal was also to plan on activities that would be easy to implement,require essentially nothing but the volunteers time, and develop a schedule thatwould not be taxing on the volunteers time commitment. It was decided that someof these activities would be one time events while others could be ongoingactivities, even after the year ended.<P>With these goals in mind, the following projects were initiated: Food Drive(ongoing), Volunteering at a nursing home in Roseville (once a month),Volunteering at the Food Banks Product Recovery and Preboxing programs (once amonth), Volunteering at the Soup Kitchen (one event completed, one in theplanning stage with youths from the Jewish community), and Volunteers to sign upfor training to teach English to refugees through UCAM.<P>For the upcoming events, the community also hopes to participate in activatesplanned for the Diversity month and the Youth Recognition Event. Along with theSuni Muslims, we hope to help the Bosnian refugees find work and employment.<P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table of Contents)</A><HR><H3><A NAME="UPDATES">Task Force Updates</A></H3><P>September 1994<P><EM><B>Note:</B> In past MIAR newsletters, goals for each Task Force have beenlisted. We have left them off this time to make room for our numerous resourcesand events for Diversity Month. If you would like to receive a copy that includesthe goals, call Cathy Polanski at 730-6256.</EM><H4>Youth</H4><P><I>Terra Cole, Chair</I><BR>The Task Force held its last school year meeting honoring its graduating seniorson Saturday, June 10. Meetings will begin in the fall.<P><B>Next Meetings:</B><BR>Recruitment in September. No schedule set yet. Contact Cathy Polanski 730-6256.<H4>Government</H4><P><I>Emily Ero-Phillips, Chair</I><BR>Final survey results were distributed to all City boards and commissions.Preliminary results were reviewed at the June meeting. In September, they willbegin to invite the chairs of the various boards and commissions to talk abouttheir recruiting efforts toward people of color.<P><B>Next Meetings:</B><BR>All meetings will begin at 3:30 p.m., and will be held in Room 220 City Hall.October 3; November 6; December 5. Contact Emily Ero-Phillips at 661-4875.<H4>Education</H4><P><I>David Tilson, Chair</I><BR>The Task force reviewed the success of the Youth Serving Organizations Conferenceheld on July 25, 1995 in the afternoon. They also reviewed its goals. A TaskForce representative is continuing to serve as support to the seven identifiedschool sites for the Public Schools Initiative Against Racism which did not meetin the summer.<P><B>Next Meetings:</B><BR>The Task Force meets every second Thursday at Anderson. Contact David Tilsen at221-4465.<H4>Civic and Arts</H4><P><I>Lyle Wray, Co-Chair</I><BR>The short performance developed by Illusion Theater and the Task Force on racismin civic and other non-profit organizations has not yet been performed. The piecewas to be made available to organizations for their annual meetings and otherevents. It will be performed on November 16 as a collaboration with theInterfaith Task Force Diversity month.<P><B>Next Meeting:</B><BR>Contact Lyle Wray at 338-0791.<H4>Media</H4><P><I>Robb Randle and Gail Rubin, Co-Chairs</I><BR>The Media Task Force continues to hold media round table discussions. The groupis working on a Community of Color Resource Directory. The members will beworking individually to recruit profiles for their directory. Letters werewritten to the media commending them on their coverage of the Indigenous gamesand the NAACP convention.<P><B>Next Meeting:</B><BR>Meets the 3rd Tuesday of each month, 12:30 p.m., at the Greater MinneapolisConvention and Visitors Association, 40th Floor, City Center, 33 South 6thStreet. Contact Gail Rubin, 797-5004.<H4>Economic</H4><P><I>Leon Rice, Mary Crowley Co-Chairs</I><BR>The group is working to expand the mural project. Staff is exploring ways toinclude winning art pieces from a Juneteenth art contest. The Credit Union in thePhillips Neighborhood is becoming a reality. The September meeting was dedicatedto discussing a funded staff position for networking. Metropolitan Councilmembers gave a presentation at that meeting.<P><B>Next Meeting:</B><BR>Noon, October 3. (Meets first Tuesday of the month). AIOIC, corner of Cedar andFranklin. Contact Cathy Polanski 730-6256.<H4>Housing</H4><P><I>Diana Buckanaga and Jose Cervantes, Co-Chairs</I><BR>A Fair Housing curriculum will be developed by and for youth to present in highschools. The Youth Task Force has been informed of this project and will workwith members on this project. The grant to fund this project was rejected by theHeadwaters Foundation. The group will be seeking alternative funding.<P><B>Next Meeting:</B><BR>Noon, the second Tuesday of the month, South Side Neighborhood Housing, 3137Chicago Ave. South. Contact Cathy Polanski 730-6256.<H4>Human Services</H4><P><I>Charlene Cole and Barry Cohen, Co-Chairs</I><BR>Human Services has three separate task forces. They are: a) Training-arrangetraining event and develop a Speakers Bureau; b) Networking and Support. Thisgroup would focus on people doing anti-racism work and also on people of colorwho are the only ones at their work place; and c) Action Group. Promote andassist agencies to develop and implement plans to deal with racism.<P><B>Next Meeting:</B><BR>Contact Barry Cohen 340-7400.<H4>Interfaith</H4><P><I>Barbara Fountain Mason and David Sterling, Co-Chairs</I><BR>The Task force is sponsoring a YEAR OF HARMONY in 1995. The group agreed to workon the following in 1995: 1.) Get the Ministerial Alliance involved; 2.)Improvepolice/community relations and climate; 3.) Faith community adoption of thePrinciples; 4.) Diversity Month; 5.) Kansas City Mayor; 6.) Youth recognition forthe Year of Harmony.<P><B>Next Meeting:</B><BR>Meets 4th Tuesday of the month, Temple Israel, 24th and Hennepin. Contact CathyPolanski 730-6256.<P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table of Contents)</A><HR><H3><A NAME="KICKOFF">Year of Harmony-Diversity in a World of Difference Kick Off</A></H3><P><I>October 24 &amp; 25, 1995</I><P><B>Central Lutheran Church</B><BR>333 12 St S, Minneapolis<BR>(Free parking in lots marked for Central Lutheran Church)<P><B>INTERFAITH CELEBRATION</B><I>October 24, 7:00-8:30P.M.</I><UL>	<LI>American Indian Drum Group	<LI>Community Choir	<LI>Shruti: Interfaith Presentation	<LI>Message by the Honorable Emanuel Cleaver, II, Mayor, Kansas City, MO.</UL><P><B>CONFERENCE</B><BR><I>October 25, 9:00A.M.-3:30P.M.</I><P>9:00-9:30<BR>Challenges, Choices and Change: Shaping a Vision for Our Diverse Population - Dr.Gonzales<P>9:30-11:30<BR><B>WORKSHOPS</B><OL type="A" SEQNUM="A" START="A">	<LI>Motivating Defeated Learners: Cultural Diversity Today - Dr. Gonzales	<LI>Differences Between Buddhism and Christianity - Sova Miev	<LI>Dealing With Anti-Immigrant Bias - World of Difference Staff	<LI>Study Circles on Race Relations - Martha McCoy	<LI>The Interfaith Movement and Racial Harmony - David Sterling</OL><P>11:30-12:30<BR><B>RESOURCES, LUNCH AND YOUTH AWARDS</B><P>12:30<BR><B>KEY NOTE ADDRESS BY MAYOR CLEAVER</B><P>1:30-3:00<BR><B>WORKSHOPS</B><OL type="A" SEQNUM="F" START="F">	<LI>Coming Together: The Bibles Message in an Age of Diversity - Curtiss DeYoung	<LI>Institute for Healing Racism - Scott Antilla, Jean Wright	<LI>Healing Hearts and Weaving Hope: Stories for Peacemaking - Jerry Blue	<LI>Understanding American Indian Spirituality - John Poupart	<LI>Islam and Christianity: Similarities/Differences - Matthew Ramandan	<LI>Combating Racism - World of Difference Staff</OL><P>3:00-3:30<BR>Sathya Baba Singing Group<BR><P>COST: October 24th: No Charge<BR>October 25th: $10.00<BR>Scholarships available.<P>Call Cathy Polanski at 730-6256 for more information.<P>Circle one workshop in the A.M. and one in the P.M. The deadline forregistration is October 19! Space is limited. Register early.<PRE>I will attend October 24 __  October 25 __  Both days __Total enclosed $10.00Name ____________________________________________Address _________________________________________Phone __________________   FAX __________________Make checks out to: Little Flock Community of Faith ChurchMail to:Att. Rev. Mason/Harmony, Little Flock Community of Faith Church128 33 St WMinneapolis, MN 55408</PRE><P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table of Contents)</A><HR><H2><A NAME="MOREACTIVITIES">Additional Diversity Month Activities</A></H2><H4>The New Board Member</H4><P><I>November 16, 3:30-5:00P.M</I><BR>Illusion Theater, 528 Hennepin Ave.<P>This play was written by Kim Hines and Michael Robins in collaboration withthe Illusion Theater for the MIAR. It deals with the hard issues and realitiesfaced by boards when they make the decision to become more diverse. Come and joinus for the first showing of this insightful work.<P>Bring your business card and throw it in the hat for a chance to win a freeshowing of this very play at your office for your board and staff. A briefreception will follow in the lobby.<P>This presentation is co-sponsored by the MIAR Civic and Arts Task Force andthe MIAR Inter Faith Task Force.<P>Call Cathy Polanski at 730-6256 to reserve your FREE tickets. Call soon, spacewill be limited.<H4>The Bahai Vision</H4><P><I>Submitted by David Sterling, Interfaith Task Force Co-Chair</I><P>This Cable TV series will air several Unity in Diversity video titles duringthe MIAR Diversity Month: Unity of Races, Unity of Nations, Unity of East andWest and Unity Without Uniformity. Consult your community cable access listingsfor scheduled days and times.<H4>Understanding and Dismantling Racism</H4><P><I>Submitted by James Addington, Interfaith Task Force Member</I><BR>October 27-29, Totino-Grace Renewal Center, Fridley<P>This workshop is for religious and community leaders, youth organizers etc. Itis especially relevant for local religious groups and organizations facing thechallenges of effective ministry and service in a dynamic multicultural context.Participants will explore the roots of racism, its systemic expression, andpractical dismantling strategies. Sponsored by Minnesota Churches Anti-RacismInitiative. James and Nadine Addington, Interfaith Task Force members, will befacilitating this workshop. For information contact Tri-council CoordinatingCommission, (612) 871-0229. 122 Franklin Av W, Room 100, Minneapolis, MN 55404.<P>The following list is a partial compilation of activities dealing with racism,racial and ethnic cultural diversity in the Twin Cities area.<P>Information reflects information each organization submitted to MIAR.Therefore, it is up to the discretion of newsletter readers to determine theworth of the material individually.<H3>WORKSHOPS, TRAINING AND SEMINARS</H3><H4>League of Minnesota Human Rights Commissions 24th Annual Conference</H4><P><I>September 23, 1995 (Saturday), 8:30 a.m.-4:00 p.m.</I><P>The conference will be held at Northwestern College, 3003 Snelling Av N inRoseville. Registration is $45.00 and includes lunch, coffee and workshops. Makechecks payable to LMHRC and mail to: Jane McPartland Treasurer, 1820 10 Av S#8, St. Cloud, MN 56301<H4>One Week Without Violence</H4><P><I>October 16-October 20</I><P>The Minneapolis YWCA sponsors a public education campaign to challenge peopleto imagine a world without violence and to work together to create strategies forchange. Each day is dedicated to an aspect of anti-violence. The theme on the20th will be fighting racism. For complete schedule call 332-0501, ext. 3137.<H4>Educational Empowerment of Minority Youth: Perspectives for the 21stCentury</H4><P><I>October 24-October 25</I><P>This conference will examine how formal, informal, and non-formal educationcan help minority youth to take leadership positions during the coming century.The conference will define new roles and responsibilities for emerging leaders inthe minority community and will assess how institutions can best assist youngpeople to prepare for these roles and responsibilities. Brooklyn College of theCity University of New York. Call Prof. Willis Butler, (718) 951-5931.<P>Race and Religion will be the topic of discussion at the November meeting ofthe Twin Cities chapter of the Parliament of the Worlds Religions. The discussionwill be based on the class by that title offered by Nantawan Lewis atMetropolitan State University this fall. Phone 771-6933 or 861-6040 after October5th for date and place. This is an open forum.<H4>Looking for Trouble: A conference on Violence Prevention and CommunityBuilding</H4><P><I>November 3-November 4</I><P>This conference is sponsored by the MN Jung Association and MASC (MinnesotansActively Seeking Community). The conference will bring together people from manydifferent communities (ethnic, professional treatment, neighborhood, artistic) toexamine the roots and possible transformation of violent behavior.Andrew-Riverside Presbyterian Church 729 South East Fourth Street, Minneapolis623-3982.<H4>Multiracial Family Conference and Celebration</H4><P><I>November 3-November 5</I><P>This conference is designed to provide a community forum of education andsupport for a broad spectrum of multiracial families, individuals and familyservice professionals. Focus on the celebration of rich differences andsimilarities while embracing many contributions to the community. Sponsored bythe Hiawatha YMCA. First Universalist Church. Call Barbara Jones, 729-7397.<H4>Revitalizing Democracy through Multicultural Education Policies, Strategiesand Action</H4><P><I>November 6-10, 1996</I><P>The Twin Cities is host for the 1996 National Association for MulticulturalEducation Conference. Call Bob Crumpton, 296-2703.<H4>Undoing Racism Workshops</H4><P><I>November 9-10</I><BR><P>Intensive 2 1/2-day workshops enable participants to understand how racism hasbecome part of our society and what we can do to eliminate it in our personal andcommunity lives. Workshops are open to community organizers, peace and socialjustice activists, religious leaders, social workers, educators, etc. CallJuanita Pekay at Pillsbury Neighborhood Services, 529-9231, Ext. 139.<H4>Keeping Our Promise to Our Children</H4><P><I>Tuesday, November 14th. 7:00-9:00 p.m</I><P>Dr. James P. Comer, renowned author of Raising Black Children, MaggiesAmerican Dream and School Power will be held at the Basilica of Saint Mary,Hennepin at 16th, Downtown Minneapolis. Cost is $5.00. To register call 939-0396,extension 500.<H4>Family in Community; Preparing Families for a Global Community</H4><P><I>November 15, 1995. 8:00 a.m.-4:30 p.m.</I><P>A workshop designed to strengthen our abilities to build community inpartnership with children and their families. Featuring: James P. Comer, M.D.,Families, Schools and Children. Author of Maggies American Dream, School Powerand Raising Black Children. Eleanor Lynch, Ph. D. Cross Cultural Competence: APrerequisite to Family-Focused Services. Josepha Campinha-Bacote, Ph. D., RN, CS,CTN Culturally Competent Services: What Are They? Sheraton Park Place, St. LouisPark, MN.<P><B>Minneapolis Community College</B><BR><I>Friday November 17, 9am-4pm</I><P>Communicating and working with people of different cultural backgrounds, aprocess approach to cross-cultural communication issues will be offered at MCC atHarmon Place 1501 Hennepin Avenue, Minneapolis.<P>A World of Difference Institute. AWOD has developed a new workshop addressingthe topic of combating anti-immigrant attitudes. This workshop is relevant foryouth service groups, civic groups, church groups or parent/teacher associations.The session includes information about the immigrant experiences that counteractsmisinformation and stereotyping. The video Minnesota Pride Minnesota Prejudicegives an extraordinary look at the immigrant experience in Minnesota, both pastand present. Call Linda Loverude, 388-7816. This workshop will be presented onOctober 25th at the Diversity Month Kick off.<H4>Extension Classes at the University of Minnesota</H4><P>Multiculturalism Extension classes will be held at the University ofMinnesota. Some examples are: Urban Indian Communities (spring) Chicano History1900-Present (fall); Cross-Cultural Child Development (winter); The Holocaust(fall); Politics of Ethnic Communities (spring); and Women, Race, and Class(spring). For the multiculturalism brochure that lists exciting, stimulatinglearning opportunities through University Extension Classes, call 624-0029. (Youdo not have to be in a degree program to enroll in Extension classes.)<H4>Television programs</H4><P><B>Channel 2</B><BR>Sunday Nov. 12, 11pm-12am Song Journey (Native American powwow) and 12am-1amStories of the Horse (traditional Lakota, Dakota, and Nakota culture)<BR>Tuesday, Nov. 15, 7-10pm, Sat. Nov. 18, 9-11pm Sun. Nov. 19, 1-4pm Hoop Dreams:Nationally acclaimed documentary Sunday Nov. 19 10-10:30pm MNTV: Identity Part 1:Local film makers examine their ethnic and personal identities<BR> Monday, Nov.20, 9-10pm The American Experience: Last Stand at Little Big Horn<BR><P><B>Channel 17</B><BR>On-going<BR>Wednesdays at 6:30pm<BR>Tony Browns Journal Current Events from an African American perspective.<BR>Wednesdays 8pm and Fridays at 5:30pm<BR>Kev Koom Siab: Hmong Issues<BR>Wed. Oct. 25 &amp; Nov. 1, 7-8pm<BR>Flight to Freedom (underground railroad)<BR>Thurs. Oct. 26, Nov. 2,9&amp;16 8:30-9pm<BR>The Color of Money: business stories of interest to people of color<BR>Wed. Nov. 1, 10-11pm<BR>Bhutan: A Himalayan Cultural Diary<BR>Wed. Nov. 8, 7-8pm<BR>Snowbird Cherokees<BR>Wed. Nov. 15, 7-8pm<BR>Filipino Americans: Discovering Their Past<BR>Wed. Nov. 15 &amp; Nov. 22, 9:30-10pm<BR>Heritage: Hispanic contributions.<BR>Wed. Nov. 22, 7-8pm<BR>Indian America: A Gift From the Past<BR><P><B>Cable TV</B><BR>(see Diversity Week Activities listed in this issue)<H3>UPCOMING EVENTS</H3><H4>Big White Fog</H4><P>by Theodore Ward. Directed by Lou Bellamy<BR><I>Sept. 22-Nov.