ave beendeveloped by the League of Minnesota Human Rights Commissions. Each is 14 1/2 x21 1/2 inches, and deals with such issues as the richness of Minnesotas ethnicdiversity, disability discrimination, sexual orientation discrimination, andsexual harassment discrimination. The posters are available at the followingcosts: $4.00 each, or in quantities (sets of four dealing with the above themes).Costs quoted include postage, handling and shipping. For further information,please call Mort Ryweck at 612-376-0525 or 612-535-1051.<H4>Race, Rage and Family</H4><P>A special one-time edition of Parenting Magazine published by Time PublishingVentures, Inc. 301 Howard Street, 17th Floor, San Francisco CA 94105. For moreinformation call 415-546-7575.<P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table of Contents)</A><HR><H3><A NAME="URBANINIT">The Economic Task Force Helps Get The Word Out About TheUrban Initiative Program</A></H3><P><I>Submitted by Dave Chapman, Economic Task Force Member</I><P>The Urban Initiative program was created in 1993 by Minnesotas Governor andLegislature to provide loans to minority-owned businesses in low income areas ofthe Twin Cities. The program will help these companies establish themselves,expand and provide jobs in their communities. This program is intended to financebusinesses that can demonstrate their potential for success.<P>The loan program is available to new or existing businesses in Minneapolis,St. Paul, Columbia Heights, Hilltop, Hopkins, Lauderdale Mendota, South St. Paul,St. Anthony, and West St. Paul.<P>Loan funds may be used for normal business expenses such as machinery andequipment, inventory and receivables, working capital, new construction,renovation and site acquisition. Funds cannot be used for financing existingdebt.<P>Businesses may apply for loans between $10,000 and $300,000 Interest rates areset by negotiation between the non-profit agency and each individual business,and will range between 2% and 10%. Terms and conditions of each loan arenegotiable.<P>Funds are awarded by the Urban Initiative Board to qualified local non-profitagencies. The agencies, in turn, review loan applications and make loans toindividual businesses. The non-profit groups also offer businesses a variety ofmanagement and technical assistance, including analyzing financial and managementneeds and linking businesses with training opportunities for employees.<P>The entire application and loan process is managed by qualified localnonprofit agencies. Several organizations have been selected to receive theinitial funds, and more will be awarded in coming months. To find out whichagency serves your business or area of the Twin Cities, call Bart Bevins,297-1170, if you are located in Ramsey, Anoka or Dakota counties or call StewartMcMullan, 297-3548, if you are located in Hennepin county. Both are on the staffof the Minnesota Department of Trade and Economic Development and can help inmatching up with the right organization or identifying other sources of businessdevelopment assistance.<P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table of Contents)</A><HR><H3><A NAME="VOTEREG">Voter Registration and Voting as an Initiative AgainstRacism</A></H3><P>In the past two elections, the discrepancy between the number of inner-cityvoters and the number of suburban voters has widened. In 1992, the top suburbandistrict, Edina, voted almost triple that of the lowest turnout district, NorthMinneapolis. If we compare the top ten turnout districts (mostly suburban) withthe bottom ten turnout districts (mostly inner city), we see almost a two-to-oneratio in participation, a difference of 90,000 votes. In 1994, we see similardifferences with much lower turnouts in the inner city districts. All the voicesin our society need to be heard! It is time we concentrate on an effort toregister voters in the lower voter participation communities of the cities ofMinneapolis and St. Paul. Let all voices be heard! For information to involveyourself in efforts to register voters, contact ProPAC.<P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table of Contents)</A><HR><H3><A NAME="WORKSHOP">Spring Workshop held by the Human Services TaskForce</A></H3><P><I>by Barry B. Cohenz</I><P>On March 24, 1995 the Human Services Task Force brought together over 200 human service providers and vendors at the International Institute of Minnesota for a half day workshop entitled FROM THE PEOPLE.<BR><P>FROM THE PEOPLE offered providers first hand insights about racism andcultural insensitivity from testimonials of peers and clients of cultures otherthan their own. In break-out group discussions they then discussed how they couldcombat racism in their own agencies. In their program materials, participantsreceived the MIAR Principles of Conduct and other MIAR literature, were invitedto sign our pledge and put their names on our mailing list. Sixty participantssigned up! Participants also had an opportunity to purchase food, clothing, artand artifacts of different cultures offered by a half dozen vendors. Evaluationswere highly positive and interest in a continuing series was overwhelming.<P>This workshop would not have been possible without the hard work of our MarchEvent Sub-Committee. On behalf of the Task Force, our sincere THANK YOU for a jobwell done to: Carol Arthur, Domestic Abuse Project Connie Bell, G.M.D.C.A.; MaryMcGurran, Ebenezer Community Services Michele Shaw, Employment Action Center;Loretta Strong-Thompson Ebenezer Community Services.<P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table of Contents)</A><HR><H3><A NAME="TOJOIN">Working Toward the Elimination of Racism in the City ofMinneapolis</A></H3><P><B>To help, join a Task Force:</B><UL>	<LI><B>Interfaith</B>	<LI><B>Education</B>	<LI><B>Media</B>	<LI><B>Youth</B>	<LI><B>Human Services</B>	<LI><B>Government</B>	<LI><B>Economic</B>	<LI><B>Civic and Arts</B>	<LI><B>Housing</B></UL><P>Call Cathy Polanski at 730-6256<P><A HREF="#TOC">(Table 