<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Minneapolis '97 Budget Framework</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#010041"><H1><CENTER><IMG SRC="sharon.gif" WIDTH="184" HEIGHT="240" ALIGN="RIGHT"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALT="Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton" BORDER="1">A BudgetFramework for a Safe City </CENTER></H1><H2><CENTER><BR>Presented by Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton<BR>to the Minneapolis City Council </CENTER></H2><H4><CENTER>August 6, 1996</CENTER></H4><P><CENTER></CENTER><P>President Cherryhomes, City Council Members, members of the IndependentBoards, City staff, and citizens of Minneapolis, good morning. I am pleasedto present a framework for City Department Heads to follow in developingtheir 1997 budget proposals. It reflects the collaborative budget processI have established with the City Council. This is the second year we haveworked with our new budget process, and I believe our focus, collaboration,and quality of our decision-making are improving as a result. You may rememberlast year we reached consensus on all major policy issues, and our onlysubstantial disagreements were on how to spend about $450,000, or abouttwo-tenths of one percent of our tax-supported budget. <BR><BR>I thank you for your participation and cooperation, and especially thankthe Department Heads for their unprecedented efforts to look beyond departmentallines to meet City-wide challenges. <BR><BR>Last year our budget strategy was successful in several ways. Faced withshrinking resources and the need to cut costs, we found ways to reorganize,consolidate and streamline, enabling us to save money and manage our citybetter. We were able to do this with minimal disruption to employees. Meanwhile,we continued to merit a Triple A bond rating - saving $3 million a yearin interest the city would otherwise have to pay on its bonds - the equivalentof a five percent increase in property taxes. <BR><BR>This year, the City continues to face the same financial pressures, causedto a great extent by the federal deficit, which tripled during the 1980s.Today, 15 percent of total federal outlays are for interest payments. Congressis responding to the deficit, not with broadly distributed belt-tighteningmeasures, but with what it calls &quot;devolution&quot; - drastic cuts ingrants to cities and states. Our State's deficit is expected to grow about$3.2 billion in the next six years as a result of devolution, and thesecuts will be passed on to the cities and towns of Minnesota. These federalreductions transfer the responsibility of reducing the federal deficit tostate and local taxpayers. The burden falls particularly hard on cities,which traditionally provide the economic, social and cultural infrastructurefor citizens of their regions and states. <BR><BR>For the last five years Minneapolis has experienced a decline in our taxbase, causing us to defer certain obligations. Now that our tax base isstabilizing, it is time to face up to them. Here are some challenges wemust meet in the near future: <MENU>Next year we must begin to fully fund the cost of self-insurance,instead of borrowing money to pay for it. <BR><BR>In 1998, we must begin to pay the full cost of the &quot;Clinton Cops&quot;program, which has been heavily subsidized in its first three years. <BR><BR>We must make significant repairs and improvements in our roads and bridges.<BR>As I indicated in my last budget address, we must make major improvementsin our water system that will cost hundreds of millions of dollars. Thereis a story in the August issue of Mpls-St. Paul magazine on the status ofour water facility, which I urge you to read to appreciate the significanceof this issue. Unfortunately, the author of this otherwise excellent storyappears to be under the impression that we have been keeping the need fora capital program for the water system some sort of secret; so what I urge<I>him</I> to read is my last year's budget address! <BR><BR><BR>Over the next several years we must also find a way to reduce commercialand industrial taxes. We must be sensitive to the fact that as downtownrecovers from the depressed commercial tax base, taxes will continue torise. A recent climate study suggests that so far taxes have not discouragedbusiness. But just this weekend I received the preliminary results of MCDA'ssurvey of what I call our &quot;horizon&quot; industries - the industriesthat will lead our economy in coming years. One in five respondents saidthey may move within two years, and those considering leaving Minneapolisgave taxes as their number-one reason, with crime not far behind. Thereis little doubt that as businesses become more cost-sensitive, high taxrates will discourage future growth. However, the method we choose to reducebusiness taxes must not interfere with the community's ability to fund ourpublic schools, nor can it result in painful property tax increases forresidents. Working together, we must find a solution that will benefit the<I>entire</I> community. </MENU><BR>Even though we cannot address all these challenges next year, we must continueto prepare for them by careful planning, living within our means and conscientiousstewardship of our resources. It would be far easier to continue to do businessas usual, and leave these problems to our successors. However, our successorsare our children, and the problems we leave them will, by that time, benearly insurmountable. <BR><BR>Fortunately, Minneapolis is better prepared than many communities to meetpresent and future needs, even in the context of the federal funding changes.This is because we prepared for them for the last two years with tough budgetsand creative redesigns. We protected citizens from drastic service cutsand higher taxes, and city employees from sweeping layoffs. <BR><BR>The framework I propose today is just as tough and creative. It describesthe path for again accomplishing our priority goals - <I>without increasingthe City's property tax rate</I>. <BR><BR>Now I will highlight some of the proposals I am instructing department headsto address as they submit their budget plans. I will begin with what I knowwe all agree must be our top priority in 1997: public safety. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Public Safety</H3>I know we all agree the top priority for Minneapolis in 1997 is public safety.It is an outrage that in the City of Minneapolis there are schools wheregunshots ring out, parks where drugs are dealt, and streets where a mothercan be murdered taking her children to buy an ice cream cone. This is notthe Minneapolis our citizens deserve, it is not the Minneapolis our childrendeserve, and I am determined that <I>this will not b</I>e the Minneapoliswe pass on to them. <BR><BR>Last year I called for unprecedented investments in public safety. Theseinvestments allowed us to raise our authorized police strength to an all-timehigh of 914 officers, and purchase $2.4 million dollars' worth of squadcars and police equipment. <BR><BR>But simply assigning more police officers to the streets is not the answer.We must fight crime the same way a general fights a war: by holding ourground, preventing all incursions, and denying the enemy a foothold. Wemust stop criminals at the very gateway to crime. We must stop them on thesidewalk where they are dealing drugs, at the doorway of the houses of prostitution,in the homes where domestic violence terrorizes innocent women and children.We must stop them as they carry illegal firearms, sell alcohol and tobaccoto children, and disturb the peace with blaring radios. Low-level, or gatewaycrimes, destroy our sense of safety, trust in each other, and create anenvironment for more serious crime. <BR><BR>Nevertheless, in Minneapolis and in Hennepin County, we do very little toprosecute gateway crimes. At my request, the Chief of Police and City Attorneyhave developed a plan for aggressive prosecution of misdemeanors, and arerecommending an investment of $245,000 to hire two additional attorneys,two investigators and three support staff. I am prepared to support thisinvestment. But the City cannot succeed in this effort alone. We need theHennepin County District Court to put the full muscle of the criminal justicesystem behind the good work of the Minneapolis Police Department. Thereare still some details to be worked out, but Chief Judge Daniel Mabley andAssistant Chief Judge Pamela Alexander have given me their strong commitmentsto consider my plan for the creation of a new misdemeanor calendar in theDistrict Court, and help us slam the door on gateway crime. <BR><BR>We need a coordinated effort in which Minneapolis police aggressively enforcemisdemeanor violations, the City Attorney has resources to prepare strongcases against them, and the District Court has greater capacity to handlethem. Many residents and police have become frustrated with the &quot;revolvingdoor&quot; that seems to release criminals as quickly as they can be apprehended.Our strategy will have two results: One, it will produce higher convictionrates, and two, it will remove trouble-makers from the streets before theyhave a chance to commit more serious crimes. <BR><BR>If we work together, we can stop today's dilapidated properties from becomingdrug houses, today's domestic assault from becoming tomorrow's homicide,and today's illegal handgun from becoming a weapon of death. <BR><BR>It is an outrage that in some Minneapolis neighborhoods - just to get toschool - our children must pass through streets of despair where they donot pass grocery stores, pharmacies and dry cleaners, but houses of prostitutionand drug houses, where they confront delinquents, bullies and gang memberswho would readily smash our children's future with a rock of crack-cocaineor a bullet. <BR><BR>City officials have many critical responsibilities, but first and foremost,we must protect our children. A community that turns its back on childrenturns its back on its own future. In February at my State of the City AddressI said we needed to place a priority on keeping children safe in our publicspaces, including city schools and parks. Since then we have been workingwith the Minneapolis Public Schools and the Minneapolis Park and RecreationBoard to outline a strategy. Today I am calling for implementation of thisstrategy, which we call Safe Schools, Safe Parks. <BR><BR>Safe Schools, Safe Parks is smart, and it's tough. It saturates with policeprotection the areas where children and their families work and recreate.It enforces a policy of zero-tolerance for crime, zero-tolerance for drugs,zero-tolerance for prostitution, zero- tolerance for guns, and zero-tolerancefor gangs. <BR><BR>I am directing the Police Department to submit plans for the 1997 budgetto increase police protection along the routes children take to school,and work intensively with school principals to develop a safety plan forevery Minneapolis public school. I am asking every city agency that sendsstaff into the community to identify workers to drive specially marked McGruffvehicles children can flag down if they think they are in danger. I am askingInspections to submit plans for zero-tolerance of code violations that createdangerous or unhealthy conditions in these areas or that deface our cityand insult our citizens. <BR><BR>I have been in discussions with the Minneapolis Public Schools to find outhow we can work together for safer schools. They have agreed to meet weeklywith police school liaison officers to identify and solve safety issues,conduct security audits, and issue ID cards that will help them keep outthe dangerous people who do not belong in our schools. <BR><BR>We send children to school so they can learn in an environment where adultsguide and supervise them, but they also need structure and positive opportunitieswhen the bell rings at the end of the school day. However, 40 percent ofthe average student's time is spent unsupervised. In my State of the Cityaddress last February, in the name of the safety of our youth, I asked theMinneapolis School Board to consider changing school hours so that childrenwill both begin and end school later in the day. <BR><BR>This morning I am happy to announce, together with School Board Chair BillGreen and Superintendent Peter Hutchinson, that the Minneapolis Board ofEducation has voted to work with the community to develop by December arecommendation to change start times beginning in 1997. Board Chair Greenand Superintendent Hutchinson, would you please stand and let this audiencethank you. <BR><BR>Minneapolis parents, this is your chance to work with the schools so yourchild may no longer have to wait for the bus or walk to school on dark wintermornings, or leave school at 1:45, perhaps unsupervised, during the veryhours juvenile crime is at its peak. <BR><BR>In 1992, we were so concerned about this problem that we started the Youthin Minneapolis Program (Y-MAP). Now that children will be staying in schoollater, I am directing the Youth Coordinating Board to begin immediatelyto redesign Y-MAP, placing more emphasis on activities that will take placein the school buildings. We need to be ready for the 1997-1998 school year.<BR><BR>I urge everyone in the community to set special interests aside, and worktogether to develop a new schedule that meets the safety needs of our children.I thank the School Board for making a change that will go a long way towardkeeping our youth safe and out of trouble. <BR><BR>I have also discussed Safe Schools, Safe Parks with the Minneapolis Parkand Recreation Board. I was shocked to learn there are parks in Minneapolisover which we have lost control, parks that been taken over by thugs, gangstersand substance abusers. It is intolerable that some of our public spaces,which our taxes support, are no longer safe enough for us to enjoy. At myrequest, Chief Olson has met with Captain Jacobs of the Park Police to determinehow the Minneapolis Police Department can help. They have agreed to outlinea plan for Park police and Minneapolis precinct commanders to take backour city parks - and do it now! <BR><BR>The Park Board and the City share the goal of protecting citizens from crime.Because I believe we can make better use of the taxpayers' dollars by poolingour resources, I will continue to explore how City and Park police can worktogether to make our city a safer place. <BR><BR>Youth need supervision, guidance and support. This community has made abig mistake by not providing it on the long sunny weekends of June, Julyand August. I congratulate the Park Board on its plans for the RecXtra program,which will offer activities for families and children on summer weekends,starting in 1997. We may discover we can not afford this program in everypark, but it is crucial to introduce it in those neighborhoods where wemust take back the parks for the families and children of Minneapolis. <BR><BR>Crime, like a noxious weed, can grow only in an environment that permitsit to grow. As a result of our new priority work team meetings, many pointsof view contributed to the discussion of how to make the Minneapolis environmentinhospitable to crime. One proposal was to deter crime by better lightingin our streets and alleys. I am asking the Department of Public Works tomeet with neighborhood and NRP groups, businesses, the City Assessor andNSP to put together a lighting-for-safety plan for consideration in nextyear's budget. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Livable Neighborhoods </H3><BR>Now I will move to our second priority: livable neighborhoods. <BR><BR>In February I spoke of the need to make Minneapolis more livable duringthe winter by digging out from snowstorms within 24 hours. Public Workshas not yet been able to identify a way to accomplish this with expendituresthat are acceptable in the present economic climate. However, we do knowwe could meet peak seasonal needs, such as making the city more passablein the wintertime and conducting community clean-ups more quickly, effectivelyand inexpensively, by changing the way we use our work force. Now we hiresummer seasonal staff whom we lay off during the winter. Yet we pay themunemployment and on-call bonuses while they are not working. All told, wepay them the equivalent of eleven months' wages for only seven months' work.It would be a better use of taxpayer dollars if we paid them 12 months ofthe year for 12 months of work, so they could help us remove snow from aroundbus stops, alley approaches, street corners and the downtown area. <BR><BR>We have other resources that we are not using. We should be talking withour friends in labor about cross-training employees for seasonal work, sothat, for example, Inspections field staff and animal control workers whosebusy season is the summer could write tickets during snow-emergencies. Housingand rental licensing inspectors could be assigned temporarily to help withweed and rubbish removal. Workers on light duty could help, too, as couldsummer youth workers. And why not ask the District Court to assign non-violentoffenders to community service? They can help us cut weeds, pick up trashand erase graffiti, to make our community more livable. I look forward toreceiving the recommendations of the work force utilization task force forinclusion in my 1997 budget. Again, we must work cooperatively with laborto accomplish our objectives. <BR><BR>I also believe we can do a better job cleaning up our neighborhoods - atno additional cost to taxpayers - just by better coordinating our streetcleaning and sanitation operations. I am asking Public Works to test sucha coordinated effort in 1997. I know the Department is planning a pilotcommunity clean-up in the Central neighborhood in August, and another inthe Phillips neighborhood in October. For the Phillips clean-up we may evenobtain the additional support of 200 of President Clinton's AmeriCorps volunteers!<BR><BR>Last year's bitter winter presented severe problems for citizens who areelderly or who struggle with disabilities. Unshoveled corners and sidewalksmade it all but impossible for them to move around out-of-doors. We canimprove the livability of our city, again at little or no cost, by expandingour Citizen Inspection program, in which community volunteers identify neighborhoodmaintenance problems, and either encourage property owners to solve them,or contact the city for help. As we look for ways to reweave the socialfabric, we must treat our citizens not as passive customers of government,but as full partners who take responsibility for their neighbors and forown community. <BR><BR>Now, in case any of you brought along my budget message from last year,I'd like you to turn to page three. In the section on sewer service, I saidour five-year plan to put the sewer fund in the black required us to makemodest increases in the sewer rates for each of those years. In 1997, thefourth year of the plan, those increases will amount to an average of 96cents per household per month. I want to remind everybody that this increaseis part of a responsible plan we all agreed to, and it should not be a surpriseto anyone. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Economic Development </H3><BR>Now I will turn to the third major priority for the City of Minneapolis:economic development. <BR><BR>If we want to grow the Minneapolis economy, we must grow our tax base. Thefundamental task of the MCDA is to recommend the investments we must maketo develop a tax base strong enough to support our local economy. We needthe MCDA's recommendations for investments we should make in housing - notjust in rehabilitation, but in land parcels we can put together to sellto meet consumer demand. I am delighted with the new housing that has sprungup in recent years along the riverfront. This excellent use of desirableland adds tremendously to both the urban environment and to our tax base.Riverfront living to date has been costly, with Saw Mill Run homes startingat $325,000, but the new Itasca units promise to be more affordable. <BR><BR>In my State of the City Address I said we need to address housing issues,especially low home ownership in the Phillips neighborhood and the NearNorth Side. We want to increase the rate of home ownership. I am askingthe MCDA to develop for a specific plan to accomplish this objective. <BR><BR>We need the MCDA to continue to emphasize the development of community commercialcorridors. They are the life blood of the residential neighborhoods thatsurround them. In 1997 we must get some important projects on line, especiallyon Chicago and Lake, Broadway, Lowry and Central Avenue. Council MemberHerron, I will work with you to help revitalize Lake Street with that Searsredevelopment project. We can accomplish our objective of creating the jobcenter, and bring exciting retail back to Chicago-Lake. <BR><BR>We are progressing with Central Riverfront development, and are on schedulewith our partners, the Minneapolis Park and Recreation Board and Minnegasco,to complete the Great River Road in the spring of 1997. We are moving aheadwith plans for new housing in the Northstar Woolen Mill and the UtilityBuilding. Through our partners on the St. Anthony Falls Heritage Board,we secured state bonds to develop Phase I of Mill Ruins Park. The Park Boardwill request 1997 capital funds from CLIC as part of the required localmatch, and I plan on approaching Hennepin County, our partner on the HeritageBoard, also to make a financial contribution to the contribution of thisnew riverfront park. The park will enhance the redevelopment of the MilwaukeeDepot site, which will be under construction by January 1. These are wonderfulhistoric sites in Minneapolis, and will be great amenities for people wholive and work and play downtown. <BR><BR>In the MCDA business survey, the need for skilled workers was the secondmost frequently cited high priority need. Remember that unemployment isonly 2.3 percent in Minneapolis, and many companies are having a hard timefinding qualified employees. This tight labor market makes it a necessityto groom a work force to meet the needs of growing businesses. The highlevel of communication and coordination needed for this effort will nothappen automatically. I am calling on the MCDA and Minneapolis Educationand Training Program (METP) to pursue plans for a work force compact tocoordinate employment and training with industry's need to fill new jobs.The compact must include the School District, community colleges, technicalschools, labor and other public and private partners. <BR><BR>If we want to feed economic growth and keep businesses in Minneapolis, wemust invest in the education and training of our citizens. If we want toaddress the double-digit unemployment we have in some neighborhoods, wemust recognize this tight job market is a golden opportunity to provideeducation and job training for inner city residents who might otherwisebe left out. The passage of the welfare bill is going to have an impacton Minneapolis. We need to be pro-active in ensuring that the people haveaccess to education and training so they can be gainfully employed and ina position to make a contribution to the community. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Healthy Families and Children </H3><BR>Our fourth City goal is to ensure healthy families and children. Last year,as a result of reduced federal funding, the City changed the way it addressedpublic health. Today's Department of Health and Family Support assessescommunity health needs, advocates to meet them, and monitors the deliveryof health care, especially with the clinics it contracts with for directcare. <BR><BR>In keeping with the emphasis we place on violence as a public health problem,I reaffirm that the City wants to advance the Health Department's role infighting crime and violence, and that it should continue with this importantwork. <BR><BR>I also want to emphasize the Department's role as an advocate for the healthof the people of Minneapolis. Health problems in Minneapolis are disproportionatelyhigh, compared to health problems elsewhere in Hennepin County. We needthe Department to be a strong advocate to help us secure the additionalresources we need to maintain good public health. <BR><BR>There has been much discussion recently about the level of student achievement.Every good parent knows a child must feel strong, healthy and energeticto perform well in school. But too many young people are held back by chronicillness and medical problems. Think about it: Can a teenager who uses drugsbe motivated to succeed in school? Can a seven-year-old who suffers fromabuse and clinical depression learn to read? Will a pregnant 15-year oldwith morning sickness be able get to school on time? Who will help thesefragile young people if, for whatever reason, their parents fail them? Whatwill happen to them in five years if no one helps them? <BR><BR>The Health Department and the Public Schools are engaged in a partnershipin which the schools are under contract to deliver clinical care to students.They believe that in the past we have focused school health service toonarrowly on treating illness, and so have adopted a new goal of prevention.I endorse this approach, because I believe it will result in healthier childrenwho are better prepared to succeed in school. I commend Commissioner DelHurt and his staff for advancing this discussion. <BR><BR>Because it is the overall goal of the city to build community, it is importantthat some department of the city be responsible for thinking about and discussinghow we improve the status of families and children. I believe this responsibilityshould lie with the Health Department. I have asked the Health Commissionerto assume responsibility for convening a task force that will involve theappropriate city departments in examining the critical issues facing familiestoday and developing an agenda for action. You will find greater detailon this proposal in your Priorities '97 documents. <BR><BR>Many of our City offices receive daily phone calls from citizens with problems.Some call with relatively simple problems - for example, a mix-up on a bill,a complaint about a pothole. Others call with problems so difficult andcomplex that they don't know who else to call or where to start. Staff dotheir best to help, but often do not have the training or full range ofexpertise to solve the problem. We already have a one-stop shop for business;why shouldn't we have one for citizens? Why shouldn't there be a place,perhaps with free parking, where taxpayers can easily obtain the information,referrals and services they are paying for? I propose that in 1997 we establishan Office of Citizen Service. I want to reorganize the way we serve citizensto most efficiently respond to <I>their</I> needs. This is a first step.<BR><BR>This office, and the Task Force for Children and Families, will take onnew importance in the face of federal devolution. It is impossible for usto predict the result devolution will have on citizens. We do know thatall the failures of our American systems - the failures of education, theeconomy, housing and the criminal justice system - eventually collide, notin the halls of Congress or the state Capitol, but in the streets of Americancities. When the safety net breaks, the people fall - on Lake Street, onBroadway, and in the alleys behind the bars. When the safety net breaks,it will be the cities that witness the damage, even if we have no resourcesto deal with them. We must prepare ourselves for the future. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Government Management </H3><BR>Our fifth and final priority is government management. When I became mayorin 1994, I pledged to improve the City management system. In 1995 I followedup by obtaining the commitment of the City Council to undertake sweepingreforms. We have made many improvements together since then, including anew finance system, regulatory reform, technology improvements. Next yearwe must finish the job. <BR><BR>Our citizens are not at all pleased to read in the paper about the lawsuitsand claims against the City that act like a slow leak in our budget. TheCity of Minneapolis currently does not have a comprehensive risk managementstrategy, and because we are self-insured, our losses have a dollar-for-dollarimpact on the size of our budget. The cost of risk is currently estimatedat $11 million. About $9.8 million is caused by losses, and the rest isfor administration and insurance premiums. A draft report from our consultantindicates that while the City may not be able to prevent all lawsuits, wecan lower our costs significantly just by improving our management. We mustconsolidate the five risk-management functions now scattered throughoutthree city departments. We must staff up to do a better job preventing lossesand returning injured workers back to the job. If we make these changes,we will save $200,000 the very first year, and upwards of $500,000 everyyear after that, because of increased efficiency and effectiveness. Thisis an investment we must make this year. It is not optional. We owe it toour citizens to stop this waste of their tax dollars. <BR><BR>The City of Minneapolis operates a fleet of vehicles that are used by fire,police, public works, inspections and other departments. Because we havenot instituted a policy of regular replacement, over a third of our vehiclesare past their replacement date and expensive to maintain. Despite the factthat a centralized pool would be more efficient and economical, we maintainour fleet at five locations throughout the city, resulting in underutilizationof vehicles, inefficient inventories and duplication of effort. Our mainrepair facilities were built in 1936, and are not adequate for modern fleetmaintenance. This kind of disarray can result in policy-makers having tomake important decisions --such as whether to invest in new vehicles --with insufficient information. <BR><BR>The director of Public Works faces major challenges in turning our systemaround. I am asking him to give me a multi-year fleet and facilities managementplan we can begin to implement next year. We must make the investments necessaryto get the fleet back onto a reasonable replacement cycle, and we need tobuild modern, efficient facilities. Implementation of this plan will resultin future cost savings. In last year's Budget Address, I said &quot;we shouldbegin now to build the funds needed to put the City on a pay-as-you-go basisfor improvements&quot; to our water system. Now we must develop a specificplan. I would like a preliminary plan by November. <BR><BR>We continue to make progress on all 14 objectives of our Human Resourcesagenda. In 1997 we will make substantial progress in two areas. We can makethe Human Resources generalist program city-wide, and we can implement theHuman Resource Information System which will give us more accurate and timelyinformation. <BR><BR><HR><H3>An Opportunity </H3>Before concluding, I want to talk about a proposal that did not come outof the budget process, but represents a very exciting opportunity. For twoweeks the whole world has been mesmerized by the Altanta Olympic Games,and we all have cheered for those young Americans who have excelled in thename of our country. Now, the Olympic Committee proposes that Minneapolisbe one of two sites in the nation for an Olympic Development Center foryoung people. The facility would be a state-of-the-art community centeroperated by the YWCA. Our residents would have access to a world-class aquaticcenter, play pockets and fountains for small children, a water games areaand even a water slide. There would be three gymnasiums and a fitness centerfor people of all ages and abilities. Council Member Dziedzic, I want youto know there will be facilities for soccer, basketball, volleyball andtrack and field, and they will be available to our Minneapolis school children.There will be child care, so the facility could serve as a gathering placefor the entire community. <BR><BR>Council Member Thurber has worked hard to coordinate the development ofthis opportunity. It would involve a partnership consisting of the MinneapolisYWCA, Minneapolis Public School District and the Minnesota Amateur SportsCommission. Funding would come from a capital drive spearheaded by the YWCA,as well as resources from the state legislature, the school district, theNRPs of Longfellow, Powderhorn and Corcoran, Hennepin County and the Cityof Minneapolis. <BR><BR>This YWCA Community Center and Olympic Development Center will enhance ourcommunity's national sports profile. It will improve the quality of lifefor our residents. It will promote dreams of excellence and achievementto our youth, and help them make those dreams come true. Finally, it willgive us an important advantage as we compete with other communities forfamilies who will live and invest in Minneapolis. Many suburban communitiesalready have excellent recreational and fitness amenities. There is no reasonthat the families and children of Minneapolis should not have them, too.<BR><BR><HR><H3>Conclusion </H3><BR>I know many of these directions will challenge the creativity of our departmentheads. I want them to remember, however, as they prepare their proposals,that if the City of Minneapolis made no changes at all in the way we dobusiness, our costs would increase by $5 million dollars in 1997. Fortunately,we will be able to absorb $3 million dollars of that increase with the increasedrevenues associated with a growing tax base. However, because I am absolutelycommitted to avoiding an increase in the tax rate, I need City Departmentsto reduce total expenditures by $2 million. <BR><BR>I hope that as you work with your Priorities '97 documents, you will beexcited by the new opportunities we have identified for making significantprogress in several areas. This is a framework for zero tolerance for crimeand violence. We <I>will</I> have safe schools and safe parks. We <I>will</I>have a criminal justice system that backs up the work of our Minneapolispolice officers. We <I>will</I> have well-lit streets free of trash, debrisand graffiti. This is a budget framework for more livable neighborhoods!Neighborhoods where our families can be strong and self-sufficient. Thisis a budget framework that recognizes our responsibility to create an economicclimate where businesses can grow and offer our citizens good jobs at goodliving wages. <BR><BR>We are making progress. We must continue to work together to build a stronger,safer city for all of our residents. <BR><BR>I look forward to our continued collaboration in this budget process. <BR><BR><HR><H5><BR>Email your comments and questions to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I></H5></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
