<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>State of the City Minneapolis 1996</TITLE>    <!-- Date: Tuesday, February 13, 1996  3:09 PM prepared for the web by Brian Wold, 673-3821 --></HEAD><BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#9EB2F2"><H1><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+5>State of the City Address </FONT><BR>Sharon Sayles Belton <BR>Mayor of the City of Minneapolis</CENTER></H1><BR><I>February 7, 1996</I> <BR><BR><BR><IMG SRC="sharon.gif" BORDER="1" VSPACE=4 HSPACE=4 WIDTH="184" HEIGHT="240"ALIGN="RIGHT" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALT="Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton"> <BR><H2><I><STRONG>Building Capacity for the 21st Century</STRONG></I></H2><BR>Council President Cherryhomes and Members of the Minneapolis City Council,I appreciate the opportunity to address you today. Members of the IndependentBoards and the Hennepin County Board, welcome. Citizens of Minneapolis,thank you for joining us. <BR><BR>I thank Principal Ann Widseth, the administration, faculty, students andparents of Jenny Lind Community School for welcoming us today. I particularlywant to thank the children who sang so beautifully a few moments ago. Let'sgive them a hand. <BR><BR>Jenny Lind represents some of the best qualities of our Minneapolis Publicschool system. It is a brand new, state-of-the-art building. <BR><BR>This kind of high-quality education is found throughout our public schools.Jenny Lind students enjoy a science program, a public-private partnershipdeveloped at the University of California at Berkeley and funded by Medtronic.It offers a program for gifted and talented children that even lets thempublish their own newspaper, and a computer-based math and reading programthat won a national award. <BR><BR>We applaud these achievements, especially since our Minneapolis schoolsface challenges many other school districts do not. Yes, they must overcomelearning barriers created by poverty. Yes, our teachers must work harderto educate the 12 percent of our children who have limited English skills,the 55 percent eligible for free lunches, the 34 percent on AFDC, the 12percent who are disabled. The success of our schools, in the face of thesechallenges, is remarkable, and more than enough reason to be proud of themand to give them the support they both need and fully deserve. <BR><BR>One of the great benefits of being Mayor of Minneapolis is the badge ofcommunity pride I wear every place I go. A couple of weeks ago I attendedthe US Conference of Mayors, and it was a pleasure to hear mayors from allaround the country sing the praises of our city. <BR><BR>Those mayors know that even though Minneapolis struggles with the same problemsthey do, we are solving them. They envy our Triple A bond rating, our citymanagement, and our progressive attitude. Many who were here two years agofor the National League of Cities convention remember how beautiful andclean Minneapolis is, and how safe it feels compared to their own downtowns.<BR><BR>I say this, not to distract us from the challenges at hand, but to makesure we do not focus on them exclusively, forgetting the positive foundationwe have to build on. For us to sustain our commitment to a healthy and thrivingMinneapolis, we need two things: first, pride in our past accomplishments;and second, a vision of a vital and thriving future. <BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><STRONG>Reviewing Our Accomplishments: 1995</STRONG></H3><BR>So let us take a few minutes to review our 1995 &quot;report card.&quot;Did we accomplish what we set out to do? How did we build on our city'salready strong foundation? <BR><BR>In my last State of the City address I said we needed to develop a long-termplan to stabilize our community, and provide the things families need tobe strong and healthy. I said then we should concentrate on the four factorsthat make the biggest difference in people's lives: housing, jobs, education. . . and safety. <BR><BR>A few months later, record homicides sent shock waves through the community.Ninety-seven men, women and even children fell victim to a terrible plagueof violence. We saw killings over drugs, over relationships, over angrywords, over a bicycle. Children were murdered by their parents, wives bytheir husbands, children by other children. <BR><BR>When we think of public safety in Minneapolis, we must remember that --overall --serious crime has been declining. In that context, we struggledto understand this tragic rise in homicides, and we took action. <BR><BR>Last July, on a 60-day trial basis, the Minneapolis Police Department sentspecially trained Operation Safe Street squads into nine neighborhoods totest a new strategy. We identified the neighborhoods suffering the mostfrom violence, and set out to remove as many illegal guns as we could fromthe streets in these neighborhoods. Our strategy worked. One hundred seventy-sevenillegal guns were confiscated, and the number of gunshots fired droppedimmediately -- in fact, below the 1994 level. Even more importantly, theword went out on the streets that if you want to stay out of trouble inMinneapolis, you'd better leave your gun at home! <BR><BR>Operation Safe Street was effective because it fought crime with a campaigndesigned and directed -- not in City Hall -- but in our precincts and neighborhoods.Police identified specific neighborhood problems, and formed a united frontwith local residents and businesses to confront crime. We are encouragedby the success of this strategy, and will expand it this spring. We arealso encouraged by Governor Arne Carlson's recognition of Operation SafeStreet's effectiveness and his efforts to fund it in Minneapolis and evenexpand it into other Minnesota communities. <BR><BR>Community policing programs such as Operation Safe Street require more policein the community. So does the downtown command, which Chief Robert Olsonestablished last year. We passed a budget with substantial increases inpolice funding, allowing us to hire and equip 10 new police officers, andwe received a federal grant for another 17 &quot;Clinton Cops&quot; to walkthe beat, and work with residents to solve problems before they jeopardizeneighborhood peace and safety. That's community policing! <BR><BR>Last year we created Precinct Response Teams, and an Organized Crime Unitthat, by this spring, will be able to deal aggressively with the difficultproblems of illegal street activity, repeat offenders, gangs and weaponssales. <BR><BR>These changes in the police department were extremely important, but sowere other changes not so widely publicized. Chief Olson often talks about&quot;attitude.&quot; Our new police administration's new attitude is resultingin major internal changes. We are moving more swiftly and decisively tofollow up on charges of officer misconduct. More importantly, we are decentralizingthe force, and placing more trust and responsibility in the hundreds ofofficers who perform their jobs with integrity -- and often, heroism. <BR><BR>In 1995 we closed one chapter on the way the Minneapolis Police Departmentworks, and opened a new one. Congratulations, Chief Olson, on an excellentjob. <BR><BR>A study we conducted last year implicates guns in more than three quartersof our youth homicides. Last year we passed a zoning ordinance to keep commercialgun sales out of residential neighborhoods -- not a panacea, but one morestep toward reducing the killing. We must do everything possible to reduceguns in our neighborhoods, to get them out of our homes, out of our neighborhoods,out of the hands of criminals, and out of the way of our children. We cando this, we must do it, and we will do it in the City of Minneapolis. <BR><BR>Good housing is essential to a stable community. Last year I proposed, andthe City Council adopted, a set of housing principles which are now theCity's official housing development policy. They encourage homeownership,reinvestment in our housing stock, and better housing choices for residents.<BR><BR>In 1995, the Minneapolis Community Development Agency helped 430 Minneapolisresidents reinvest in their homes with nearly $2.3 million dollars worthof home improvement loans, and made 716 residential mortgage loans totalingmore than $54 million. Ladies and gentlemen, that was an all-time record!<BR><BR>Meanwhile, the Minneapolis Public Housing Authority, or MPHA, helped 17public housing and Section 8 families become first-time homeowners. <BR><BR>MPHA designated four public high-rises -- 900 units -- for the elderly.It rehabbed 70 single-family homes, and modernized 22 high-rises, includingthe Cedars Complex, Hiawatha Towers, and 1815 Central. We made a dramaticdifference at the 1710 Plymouth Building. Once a crime-infested tower thatdisfigured an entire neighborhood, it is now beautiful modern housing forthe elderly, and an asset to the community. Horn Tower in the Lyndale neighborhoodis being renovated, and promises to improve the lives of hundreds of residents.<BR><BR>Using HUD funds from the Hollman out-of-court settlement, MPHA has alreadyfound good homes for 80 of the 300 affected families previously living insubstandard housing. Sixteen of them are now Minneapolis homeowners. Mycommitment to those affected by this lawsuit is to find them better housingthan they had before, in a location they have chosen themselves. <BR><BR>Just this week I received news that the MPHA's Modernization and Elderly-OnlyHighrise Programs were nominated for national awards. MPHA's work is beingrecognized nationally; let's give Director Cora McCorvey and her peoplea hand and recognize them right here at home, as well! <BR><BR>Our residents showed renewed commitment to improving their neighborhoods.Twenty-four excellent Neighborhood Revitalization Plans were approved lastyear. Some of them demonstrated outstanding cooperation among neighborhoods-- for example, the four neighborhoods that collaborated on the Longfellowplan, and the five that collaborated to keep Camden Health Clinic in thecommunity's commercial district. <BR><BR>We thank the hundreds, maybe thousands of residents who took responsibilityfor the well-being of their own communities through the NRP process. Thisis a great program, and we must work harder to insure its success. <BR><BR>Our employment picture continued to improve in 1995. Last year our unemploymentrate was only 3.3 percent -- four-tenths of a point lower than 1994's. Iam happy to say that this is the lowest unemployment rate Minneapolis hashad since 1978! <BR><BR>That is welcome news... but it ignores the thousands of discouraged workerswho no longer show up in the statistics, and the double-digit unemploymentin some neighborhoods. Unemployment is approximately 15 percent in boththe Near North, and Phillips neighborhoods, according to the last census.Even the low overall 3.3 percent unemployment rate translates into 34,000Minneapolis adults without jobs. <BR><BR>Last year our Minneapolis Employment and Training Program, through our NETNetwork, trained, placed and kept 1,400 hard-to-employ people on the job,for an average hourly wage of $7.50. Their combined earnings of nearly $20million paid back four dollars for every one spent on this program. <BR><BR>In our 1996 budget we asked the private sector to raise $1.2 million tostabilize this program. We hope to meet our goal by the end of June. <BR><BR>Last year the Bemis Company Foundation helped us deal with an importantemployment challenge. In the suburbs, where 85 percent of the new jobs are,employers are in need of workers, especially for the late shifts. Meanwhile,unemployed city residents want those jobs but can't get to them for lackof bus service. Bemis made a generous grant to our Neighborhood EmploymentNetwork to work with Loring-Nicollet Job Bank, and the Southwest Metro BusCompany, to help establish the regular bus runs needed to get people tothese jobs. <BR><BR>Good jobs are created by strong businesses, and the MCDA's Business FinancePrograms were of exceptional assistance to the city's business communitylast year. Business financing totaled $215 million, compared to $55 millionthe previous year. As a result, 539 new jobs were created -- the majorityof them industrial -- and more than 4,000 jobs were preserved. 1995 wasalso the year we acquired the Target Center, and financed a new entertainmentvenue downtown, the Hey City Stage. <BR><BR>These employment programs, together with our housing initiatives, have helpedthousands of Minneapolis residents stabilize their lives. In fact, the numberof residents living in the same place more than three years rose to a five-yearhigh in 1995, while the number who lived in the same place less than sixmonths fell to an all-time low. This is excellent news -- a sign that weare moving in the right direction, that our strategies are working. <BR><BR>There were other signs of a healthy, job-producing economy. The value of1995 construction permits exceeded 1994's by 18 percent, partly becauseof the Federal Reserve Bank construction, and partly because homeownersare starting to use NRP housing funds to improve their homes. The downtownvacancy rate fell again, from 12.2 percent to 9.7 percent. Twelve more acresof urban &quot;brownfields&quot; were converted by the MCDA's MILES programinto commercial and industrial sites where Minneapolis residents will eventuallybe able to find jobs. A good example of the MILES program at work is itsclean-up of the Grace Lee Manufacturing Company site in Northeast Minneapolis,which is now being used by Harmony Scenic, Incorporated. Minneapolis isa national model for cleaning up polluted land and restoring it to the taxrolls. <BR><BR>Not all the cleaning-up we did last year was job-related. Some of it willimprove the quality of our lives outside of work. The Chain of Lakes CleanWater Partnership, now in its third year, broke ground this fall for CedarWetlands, a project that will provide a natural filter for stormwater pollutantsthat would otherwise run into our lakes. It will help us restore our beautifullakes from &quot;green to clean.&quot; <BR><BR>In the past year, the Minneapolis Park and Recreation Board has upgradedmany of our beautiful parks. They have already begun to develop the comprehensiveframework for our Chain of Lakes, and I look forward to seeing the completedplan. I congratulate the Park system for its fine work. <BR><BR>Last year in my State of the City Address I called for closure on a lingeringquestion: &quot;Should Minneapolis establish community schools to promoteboth family and community support the education of our young people.&quot;<BR><BR>After extensive community discussion, the Minneapolis School Board decidedto create a system of community and magnet schools. For the first time inyears, parents of this year's kindergartners will be able to choose to sendtheir children to a community school near their home, such as Jenny Lind,or a magnet school across town. <BR><BR>We welcome this opportunity to embrace the growth and education of our childrenin our own neighborhoods. We look forward to moving our community schoolsto center-stage, where they can once again be a focus of family and communitylife, where they can help us strengthen, and where necessary, reweave thefabric of our community. <BR><BR>I applaud the Minneapolis School Board members, administration and facultyfor their commitment to make this change, and thank the Minneapolis citizenswho participated in this important community discussion about our children'swelfare. <BR><BR>As we all know, this matter is not quite closed. The State Board of Educationstill must approve a waiver allowing us to proceed with this plan, and weencourage it to do so quickly. <BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><STRONG>Building 21st Century Capacity: 1996</STRONG> </H3><BR>The State of the City Address gives us an opportunity at the beginning ofeach year not only to review our progress, but to look forward to the future.It's a time to renew our vision of Minneapolis as a prosperous and culturallyvibrant city, as a city that asserts its place in the global economy, anda city that does now, and will continue, to serve as the cultural and economicgateway to the state of Minnesota. <BR><BR>If we are going to continue to serve as that gateway, we must be preparedto change and keep pace with the rest of the world. We can prepare for thefuture by building our city's capacity for the 21st Century. <BR><BR>We have worked hard in the last two years to build the capacity of Citygovernment -- upgrading our own management and technology systems, streamliningoperations and reducing costs, to prepare for the days ahead. I'd like tothank the City's management team for their great work, and I would likeall Charter Department heads to please stand up. <BR><BR>We also have also created powerful tools -- including those housing, employment,business and police programs I have just mentioned -- to help the communitybuild 21st-century capacity. Now, in the coming year, we must work on applyingthese tools strategically in each of those four areas we said are criticalto our citizens: jobs, housing, education and public safety. <BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><STRONG>Building Capacity with Jobs and Economic Development</STRONG></H3><BR>First, jobs. Let me share something with you. Last month, while I was atthe U.S. Conference of Mayors in Washington, I visited the Frederick DouglassMuseum. On the wall was a framed quotation that has haunted me ever sincemy return. Listen to what Frederick Douglass had to say: &quot;Neither we,nor any other people, will ever be respected 'till we respect ourselves,and we will never respect ourselves 'till we have the means to live respectably.&quot;<BR><BR>How do we help citizens gain respectability? By giving them an education.By giving them a job. Give them a job, so they can pay their own way, providefor their children, buy their own house, take a vacation. <BR><BR>We need a sound jobs-creation strategy that brings more community educationand career training to city neighborhoods in which there is high unemployment.<BR><BR>The strategy needs to begin with gearing up Minneapolis businesses to becompetitive in the global economy. In July the Metropolitan Council andthe Humphrey Institute released a study identifying four industries thatmust lead the way. They are: printing and publishing, machinery and metalworking,computers and software and bio-medical technologies. I call them our &quot;horizonindustries.&quot; <BR><BR>In 1996 the MCDA, which is newly focused on nurturing our home-grown businesses,will survey Minneapolis firms in these horizon industries to determine theirfuture needs. Then, to ensure that they grow and prosper, we will assistthem with their financing; we will provide them a work-force trained tomeet their specific needs; we will help them locate their facilities inadvantageous locations; and, if necessary, we will provide them loans tohelp them purchase the equipment they need. <BR><BR>As we grow and prosper we want to preserve and protect our heritage, includingour historic buildings. But the costs of preservation can be prohibitive.We are moving forward in this session of the Legislature to establish aHeritage and Historic Tax Increment Subdistrict to help us redevelop ourhistoric buildings. <BR><BR>This district will include all Minneapolis properties on the National Registerof Historic Buildings. It will be a tool to help us, for example, preservethe Grain Belt building, the Ivy Tower, and buildings in the Warehouse andCentral Riverfront areas -- all of them part of the architectural heritagethat makes Minneapolis unique. <BR><BR>Block E is an important economic development opportunity because it hasthe potential to be a linchpin for all downtown, connecting the warehouse,shopping and entertainment districts. One of our community's foremost expertsin finance, real estate and development, Mr. Bill Reiling of Towle FinancialServices, recently commented that &quot;how (we use) Block E is a 100-yeardecision.&quot; He is right. We must not force something to happen therejust to satisfy a desire to move quickly. <BR><BR>In 1996 we will continue to use our best resources to help us make gooddecisions on Block E. I am happy to announce today that Mr. Reiling hasagreed to share his wisdom and experience with us by serving pro bono asa senior adviser to the City and the MCDA, and to help us put together astrategic development plan for Block E. <BR><BR>Mr. Reiling wanted to be with us today, but, shrewd decision-maker thathe is, he apparently determined that in view of our 100-year record coldhe perhaps would rather be elsewhere -- I think he's playing golf in Florida!So even though he can't hear us, let's give him a hand to show him our appreciation!<BR><BR>We need economic development throughout our city, not only downtown. Thisyear we must get serious about redesigning the major commercial corridorthat cuts across South Minneapolis: Lake Street. We must rethink where toimprove its commercial nodes in relation to nearby population centers, andfind the capital needed for redevelopment. The MCDA has been working withthe Neighborhood Revitalization Program to develop a city-wide CoordinatedNeighborhood Commercial District Revitalization Plan. In December the CityCouncil identified Lake Street as its first area of focus. Our goal is tobegin implementing the plan for Lake Street redevelopment by July 1, andlaunch the commercial revitalization of our South Minneapolis neighborhoods.<BR><BR>Minneapolis is blessed with an extraordinary gift: the Mississippi riverfront.We've been working on it for 25 years, dating back at least to the early1970s when we drew up a Central Riverfront plan. Today we have NicolletIsland, the Whitney Hotel, and a stunning suspension bridge. Lovely townhouseand condominium communities have sprung up in the past two decades, withnames that proudly reflect the area's history and beauty: Lourdes Square,La Rive, The Falls, The Pinnacle, Winslow House and Riverwest. <BR><BR>This year on the riverfront, we must and we will complete the Great RiverRoad, and open the long-awaited St. Anthony Falls Historic InterpretiveTrail. We will work with the University of Minnesota to move the steam plantoff-river. I congratulate and thank the Board of Regents for sharing ourvision for reclaiming our great Riverfront, and we hope the Legislaturedoes, too. Thank you, Council Member Campbell, for your leadership on thisissue. <BR><BR>With much of the Central Riverfront development completed, it is time tobring the same inspired vision, careful planning and long-term commitmentto the northern part of the river. I am asking the Planning Department andthe MCDA to make Upper Riverfront Redevelopment, in North and NortheastMinneapolis, a top priority. <BR><BR>The Upper River Citizens Advisory Committee, chaired by Michael Rainville,has already begun to explore how we can integrate the beauty of the riverinto the surrounding neighborhoods. Now we must complete that plan, emphasizingpublic access, environmental quality, and a thoughtful transition away fromuses that degrade the riverfront and its surrounding neighborhoods. In theirplace we want residential, recreational, commercial and industrial usesthat are more river-friendly. <BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><STRONG>Building Capacity with Housing</STRONG></H3>Now let's consider housing. The rate of single-family home-ownership isrelatively high in Minneapolis -- almost 90 percent. <BR><BR>But it's a different story in some neighborhoods: On the Near North sideit is 71 percent, a drop of 16 percent from 1984; in Phillips, it is 64percent -- a drop of 18 percent in just 12 years. <BR><BR>We are trying to build stability in our neighborhoods, but we will not succeeduntil we focus our resources strategically in the two neighborhoods withthe greatest housing and employment needs -- Phillips and the Near Northside. As I pointed out a few moments ago, the City of Minneapolis now hasexcellent job- and business-development tools. This year, let's put themto work in the neighborhoods that need them the most. <BR><BR>Minneapolis needs the federal government to be a strong housing partner.Last month at the U.S. Conference of Mayors, Henry Cisneros, Secretary ofHousing and Urban Development suggested that the federal government createa way for people to apply their Section 8 housing funds to the purchaseof a new house. This is the kind of innovative programming we need fromthe federal government -- real solutions that help people who are strugglingto improve their lives. <BR><BR>We must tap the resources of the great University we are privileged to havein our city to help us find solutions locally. I have begun discussionsabout creating a model of cooperation between residents of the GlendaleHousing Project and their local PICA/Headstart participants, and the Universityof Minnesota. We want to explore how to better the lives of these residentsand their children. We will look to our federal government partners to supportthis pilot project. <BR><BR>One of the things that keeps a downtown alive is a vigorous downtown residentialcommunity. Our downtown neighborhoods are already about 20,000 residents-strong-- in Loring and Elliot Park, and along the Mississippi Riverfront. We willfurther strengthen these great residential neighborhoods by introducinganother 1,500 residential units. Let me highlight a few. <BLOCKQUOTE>Sixty beautiful townhome condominiums at The Landings at SawMill Run, near the Plymouth Bridge; <BR><BR>Forty-one condominium lofts in the Northstar Woolen Mills building nearour newly restored Stone Arch Bridge;<BR><BR>Thirty-nine apartment units at the old Tension Envelope Building in theWarehouse district; <BR><BR>Twenty townhouses and 20 low-income apartments on the Marquette Block rightbehind Lourdes Square;<BR><BR>And at Heritage Landing in the Itasca area, 612 beautiful townhouse condominiums,which will be the largest homeowner development in Minneapolis!</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>This bricks-and-mortar investment is a solid vote of confidence in the futureof our downtown. I congratulate the Downtown Council, Chamber of Commerce,the Downtown Residents Association, and the City Council for their hardwork and continuing commitment in our great city and our great downtown.<BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><STRONG>Building Capacity with Education</STRONG></H3>Next, let us look at what we must do for education. In Minneapolis, it isthe School Board -- not the City -- that determines what happens insidethe school building. But the City can and must support the schools in anumber of ways. <BR><BR>One way is to make sure our children are prepared to learn and make thebest of their learning opportunities. In January the SEARCH Institute releasedan in-depth study of adolescent youth in Minneapolis that identified thedevelopmental assets that are absolutely crucial to youth development. Theyrange from experiencing family love and support to feeling safe; from doinghomework to having positive values. The report contained shocking news,however: The average young person in Minneapolis, regardless of race orgender, has fewer than half the assets needed to grow up strong and healthy.<BR><BR>Furthermore, the study produced stunningly convincing statistics to showthat youths who lack assets are more likely to be depressed, violent, andinvolved with drugs. The study makes it clear that the failure of the adultsin Minneapolis to care for their children is creating a problem of tragicproportions. <BR><BR>At the same time the study offers much hope. It makes it clear that thethings we must do to bring this youth tragedy to a close are not mysterious.Many are simple and obvious things, like reading to our children, makingsure children have a chance to see their grandparents, talking to neighborhoodyoungsters. There are other things organizations can do -- churches, neighborhoodgroups, businesses. <BR><BR>Today we are launching a campaign we want every Minneapolis adult to join-- a campaign to Invest in Children. The Youth Coordinating Board has printedup cards -- like little recipe cards -- with the list of things the studysuggests you can do to support our youth. There's a card for you if youare a parent, a neighbor, a teacher or a journalist; if you own a business,work for a non-profit, or are active in a church. We have them right outsidethe gym. I ask everyone here to pick one up. Study it, and use it to inspireyour own activities to change the life of a child. <BR><BR>Let me tell you the first thing the City is going to do to respond to thecall to Invest in Children. We must do a better job of engaging our youthin positive after-school activities. Places to Grow, another SEARCH Institutestudy, commissioned by my office, says we already have enough activitiesfor our youth -- the problem is that our young people just don't know aboutthem. Now, in this electronic age, there is no reason Minneapolis can'thave a hotline, so that any child old enough to use the phone can find activitiesthat are constructive, interesting and fun. This hotline must be up andrunning by June 1. <BR><BR>Education is not just for children. In the 21st Century, life-long educationwill be more important than ever. I am pleased that this year the MinneapolisPublic Library System will begin a renovation of the historic Hosmer Library,and part of this renovation will be a Technology Learning Center. The librarysystem will also be able, by the end of this year, to hook its customersup to the Internet and a vast array of other technological highways. <BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><STRONG>Building Capacity with Public Safety</STRONG></H3><BR>We have worked hard to create community schools for our children. But ina few neighborhoods, children are afraid to walk to those schools; and theirparents don't want to send them. Why? Because they are surrounded by boarded-upbuildings, crack houses, and sometimes even the sound of gunfire. A fewyears ago we created drug-free zones around our public schools. We havethe drug-free signs around the schools -- you've seen them. But let's behonest: What do they really mean? They represent good laws, but are thoselaws being used to the extent possible? <BR><BR>This year we must put real meaning behind those signs, real strategies towork around our schools and parks. I am asking the Police Chief and CityCoordinator to recommend how to use the total resources of the City to closedown crack houses, rehabilitate or tear down the boarded buildings aroundour schools and parks, and help in any other way to create real drug-freezones. Our children must be guaranteed safe passage as they walk to andfrom schools and parks! <BR><BR>Chief Olson has already directed his precinct commanders to work with eachschool principal to meet the school's specific safety needs. He has relievedschool liaison officers of their other duties to work exclusively with theschools. I am asking the other city departments to follow suit and makeour children a number-one priority. We are making major investments in communityschools. We must also invest time and resources in the communities thatsurround them. <BR><BR>Only a few years ago juvenile crime meant a joyride in a stolen car or aschoolyard fight. In 1995, it meant that 21 of our 97 homicides were committedby youth -- at a time when most other serious juvenile crimes were on thedecline. I asked our Health Department to analyze juvenile homicide, tohelp us understand why it is increasing. The Department's findings werepresented at an all-day community meeting attended by some 200 citizens,as well as by several Council Members. The Department is working with thosecitizens to identify how to intervene in what is, without a doubt, our community'smost disturbing, and dangerous, problem. <BR><BR>Most juvenile crime is committed right after children leave school, whenthey are unsupervised and have nothing constructive to do. I ask the MinneapolisSchool Board to consider changing the hours school is in session, so thatchildren can stay safely in school until their parents come home from work.We need to forge the link between school and after-school activities. Iam committed to finding resources to make this happen. <BR><BR>It is no secret that illegal drugs are driving much of today's crime, includingour high homicide rate. Because the drug problem is complex, affecting notonly public safety, but physical and mental health, and the welfare of entirefamilies, we have been working to coordinate the City's law-enforcementresources with Hennepin County's law enforcement, financial assistance andchemical health services. <BR><BR>Last year I announced a program in which officers making drug arrests refercocaine-addicted mothers to Hennepin County Chemical Dependency services.Progress was slow, but women did seek treatment through this program ona voluntary basis, and we learned that by integrating our anti-drug activitieswith the County's, we were on the right track. <BR><BR>We have also been conducting &quot;knock and talks.&quot; Officers fromSAFE and patrol units visit addresses where drug activity is suspected.If they are allowed inside, they provide referral information about Countychemical-dependency programs, and warn the parties that if they don't changetheir ways, they can expected to get busted. <BR><BR>Now I am proposing that we take another step with the County. Professionalswho work in this area believe that when drug activities are conducted inthe home, it is almost certain that household funds -- including assistancepayments -- are being mismanaged. We do know that a certain amount of publicassistance funds wind up in the hands of drug dealers. I am asking HennepinCounty to review the cases of clients convicted of drug charges to determineif there is mismanagement of public funds, and if there is, to provide futureassistance mostly in the form of vendor payments for rent, utilities andother necessities, instead of cash. <BR><BR>In addition, because there are chemically dependent recipients of publicassistance who want help in getting over their addiction, I propose thatwe step up our efforts to encourage them to join the vendor program on avoluntary basis. Some people may view this program as punitive, but we havea drug crisis in our city, and we must take bold steps. The vendor programwill help ensure that the first of the month will no longer be the day thedrug man gets paid in Minneapolis! <BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><STRONG>Regional Issues</STRONG> </H3><BR>Because Minneapolis is the economic gateway for the region, it faces issuesthat are regional in scope, and require regional cooperation. This yearwe will face four issues that have enormous impact on the role the city,the state and the region will play in the global economy. <BR><BR>The first is the expansion of the Convention Center. Last year, one outof every 20 Minnesota businesses exhibited at the Convention Center -- and80 percent were from outside Minneapolis! Convention Center visitors fromoutside Minnesota spent $129 million here last year, and, if the facilityis expanded, they will contribute $14 million in tax revenue every year.<BR><BR>No wonder Twin Cities Business Monthly recently reported that ConventionCenter expansion is one of the top legislative priorities of Twin Citiesbusiness leaders. I call on business leaders throughout the region to helpMinneapolis get the Convention center expansion included in the 1996 legislativebonding bill. The expansion creates 4,000 new jobs that pay good wages andbenefits. Who could be against that? <BR><BR>In 1995 I appointed an Airport Task Force to identify all of the vestedinterests Minneapolis has in the airport: economic, social and aesthetic.The Task Force will present its recommendations to the City Council on February13. <BR><BR>It is clear that the debate about the location of the airport will cometo a conclusion soon -- I personally hope not before the public has itssay. Whatever the decision, Minneapolis must be assured that substantialresources and tools will be set aside for further sound insulation and otherneighborhood noise-mitigation efforts. And top that off with Stage III aircraft.Now! <BR><BR>Another important regional issue is transit. Last fall the Metropolitanarea experienced its first transit strike in more than 25 years. Althoughthe popular perception was that not many problems were created by the strike,city residents suffered. People couldn't get to work, go shopping or getto medical appointments. We understand that the MCTO needs better funding.But that funding problem must not be solved at the expense of people whohave no alternative to public transportation! <BR><BR>The strike was a wake-up call. It was warning us that that we must movequickly to secure a stable, independent funding source for metropolitantransit, such as the general sales tax; that we must design a transit systemto meet the needs of the people who need it the most, including those inthe city who want to get to suburban jobs, a system that provides an attractivealternative to the private car. The City of Minneapolis will be at the Legislatureworking for this kind of resolution. <BR><BR>The financial strength of Minneapolis has permitted us -- over several decades-- to play a key role in supporting the sports and entertainment that contributeso significantly to the state and regional economies. As the baseball stadiumdiscussion at the Legislature continues, the City must move forward andidentify the most appropriate location for the new ballpark. I stronglybelieve that Minneapolis has the infrastructure to support new sports andentertainment facilities. The stadium must be in downtown Minneapolis! <BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><STRONG>Conclusion</STRONG></H3><BR>As I conclude this State of the City Address, I want to remind you of afew things. In the past two years we have worked hard to develop the toolswe need to create capacity for the 21st Century. Now we have arrived atthe point where we can put those tools to work. <BR><BR>We created clear housing principles and powerful finance tools. Now we mustuse them strategically to build stability, especially in the neighborhoodsthat need it the most. <BR><BR>We strengthened the MCDA and focused it on serving businesses that havetheir roots here and will provide jobs for our residents. Now we must focusits work even more closely on the industries that will figure prominentlyon the horizon of the 21st Century, and work more closely with those neighborhoodswith high unemployment. <BR><BR>We are creating community schools for our children. Now we must build thecommunity structures -- in our homes, neighborhoods, churches and localbusinesses -- to support them so they will be successful. <BR><BR>We are reforming and decentralizing the Minneapolis Police Department. Thosechanges allow the department to enter partnerships with citizens on theneighborhood level so we can all fight crime together and make our citysafe. <BR><BR>We cannot do this alone. Now, more than ever, we need the support and collaborativeefforts of the City Council and our citizens to keep this city great. Let'sdo it! <BR><BR>Thank you. <BR><BR><BR><HR><BR><BR><H5>Email your comments and questions to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I></H5></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
