<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>Winter Parking Ban 1996-1997</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<H2>City Bans Parking on Even Side of Residential Streets</H2>

<P>December 17, 1996 -- Due to high levels of snow accumulation, Minneapolis
officials have determined that it will be necessary to ban parking on the
even side of residential streets for the remainder of the winter.</P>

<P>The ban will begin at 8 a.m. Wednesday, December 18, when the current
Snow Emergency ends. It will remain in effect until April 1 or until the
City is confident that the snow season is over.</P>

<P>&quot;We realize this will inconvenience many Minneapolis residents,&quot;
says Public Works Director David Sonnenberg, &quot;but the welfare and safety
of the public in terms of our ability to get emergency vehicles through
the streets must take precedence over the inconvenience.&quot;</P>

<P>Sonnenberg adds that last winter was the first time since the winter of
1991-92 that the City had to restrict parking to one side of the street.
&quot;We have already received as much snowfall this season as we had by
mid-January last winter,&quot; he says.</P>

<P>During Snow Emergencies, cars will be allowed to park on the even side
of the street on the odd-side plowing day. Vehicles parked on the even side
any other time will be subject to tagging and towing. Enforcement will begin
immediately.</P>

<P>Complete Snow Emergency parking information is always available on 348-SNOW,
the City's 23-hour hotline, as well as City Cable Channel 34 and the City
web site at <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/index.html">www.ci.mpls.mn.us</A>.</P>

<P>To ensure public safety after heavy snowfalls, Sonnenberg also reminds
residents and business owners to clear their sidewalks down to the pavement,
across the full width, and all the way to the corner after the plows have
gone by for the last time. City ordinances require that sidewalks of single-family
homes and duplexes be cleared within 24 hours after a snowfall. Sidewalks
in commercial areas and adjacent to apartment buildings must be cleared
within four daytime hours.</P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=-1>For more information:</FONT></P>

<P>Brian Lokkesmoe<BR>
Public Works<BR>
673-3316
</BODY>
