<HEAD>

<TITLE>THE HOMESTEAD CLASSIFICATION</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS ABOUT HOMESTEADING A PROPERTY</H2>

<H4>Why do people apply for a homestead classification?</H4>

<P>
The State of Minnesota encourages home ownership by providing
owner-occupied properties reduced property taxes. The reduction
is very beneficial to the property owner. The owner of a homestead
property valued under $72,000 pays 54% less taxes than a non-homestead
property. As the property value increases, the percentage of reduction
decreases. 
<H4>Who can receive this benefit?</H4>

<P>
If you own real property and you, or a <A HREF="relative.html">qualifying relative</A>, occupy
the property on the 1st of December, you may apply for homestead
status.
<H4>What does ownership mean?</H4>

<P>
You must have a valid deed granting you title to the property.
In order to be recognized as a valid deed, the deed must be registered
with the Hennepin County Registrar of Deed. 
<H4>What does occupy mean?</H4>

<P>
You and all other owners must use the property as your main residence,
in other words, you must live there. Temporary and token occupancy
is not considered sufficient to receive homestead treatment. If
more than one person owns the property and any of the owners do
not reside at the property, then the property may receive a <U>fractional</U>
homestead classification.
<H4>Can a relative homestead a property for me?</H4>

<P>
<A HREF="relative.html">Qualifying relatives</A> may become substitute occupants for the property
owner. <BR>
Qualifying relatives include <U>only</U> the following: parent,
child, stepparent, stepchild, grandparent, grandchild, brother,
sister, uncle, and aunt.
<H4>I own an apartment building, can I homestead it?</H4>

<P>
Just about any type of property that can be lived in can be classified
as homestead. However, unlike common residential properties, apartment
buildings with four or more units and other types of properties
are usually limited to receiving the homestead treatment on the
first $72,000 of market value.
<H4>How do I apply for a homestead classification?</H4>

<P>
Inform the City Assessor that you own a property and that you,
or a qualifying relative, occupy the property. Provide the City
Assessor with documentation to prove your claim. This may done
by fax, mail, or in person.
<H4>When do I need to apply?</H4>

<P>
The sooner the better after purchasing and moving into your home.
If you purchase and occupy non-homestead property before December
1, and apply for homestead treatment before December 15, then
the homestead level of taxation will begin in the next year.
<H4>Where can I get more information on homesteads?</H4>

<P>
Please, call or write us. Our address and phone number follow:
<P>
City Assessor - Homesteads Telephone: 673-2382<BR>
309 - 2nd Avenue South - Room 100 Fax: 673-3538<BR>
Minneapolis, MN 55401-2234
</BODY>

