<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#040028" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><H1><CENTER>Institutional Network (I-NET) Expansion Negotiations </CENTER></H1><H2><CENTER>Outline </CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><A HREF="#Intro">Introduction</A><A HREF="#At Stake"><BR>What's at Stake<BR></A><A HREF="#Benefits">Benefits and Drawbacks<BR></A><A HREF="#Issues">Outstanding Issues<BR></A><A HREF="#Direction">Direction<BR></A><BR><I>Presented by the City of Minneapolis and Paragon Cable</I></CENTER><P><A NAME="Intro"></A><HR><H2>Introduction </H2>Representatives of the City of Minneapolis, MTN and Paragon Cable have meta number of times to explore issues of mutual concern and benefit in lightof accelerating change in telecommunications technology, competition andderegulation. Discussions have led to a greater appreciation of the roleand expertise of each party and how each may continue to support the otherin the spirit of the franchise that has existed since 1983. <BR><BR>All parties are in the process of negotiating a lease agreement, whereinthe City will lease to Paragon all PEG (public, educational, government)access channel capacity until the year 2004. The City through the MTN willreserve four channels on the 'A' cable (32,33,34,35) and eight channelson the 'B' cable (32,33,34,35,39,42,46,49) for video PEG access programming.Under these terms, the City will be returning 18 channels to Paragon. <BR><BR>In exchange, Paragon will expand the City's existing Institutional networkby adding a total of 25 new sites, will construct a dedicated fiber opticbased voice, video and data system for the Public Schools and constructa fiber connection from Paragon head-end directly to the MTN. <BR><A NAME="At Stake"></A><HR><H2>What's at Stake </H2><B>The City Will Receive </B><BR>The City of Minneapolis will receive: A fiber optic/coaxial network connectingCity Hall with: <UL>  <LI>MCDA   <LI>2nd, 3rd, 4th and 5th Precincts   <LI>Traffic Center   <LI>Street Department   <LI>Equipment Division   <LI>Convention Center   <LI>Minneapolis Telecommunications Network (MTN) </UL><BR>Paragon values this installed infrastructure at $354, 520* Paragon shallprovide 24 hour a day maintenance for the network, which Paragon valuesat $75,000 annually* A fee from Paragon for use of the 18 channels. Thefranchise designates it as a nominal fee.** <H5>*No independent valuation currently exists <BR>**Formula for setting the &quot;nominal fee&quot; is yet to be determined</H5><BR><B>The Minneapolis Public Schools will receive</B><BR>Fiber I-Net connections to seven (7) schools including: <UL>  <LI>Anthony   <LI>Sanford   <LI>Anwatin   <LI>Northeast   <LI>Folwell   <LI>Olson Middle   <LI>Franklin </UL>Fiber replacements of existing Coax I-Net connections to: <UL>  <LI>North High School   <LI>Roosevelt High School </UL>The following five (5) high schools will remain on their existing I-Netconnections but will get transmission equipment to connect the schools together:<BR>Edison <BR>Henry <BR>Southwest <BR>South <BR>Washburn <BR>A fiber I-Net connection will be installed at the Work Opportunity Center.The District Service Center, currently on fiber, will receive new switchingequipment. The Fire Training Center will remain on coax and receive newequipment. All seventeen (17) sites will be upgraded to two-way video capability,allowing full interactive and remote learning participation from each site.<BR><BR>Paragon figures this as an initial projected cost of $495,597*. <H5>*No independent valuation currently exists </H5><BR><B>The MTN will receive</B><BR>Paragon Cable will build and maintain fiber optic connections between theMTN's St. Anthony Main (SAM) facilities and the cable system head-end onPlymouth Avenue North. With this fiber link, the technical quality willimprove and allow the MTN to continue to broadcast live and with remotefeeds. Paragon's installation of the fiber will allow MTN to playback tapesfrom their SAM location with virtually no loss in signal to the cable head-end.Paragon has agreed to pay for the move and consolidation of MTN's playbackequipment and staff. MTN will have high speed access to the Internet atthe Supercomputer Center. This will allow MTN to increase their serviceto non-profit organizations. <BR><BR>In addition, Paragon has agreed not to challenge MTN fundraising relatedto its non-profit Internet services. Paragon Cable will continue semi-annualpayments to the MTN. <BR><BR>Paragon values this investment at $243, 410* <H5>*No independent valuation currently exists </H5><BR><B>The Minneapolis Community and Residents will receive</B><BR>An Expanded Institutional Network, which will give residents more efficientand varied methods to communicate with City offices and staff. More cableprogramming will be added to the cable service, as Paragon receives morechannels. Paragon will add 5 additional cable programs per year. New commercialservices being considered include: The Home and Garden Channel, the InternationalChannel, MS/NBC, Fox News, The Outdoor Network, America's Health Network,Speed Vision and The Classic Sports Network. High speed access to the Internetfor non-profit organizations through the MTN and the Supercomputer Center.Future competition in the marketplace. As Paragon becomes more competitivewith US WEST for residential services such as voice, data (Internet) andvideo programming, prices may lower and the variety of services will increase.<BR><A NAME="Benefits"></A><HR><H2>Benefits and Drawbacks</H2><B>How City Government and City Schools will Benefit with a High Speed Network</B><BR>The system will meet the communication needs of a growing City and Schoolorganization, as well as the growing communication expectations of its citizensand students. Exclusive, high reliability lines at key locations for theCity and the Schools will improve employee productivity and enhance public/studentsafety. <BR><BR>Schools will use the expanded Institutional Network to create &quot;virtual&quot;classrooms and alternative ways of reaching students and managing schools(3 to 7 years out). The system for the Schools, City and MTN will each beindependent, but will be able to be interconnected and expanded. <BR><BR>Both the City and the Schools will have a high-speed internet connectionthrough the MTN and the Supercomputer Center. <BR><BR>The City will use the expanded I-net for high speed communications. TheI-net could replace pieces of CityNet and it could save the City rentalcharges from companies such as US WEST and Norstan (3 to 7 years out). Forexample, the City could save $50,000 annually in US WEST data line chargesin 1997. The City and the Schools could save more in maintenance/lease costsin 1998 and beyond* <H5>*We do not have accurate estimates at this time </H5><BR><B>Paragon's benefits will include</B><BR>Relief from current franchise language that obligates Paragon to providethe City with 25% of its channel capacity for public access programming.Paragon will receive eighteen (18) more channels which will allow them toadd more programming, which will in turn increase Paragon's revenue. <BR><BR>The US telecommunications market is in the midst of tremendous and rapidchange -- toward competition within and a convergence of cable TV, computerand telephone industries. The additional channels will help Paragon staycompetitive with entrants into the telecommunications marketplace such assatellite and microwave multi- channels providers. Paragon will have a highermarket value -- should Time Warner, Inc. decide to sell the Paragon system.Currently, it is not in the interest of Paragon to invest in its systemand increase its market value, where 25% of the capacity is reserved forthe public. <BR><BR>Paragon will receive back 2,320 square feet of office space in the 801 Plymouthlocation. (The space is currently used by the MTN for their tape playback.)Paragon will be released from the franchise obligation to provide FM service.Paragon has agreed to provide an antenna allowing receipt of these signalsto interested subscribers. <BR><BR><B>What is the City of Minneapolis giving up? </B><BR>Minneapolis will be giving up 18 channels, by giving up the franchise languagethat requires 25% of system capacity be reserved for public access* TheCity does retain the right to claim additional PEG channels when needed.With additional funding**, these 18 channels could be used by the City foradditional programming such as: <UL>  <LI>Stolen goods preview channel   <LI>Live phone-in counseling sessions   <LI>City Council Committee meetings   <LI>Interactive voting channel </UL>(These unused channels have little or no &quot;market value&quot; to theCity because according to our franchise agreement, we cannot use them tocompete against Paragon or lease them to a Paragon competitor. We do nothave the revenue potential from non-profit sources.) <BR><BR>The City would also give up 2,320 square feet of office space located atParagon's head-end at 801 Plymouth Avenue North. <H5>*The nature of this lease back is an undecided issue <BR>** This additional funding could come from the 1.5M franchise fee the Cityreceives annually from Paragon. Currently, these dollars are funneled directlyinto the General Fund. </H5><A NAME="Issues"></A><HR><H2>Outstanding Issues </H2>(1) Terms of the Lease-back arrangement. Does the City want to give up the25% franchise language? <BR>(2) Fair Use Value for Paragon using the City's eighteen (18) channels.<BR>(3) I-net Ownership <BR>(4) Service Level Agreement--The City must be able in insure quality ofnetwork &quot;up-time.&quot; Maintenance requirements must be agreed upon.<BR><A NAME="Direction"></A><A HREF="#Direction"> </A><HR><H2>Direction to City Staff By November 1, 1996</H2><UL>  <LI>Conduct an independent study of Time Warner, Inc.'s business strategyand Time Warner, Inc.'s projected value of the 18 channels. This independentstudy will be conducted by Larry Greenberg at a cost of $10,000 and willallow the City to negotiate a channel usage fee that reflects a fair andreasonable price, using a non- disclosure approach.   <LI>Complete a detailed analysis of future cost/benefit of the fiber I-Net.   <LI>Resolve the terms of the lease-back arrangement.   <LI>Propose an interim agreement, wherein Paragon can immediately beginconstruction on laying fiber to the police precincts. If no final agreementis reached, the City will reimburse Paragon for actual construction costsincurred.   <LI>Resolve the I-Net ownership issue. Write a service level agreementthat insures a highly reliable I-net will be constructed. <BR></UL><HR><A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/">Home</A> | <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/hot">What'sHot</A> | <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/events.html">Events</A> | <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/topics">Topics</A>| <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/departments">Departments</A> | <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/publications">Publications</A>| <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/friends.html">Other Sites</A> <HR>Copyright&copy; 1996, City of Minneapolis. See <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/disclaimer.html">Disclaimer</A>for legal information.<BR>Maintained by the <A HREF="http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us/rangers.html">CyberspaceRangers</A>. Updated Tuesday, September 10, 1996. <BR><BR>Comments or suggestions? Send email to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I>.</BODY></HTML>
