<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>On The Agenda</TITLE><!-- Date: Monday, January 22, 1996  4:05 PM  Brian Wold, 673-3821, for Bill Carter--></HEAD><CENTER><H1>On The Agenda</H1><H2><I>City of Minneapolis Actions & Issues  -  January 19, 1996 </I></H2></CENTER><p><P><hr><P><BODY><H2>City Retains Triple-A Bond Rating</H2><P>Both Moody's and Standard & Poor's have reaffirmed their triple-A ratings on City of Minneapolis general obligation bonds. Triple-A is the highest credit rating category for municipal bonds. <p>The rating agencies noted that the City reduced its overall bonded indebtedness by $38 million in 1995. The reduction occurred mostly in tax increment bonds. The City's debt levels are expected to continue declining as future borrowing will be largely limited to routine improvements.   <p>The rating agencies said that Minneapolis has maintained its position as the economic center of the growing seven-county metropolitan area. The city's tax base is recovering from an oversupply of office space. Residential values continue to increase and commercial values have increased significantly. Estimated fair market value of taxable property increased 14.3 percent from $11.9 billion in 1994 to $13.6 billion in 1995. <p>"Minneapolis has remained strong through prudent financial management," said John Moir, City Finance Officer. "By reaffirming the City's AAA/Aaa bond ratings, the rating agencies have shown complete confidence in the City's financial management controls and practices."<p>Mayor Sayles Belton says she hopes that the Governor and the legislators pay attention to the ratings reports. "Moody's describes us as the economic center of this region," she said. "Our 8 percent of the population pays 11 percent of the state's income taxes and 18 percent of corporate taxes. Twelve percent of the state's work force is employed in Minneapolis. This city carries more than its own weight and it's in the state's best interest to keep our city strong."<p>Minneapolis is one of only two cities its size to hold AAA rating from both Moody's and Standard & Poor's. The other city is Charlotte, North Carolina.<p>The City sold $68.5 million of general obligation refunding bonds Thursday. The current low interest rates will reduce the interest expense for Minneapolis taxpayers.State of the City set for Feb. 7Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton will deliver her 1996 State of the City Address at 5 p.m. Wednesday, February 7, at Jenny Lind School, 5025 Bryant Avenue North. The address is free and open to the public. It will also be aired on City Cable 34.`<P><hr><H2>Jan. 12 City Council Actions</H2>At its regular meeting on January 12 the Minneapolis City Council:<p>- Reappointed members of the Public Housing Authority and concurred with the Mayor and City Council President on reappointment and appointment of members of the Senior Citizen Advisory Committee.<p>- Authorized acceptance of a $352,000 federal  grant for the Multi-jurisdictional Narcotics Enforcement Task Force and executed related agreements for Hennepin County and City matching funds.<p>- Denied rental dwelling licenses at 2312-14 North 6th St and 10 East 15th St.<p>- Approved demolition of nuisance structures at 3631 Queen Avenue North, 2911 Morgan Av N, 2706 13th Av S and 417 26th Av N.<p>- Authorized an agreement with the Minnesota Department of Health to implement the Immunization Action Plan for 1996.<p>- Authorized staff to participate in a feasibility study of improving street connection from the Parade area to the Bassetts Creek valley and directed that effected neighborhoods be involved.<p>- Accepted donation from the Jay & Rose Phillips Family Foundation to support the Phillips Neighborhood Gateway project.<p>- Allocated a fixed amount to each City Council office with unexpended funds to be returned to the General Fund, recognized additional staff in the Council President's office.<p>- Approved City Council officers and committee assignments for 1996. Please see accompanying article.<p> <p> This is a partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or for details on specific actions, call 673-3130.<P><hr><H2>1996 City Council Officers and Committee Assignments</H2><I>City Council President</I>- Jackie Cherryhomes<br> <I>Council Vice President</I>  - Joe Biernat<br> <I>Council Majority Leader</I>- Joan Campbell<P><B>Claims Committee</B>   Chair, Herron   Members, Schulstad, Minn. Meets at 9:30 a.m. on Mondays of the first week of the second cycle of Council meetings. Coordinators - Jackie Graack, 673-2046, and Julie Norrid, 673-2296.<p> <B>Community Development</B>   Chair - Niland   Members - Scott, Biernat, Herron, McDonald, Mead. Meets at 9:30 a.m. on Mondays of the first week of the first cycle and at 5 p.m. Mondays of the first week of the second cycle. Coordinator - Micola Foley, 673-3131.<p> <B>Intergovernmental Relations</B>   Chair - Rainville   Members - Dziedzic, Campbell, Cherryhomes, Thurber, Minn. Meets at 2 p.m. Thursdays of the first week of each cycle. Coordinator - Jan Belsaas, 673-3132.Public Safety & Regulatory Services    Chair - Biernat    Members - Cherryhomes, Herron, Thurber, McDonald, Mead. Meets at 1:30 p.m. Wednesdays of the first week of each cycle.<p> <B>Transportation & Public Works</B>   Chair - Dziedzic   Members - Rainville, Campbell, Scott, Niland, Minn. Meets at 9:30 a.m. Thursdays of the first week of each cycle. Coordinator - Graack.<p> <B>Ways & Means/Budget</B>   Chair - Campbell   Members - Rainville, Dziedzic, Cherryhomes, Thurber, Schulstad. Meets at 9:30 a.m. Tuesdays of the second week of each cycle. Coordinator - Norrid.<p> <B>Zoning & Planning</B>   Chair - Scott    Members - Niland, Biernat, McDonald, Mead, Minn. Meets at 1:30 p.m. Tuesdays of the first week of each cycle. Coordinator - Irene Homo, 673-2219.<p> <B>Executive Committee</B>   Members - Mayor Sayles Belton, City Council President Cherryhomes, and Council Members Niland, Herron and Schulstad. Meets a 9:30 a.m. Wednesdays every week. Coordinator - Jan Hrncir, 673-3130.<p> <B>Elections Committee</B>  Chair - Biernat    Members - All Council Members. Meets at call of the chair. Coordinator - Hrncir.<p> <B>Rules Committee</B>  Chair - Rainville    Members - All Council Members. Meets at call of the chair. Coordinator - Hrncir.<p> <B>Taxes Committee</B>  Chair - Schulstad    Members - All Council Members. Meets at call of the chair. Coordinator - Hrncir.<P><hr><H2>City Council Committee Item</H2>The Community Development Committee will hold public hearings at 9:30 a.m. Monday, January 29, in 319 Citry Hall to consider at ordinance amendment pertaining to MCDA administrative procedures and proposed actions related to the Camden Medical Facility site. More information: 673-3131.<P><hr><H2>City & County Agree on Waste</H2>City of Minneapolis and Hennepin County officials announced an agreement -in-principle on solid waste disposal at a January 18 news conference. The agreement avoids a potentials lawsuit by the County against the City. If approved by the County Board and City Council, the agreement provides that the City will deliver solid waste collected in Minneapolis to the County, as opposed to shipping it to out-of-state landfills. <p>"I never lost faith that the City and County would work out their differences without going to court," said Mayor Sayles Belton. "What happen in our negotiations was that both sides listened to each other, and both gave alittle bit. The City recognized that it was part of the County's disposal system and therefore would participate. That makes this agreement realistic. The County recognized that it should charge the City a reasonable fee. That makes it fair."<p>Videotape of the news conference will air on City Cable 34 Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays at 6 p.m. for the next several weeks. <P><hr><H2>City Cable 34 Highlight</H2>City Beat, hosted by Kent Robbins, features Assistant City Engineer Brian Lokkesmoe on the parking ban and Planning Director Paul Farmer on The Minneapolis Plan. Tuesdays at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 9 p.m,, Saturdays at 7 :30 p.m.<P><hr><H2>Minneapolis Plan Workshop Feb.24</H2>All Minneapolis residents are invited to participate in a half-day workshop to develop citywide solutions on issues affecting neighborhoods.  The event will take place at the new Whittier Park building at 26th Street and Grand Avenue South from 8:30 a.m. to 12:45 p.m. on Saturday, February 24. <p>The Minneapolis Neighborhood Revitalization Program, the Minneapolis Planning Department and neighborhood leaders from across the city will discuss Economic Development, Community Building, Education, Safety, Housing, Transportation, and Parks and Environment.  The general session will break into two groups to address the  issues.<P><hr><H2>Open Appointments</H2> Positions are open on the following boards and commissions. Applicants must be residents of Minneapolis except under special conditions. Application forms and detailed position announcements are available from the City Clerk. Call 673-2735. Applications must be filed by the due date.<p>Five positions are open on the Minneapolis Advisory Committee on Drug & Alcohol Problems. The 21-member committee advises the Mayor and Coiuncil on chemical dependency and treatment isssues. More information from 673-2735. Deadline: February 9.<BLOCKQUOTE>City of Minneapolis, Office of Public Affairs<br> 323M City Hall, 350 South 5th Street<br> Minneapolis, MN 55415-1300</BLOCKQUOTE><P><hr><H2>Use Salt Carefully</H2>Winter is here.  With winter comes snowstorms.  And on the heels of the snow comes the salt.  It seems to be everywhere - on your car, your sidewalk, your clothes and shoes.<p>Just how much salt is used in Minneapolis each winter?  That depends on the amount of snowfall and the weather conditions.  Last winter was mild, with little snowfall, and more than 18,000 tons of salt were used.  In addition, over 18,000 tons of sand were applied.<p>The effects of this salt use are most evident on our cars. In fact, half of all automobile corrosion is due to road salt. However, the metal in bridges and underground cables can fall victim to salt corrosion. Roadside trees, shrubs, and grasses are also damaged by salt.<p>Aquatic vegetation can be injured by the chloride in salt.  This occurs when runoff is channeled into small lakes, streams, and wetlands.  With the accumulation of salt on paved surfaces, this threat increases in the spring.  As the snow melts, salt and sand are washed off.  These high concentrations can be toxic to aquatic vegetation.  <p>While there are alternatives to salt, such as potassium chloride, calcium chloride and calcium magnesium acetate, salt remains the best option for ice removal due to its high deicing ability, its usability at low temperatures, and its low cost. The best way to reduce the impact on our water is to reduce our overall salt use.<p>You can minimize your use of salt by following these simple tips:<BLOCKQUOTE> <B>Sun</B>- Use salt on sunny days when it is most effective.<P> <B>Temperature</B>- Use salt at temperatures of 15 degrees F or higher.<P> <B> Shovel</B> - Remove snow as soon as possible after snowfall, before it becomes packed down and icy.  Remember, city ordinances require that sidewalks of single family homes and duplexes be cleared within 24 hours after a snowfall.  <P> <B>Prevent</B> - If snowfall is to be followed by rain, leave snow down to absorb the rain and prevent icy conditions from forming.  Be sure to remove the snow as soon as the rain stops.<P> <B>Sand</B> - Use sand more often.  Call 673-2441 to get your free sidewalk sand.  Sand should be swept up around your home and reused to keep it out of waterways. <P> <B>Store</B> - Keep unused sand or salt in covered buckets.<P> <B>Sweep</B> - Clean up any spilled or excess sand or salt and use it another time.<P> <B>Chip</B> - Get out and chip away at the ice on your sidewalk.  You might even find out that you enjoy the cool, crisp winter air.</BLOCKQUOTE> <P><hr>Questions or comments? Send email to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I>.<p><hr><p><H6><I>ON THE AGENDA</I> provides information on issues, programs and actions of the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-2011. Prepared for the Web by Brian Wold. For sign language interpreting call TTY 673-3250. Available in alternative formats. This is Issue 8, Volume 12. The next issue will be February 2. Please send address changes to Public Affairs, 323M City Hall, 55415, or fax to 673-3250.</H6></BODY></HTML>
