 meeting on January 26 the Minneapolis City Council:<P>-- Approved contract with Minnesota Department of Health for Project LID (Lower Infant Deaths); City will conduct a community-based infant mortality review from January 1996 through December 1997.<P>-- Approved agreement with Project Offstreets to provide AIDS prevention and risk reduction services to homeless and sexually exploited adolescents.<P>-- Approved agreement with Hennepin County Medical Center for continuation of physician and midwife services through 1996.<P>-- Approved demolition of nuisance structure at 2203 Lyndale Av N.<P>-- Designated locations for the 1996 Non-Residential Paving Program; projects are North Loop Commercial, Johnson St NE and Hennepin/Lyndale Realignment.<P>-- Authorized short-term agreement with Hennepin County for disposal of solid waste, pending negotiation of long-term agreement.<P>-- Granted block party permit to the Mill City Music Festival of the Arts for a Labor Day weekend event in the Warehouse District that will feature local and national musical talent.<P>This is a partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or for details on specific actions, call 673-3130.<HR><H3>Open Appointments</H3><P>Positions are open on the following boards and commissions. Applicants must be residents of Minneapolis except under special conditions. Application forms and detailed position announcements are available from the City Clerk. Call 673-2735. Applications must be filed by the due date.<P>-- Five positions are open on the Minneapolis Advisory Committee on Drug & Alcohol Problems. The 21-member committee advises the Mayor and Council on chemical dependency and treatment issues. More information from 673-2735. Deadline: February 9.<P>-- One position is now open on the Shingle Creek Watershed Management Commission. Nine cities within the watershed each appoint a representative and an alternate to the commission. The commission is responsible for setting 