<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>OTA 2/15/96</TITLE><!-- Date: Friday, February 16, 1996  4:16 PM --></HEAD><BODY><H1>ON THE AGENDA</H1><P><H2>City of Minneapolis Actions and IssuesFebruary 15, 1996</H2><P>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions of the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. For sign language interpreting call TTY 673-3250. Available in alternative formats. This is Issue 10, Volume 12. The next issue will be March 1. <P><HR><H3>Council Improves Collaboration Between Planning and MCDA</H3>On February 9, the Minneapolis City Council approved an ordinance to improve collaboration between the City's planning and development programs and streamline its development operations. The ordinance requires cooperation and collaboration between the MCDA and the City Planning Department. The MCDA operates the City's development program while the Planning Department is responsible for strategic planning programs. <P>Provisions of the ordinance include:<BLOCKQUOTE>- The MCDA will work with the Planning Department each year to present a report evaluating the effectiveness of MCDA projects and programs, allowing for better strategic planning. - Teams that include staff from MCDA as well as Planning and other City departments will review significant development proposals. The City Council will have substantially less involvement in daily agency management, but it will approve the strategic plans and the annual MCDA budget. - The MCDA executive director will have the authority to implement projects. The ordinance broadens the executive director's authority to include making offers on properties, settling condemnation actions, entering into citizen participation contracts, and increasing or decreasing personnel within an approved budget.</BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR><H3>Home Tour Seeks Volunteers</H3>When more than 40 Minneapolis and Saint Paul homeowners open their doors to visitors May 4 and 5, thousands of people will get a look at the quality and diversity of city living. Tour organizers are seeking volunteers to help promote city living and ensure that the tour runs smoothly. Homes will be open on Saturday, May 4, from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., and Sunday, May 5, from 1 to 5 p.m. Volunteers spend a half day in a home in their area, greeting and monitoring visitors. Beyond a belief in the quality of city living, no special expertise is needed. To volunteer, call 673-3821.<P><HR><H3>Recycling Calendars To Be Sent </H3>City residents will receive recycling calendars by mid-March. The City's Division of Solid Waste and Recycling explained that the delay was caused by negotiations for the City's recycling processing contract. The old contract ended December 31, 1995. "The problem was that we wanted to add boxboard, office paper, and mail; but the vendors all had different specifications," explains Jack Yuzna, Assistant Director of Solid Waste and Recycling. "We did not want to tell our customers one thing, and then change the recycling guidelines a few months later."<P>The new contract should yield an extra $300,000 in recycling revenues this year. The Division of Solid Waste and Recycling says that this, along with the reduced garbage tipping fee at the incinerator, will mean no fee increase for Solid Waste and Recycling services in 1996. For information about Solid Waste and Recycling, call 673-2917. <P> <HR><H3>February 9 City Council Actions</H3>At its regular meeting on February 9 the Minneapolis City Council:- Directed staff to negotiate development terms for North Star Woolen Mill Residential Project.- Approved actions related to MCDA and Planning Department procedures. Please see accompanying story.- Set City's position related to items before the Legislature as follows: 1) City's crime prevention priorities, 2) City's opposition to proposed vacant building legislation, 3) City's support of proposed Historic Preservation Tax Increment Subdistrict legislation, 4) City's opposition to proposed legislation related to tobacco sales to minors that would reduce local efforts.3)    Supported a public/private partnership for development of YWCA and Urban Sports Center. - Approved appointments to the Minneapolis Advisory Committee on People with Disabilities, Citizens' Environmental Advisory Committee, and Minneapolis Television Network.- Approved demolition of nuisance structure at 1820 West Broadway.- Approved an option for the taxicab lottery process.- Authorized acceptance of funds from the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation and the Minneapolis Foundation for the Youth Homicide Forum.- Approved a memorandum of understanding regarding neighborhood commitments of NRP funds to support the demolition of boarded buildings and authorized agreements necessary to implement activities.- Authorized a cooperative agreement with the Park Board for design and construction of the Bassett Creek Trail Project.- Authorized City participation in pollution cleanup activities at the Schnitzer Iron and Metal site.- Approved submission of 12 applications seeking funding for park projects from the Legislative Commission on Minnesota Resources.- Approved the following actions related to Victim/Witness and Domestic Abuse Advocacy services: 1) Issuance of an RFP for provision of victim/witness services in the City Attorney's office, 2) Establishment of a working group to develop an RFP for provision of domestic abuse advocacy services, 3) Authorization for the Domestic Abuse Project (DAP) to continue advocacy services until a permanent provider is selected, 4) Providing funding for interim DAP services.- Adopted the City's draft comments regarding the Draft Environmental Impact Statement on the Dual Track Airport Planning Process.- Endorsed the continuum of care planning effort recommended by the Task Force on Homeless Adults and Families.- Adopted modifications to the Camden Redevelopment Plan related to the Camden Medical Facility.<P>This is a partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or for details on specific actions, call 673-3130.<P><HR><H3>Students Play Ball with Minneapolis PAL</H3>The Minneapolis Police Athletic League's first basketball season is off to a great start. The League has five girls' and eight boys' teams of Minneapolis students ages 7 to 14. The Minneapolis Police Department provides coaches and jerseys. Games are every Monday and Thursday at 2:30 p.m. at Folwell and Franklin Middle Schools. The Minneapolis PAL, which was formed six months ago, is part of a national organization of police officers working with youth and their communities. Its purpose is to promote respect through athletic and recreational activities. <P><HR><H3>Parks Accepting Reservations March 4</H3>It's not too early to start thinking about spring and picnicking in City parks. The Minneapolis Park and Recreation Board's Special Services Division will begin accepting reservations for outdoor picnic area covered shelters beginning March 4 in person and March 5 by phone. Permits can be obtained for facilities at Beard's Plaissance, Boom Island, Columbia, Minnehaha Falls, Mississippi River Flats, Theodore Wirth Picnic Area, and Wabun Park. To make a reservation, stop by the Park Board's permit office in the Minneapolis Grain Exchange Building, 400 South 4th Street, Suite 109, or call 661-4817.<P>State of the City 1995 Report Provides Statistical Portrait of MinneapolisWant to know how many single family homes there are in the City's Southwest community or what percentage of the City's population is between the ages of 25-44? You can find the answers to those questions and more in the newly released "State of the City 1995." The 186-page report published by the City's Planning Department provides a statistical portrait of Minneapolis. It contains useful information on population, housing, employment, transportation, education, and crime in the city. Pick up a copy of the report in Room 210 City Hall, 350 South Fifth Street.<P><HR><H3>Minneapolis To Hire Police Officers</H3>From February 26 to March 15 the City of Minneapolis will be accepting applications for approximately thirty Police Officer positions.    Requirements are Peace Officer Standard Training (P.O.S.T.) eligibility, good eyesight and hearing, ability to pass a medical/psychological exam and criminal background investigation prior to hire and eligibility for a MN driver's license.    City residency is required after probation.    Starting salary is $2323 per month.    For an application call Sharon Foster at 673-2281.<P>    <HR><H3>Get Ready for Kindergarten</H3>Early Childhood Screening, required of all Minnesota children before they can enter kindergarten, can be done long before a child reaches kindergarten age.    In fact, it can be scheduled anytime after age three-and-a-half. "Most parents wait to fulfill this requirement until the summer before their child is planning to enter kindergarten," says Betty Flanigan, Director of 348-TOTS, a program of the Minneapolis Department of Health and Family Support. "But we highly recommend scheduling an appointment earlier, because the sooner we do the screening, the sooner we can give parents the information they need to prepare their children to succeed in school."<P>Screening is free and takes only about 20 minutes.  In addition to a height, weight, vision, and hearing check, it includes a review of immunizations, a health and family questionnaire, and a developmental check. Screening takes place at a variety of convenient locations throughout the city, including parks, child-care programs, community centers, and the Public Health Center in downtown Minneapolis. Minneapolis parents may call 348-TOTS (8687) to schedule an appointment.<P>    <HR><H3>Health Services Will Continue</H3>The City of Minneapolis will close its three maternal and child health clinics at the end of February due to changes in the health care system and anticipated steep cuts in federal and state aid. Many services formerly provided by the Department of Health and Family Support will be provided by contractors.<P> "Some confusion surrounds the recent decision to transfer the provision of direct health-care services to contractors and to place greater emphasis on assessing community health needs and developing public policies to meet those needs," said Acting Health Commissioner Del Hurt. "The Minneapolis Department of Health and Family Support is not closing; nor is it abandoning the health needs of low-income women and children."<P>The Neighborhood Health Care Network, a network of community-based clinics, will provide most direct-care services.; the telephone number is 489-CARE. Contractors will also provide dental services for children (673-3020); prekindergarten and other childhood developmental screening services (348-TOTS); the WIC nutrition program for women, infants, and children (673-3500); health services in the school-based clinics; and visiting nurses.<P><HR><H3>Solutions for Winter Hazards</H3>With the winter weather providing snowy and icy conditions, roads take a beating. Potholes are created by water freezing and then thawing in cracks causing the road to expand. The Department of Public Works is repairing the roads, but the speed of the maintenance is determined by weather conditions. After being repaired, potholes can easily return due to the freeze/thaw factors and stress from traffic.<P>	The weather has also made walking on sidewalks difficult. Ice buildup coats many city sidewalks potentially increasing accidents. It is up to every property owner to remove ice and snow and to cover trouble spots with sand, which will make better traction for pedestrians. The City of Minneapolis provides free sand to residents. Locations: 1809 Washington St. NE, 121 Glenwood Av. N, 6036 Harriet Av. S., 4444 Snelling Av. S, and 2710 Pacific St.<P> <HR><H3>Open Appointments</H3>Positions are open on the following boards and commissions. Applicants must be residents of Minneapolis except under special conditions. Application forms and detailed position announcements are available from the City Clerk. Call 673-2735. Applications must be filed by the due date.<BLOCKQUOTE>- One position is now open on the Shingle Creek Watershed Management Commission.    Technical knowledge of surface and underground water resources is required. Call 673-3626 for more information. Deadline: February 23.- Four positions are open on the Minneapolis Commission on Civil Rights. The commission implements the City's Civil Rights policies through education, mediation and enforcement. More information from 673-2147. Deadline: March 1.- One position is open on the Charter Commission. Any qualified voter of the City of Minneapolis can apply. Call 673-3131 for more information. Deadline: March 4</BLOCKQUOTE>.<P><HR><H3>Planning Commission Hearings</H3>The commission will hold public hearings starting at 4:30 p.m. Wed., March 6, in 317 City Hall on the following:- Rezoning to permit drive-up bank at 3033 University Av SE.- Conditional Use Permits for paint warehouse and mixing facility at 4539 Hiawatha, sign at 347 E 36th St, and currency exchange at 1804 Nicollet.More information from 673-5836.<P><HR><H3>City Cable 34 Highlights</H3>- Eye on Crime is a new show on City Cable 34. Hosted by Deputy Chief Bill Jones, it includes the long-running and popular "Twin Cities 10 Most Wanted." New segments include "In The Spotlight" which features safety and crime prevention tips, "Crime Stoppers" courtesy of KSTP Channel 5, and "Open Files" which features interviews with Minneapolis Police Department investigators about cases that are still open. Tune in Tuesdays at 8:30 p.m., Thursdays at 6:30 p.m., Saturdays at 9:30 p.m. or Sundays at 6:30 p.m. - The current City Beat features a discussions of plans for the Bassett Creek Bike Trail and a new ordinance that regulates specialty food stores. Join host Kent Robbins Tuesdays at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 9 p.m. and Saturdays at 7:30 p.m.- The Mayor's February 7 State of the City Address can be seen on City Cable 34 Tuesdays at 9 p.m., Thursdays at 5:30 p.m. and Saturdays at 8:30 p.m. Hard copies of the address can be ordered by calling 673-2100.<P><HR><H3>Community Items</H3>The 35W Solutions Alliance, the Minnesota Transportation Alliance, and the North Metro Mayors will hold a Transportation/Transit Summit on Wednesday, Feb. 21. The objective of the half-day meeting is to build a united, bipartisan voice to advocate for enhanced funding for highways and transit. State legislation is currently pending for enhanced transportation and transit funding, and the summit will work to create a single, united force to lend political support to these initiatives. The summit will be at the Minneapolis Convention Center. Following a buffet breakfast, the working session will begin at 9 a.m. Wednesday and end at noon. Call 673-2213 for more information.<P>Upcoming events sponsored by the Minneapolis Center for Neighborhoods include the following: - Second Annual State of the Neighborhoods Address on Thursday, February 22, from 5:30 to 7:30 p.m. at Plymouth Church, 1900 Nicollet. - Human Development Roundtable on Tuesday, February 27, from 6:30 to 8:30 p.m. at St. Mark's Cathedral on the south edge of Loring Park.- Sustainable Communities Resource Fair and Workshop on Saturday, March 2, from a.m. to 1 p.m. at Waite House, 2529 13th Avenue South.- Housing Roundtable on Thursday, March 21, from 7:30 to 8:30 p.m. at Hennepin United Methodist, 511 Groveland.Call 627-1850, extension 414, for details.<P><HR><P>Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton's <A HREF="/publications/State_o_City.html"> <i> State of the City</i> </A>address is now online.<hr> <P><CENTER><H5>Questions or comments about <I>On The Agenda</I>? Send email to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I> </H5></CENTER>