<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>OTA 3/1/96</TITLE><!-- Date: Friday, February 16, 1996  4:16 PM --></HEAD><BODY><H1>ON THE AGENDA</H1><P><H2>City of Minneapolis Actions & Issues  -  March 1, 1996</H2><P><I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions of the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. For sign language interpreting call TTY 673-3250. Available in alternative formats. This is Issue 11, Volume 12. The week of March 11 is an off week for the City Council. The next issue of On the Agenda will be March 22. </I>	<P><hr> <p> <H3>New Squad Cars Arriving</H3>The Minneapolis Police Department will have 120 new marked squad cars on city streets by the end of May. This is the largest number of squad cars the City has purchased at one time, bringing the department's total to 225. <P>The City purchased the cars from Superior Ford for $2,286,000. The plain white Crown Victorias, which come equipped with only two spotlights, arrived January 10 at the Municipal Garage, 1217 West Lake Street, to get outfitted for duty. <P>Nine workers in the Equipment Division of the Public Works Department put on the light bars, dividers, front and rear flashing lights and decals. The radios are installed at the City's Communications Shop.<P>Workers are rolling out six cars a week. There are a total of 42 new squad cars on the road to date. Eighty of the new cars will replace existing squads. <P><hr> <p> <H3>February 23 City Council Actions</H3>At its February 26 meeting the Minneapolis City Council took the following actions.<P><BLOCKQUOTE>- Approved 1995 Housing Impact report.<p> - Approved Year XXII Citizen Participation and Technical Assistance Plan.<p> - Established a Living Wage Jobs Task Force and appointed members.<p> - Approved NRP First Step plans for the East Isles and Standish-Ericsson neighborhoods.<p> - Approved NRP Action Plans for Cleveland, Longfellow and Kenwood Isles neighborhoods.<p> - Passed an ordinance that requires permits for the possession or consumption of intoxicating or nonintoxicating liquor in open air parking lots.<p> - Authorized 1996 contract for Community Health services and 1996-1997 contract for Maternal and Child Health services.<p> - Approved issuance of 35 new taxicab licenses to existing service companies by lottery, and of 35 licenses in one block to Green & White, a new service company.<p> - Approved City's operation of school-based clinics through 1996.<p> - Authorized bid proposal to host the 2002 International Association of Chiefs of Police conference.<p> - Issued request for proposals for consulting engineer services to study traffic issues in the Cedar Isles Dean neighborhood.<p> - Designated Jefferson East and Shingle Creek West areas for 1996 Residential Paving Program and set public hearing for March 21 on proposed assessments.<p> - Accepted state funding and approved allocation plan for 1996 Community Resource Program.<p> - Approved membership of 1996 Board of Equalization.<p> - Received state funding for YouthWorks/Americcorps program.<p> - Approved contract for provision of employee assistance and chemical/substance abuse services.<p> - Found Southeast Minneapolis Industrial Center environmental assessment worksheet to be adequate.<p> - Approved name change from Fuller to "Tangletown" neighborhood.<p> - Approved a resolution supporting the request of the Minneapolis Public Schools for a variance from current desegregation rules to be granted by the Minnesota State Board of Education. The variance would allow more families and broader choice of magnet, community and partner schools.</BLOCKQUOTE><P><p> This is partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or for details on specific actions, call 673-3130.<P><hr> <p> <H3>City of Minneapolis News Briefs</H3><B>City Will Join New Radio Net</B>The City Council will join the State of Minnesota and Hennepin County in a new Regional 800 MHZ Trunked Radio System being developed by the Metropolitan Council. For a cost of $15 million in advance and $1 million per year, the new radio system will provide the Public Works, Police and Fire departments greater interaction and more efficient use of frequencies. The new system is expected to be up and running in three years. <P><B>Whittier Community Center Dedicated</B>The new Whittier Community Center, 2600 Grand Avenue, was dedicated Saturday, February 24. The center, which was built with more than $1.8 million of Whittier's Neighborhood Revitalization Program funds, features a gymnasium, several multipurpose rooms, a commercial kitchen, an arts and crafts room with a pottery wheel and kiln, and a youth game room. The community center and gym will be used by students in grades K-5 who will attend a new Whittier School, which will be built on an adjacent site and completed by fall 1997.<P><B>Council Requires Permits for Tailgaters</B>Tailgaters who want to have a beer in the parking lot before the big game will now need to have a permit. An ordinance approved by the City Council February 23 requires parking lot owners to apply for a permit to allow consumption of alcoholic beverages in open air parking lots prior to major sporting events at the Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome. Permits will be issued on an event-by-event basis.<P><hr> <p> <H3>City Cable 34 Highlights</H3><p> -<I>Eye on Crime</I> debuted on City Cable 34 in February. Hosted by Deputy Chief Bill Jones, the first show included the popular "Twin Cities 10 Most Wanted." New segments are "In The Spotlight" which features safety and crime prevention tips, "Crime Stoppers" courtesy of KSTP Channel 5, and "Open Files" which features interviews with Police Department investigators about cases that are still open. The February show will run through March 5. The March edition will air starting March 7. Tune in Tuesdays at 8:30 p.m., Thursdays at 6:30 p.m., Saturdays at 9:30 p.m. or Sundays at 6:30 p.m. <p> - The current <I>City Beat</I> features a lively discussion with Zib Hinz of the Minneapolis Public Schools on the wavier requested by the School Board from desegregation guidelines. Andrea Hart Kajer, the City's Director of Government Relations, is the guest for the second segment. She and host Kent Robbins discuss the current session of the legislature. Tune in Tuesdays at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 9 p.m. and Saturdays at 7:30 p.m.<p> -<I>Animal Tracks</I>, sponsored by Minneapolis Animal Control, features hearing guide dogs this month on Saturdays at 5 p.m.<p> - The March edition of <I>Artifacts</I> features a dancer, a potter, a Serbian translator, a skateboarding chicken and house that takes off like a rocket - just the usual drama and intrigue. Join hosts Phill Lindsay and Janet Zahn Tuesdays at 7:30, Thursdays at 7 P.M. and Saturdays at 5 p.m.<P><hr> <p> <H3>Accomplishments</H3>The Neighborhood Revitalization Program received a National Excellence Award in February. The NRP was one of 25 winners chosen from among 175 submissions after a site evaluation by a committee chaired by Henry Cisneros, Secretary of HUD. <P>The Sex Crimes Unit of the Police Department was named Investigative Unit of the Year by the Grant Hussey Foundation. The unit received a plaque in recognition of the teamwork that allowed them to solve multiple serial rape cases and arrest two suspects who received life imprisonment for crimes committed from 1991 through 1993. <P>The Greater Minneapolis Convention and Visitors Association shattered its 1994 record performance during 1995 by booking 341 conventions, meetings, and trade shows to be held in Minneapolis in the next several years. These bookings will attract approximately 415,000 people to the metro area who will spend an estimated $275.4 million during their visits. In 1995, GMCVA hosted and serviced a record 320 conventions and special events. The estimated direct economic impact was approximately $244 million - a 35 percent increase over 1994.<P><hr> <p><H3>City Council Committee Items</H3><B>Community Development</B>- 5:30 p.m. Thursday, March 21, 319 City Hall - Modification to the Seward South Urban Renewal Plan, modification to the Common Plan, and to the Deep Rock Tax Increment Finance Plan and Hazardous Substance District. Information 673-5193.<P><B>Zoning & Planning</B>- 2 p.m. Tuesday, April 2, 319 City Hall - Moratorium on establishment and licensing of motels in the B3, B3S and B3C zones. Information 673-2065.<P><P><hr> <p> <H3>Open Appointments</H3>Positions are open on the following boards and commissions. Applicants must be residents of Minneapolis except under special conditions. Application forms and detailed position announcements are available from the City Clerk. Call 673-2735. Applications must be filed by the due date.<p> <BLOCKQUOTE>- Six positions are currently vacant on the Minneapolis Advisory Committee on Drug & Alcohol Problems. The committee advises the Mayor and Council on chemical dependency treatment issues. Call 673-2735 for a full announcement. Deadline March 8.<p> - One position is open on the Charter Commission. Any qualified voter of the City of Minneapolis can apply. Call 673-3131 for more information. Deadline March 4.</BLOCKQUOTE><P><hr> <p> <H3>Community Items</H3>- Applications for the annual <B>Metro Paint-A-Thon</B> are due May 1. Eleven thousand volunteers will paint approximately 380 homes of seniors and disabled persons the first weekend in August. Homes must be owned and occupied by a person 60 years of age or older, or by persons of any age with permanent disabilities. Homes must also be single-family dwellings that needs paint, but are structurally sound. Owners must meet maximum income guidelines. Maximum monthly incomes are: one person, $1,057; two persons, $1,310; three persons, $1,581; and four persons, $1,844. Homeowners can call 870-3660 for an application.<P>- The <B>Downtown Minneapolis Residents Association</B> will hold an election for a NRP Steering Committee position from 7 to 8:30 p.m. Thursday, March 14, at the downtown library. Information from 220-3836.<P><HR><P><CENTER><H5>Questions or comments about <I>On The Agenda</I>? Send email to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I> </H5></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
