<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>OTA 3/1/96</TITLE><!-- Date: Friday, February 16, 1996  4:16 PM --></HEAD><BODY><H1>ON THE AGENDA</H1><P><H2>City of Minneapolis Actions & Issues - April 5, 1996</H2><P><I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions of the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. For sign language interpreting call TTY 673-3250. Available in alternative formats. This is Issue 13, Volume 12. The next issue will be April 17.</I> <HR><P><H3>Minneapolis & Saint Paul Home Tour to Showcase Excitement of Urban Living - Saturday, May 4, and Sunday, May 5</H3><P>See firsthand what residents of Minneapolis and Saint Paul love about city living, when they open their doors for the ninth annual Minneapolis & Saint Paul Home Tour. The free, self-guided event will feature more than 40 homes, including a house designed by Frank Lloyd Wright, a floating bed and breakfast, and a geodesic dome, all of which will be open from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Saturday, May 4, and from 1 to 5 p.m. Sunday, May 5. <P>New this year will be walking tours of three Minneapolis neighborhoods - Old Highland, Bancroft, and the Mississippi Mile, which includes Nicollet Island. In addition to historic homes, artists' lofts, and elegant condominiums, these tours will spotlight neighborhood landmarks and amenities.<P>"People love to go on the Home Tour to see how magnificent old homes have been restored and remodeled, but this year the event will include opportunities to see something besides beautiful woodwork and stained glass," says Leah Proctor, president of the Old Highland Association. "By organizing walking tours, we hope to help visitors get better acquainted with the community and what that community has to offer."<P>In Saint Paul, the annual Cinco de Mayo celebration will take place during the same weekend as the Home Tour, and organizers hope those attending one event will also attend the other.<P>The Home Tour is organized by the cities of Minneapolis and Saint Paul to build community awareness, encourage home improvement, and promote city living. Homes on the tour are typically not for sale. Estimated attendance last year was more than 40,000.<P>Copies of a 20-page Home Tour guide, containing descriptions and photos of all the homes, will appear in subscriber copies of the Pioneer Press on May 1 and the Star Tribune on May 2. The guide will also be available in Target Stores and metro area Norwest offices the week before the tour. <P><H4>Tour Volunteers Still Needed</H4> Volunteers are needed to help staff homes on the tour. Volunteer responsibilities include welcoming visitors, directing traffic through the homes, and answering questions about city living. It's an excellent way to make contacts and promote buying in the city. Three shifts are available: Saturday morning (9:30 a.m.-1:30 p.m.), Saturday afternoon (1-5:30 p.m.), and Sunday afternoon (12:30-5:30 p.m.). For more information, please call the Minneapolis Office of Public Affairs, 673-2491.<HR><P><H3>Minneapolis Street Sweeping Starts Monday, April 15</H3>No Parking signs will be posted the day before sweeping. Parking will be banned from 7 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. the day of the sweep. Enforcement of the No Parking ban and towing will begin at 8 a.m.Alleys will be swept starting April 8. <HR> </H3> <P><H3>March 29 Minneapolis City Council Actions</H3><B>Appointments</B> <P>The Council approved appointments to the following boards and commissions.- Arts Commission: Confirmed City Council President's appointment of Timothy D. Willettte as an arts organization member, Robert E. Kelly and Rochelle Woldorsky as an artist members, and William Stark as a lay member.- Nicollet Mall Advisory Board: Appointed Dale Amondson representing Dayton's.<P>- Civil Service Commission: Approved appointment of Christine Siewert to fill unexpired term of Richard O. Johnson.<P><B>Community Development Committee</B> <P>- Increased maximum loan amount limits for MCDA's CDBG Deferred Loan and High Risk Loan programs; and created a new Housing Rental Rehabilitation program.<P>- Approved NRP funds for two neighborhoods: Elliot Park, $60,000 for Hinkle Murphy mansion restoration; and Corcoran Park, $350,000 for First Step activities.<P>- Approved a loan to Project for Pride in Living to stabilize 16 multifamily structures.<P>- Approved a loan for the redevelopment of 900 Hennepin Avenue.<P>- Approved a Livable Communities Demonstration Pilot Project grant application for development of the 4th Avenue South and Lake Street area.<P><B>Public Safety & Regulatory Services</B> <P>- Approved reinstatement of Rental Housing License at 3117-19 16th Av S; denied license for 1913, 1915 and 1919 Columbus Av S.<P>- Approved demolition of 1407 Thomas N.<P>- Accepted recommendations of Mayor's Task Force on Business Regulation.<P>- Approved a letter of understanding with the Central Community Housing Trust for office space at 700 First Av N to be used for the Minneapolis Police Downtown Command Center.<P><B>Transportation & Public Works</B> <P> - Approved agreement with MnDOT for City's required cost participation in projects, including future landscaping, of Hiawatha Avenue from East 24th and East 32nd Sts.<P>- Authorized solicitation of proposals for Fire Training Simulator.<P>- Approved Alley Speed Hump program.<P>- Passed an ordinance related to Water Management and Preservation of Wetlands.<P>- Revised 1996 rates for nonresidential paving assessments from $1.21 to $.88 per square foot.<P>- Approved plans for skyway connecting new Federal Courthouse to the Public Health Center and for tunnel between the Courthouse and City Hall; directed staff to resolve issues related to connection between Courthouse and Haaf Parking Ramp.<P>- Approved construction agreement with MnDOT for decorative railings and lighting on bridges spanning Interstate 35W at 26th, 28th, 46th and 50th Streets and at Diamond Lake Rd; appropriated funds for the project; direct that a letter be sent to impacted neighborhoods requesting financial participation; and designated this design as the standard for future new and renovated bridges.<P><B>Ways & Means/Budget</B> <P> - Accepted donation by the American Jewish Congress for the Mayor's airline fare to the Jerusalem Conference of Mayors.<P>- Approved labor agreement with the Minneapolis Police Officers' Federation for April 16, 1994 through October 14, 1998.<P>- Authorized revised Park Board grant application to the Legislative Commission on Minnesota Resources for the Lakeshore Bioengineering Restoration project.<P>- Approved submission to the Mayor of the 1996 Local Plan for Employment and Training.<P>- Amended the Job Bank Ordinance to extend the eligibility date for health insurance benefits for laid-off employees.<P>- Authorized the use of current funds for certain water and parking system projects that were originally scheduled for bonding.<P>- Passed a resolution supporting Minnehaha Academy's application for a "Mighty Ducks" Ice Arena Renovation grant.<P><B>Zoning & Planning</B> <P> - Designated the Parker House, 4829 Colfax Av S, Franklin House, 2405 West 22nd St, and the Friedell House, 2700 Chowen Av S, for heritage preservation.<P>- Rezoned 1010 West Lake St to allow development of an existing building into a shopping center.<P><B>Committee of the Whole</B> <P>- Approved actions to remove hazardous substances and prepare the Deep Rock site, 2700 East 28th St, for development.<P>This is partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or for details on specific actions, call 673-3130.<HR><H3>City Seeks Participants for McGruff House Program</H3>The City of Minneapolis is looking for residents who are willing to open up their homes in the McGruff House program. McGruff Houses are safe places where children can go if they feel they are in danger on their way to and from school.<P>McGruff House participants no longer have to be at home all day long. The City changed the program's rules late last year allowing people to "generally" be home mornings or afternoons. The old rules required people to be home all morning and afternoon. <P>"The rule change opens it up to people who work part time," said John Baumann of the police department's Community Crime Prevention, which coordinates the McGruff House program. "We need more people to participate."<P>The program, which is celebrating its 10th anniversary this year, has approximately 650 McGruff Houses throughout the City.<P>Prospective McGruff House participants must fill out an application; agree to a criminal history check for all household members age 14 and older; and provide references. A Minneapolis police officer will also do a surprise visit of the home. For more information on the McGruff House program, call Charlyn Cadwell at 673-2922.<HR><P><H3>Minneapolis Initiative Against Racism Receives National Award</H3>The Minneapolis Initiative Against Racism program has received a 1996 City Cultural Diversity Award from the National Black Caucus of Local Elected Officials. The city program was first runner up among cities with populations between 100,000 and 400,000.<P>Four first-place winners and four runners up received engraved silver awards at the "Celebrate Diversity" Breakfast March 10 during the National League of Cities Annual Congressional City Conference in Washington, D.C. Henry Cisneros, secretary of Housing and Urban Development, was the keynote speaker.<P>Cisneros spoke about the community's role in creating a sense of inclusiveness. "This sense of inclusiveness in communities is not going to happen because we run into each other at a cocktail party at the museum association," he said. "It will be when leaders like you formally, structurally, systematically think about inclusiveness as a major part of your job."<P>The MIAR was formed in 1992 to break the cycle of racial misunderstanding, prejudice and racism in order to provide equal economic and social access to people of all cultures and races in the community. Nine task forces consisting of representatives from both government and the community at large are working to eliminate racism in housing, education, media, government, employment, civic groups and arts, human services and religious institutions and among youth. The MIAR Awards were created in 1995 to honor individuals and organizations who have made strides in the fight against racism.<P>More than 21 percent of Minneapolis' population are people of color, according to the 1990 census. "We want to make it known that Minneapolis is a city that respects its diversity and encourages those who do not to think and act differently," said past MIAR co-director Tara Buckner.  <P>The NBC-LEO's City Cultural Diversity Awards are designed to promote the concept of cultural diversity in local governance through citizen and community participation. Rochester, New York took top honors in the 100,000 to 400,000 population category. Other top winners were Columbus, Ohio (over 400,000); Richmond, California (25,000 to 100,000); and Natchez, Mississippi (Under 25,000). Runners up were Casa Grande Arizona (Under 25,000); Roswell, New Mexico (25,000 to 100,000); and Boston, Massachusetts (Over 400,000).<HR><P><B><H3>City of Minneapolis News Briefs</H3>Council Honors North High Team</B>The City Council honored the North High School boys basketball team March 29 for winning the 1996 Class AA championship in the Boys State Basketball Tournament. The Polars are the 13th team to win back-to-back titles in the tournament's 87-year history.<P><B>Council Approves Speed Humps</B>At the March 29 meeting, the City Council approved a procedure for speed humps in alleys to slow down drivers. A test of the recycled plastic speed humps in about a dozen alleys last year was successful. Under the proposed program, at least 75 percent of property owners on a block must petition the city to install the speed humps. The block must pay for the installation, estimated to cost $520 for a three-hump alley, and agree to remove them between Nov. 1 and April 1 to accommodate snow plowing. Contact Rick Dahl, 673-2411 <P><B>Neighbors Celebrate Phelps Park Center</B>On March 30, Bancroft, Bryant, Powderhorn Park and Central neighborhood residents marked the ground breaking of the new Phelps Park Community Center, Chicago Av. at 39th St., with a "Wonder Web Celebration." Participants brought "wondrous" objects that were be woven into a web of wire and rope with the help of community artists. The web will be displayed in the new community center. Construction in Phelps Park includes a new gym and a renovated community center. When the center reopens in September 1996, it will be the permanent site for the Southside Boys & Girls Club. Bryant, Bancroft, and Powderhorn neighborhoods used $750,000 of their NRP funds for the park project. <P><B>City to Provide Lead-Safe House</B>Beginning April 1, Minneapolis residents have a safe place to stay while their own homes are undergoing lead hazard reduction. The City of Minneapolis has contracted with the Phillips Lead Project to provide a lead-safe house in the neighborhood. A $25,000 State Health Department grant awarded to the Minneapolis Lead Poisoning Intervention Program earlier this month will pay for furnishings and rental of the property through September 1997. The maximum stay at the safe house is two weeks. <HR><H3>Open Appointments</H3>Application materials are available from the Office of the City Clerk, 350 South 5th Street, 304 City Hall, Minneapolis, MN 55415-1382; telephone 673-2735. Persons can apply on their own behalf, nominate other persons for consideration, or request the Office of the City Clerk to provide application materials to other persons.<P> - Qualified voters of the City of Minneapolis are eligible to submit applications for appointment to the <B>Minneapolis Charter Commission</B>. The Chief Judge of Hennepin County District Court, the Honorable Kevin S. Burke, will appoint one person for the term of June 1, 1996 through June 1, 2000. The time set by the Charter Commission for its meetings is 4:00 p.m. on the second Thursday of each month. The Charter Commission may propose amendments to the Minneapolis City Charter on its own initiative or on request of the City Council. No persons may be appointed to more than two successive terms as a commission member. Additional information on the Commission and application procedures is available from Charter Commission Clerk, Michola Foley, telephone 673-3131. Deadline is May 6. All applications will be forwarded to the Chief Judge for consideration.<P>- Five positions are open on the <B>Commission on Civil Rights</B>. The commission implements the City's civil rights policies through education, mediation and enforcement. Residency required. More information from 673-2147. Deadline is April 12.<HR><P><H3>Planning Commission Hearings</H3>Wed., April 10, 4:30 p.m., 317 City Hall:- Vacation of a portion of Grand Av S between 26th and 27th Streets.- Zoning code amendments restricting parking of passenger and recreational vehicles greater than or equal to six feet in height to locations no closer than 10 feet from any habitable building, and making video stores and coffee shops subject to site plan review.Wed., April 24, 4:30 p.m., 317 City Hall:- Rezoning at 1901 Nicollet to permit motor vehicle repair.- Lot area and yard variations at 510 West 53rd St to permit lot subdivision and construction of new single-family dwelling.More information from 673-5836<P><CENTER><H5>Questions or comments about <I>On The Agenda</I>? Send email to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I> </H5></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
