r had to turn away: 12 thousand National Education Association delegates, 12 thousand International Dairy Foods Association delegates, 16 thousand National Urban League Delegates....and thousands of others - in fact, a total of 195 thousand visitors who would have enriched our state by $150 million dollars. <P>"The Governor's logic in permitting this situation to continue escapes me. "Governor Carlson says the reason for his veto is that Minneapolis doesn't have a financial plan to finish the convention center. However, he has refused to assign anyone in his administration to work with us on the parameters of a plan that would be acceptable to him. The Governor knows that Minneapolis, almost single handedly, has created a global marketplace for the whole state by building the Convention Center. He knows that the total cost of the Convention Center is $520 million - and that already the City has picked up the tab for the first $350 million.<P> "Now that it's time to finish the project, Minneapolis wants the Governor and the State of Minnesota to be our partner. The Convention Center is a state resource and a state project. It was the only bonding bill project that would have benefited everybody in the state. "The Convention Center makes sense. The Governor's veto does not."<P>Minneapolis City officials maintain that although they attempted to work with the Carlson Administration to complete a finance plan, no one within the Administration was formally assigned to work with them on the parameters of an acceptable plan.<P>During the Legislative session, the City proposed to legislators and to the Carlson Administration a proposal for amortizing the $160 million Convention Center project. Members of the Carlson Administration did caution the City that the proposal would still require the state to use its own bonding capacity. The City took this constraint quite seriously, and commissioned an outside consultant, Evenson Dodge, to provide options that might mitigate this burden. That report is due in early May. <P>The City has always assumed that the Governor would not authorize the issuance of any bond proceeds to the Convention Center project until he was satisfied that there was available a suitable long-term financing plan. In fact, the language of the bill designates the $12 million only after this condition is satisfied.<P> The veto means that for another year the City cannot negotiate for the needed land, cannot move forward on a financing plan, or tell prospective conventions that Minneapolis might be able to accommodate their needs after the year 2001.<P>The Mayor said, however, that although this is a setback, the City will continue to pursue the completion of the Convention Center with our business and labor partners throughout the State of Minnesota.<P><HR> <H3>May 4 & 5 Home Tour Adds Focus on Neighborhoods for First Year</H3> <P>This year, visitors to the Minneapolis & Saint Paul Home Tour will be able to explore entire neighborhoods as well as fine homes. For the first time, the Home Tour has partnered with neighborhoods to organize three neighborhood tours. Visitors will be able to see several of the neighborhoods' most distinct homes as well as enjoy guided tours and entertainment, learn the history of the neighborhood and meet neighbors.<P>The neighborhood tours occur during the same hours of the Home Tour: on Saturday, May 4, from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. and on Sunday, May 5, from 1 to 5 p.m. Like the Home Tour, neighborhood tours are free of charge.<P>In North Minneapolis' Old Highland neighborhood, four homes will be open. In addition, the neighborhood is hosting local bands and an information fair. Pick up information at 1604 Emerson Av. N.<P>Along the Mississippi Mile, the city's newest, oldest neighborhood will feature guided walking tours of four historic areas, and a glimpse of new and restored condos; artists' lofts and studios; as well as information about the history and future of the area. Visitors can also pick up a flyer and explore the riverfront on their own. Pick up information or sign up for a guided tour at De La Salle High School on Nicollet Island.<P>A "classic" south Minneapolis neighborhood, Bancroft is highlighting its latest developments with a look at the Phelps Park project, which is currently under construction. Visitors will also be able to tour several of the neighborhood's homes and businesses. Start your tour at 3945 Chicago Av. S.<P>For more information about the Home Tour or its neighborhood tours, please call 673-CITY, option 10.<P><HR><H3>April 12 City Council Actions</H3> <P><B>Appointments</B> The Council approved appointments to the following boards and commissions.- Shingle Creek Watershed Management Commission: Appointed Craig Cooper.- City Planning Commission: Reappointed Judith Martin and Timothy Baylor.<P><B>Community Development Committee</B> - Approved 1995 Housing Impact Report.- Directed City Attorney to begin eminent domain for two parcels of land needed for Hosmer Community Library project.- Received a report on marketing program for Block E.- Accepted Hennepin County NRP funds for Shared Living Residence project, 3627-33 Chicago.Intergovernmental Relations- Passed a resolution urging restoration of federal funding for the Summer Youth Employment and Training Program.<P><B>Public Safety & Regulatory Services</B> - Authorized contract with Youth Coordinating Board for 1996 Way To Grow program.- Waived block event fee for National Night Out applications received by July 12, set $15 for applications received by July 23, and directed denial of applications received after July 23. (National Night Out is August 6. Call CCP/SAFE, 673-3015, for information.)- Denied Rental Housing License at 2723 Dupont Av N.- Approved demolition of 2900 Dupont N.- Authorized RFP for operation of The CITYSTORE which provides employment and training for Minneapolis youth and an outlet for unclaimed property.- Accepted Technical Advisory Committee recommendations regarding a hotel license for the Falls Motel, 5248 Minnehaha.<P><B>Transportation & Public Works</B> - Authorized submission application for a Twin Cities Water Quality Initiative technical grant for the Shingle Creek Regional Stormwater Pond.- Approved plans and directed City Engineer to proceed with construction of streets, storm drains, traffic signals and street lighting for the Quarry Project, Johnson St NE at New Brighton Blvd.- Authorized solicitation of bids for electronic parking meters which will accept prepaid cards as well as coins.- Directed the Department of Public Works not to proceed with installation of signage related to the 24-Hour Snow Plan; also directed that Public Works implement personnel changes to allow for more effective snow removal under the current system.<P><B>Ways & Means/Budget</B>- Approved revisions to the FY95 Consolidated Plan and the submission of the FY96 plan to HUD.- Accepted funds donated by Dayton's for the Minneapolis Initiative Against Racism.- Entered into a contract with the Minneapolis Youth Trust to provide City funds for 1996 New Workforce program.- Approved Community Resource Program contracts with Youth Coordinating Board for Phat Summer and with the Police Athletic League.- Contracted with the Metro Visiting Nurses Association for Lead Research Project.- Directed a 1.7% reduction of General Fund appropriations to meet 1996 budget.<P><B>Resolutions</B>- Approved a resolution proclaiming April 17 as Police Athletic League Day.<P><I>This is partial list of actions. For a full list, or for details on actions, call 673-3130.</I><HR><H3>Council Member to View Kondirators</H3>A Minneapolis City Council Member and a City Environmental Inspector will collect facts about three Kondirators in England the week of April 22.<P>Third Ward Council Member Joe Biernat and Minneapolis Environmental Inspector Thomas Frame and will inspect Kondirators, which are German-made metal shredders, in Birmingham, Sefton and Stockton-on-Tees. There are no Kondirators in North America, but construction of one has been proposed along the Mississippi River in North Minneapolis, an area that Biernat represents. Biernat is paying the cost of his own transportation for the trip.<P> Biernat and Frame will meet with local government officials, residents who live near the Kondirators, managers of the facilities, and environmental organizations. Staff from the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency have accepted an invitation from the City to attend these meetings. Biernat and Frame also will collect videotape, slides and samples.<P> After their return, Biernat and Frame will present the results of their inspections to the City Council and neighborhood organizations at a series of meetings. They will also present their information at a meeting of the MPCA Citizens Board. The Board will determine the adequacy of an Environmental Assessment Worksheet for the project in the next few months. <P>Last December, Biernat saw a metal shredder in Phoenix. "It was tremendously valuable to talk with neighborhood residents and workers in the plant," he said.<P> "The Kondirator is one of the most important issues facing the residents of North and Northeast Minneapolis, but no one from the City or the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency has actually seen one," Biernat said. "I believe that it is essential to see these operations firsthand and then share the information with my constituents."<P><HR><H3>Participants Needed for McGruff</H3>The City of Minneapolis is looking for residents who are willing to open up their homes in the McGruff House program. McGruff Houses are safe places where children can go if they feel they are in danger or need assistance from an adult.<P>McGruff House participants no longer have to be at home all day long. The City changed the program's rules late last year allowing people to "generally" be home mornings or afternoons. The old rules required people to be home all morning and afternoon.<P> "The rule change opens it up to people who work part time," said John Baumann of the Police Department's Community Crime Prevention, which coordinates the McGruff House program. "We need more people to participate."<P>The program, which is celebrating its 10th anniversary this year, has approximately 650 McGruff Houses throughout the city.<P>Prospective McGruff House participants must fill out an application; agree to a criminal history check for all household members age 14 and older; and provide references. A Minneapolis police officer will also do a surprise visit of the home. For more information on the McGruff House program, call Charlyn Cadwell at 673-2922.<P><HR><H3>City Cable 34 Highlights</H3>-<B><I>Eye on Crime</I></B>, hosted by Deputy Chief Bill Jones, features Detective Cindy Hoxie of Hennepin County Sheriff's office presenting the Twin Cities 10 Most Wanted, as well as a "walk along" with the Downtown Beat Patrol and an in-depth look at the increase of pickpockets in Uptown. Tuesdays at 9 p.m., Thursdays at 6 p.m. and Saturdays at 9 p.m.<P> -<B><I> City Beat</I></B> features a recap of the April 12 City Council meeting and host Kent Robbins' conversation with Assistant City Coordinator Jude Poseley about the 1996 Home Tour. Tuesdays at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 8:30 p.m. and Saturdays at 7:30 p.m.<P>-<B><I>Mayor's Roundtable</I></B>  Mayor Sayles Belton discusses reclaiming polluted land for business development with MCDA Executive Director Rebecca Yanisch and Northside business owner Joe Werner. The Mayor will also talk with Heritage Preservation staffer Amy Lucas and community advocate Michael Rainville about riverfront development. Tuesdays at 9 p.m., Thursdays at 6 p.m. and Saturdays at 9 p.m.<P>- Don't miss the April edition of <B><I>Artifacts</I></B>. Join hosts Phill Lindsay and Janet Zahn Tuesdays at 7:30 p.m., Thursdays at 7 p.m. and Saturdays at 5:30 p.m. for what's new in the arts. And mark your schedule or set your VCR for the live broadcast of the <B><I>April 26 City Council<</I>I></I></B> meeting or for a repeat Monday, Wednesday or Friday at 6 p.m.<P><HR><H3>City of Minneapolis News Briefs</H3><B>Program Will Improve Parking Safety</B> <P>To keep city parking lots and ramps safe from trespassers, the Police Department's SAFE unit is signing up lots and ramps in the "No Trespassing Sign" program and the Minnesota Crime Alert Fax Network. Those who sign up for both programs will receive a free booklet of public arrest records and mug shots of people who have been arrested for tampering with a motor vehicle or trespassing on any lot in Minneapolis.<P><HR> <H3>Open Appointments</H3> <P>Application materials are available from the Office of the City Clerk, 673-2735. - Qualified voters of the City of Minneapolis may to submit applications for appointment to the <B>Minneapolis Charter Commission</B>. Call 673-3131 for details. Deadline is May 6.<P><HR><H3>Council Committee Item</H3>The Ways & Means/Budget committee will hold a public hearing at 10 a.m., Tuesday, April 23 in 319 City Hall on an appointment to the Minneapolis Television Network board of directors. Call 673-2911.<P><HR><H3>Community Note</H3>Community leaders, volunteers, government officials and everyone interested in the goal of nonviolent communities can participate in a free satellite conference May 1 on the University of Minnesota St. Paul Campus. The conference will include a teleconference and a local discussion on violence and action plans to create nonviolent communities. The sponsor is the Minnesota Partnership for Non-Violent Communities. Call 430-6805.<P><HR><H3>Planning Commission Hearings</H3>Wed., April 24, 4:30 p.m., 317 City Hall:- Land survey and street vacation in the vicinity of 18th Av SE and Elm St SE.- Street vacation of a portion of 7th St between 20th and 22nd Avs S.- Alley vacation for Hosmer Library renovation.- Zoning code amendment related to power plants in the Mississippi River Critical Area.- Preliminary plat in the vicinity of 323 St. Anthony Av.- Conditional use permit for building cooling facility at 100 North 1st St.More information from 673-3710.<P><HR> <CENTER><H5>Questions or comments about <I>On The Agenda</I>? Send email to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I> </H5></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
