ine, operated by the Youth Coordinating Board, will provide Minneapolis youth information on hundreds of athletic, recreational, enrichment and employment opportunities. The hotline will be available starting June 18. In announcing Safe Summer, the Mayor recalled last year's record homicide rate. "The memory of the pain and violence of last year is still fresh in our minds. We must not, and will not, relive those tragic days. If any good can come of them, it must be a resolve on the part of all of us - police, clergy, business people, youth workers, neighbors, parents and young people - that this year will be different. This year we will work as one to do whatever is necessary to bring peace to our homes, peace to our neighborhoods, and peace to our city."<P>"Government can provide tools, but it takes citizens to put them to work," the Mayor said. "The City can put that new cop on the beat, but the way that officer is going to be successful is for the people in the neighborhood make the effort to meet that officer, and make a partnership with him or her to work together to prevent crime in the community."<P> Chief Olson stressed the need for community involvement. "Gangs, violence and youth crime are a reality in America's major cities and Minneapolis is no exception. Even with the very successful programs initiated over the years, we can never let down our guard. Only through the strong cooperation of the citizens, the police and government will we ever be able to make a difference in protecting the quality of life for our residents. These new initiatives are also designed to address the root issues that feed the fires of disorder and youth and gang violence."<P>The Mayor said Safe Summer builds on successes of the past two years. "Last year we experimented with Operation Safe Streets - police saturation of targeted neighborhoods. It worked. It provided relief to those neighborhoods. This summer we intensify that effort with more police, in more neighborhoods, working with more people in the community to prevent crime."<P><I>Video of this news conference will be shown on City Cable 34 starting June 7. It will follow live coverage and tape repeats of City Council meeting.</I><P><HR><H3>May 24 Minneapolis City Council Actions</H3>At its May 24 meeting the Minneapolis City Council took the following actions.<P><B>Appointments</B><P>The Council approved appointments to the Minneapolis-St. Paul Strategic Investment for Living Wage Jobs Task Force: Alexa Bradley (MAPA), Thomas Burke (Norwest Bank), and Evelyn Miks (AFSCME). <P><B>Community Development Committee</B><P>- Approved revenue bonds for Minneapolis Career Center, Inc to acquire and renovate former Sears warehouse at 2929 Elliot Av S.<P>- Approved Neighborhood Revitalization Program plans and funds:<P><LI>Northeast Park Neighborhood, $510,000 for Action Plan activities which include a home improvement matching grant program, traffic calming measures, and improvements to Northeast Park.<LI>Audubon Park Neighborhood, $2,798,845 for Action Plan activities which include low interest housing loans, rehabilitation of distressed properties, tree planting, improvement of Central Avenue and Johnson Street commercial areas and revitalization of the Hollywood Theater.<LI>Harrison Neighborhood, $450,000 for First Step Plan activities which include rehabilitation of blighted housing, a tool lending library, a master plan for Glenwood Avenue, block club organization and provision of security lights.<LI>Waite Park Neighborhood, $250,000 for First Step Plan activities which include an interest rate buy-down program to encourage housing rehab and development of a restorative justice program.<LI>Holland Neighborhood, $10,000 of early access funds for a inter-neighborhood Central Avenue Corridor Study<LI>Waite Park Neighborhood, $190,250 of early access funds to upgrade Waite Park Elementary School for its transition from grades 4-6 to K-6 and to enhance REC Plus latchkey program.<P>- Approved Preliminary Planning Fund allocations for Southeast Minneapolis Industrial Area (SEMI) project, 7th Street Business Center, and the Lyndale Gateway project.<P>- Authorized MCDA to negotiate with FORECAST Public Artworks for arts programs and entertainment events on Block E as an interim use.<P><B>Public Safety & Regulatory Services</B><P>- Authorized demolition of nuisance buildings at 617 26th Av N and 617 Lowry Av N.<P>- Approved architectural and engineering services proposal by Julie Snow Architects, Inc. for new Fifth Precinct Police Station.<P><B>Transportation & Public Works</B><P>- Passed an ordinance related to illegal dumping.<P>- Authorized RFP for engineering services related to parking issues in the Lowry Hill neighborhood; the study is in conjunction with the neighborhood's NRP plan.<P>- Directed that a report of an interdepartmental  Transit and Transportation Work Team be submitted to the Transportation & Public Works and Intergovernmental Relations committees not later than the first cycle of November in order to have a plan to propose to the 1997 Legislature.<P>- Accepted a proposal for architectural and engineering services submitted by Luken Architecture PA for the Fire Training Simulator project.<P><B>Ways & Means/Budget</B><P>- Approved the following organizations to participate in the City's 1996 Charitable Campaign: Cooperating Fund Drive, The Health Fund of Minnesota, Open Your Heart to the Hungry and Homeless, The College Fund/UNCF, United Arts, Minnesota Environment Fund, and United Way of Minneapolis Area.<P><B>Taxes</B><P>- Approved 1996 assessment rolls and received report of the Board of Equalization. Of the 143 applications heard by the board, 82 assessments were lowered, two were raised and 59 held at their proposed levels.<P><B>Resolutions</B><P>- A resolution sponsored by all Council Members honors Billy Graham for his years of service and declares June 17 to 23 to be Billy Graham Week in Minneapolis.<P>- A resolution sponsored by 11 Council Members calls upon the U.S. Congress to raise the federal minimum wage.<P> <B>Further Information</B><P>This is partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or for details on specific actions, call 673-3130.<P><B>Corrections</B><P>The May 17 issue of On The Agenda incorrectly reported the May 10 action of the City Council related to the Transfer Station on 21st Avenue South. The station is not being moved; Council action was taken only on a street closure. The summary of Council actions also omitted the approval of regulations that protect construction and demolition sites from erosion.<P><HR>	<H3>Jobs Task Force to Hold Hearing</H3><P>The Joint Minneapolis/Saint Paul Living Wage Jobs Task Force will hold a public hearing Wednesday, June 12, on a living wage jobs policy for the two cities. The hearing will be 7 to 9 p.m. at Peavey Neighborhood Center, 730 East 22nd St.  The purpose of the hearing is to inform the task force's deliberations on a recommended policy. The task force will also hold hearings in August to receive comments on its recommendations.<P> The mission of the task force is to develop and propose job creation and retention policies for the two cities and their development agencies when their economic development dollars are allocated. The proposed guidelines will include provisions for the creation of new jobs in the cities and target jobs for city residents which pay enough to keep a family of four above the federal poverty level.<P><HR><H3>City News Briefs</H3><B>Haaf Garage Wins Award</B><P>The Jerry Haaf Garage, 424 S. Fourth St., Minneapolis, has won an Award of Merit from the International Parking Institute for design of facilities with less than 800 spaces.<P> <B>City and FDA Form Partnership</B><P>The City's Environmental Health Division and the U.S. Food and Drug Administration have teamed up to better protect consumers in the first such pairing in the state. The partnership agreement calls for specialized training and joint enforcement efforts. Training by the FDA and University of Minnesota will better equip Minneapolis sanitarians to deal with the challenges of emerging ethnic food trends and food safety issues.<P>   <B>"Waters Off" Project Wins Award</B><P>The "Waters Off" project, founded and organized by Plumbing Inspections supervisor Joe Tapsak, has received a Governor's Commendation Award from Partnership Minnesota for providing free plumbing repair work to elderly and low income residents throughout the Twin Cities.<P><HR> <H3>Planning Commission Agenda</H3>The commission will hold public hearings at 4:30 p.m. Wednesday, June 5, in 317 City Hall on the following:<P>- Conditional use permits for transitional housing at 2739 Cedar, coffee shop at 2649 Lyndale S, sign at 425 S 7th St, antenna at 1201 12th Av N, antenna at 400 East Lake, commercial use of third floor at 3112 Hennepin, and automobile convenience store at 3354 Penn Av N.<P><HR><H3>City Council Committee Items</H3><P>- An application has been received by residents on West 43rd Street between York & Zenith Avenues South for a Critical Parking Area.  A  hearing will be held by the Transportation & Public Works Committee in the near future.  Call the City Clerk's Office, 673-2046.<P>- The Zoning & Planning Committee  will hold a public hearing at 1:45 p.m. Tuesday, June 18, in 319 City Hall on a moratorium on the establishment of telecommunications antennas and transmission base sites including personal communication services networks. Information from 673-2219.<P><HR><H3>Board of Adjustment</H3>The board will conduct a public hearing at 2 p.m. Wednesday, June 12, in 319 City Hall to consider variations, nonconforming uses are other matters at the following addresses: 3019 47th Av S, 2572 West Lake of Isles Pkwy, 80 Malcolm Av SE, 514 N 3rd St, 5337 Bloomington Av, 2600 Aldrich Av N, 731 Pierce St NE, and 208 22nd Av NE.<HR><CENTER><H5>Questions or comments about <I>On The Agenda</I>? Send email to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I> </H5></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
