ns' Academy Starts Sept. 9</H3> <P>The Police Department is now accepting applications for its next Citizens' Academy. This is the fifth session of the popular program and the first to be held at the Minneapolis Police Department Second Precinct. The academy will meet on Monday nights from September 9 through November 25. Enrollment will be limited to 30 students.<P>The academy provides an inside look at law enforcement. Students tour the 9-1-1 dispatch center, watch a demonstration from the canine unit, take a ridealong with a patrol officer and participate in the Shoot/Don't Shoot video scenarios. Other topics include community oriented policing, drug enforcement, gang investigations, internal affairs procedures, case investigations and relations between the police and the media.<P><I>Call the 673-3391 for an application.</I> Participants must live or work in Minneapolis and be at least 21 years old. They can never have been convicted of a violent felony and must have no felony convictions in last five years or misdemeanor arrests in the last six months. <P><HR><H3>Awards Nominations Sought</H3> <P>The City is now accepting nominations for the ninth annual Minneapolis Awards. To be presented October 30, the awards honor people whose exceptional efforts have enriched the Minneapolis community. City officials will present the awards at a reception at International Market Square.<P> Any person who lives or works in Minneapolis is eligible. Recipients are selected by a committee of City officials and community representatives. The awards recognize those who have gone the extra mile to ensure the vitality of our arts, education, health and wellness, business, media, social services, parks and recreation, neighborhoods, science and technology, sports, youth, or government.<P><I>Nomination forms are available from the Office of Public Affairs, 673-2491. Nominations are due by Wednesday, August 28.</I> <P><HR><H3>June 7 City Council Actions</H3> <P><B>Community Development Committee</B> <P>- Directed staff to negotiate a redevelopment contract with Ryan Properties for the construction of an 750,000 square foot office tower on the Conservatory site (800 Nicollet Mall) and to draft development program, Common Project and tax increment financing documents.<P>- Approved Federal Low Income Tax Credits for Alliance Center, Phillips Design and Marvin Gardens projects.<P>- Approved Neighborhood Revitalization Program plans and funds for the following neighborhoods: Windom Park Neighborhood, $278,000 for a First Step Plan home improvement program.<P>- Approved 1996 budget allocation for the HOME program.<P>- Approved funding from Convention Center Sales Tax proceeds for the Northeast Neighborhood Early Learning Center.<P>- Approved 1996 funding strategy for the Minneapolis Industrial Land and Employment Strategy (MILES) program.<P><B>Public Safety & Regulatory Services</B> <P>- Approved Sidewalk Cafe Permits for six locations. The number of sidewalk cafes has grown substantially in recent years; the City currently licenses 107.<P> - Approved an ordinance related to sale of wine and beer at block events. Provisions include prior approval of a security plan and a limitation to events sponsored by organizations in the central and neighborhood business districts.<P>- Executed a contract with Hennepin County that provides for the county to continue to provide child health screening services under the 348-TOTS program.<P>- Authorized grant applications to the Minnesota Department of Public Safety's Community-Oriented Policing (COP) program to establish a "Weed & Seed" crime prevention program and to provide funding for additional police services in high-crime areas.<P><B>Ways & Means/Budget</B> <P>- Approved appointment of Michael Norton as Acting City Attorney.<P>- Authorized the execution of documents related to the City's partnership with the Edison Youth Hockey Association to develop an indoor ice arena.<P>- Authorized a request for proposals for the provision of domestic violence advocacy services.<P>- Accepted funds and issued fund availability notices to community agencies for the following programs:A) State and federal funds for Dislocated Worker Services program.B) State funds for the July 1996 through June 1997 implementation of Older Worker, School-To-Career for At-Risk Youth and Adult Employment and Training programs.C) Hennepin County funds for continuing implementation of the STRIDE program which provides employment and training for individuals who are participating in Aid for Families for Dependent Children program. D) County funds for the Minnesota Family Investment program, a demonstration project for families who receive public assistance.<P><B>Zoning & Planning</B> <P>- Extended the moratorium on movie theaters in Uptown until December 1997.<P>- Added a chapter to the Zoning Code titled "Industrial Living Overlay District." The chapter's purpose is to encourage the rehabilitation and reuse of existing industrial structures by providing for limited residential uses.<P><I>This is partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or for details on specific actions, call 673-3130. The minutes of recent City Council meetings can be found on the Internet at http://www.finance-commerce.com <P>City Cable 34 provides live coverage of City Council meetings. The next meeting begins at 9:30 a.m. Friday, June 28. Coverage is repeated Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays at 6 p.m.</I> <HR><H3>City Cable 34 Highlights</H3><P>City Beat airs Tuesdays at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 8:30 p.m. and Saturdays at 7:30 p.m. Host Kent Robbins' guests this week are Phil Handy of MCDA who talks about the Conservatory development project and Deputy Police Chief Greg Hestness who talks about Community Oriented Policing initiatives.<P>Mayor's Roundtable airs Tuesdays at 9 p.m., Thursdays at 6 p.m. and Saturdays at 9  p.m. Join host Mayor Sayles Belton and guest David Wiggins of the Minnesota Historical Society to talk about the Riverfront Heritage Trail.<P><HR>					<H3>Rental Licensing Vacancy</H3> <P>One position is currently vacant on the Rental Dwelling License Board of Appeals. The board hears and decides appeals from staff recommendations to deny, not renew, revoke, or suspend a rental dwelling license or provisional license. The board has seven members appointed by the City Council to two-year terms. Members must be residents. The board meets monthly or more frequently at the call of the Chair. For more information about the board's activities call 673-5824. Deadline is June 28. <I>Applications are available from the City Clerk, 673-2735.</I><P><HR> <H3>City Council Committee Items</H3><P>The Ways & Means/Budget Committee will hold public hearings on Tuesday, June 25, on the following items. <I>For more information call 673-2296.</I><P>10 a.m. - Amendment to the City employee residency requirement clarifying that persons who have retired or otherwise left City employment will be considered new employees subject to the residency requirement if they accept another City position.<P>10:30 a.m. - Interviews of applicants for appointment to the Minneapolis Telecommunications Network Board of Directors.<P>11 a.m. - Concurrence of the Mayor's appointment of Blair Rosenthal to the Minneapolis Civil Rights Commission.<P><HR><H3>June 26 Board of Adjustment</H3><P>The board will conduct a public hearing at 2 p.m. Wednesday, June 26, in 319 City Hall to consider variations, nonconforming uses are other matters at the following addresses. <I>For more information call 673-5836.</I><P>- 1817 3rd Av S, 3946 Lyndale Av N, 2312 Lake Place, and 118 West 48th St.<P><HR><CENTER><H5>Questions or comments about <I>On The Agenda</I>? Send email to <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I> </H5></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
