<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>On The Agenda -- 07/03/96</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><H1>ON THE AGENDA</H1><H2>City of Minneapolis Actions & Issues -- July 3, 1996</H2><I>On The Agenda provides information on issues, programs and actions ofthe City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. Forsign language interpreting call TTY 673-2626. Please send address correctionsto 323M City Hall, 55415 or fax to 673-2011. On The Agenda and other Citydocuments are available in alternative formats; call 673-2009. <BR><BR>This is Issue 19, Volume 12. The next issue of On the Agenda will be July19. </I><BR><BR><HR><H3>Get ready for <A HREF="/departments/police/nno/index.html">NationalNight Out</A>, Tuesday, August 6. <BR></H3><HR><H3>City Launches the &quot;What's Up&quot; Youth Information Line</H3>It's summer, finally. For grade school and high school students that meansgetting away from the ritual of attending classes, studying, and going toschool sporting events and other extracurricular activities. It also mightmean some serious down time with nothing to do. <BR><BR>Youth now have a new way to find out what to do in Minneapolis by simplypicking up the phone and calling <I>What's Up?</I> (399-9999), a new youthinformation line developed by the Minneapolis Youth Coordinating Board.<BR><BR><I>What's Up?</I> is the Twin Cities' first phone line that directly connectsyoung people to Minneapolis youth programs and activities. A recent study,conducted by the Search Institute for the Youth Coordinating Board, foundthat half of Minneapolis' young people ages 7 to 14 are not involved inconstructive youth development activities. One of the main reasons, accordingto the <I>Places to Grow</I> study, is lack of knowledge about availableprograms. Students interviewed for the study reported, however, that &quot;ifthere was a phone number to call that told us what's going on, we'd useit.&quot; And so the Minneapolis Youth Coordinating Board developed <I>What'sUp?</I> <BR><BR>The information line, staffed entirely by Minneapolis youth, operates from2  p.m. to 8  p.m., Monday through Friday, and from noon to 5  p.m., Saturdayand Sunday. <BR><BR>Here's how <I>What's Up?</I> works: youth call in and make initial contactwith peer operators, who can link callers to Minneapolis athletic activities,civic groups, community education classes, youth crisis counselors, jobopportunities, mentoring programs, park and recreation events, and weeklyentertainment stored in a database. Through a specially-designed geographiclocator computer program, engineered by the City's Engineering and Designdivision, operators can advise callers on the nearest place to participatein these programs and activities, and then actually connect their call toprogram organizers. <BR><BR>&quot;The Minneapolis Youth Coordinating Board has established a goal thatby the year 2000, 80 percent of Minneapolis young people ages 7 to 14 willbe involved in at least one youth development activity,&quot; the board'sExecutive Director, Colleen Moriarty said. &quot;<I>What's Up?</I> is acritical tool to help us meet that goal.&quot; <BR><BR><I>What's Up?</I> is made possible from sponsorship and donations from BrookfieldLePage, City of Minneapolis, Crisis Connection, Hennepin County, Karwoski& Courage Public Relations, McKnight Foundation, Minneapolis Employmentand Training, Minneapolis Department of Neighborhood Services, MinneapolisPark and Recreation, Minneapolis Public Library, Minneapolis Public Schools,Paragon Cable, Quik Print, Stay Alive Project, Transtop, Twin Cities One-to-Oneand Youth Trust. <BR><BR>Call Annie Nelson, 673-2060, for more information on <I>What's Up?</I> orthe Minneapolis Youth Coordinating Board. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Graffiti Increasing -- Brochure and Presentations Available </H3>As graffiti becomes a more common sight in Minneapolis, residents and businessowners need to know what they can do to stop it. <BR><BR>The Inspections Division and Police Department's Community Crime Prevention/SAFEUnit have produced a brochure entitled &quot;What You Can Do About Graffiti,&quot;that has free information on prevention, removal tips, removal productsand resources. <BR><BR>The city's graffiti problem is rapidly increasing, according to Jose Cervantesof the Minneapolis Department of Inspections. The Housing Section has issuedmore than 1,800 violation notices for graffiti this year as of June 5. Thatfigure is expected to rise to more than 2,500 by the end of the year, Cervantessaid. About 75 percent of the graffiti in the city is done by taggers, whoput their scrawls on as many buildings and street fixtures as possible togain recognition or fame. The rest is done by gang members who use graffitito mark their turf or send messages to rivals. <BR><BR>The City has taken a tough stance against graffiti in the past year withadditional laws, aggressive enforcement and education programs. <BR><BR>&quot;Community involvement is essential to reducing our graffiti problem,&quot;Cervantes said. &quot;This new brochure provides information to help peopleget involved. By following these tips, people can help keep graffiti fromtaking hold in their neighborhood.&quot; <BR><BR>Some important tips from the brochure are: <UL>  <LI>Report graffiti. Call 911 if you see graffiti being done or Teleserveat 348-9392 if you are a victim of graffiti.   <LI>Remove graffiti as soon as possible. Left alone, graffiti attractsgraffiti.   <LI>For removal assistance, call the Graffiti Hotline at 673-2090. TheCity offers free graffiti removal and paint-over services for residentsand businesses. Graffiti removal on other types of property is done by theowner. For example, graffiti on phone booths is removed by US West.   <LI>If you are removing graffiti yourself, you can pick up a free productat Minneapolis fire stations or purchase it at hardware, paint or auto stores.</UL>The Inspections Division will do free presentations on graffiti preventionand removal to block clubs, schools and businesses. CCP/SAFE can also provideinformation on controlling graffiti. Call 673-3015  to request a brochure.<BR><BR><HR><H3>City of Minneapolis News Briefs </H3><B>Employee's Invention Saves Money</B>  Minneapolis employee Charlie Runninghas invented a device that will simplify encasing electrical conduits inconcrete for traffic signals and street lights. The invention will savethe City thousands of dollars in labor and equipment rental each year. Thedevice, called The Running Connector, features a thin metal pipe glued toa PVC conduit tube. It easily attaches to existing pipe buried beneath thestreet without jack hammering through layers of concrete. More informationfrom Charlie Running, Public Works, 673-5750. <BR><BR><A NAME="anchor229796"></A><B>City to Add On-Street Bicycle Lanes</B>  Tomake city streets more bicycle friendly, Minneapolis has added seven newbicycle lanes. The lanes are on Park and Portland Avs. between 28th St.and Minnehaha Parkway; 10th and 11th Sts between Glenwood and Hennepin Avs.;E. 24th St. from Hennepin to 3rd Av.; Hennepin Av. from 10th to 11th St.and the Hennepin Bridge to Washington Av.; and Glenwood Av. from 12th to10th St. More information from Rhonda Rae, Public Works, 673-3439. <BR><BR><B>City Donates Computers</B>  Old computers will get new life at localsocial service agencies. The City recently donated almost 200 used computers,printers and other hardware to Sabathani Community Center's Horizons YouthProgram, Project for Pride in Living's Surplus Home & Office Products programand Oak Park Heights prison. At Sabathani, 35 computers will be used inan academic support program for students and given to youth who improveacademically. Details from Ron Hildeen, Information & Technology Services,673-3237. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Selected June 28 Minneapolis City Council Actions </H3><B>Community Development</B> <BLOCKQUOTE>- Accepted funds from the Minnesota Housing Financing Agencyfor equity participation loans. <BR>- Appropriated funds to stabilize the Washburn Crosby Complex. <BR>- Approved use of $1.5 million in NRP funds by the Minneapolis Public Schoolsfor facility improvements needed for the transition to community schools.</BLOCKQUOTE><BR><B>Appointments</B> <BLOCKQUOTE>- Reappointed Amy Yellowthunder to the Police Civilian ReviewAuthority. <BR>- Concurred with the Mayor's recommendation to appoint Shelly Prouix, JimRamnaraine and Debra Smith-McGee to the Advisory Committee on People withDisabilities. <BR>- Made the following appointments to the Bicycle Advisory Committee: NickKitchar representing the bicycle courier business, Fred Eisenbrey as a bicyclecourier, and Gary Shoquist representing the Minnesota Bicycle Coalition.<BR>- Concurred with the Mayor's appointment of Blair A. Rosenthal to the CivilRights Commission. <BR>- Appointed Ryan Young to the Minneapolis Telecommunications Network Boardof Directors. <BR>- Appointed Robert Copeland, Robert Greenberg and Linda Messenger to theHeritage Preservation Commission. <BR>- Appointed Donna Bell, Peggy Sand, Jerry Searles, Darcy Seaver and GregoryCondra to the Committee on Urban Environment. </BLOCKQUOTE><BR><B>Public Safety &amp; Regulatory Services</B> <BLOCKQUOTE>- Passed ordinance amendments related to environmentally acceptablepackaging. <BR>- Authorized $2,240,000 contract with Neighborhood Health Care Network toprovide health care enhancement and direct clinical services during 1996.<BR>- Approved demolition of nuisance buildings at 340 Morgan Av N, 330 LoganAv N and 421-23 4th Av NE. <BR>- Passed ordinance amendment related to inspections guidelines of rentalproperties. </BLOCKQUOTE><BR><B>Transportation &amp; Public Works</B> <BLOCKQUOTE>- Authorized solicitation of proposals from engineering consultingfirms for services related to traffic issues in the East Isles neighborhoodwith costs to be paid from the neighborhood's First Step NRP funds. <BR>- Passed actions approving new paving, streetscaping and lighting for NicolletAvenue from Grant to 29th Streets. <BR>- Approved City's participation in the 1996 Aquatennial festival to be heldJuly 12 to 21. <BR>- Directed the City Engineer to prepare a repair and financial plan forthe Cedar Lake Road bridge over Burlington Northern railroad tracks. <BR>- Authorized providing property line information to public on a mail orwalk-in basis only with a charge of $10 per property. <BR>- Approved installation of bicycle lanes. See <A HREF="#anchor229796">NewsBrief</A> in this issue of <I>On The Agenda</I>. <BR>- Accepted contributions totaling $900 from resident associations to bededicated to the cost of planning for the revitalization of the Loring Greenway.<BR>- Directed that work proceed with modifications to the intersection of HennepinAv S and West 28th St with costs to be reimbursed from the East Isles neighborhood'sFirst Step NRP plan. </BLOCKQUOTE><BR><B>Ways &amp; Means/Budget</B> <BLOCKQUOTE>- Passed an amendment to the residency ordinance clarifyingthat persons who retire and are rehired to City service are subject to residencyrequirements. <BR>- Authorized special duty time for fourteen Police Department band membersto participate in the July 11 Northwest Minneapolis Showboat Days Parade,Aquatennial parades on July 13 and 17, and the Northeast Parade on July23. <BR>- Authorized donations from the McKnight Foundation, Minnegasco, Beim Foundation,Charles Warner and Sandra Speiler for the Phillips Neighborhood Gatewayproject. <BR>- Approved 1996-1997 allocation plan for the Community Resource program.<BR>- Authorized contract with People of Phillips to implement a program totrain residents in property management. <BR>- Entered into a master agreement with the Minnesota Department of EconomicSecurity for Job Training Partnership Act funding through June 1999. <BR>- Accepted donation from Dayton's for the Minneapolis Initiative AgainstRacism. <BR>- Accepted FY96 Consolidated Plan entitlement totaling $22,178,000 and authorizedgrant agreements with HUD and amendments to the CDBG, HOME, ESGP & HOPWAsubcontracts. <BR>- Authorized Elections Department to send post cards to voters with pollingplace changes. </BLOCKQUOTE><BR><B>Zoning &amp; Planning</B> <BLOCKQUOTE>- Approved a moratorium on the establishment of telecommunicationantennas and transmission base sites, including personal communication networks.<BR>- Approved transportation management plans for two Uptown businesses. <BR>- Concurred with the Planning Commission's recommendation of the &quot;concentrateddevelopment&quot; option and parts of the &quot;growth centers&quot; optionof the Metropolitan Council's <I>Growth Options for the Twin Cities MetropolitanArea</I> report. </BLOCKQUOTE><BR><B>Resolutions</B> <BLOCKQUOTE>- Approved a resolution honoring the &quot;Thinking Big&quot;art project. <BR>- Passed a resolution opposing proposed rescheduling for the Twin City Districtof the Minnesota Amateur Hockey Association. <BR>- Approved a resolution honoring Andrew Aspin for his designation as MinnesotaPolice Officer of the Year. <BR>- Approved a resolution honoring Christine Joy Bahnemann. <BR>- Approved a resolution urging Japs-Olson Printing Company to stay in Minneapolis.</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>This is a partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or fordetails on specific actions, call 673-3130. The minutes of recent City Councilmeetings can be found on the Internet at <TT><A HREF="http://www.finance-commerce.com/">http://www.finance-commerce.com</A></TT>.City Cable 34 provides live coverage of City Council meetings. The nextmeeting begins at 9:30 a.m. July 12. Coverage is repeated Mondays, Wednesdaysand Fridays at 6 p.m. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Council Committee Hearings </H3><B>Community Development</B>  Details from Michola Foley, 673-3131. Mon.,July 15, 5:30 p.m., 319 City Hall: - Land sale at 615 E 36th St. - Redevelopmentof Conservatory site. <BR><BR><B>Ways &amp; Means/Budget </B> Details from 673-2147. Tues., July 9, 10a.m., 319 City Hall: - Interviews of applicants for appointment to the CivilRights Commission. <BR><BR><B>Zoning &amp; Planning </B> Details from Irene Homo, 673-2219. Tues.,July 15, 1:30 p.m., 319 City Hall: - Moratorium on the establishment orexpansion of commercial & industrial uses in the East Hennepin Study Area.- Moratorium on the establishment, expansion or change in the location ofsocial service facilities in the Central Business District as defined bythe area bounded by the freeway ring, 3rd Av N & the Mississippi River.July 10 <BR><BR><HR><H3>Planning Commission  </H3>For more information call 673-5836. Wed., July 10, 4:30 p.m., 317 City Hall:- Conditional use permits for expansion of existing building for recyclingfacility at 1025 33rd Av SE. - Site plan for sign at 3637 11th Av S. July10 Board of Adjustment Details from 673-5836. Wed., July 10, 2 p.m., 319City Hall. Variances, nonconforming uses or appeals at 2600 Nicollet, 146Edmund SE, 700 22nd Av NE, 4001 York Av S, 5425 Fremont Av S, and 2212 25thAv S. <BR><BR><HR><H3>Open Appointments </H3>Four positions are vacant on the Minneapolis <B>Advisory Committee on Drug& Alcohol Problems</B>. The committee advises the Council and Mayor on chemicaldependency treatment and management issues with special attention to theneeds of youth, elderly, minority, and chronic alcoholic populations andto innovative program approaches. The committee has 21 members appointedby the Mayor and confirmed by the City Council. More information from AmyStegora-Peterson, 673-2735. Deadline is July 26. <BR><BR>Four positions are currently open on the <B>Examining Board of Truth-In-HousingEvaluators</B>. The board issues certificates of competency to persons whoevaluate single- and two-family dwellings under the City's Truth-in-Saleof Housing Ordinance. The board also reviews content on the Truth-in-Housingevaluation and makes recommendations to the City Council regarding neededchanges. For detailed information call Al Olson, 673-2031. Deadline is July19. <BR><BR>Call 673-2735 for application forms. Hearing impaired persons may call TTY673-2157 between 9 a.m. and 4:30 p.m., Monday through Friday. <BR><BR><HR><BR><H5><CENTER>Questions or comments about <I>On The Agenda</I>? Send emailto <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I></CENTER></H5></BODY></HTML>
