 early access funds to acquire a building at16th and Chicago Av for a food buying club. <BR>- Approved request from the East Calhoun neighborhood for $25,000 of NRPearly access funds for a traffic study. <BR>- Approved NRP first step plan for the Fulton neighborhood. Activities includedin the $248,590 plan include a neighborhood festival, a transportation planfor 50th Street, a home improvement revolving loan fund, boundary signs,information kiosks and public safety programs. <BR>- Appropriated funds for site acquisition for the Camden Medical Clinic,42nd and Lyndale Avs N. <BR><B>PUBLIC SAFETY & REGULATORY SERVICES </B><BR>- Revoked rental dwelling license for property at 2300-24 Pleasant Av S.<BR>- Approved demolition of nuisance buildings at 3530 Elliot Av, 3113 6thSt N and 3024 Cedar Av. <BR>- Authorized City officials to support a partnership with the City of SaintPaul to build and manage a joint animal control shelter. The subject matterof reinstating funds to the 1996 budget for animal control, and of increasingrevenues through the sale of more licenses, was returned to the Public Safetyand Ways & Means committees. <BR>- Accepted a $50,000 community-oriented policing grant from the State ofMinnesota. <BR><B>TRANSPORTATION & PUBLIC WORKS</B> <BR>- Approved actions related to ornamental street lighting in the Healy Blockarea. Streets included are Clinton, 2nd and 3rd Avs S from Lake St to East33rd St. <BR>- Approved increases in fees charged by the City for no parking, loading,and valet zones that are located outside of parking meter areas or metertimes of enforcement. <BR>- Authorized installation of ornamental lighting on 5th Av S from 26th Stsouth to the railroad tracks with the cost to City to be reimbursed by Honeywell.<BR><B>WAYS & MEANS/BUDGET</B> <BR>- Authorized issuing a request for proposals to obtain a facilitator forthe Convention Center Employee/Management Work Team. <BR>- Approved funds to implement portions of the Phillips NRP American IndianAction Plan and authorized contracts or fund availability notices with employmentand training providers. <BR><B>ZONING & PLANNING </B><BR>- Approved a moratorium on the establishment or expansion of surface parkinglots in the Downtown Surface Parking Study Area. <BR>- Approved a moratorium on changes in land use along Hennepin Av S between31st & 36th Sts. <BR><BR><I>This is partial list of City Council actions. For a full list, or fordetails on specific actions, call 673-3130. The minutes of recent City Councilmeetings can be found on the Internet at http://www.finance-commerce.com.City Cable 34 provides live coverage of City Council meetings. The nextmeeting begins at 9:30 a.m. July 26. Coverage is repeated Mondays, Wednesdaysand Fridays at 6 p.m. Videotape of a a recent Police Department promotionceremony and of Fire and Police Department graduation ceremonies will followCity Council coverage. </I><BR><HR><H2>Charter Hearing August 8</H2>The Minneapolis Charter Commission will conduct a public hearing at 4 p.m.Thursday, August 8, in Room 317 City Hall, to consider the following proposalsto amend the City Charter. The commission is considering placing them onthe November ballot. <BR>- Proposed amendment eliminating staggered terms for Council Members . <BR>- Proposed amendment adding a provision for wine licenses for restaurantswhich do not meet the seven contiguous acres standard. <BR>- Proposed amendment eliminating the Minneapolis Board of Park Commissioners,establishing an investment land trust for the Park Board property, to bemanaged by appointed trustees, and merging the remainder of Park operationsinto a City department. <BR><I>For more information call Michola Foley, 673-3131. Hearing impaired personscan call TTY 673-2626. <BR></I><HR><H2>Council Committee Hearings </H2><B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT <BR></B><I>Details from Michola Foley, 673-3131. </I><BR>Monday, July 29, 9:30 a.m., 319 City Hall: <BR>- Revenue bonds for Catholic Charities to acquire, construct, rehab andequip various projects in Hawthorne, Jordan, North Loop, Near North, Phillips,Downtown West & Northrup neighborhoods. <BR>- Revenue bonds for A-1 Halper Box Company, 3552 & 3558 North 2nd St, toacquire, renovate and equip an existing building for box manufacturing andother uses. <BR>- Revenue bonds for Minnesota Orchestral Association, 1111 Nicollet Mall,to remodel and refurbish auditorium. <BR>- Draft update of Focus MCDA: Future Directions and Priorities, which isthe MCDA's business plan. <BR>- Lot division and land sale of the property at 3547 23rd Av S. Monday,August 12, 5:30 p.m., 319 City Hall: - Grantee Performance Report for the1996 Fiscal Year Consolidated Plan. For information call Larry Fehlen, 673-3350.<BR><B>ZONING & PLANNING</B> <BR><I>Details from Irene Homo, 673-2219. </I><BR>Tuesday, July 30, 1:30 p.m., 319 City Hall: <BR>- Ordinance related Capital Long Range Improvement process. <BR>- Continuation of hearing on the moratorium on the establishment or expansionof commercial & industrial uses in the East Hennepin Study Area. The moratoriumhas been expanded to include residential uses. <BR><HR><H2>City Cable 34 Highlights </H2><B><I>City Beat </I></B>airs Tuesdays at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 8:30 p.m.and Saturdays at 7:30 p.m. Host Kent Robbins' guest is Carol Brusegar ofCommunity crime Prevention/SAFE who will talk about National Night Out andwhy it's important to think of every night as National Night Out. Robbinsalso recaps July 12 City Council actions. <BR><B><I>Mayor's Roundtable </I></B>airs Tuesdays at 9 p.m., Thursdays at 6p.m. and Saturdays at 9 p.m. Mayor Sayles Belton discusses current issueswith her guests. <BR>Watch <B><I>Eye On Crime </I></B>Tuesdays at 8:30 p.m., Thursdays at 6:30p.m., Saturdays at 7 p.m. or Sundays at 6:30 p.m. Detective Cindy Hoxieof Hennepin County presents the Twin Cities 10 Most Wanted while host MinneapolisDeputy Chief Bill Jones features a Community Crime Prevention/SAFE unit.<BR><HR><H2>July 24 Planning Commission </H2><I>For more information call 673-5836.<BR></I>Wednesday, July 24, 4:30 p.m., 317 City Hall: <BR>- Location of a church in a former bowling alley in a B2S district at 1800Lowry Av N. <BR>- Final plat for development in vicinity of 4th Av N and West River Pkwy.<BR>- Site plan review for an automobile combination convenience facility at3354 Penn Av N. <BR>- Conditional use permit to replace an illuminated sign at 1221 NicolletMall. -<BR> Location of a motor vehicle repair garage at 3700 Chicago. <BR><HR><H2>June 26 Board of Adjustment </H2><I>For more information call 673-5836. </I><BR>Wednesday, July 24, 2 p.m., 319 City Hall: Variances, nonconforming usesor other matters at the following addresses: 3058 Stinson Blvd NE, 2506Sheridan Av S, 2605 40th Av S, 4235 5th Av S, 5339 Emerson Av S, 4033 WashburnAv S, 2812 Park, 2222 N 6th St & 419 23rd Av N, 118 West 48th St, 2312 LakePl, 1800 Lowry Av N and 1221 Nicollet Mall. <BR><BR><BR><HR><H5><CENTER>Questions or comments about <I>On The Agenda</I>? Send emailto <I><A HREF="mailto:opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us">opa_mpls@ci.mpls.mn.us</A></I></CENTER></H5></BODY></HTML>
