<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY><H1>ON THE AGENDA</H1><H2>City of Minneapolis Actions & Issues - August 2, 1996</H2><I><BR><BR>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions of theCity of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. Thisis Issue 21, Volume 12. Next issue will be August 16. Please send addresscorrections to 323M City Hall, 55415 or fax to 673-2011. ON THE AGENDA andother City documents are available in alternative formats, call 673-2009.The City provides sign language interpreting for City programs and services,call TTY 673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity &shyp;Affirmative Action Employer. </I><HR><H2>Mayor to Deliver Budget Framework Address August 6 </H2>Mayor Sayles Belton will deliver her 1997 Budget Framework Address to theCity Council at 10:30 a.m. Tuesday, August 6. The address describes theMayor's policy priorities and the City's financial outlook for 1997. August6 is also National Night Out. <BR><BR><I>Both events will be covered by City Cable 34. The Mayor's address willbe carried live with repeats Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays after the cablecastof City Council meetings. The full address will be available on the Internet.Highlights will be provided in the August 16 On The Agenda. Coverage ofNational Night Out will appear on Eye on Crime. </I><HR><H2><BR>Selected July 26 Minneapolis City Council Actions</H2><B>APPOINTMENTS </B><BR>- Approved reappointment of Daryl Lynn to the Police Civilian Review Authority.<BR>- Confirmed Mayor's appointment of Meg Forney, Lila Jacob, Thomas Adamsand Joni Herren to the Committee on Urban Environment. <BR><B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT </B><BR>- Authorized submission of application for a $6 million HUD grant for leadabatement and committed local matching funds. <BR><B>PUBLIC SAFETY & REGULATORY SERVICES</B> <BR>- Approved contract amendments to assign Minneapolis Police Officers tothe Fugitive Task Force and to the Violent Crime Strike Force with overtimecosts to be paid by the FBI. <BR>- Approved restructuring of the Minneapolis Emergency Communication Centeras bureau of Police Department with the MECC User Board to continue to provideoversight and policy direction. <BR>- Authorized $126,000 increase in Animal Control Budget to cover currentshortfall and challenged the department to raise an additional $50,000 inrevenue through a pet licensing campaign. The campaign will stress the benefitsof pet licensing but will not include door-to-door canvassing. See articleis this issue of On The Agenda. <BR>- Authorized submission of a grant application to the State of Minnesotafor community oriented policing funds and search for additional fundingunder federal Universal Hiring Program; approved 10-person increase in PoliceDepartment's authorized strength contingent upon receipt of funds. <B>TRANSPORTATION& PUBLIC WORKS</B> <BR>- Approved an agreement to allow use of the marquee of the Varsity Theater1306 4th St for promotion of Dinkytown area. <BR>- Approved NRP transportation planning funds for testing of traffic calmingmeasures in Prospect Park and East River Road neighborhoods ($35,000) andin the Fulton neighborhood ($3,900) - Approved $27,400 in NRP funds fora parking ramp feasibility study in the Lowry Hill neighborhood. <BR>- Directed temporary repair and long-term replacement plan for Cedar LakeRoad bridge over Burlington Northern railroad tracks near Cedar and BrownieLakes. Temporary repairs will cost $300,000 and extend the life of the bridgeby five years; half will be funded by the Park Board and half by the railroad.<BR>- Appropriated funs for installation of a stormdrain and removal of contaminatedsoil at the Valentine-Clark superfund site as part of the Bridal Veil Creekstorm drain project. Sources of funds are the University of Minnesota, Cityof Saint Paul, the United States Environmental Protection Agency and theMinnesota Pollution Control Agency. <BR>- Authorized issuance of request for proposals for geotechnical and environmentalconsulting services to determine if there is a risk associated with theash deposited at the Kasota Industrial Park from City incinerators decadesago. <BR><B>WAYS & MEANS/BUDGET</B> <BR>- Issued a fund availability notice to provide NRP funding to Club Fed throughthe Sumner-Glenwood action plan. <BR>- Received $980,800 in funding from the Minnesota Department of Public Safetyto hire 10 new police officers, pay overtime costs, and implement &quot;Weedand Seed&quot; project near Richard Green School. <BR><B>MAYOR'S VETO</B> <BR>- Sustained Mayor's veto of an action which would have revoked rental dwellinglicense at 2300-24 Pleasant Av S. <BR><BR><I>This is partial list of Council actions. For a full list, or for detailson any action, call 673-3130. The minutes of City Council meetings can befound at http://www.finance-commerce.com. The next Council meeting beginsat 9:30 a.m. August 9. Watch live on City Cable 34 or repeats Mondays, Wednesdaysand Fridays at 6 p.m. </I><HR><H2>Minneapolis Launches Pet Licensing Campaign</H2>Minneapolis Animal Control is initiating a campaign to encourage more catand dog owners to license their pets. The campaign, supported by the Mayorand Minneapolis City Council, is aimed at reducing the number of animalspermanently lost, impounded, or destroyed each year when their owners can'tbe found. Cat and dog licensing is required by ordinance in Minneapolis,but many owners don't realize licensing can better ensure their animal issafely returned home if it is lost or stolen. <BR><BR>&quot;We want to reduce the number of animals who are impounded or mustbe destroyed because there's no way to identify them,&quot; says LeslieYoder, Animal Control Manager. &quot;The benefits of pet licensing are wellworth the small cost. If your animal is ever lost or strays, it can be easilyidentified and returned home. You also avoid the impound fee to recoveryour animal from the shelter.&quot; Yoder says the public benefits becauselicensing requires cats and dogs to have current rabies vaccinations andmakes it easier to track an animal if it has bitten someone. <BR><BR>Animal Control staff will be carrying their licensing campaign into thecommunity to neighborhood events, libraries, pet stores, veterinary officesand precinct stations, to educate owners about benefits of licensing, andprovide licensing opportunities. &quot;There's nothing worse for a cat ordog owner than losing their animal,&quot; says Yoder, &quot;and nothingmakes us happier than to return a pet to its owner. If the campaign savesanimals, it's well worth the effort.&quot; <BR><BR><I>Minneapolis City Code currently requires licensing for cats and dogsmore than four months old. Pets which are spayed, neutered or less thaneight months old can be licensed for $10; others are $15. For additionalinformation on pet licensing, call Animal Control at 348-4250, or City Licensingat 673-2050. </I><HR><H2>Police Athletic League Will Sponsor Flag Football League </H2>The Minneapolis Police Athletic League (P.A.L.) will sponsor a flag footballleague for 5th and 6th grade boys and girls this fall. The eight-week seasonbegins September 10 with two practices and a game each week. Several coacheswill be Police Officers giving the players a chance to get to know the menand women behind the badge. P.A.L. is a national organization of policeofficers in partnership with youth and their communities. It is designedto foster mutual respect between youth and officers through athletic andrecreational events. <BR><BR><I>Application forms for the flag football league are being mailed to parentsof all Minneapolis 5th and 6th graders. Parents can also get informationby call 827-9560. </I><HR><H2><BR>Club Fed Announces August 13 Youth Power Jam at Target Center </H2>City Council President Jackie Cherryhomes and youth from CLUB FED announcedthis week that CLUB FED's Youth Power Jam will be held at the Target Centeron Tuesday, August 13. Youth Power Jam participants will sign a pledge tokeep their communities free of violence and will observe a moment of silenceto honor local homicide victims. Entertainment will include top-ten concertacts Goodie Mob, Quad City Dis, Monifah and Puppies along with a nationaldrill team competition. The event will also feature a youth fair with informationon educational, career and service resources. CLUB FED's objective is fillthe Target Center with youth and family members who are committed to preventingviolence. The event will begin at 5 p.m. and end at 9 p.m. <BR><BR>Officials also launched the What's Up Poll on Tuesday morning. CLUB FEDinterns polled youth and adults on their choice for President and othercritical issues through Friday, August 2, from a booth at Nicollet Malland 7th Street. Their purpose was to demonstrate to youth how fun the politicalprocess can be, as well as to take a snapshot of what voters are thinkingabout. <BR><BR><I>Tickets for the Youth Power Jam are $16 and can be purchased at all Ticketmasteroutlets or the Target Center box office. Results of the What's Up Poll willappear in a future issue of On The Agenda. Call 377-9441. </I><HR><H2>Hearing Set on FY95 Consolidated Plan Performance Report </H2>The Community Development Committee of the City Council will conduct a PublicHearing, pursuant to HUD's Citizen Participation requirements, on the City'sFY95 Consolidated Plan Performance Report on Monday, August 12, beginningat 5:30 p.m. in Room 319 City Hall, 350 South 5th St. <BR><BR>Staff of the City of Minneapolis, the Minneapolis Community DevelopmentAgency (MCDA), and the Minneapolis Public Housing Authority (MPHA) encourageparticipation in the development of the City's FY95 Consolidated Plan PerformanceReport for Community Development Block Grant (CDBG), HOME Investment PartnershipsProgram (HOME), Emergency Shelter Grants Program (ESGP), and the HousingOpportunities for Persons with AIDS (HOPWA) federal entitlement funding.The FY95 Consolidated Year is June 1, 1995 through May 31, 1996. Citizenscan attend the public hearing, speak at the hearing, and/or submit writtencomments before, during, or after the hearing. <BR><BR>The FY95 Consolidated Plan is available for review at the Minneapolis Grants& Special Projects Office (200 City Hall), Municipal Information Library(300 City Hall), MCDA (700 Ceresota Mill), and all Minneapolis Public Libraries.The FY95 Consolidated Plan Performance Report is available for review atthe Minneapolis Contract Management Office (325M City Hall) and at the publichearing. <BR><BR>If you are unable to attend this Public Hearing, you can send comments youfeel should be considered during the development of the City's FY95 ConsolidatedPlan Performance Report to the Office of Grants & Special Projects, Room200 City Hall, 350 South Fifth Street, Minneapolis MN 55415. If you haveany questions, contact Ken Brunsvold at 673-2348 or by fax at 673-2728.<HR><H2>Council Committee Hearings </H2><B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT <BR></B><I>Details from Michola Foley, 673-3131. </I><BR>Monday, August 12, 9:30 a.m., 319 City Hall: <BR>- Lot division and land sale of the property at 21 West 32nd St. <BR>- Issuance of up to $4.6 million of industrial development revenue bondsfor Ambassador Press, Inc. to finance a manufacturing facility at Washingtonand 14th Avs N. <BR>- Issuance of up to $6 million of industrial development revenue bonds forThe Community Home Program Company to finance construction of 11 duplexes& 8 single units of adult foster care facilities at various sites in HennepinCounty. <BR>- Issuance of up to $1.35 million of industrial development revenue bondsfor Turning Point, Inc to finance a chemical dependency treatment projectat 1500 Golden Valley Road. <BR><B>TRANSPORTATION &amp; PUBLIC WORKS<BR></B><I