<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY><H1>ON THE AGENDA</H1><H2>City of Minneapolis Actions & Issues - August 21, 1996<BR></H2><I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions ofthe City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. Thisis Issue 22, Volume 12. Next issue will be September 6. Please send addresscorrections to 323M City Hall, 55415 or fax to 673-2011. ON THE AGENDA andother City documents are available in alternative formats, call 673-2009.The City provides sign language interpreting for City programs and services,call TTY 673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity - AffirmativeAction Employer.</I><HR><H2>Mayor Proposes Zero-Tolerance for Crime, Zero Increase in Tax Rates</H2>Zero-tolerance for crime is Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton's top 1997 budgetpriority. On August 6, she outlined a &quot;smart, tough&quot; crime-fightingprogram in her 1997 Budget Framework Address. <BR><BR>The Mayor presented her &quot;Framework for a Safe City&quot; message toan audience of city officials and community leaders. The speech launchesthe budget-preparation season by giving department heads a policy frameworkfor proposing their respective budgets. The Mayor makes her final budgetrecommendations to the City Council in November.<BR><BR>The City would use saturation police patrols in neighborhoods and aroundschools and parks to enforce zero-tolerance for misdemeanors which she saidwere &quot;gateways to crime.&quot; She said the program calls for the CityAttorney to more aggressively prosecute misdemeanors, and that she has askedthe Hennepin County District Court to &quot;put the full muscle of the criminaljustice system behind the good work of the Minneapolis Police Department.&quot;<BR><BR>The Mayor said the Minneapolis Board of Education has responded to her calllast year to begin and end the school day later so that children would beoff the streets during peak crime hours. <BR><BR>&quot;I am happy to announce, together with School Board Chair Bill Greenand Superintendent Peter Hutchinson, that the Minneapolis Board of Educationhas voted to work with the community to develop by December a recommendationto change start times beginning in 1997.&quot; She outlined an intensiveprogram of cooperation between the schools and the City, including police-protectedsafe routes for children who walk to school. <BR><BR>The program &quot;enforces a policy of zero-tolerance for crime, zero-tolerancefor drugs, zero-tolerance for prostitution, zero-tolerance for guns, andzero-tolerance for gangs.&quot;<BR><BR>She said the City must assist the Park Police with park security, and encouragedthe Minneapolis Park and Recreation Board to proceed with its proposed RecExtraprogram, which will offer activities for families and children on summerweekends, starting in 1997. She said it was crucial to introduce the programin &quot;neighborhoods where we must take back the parks for the familiesand children of Minneapolis.&quot;<BR><BR>Pointing out that last year her 1996 budget raised the authorized policestrength to an all-time high, she said that simply assigning more policeofficers to the streets is not enough. &quot;We must fight crime the sameway a general fights a war: by holding our ground, preventing all incursions,and denying the enemy a foothold. We must stop criminals at the very gatewayto crime. Low-level, or gateway crimes, destroy our sense of safety, ourtrust in each other, and create an environment for more serious crime.&quot;<BR><BR>Although the Mayor asked for plans for a number of new initiatives, shesaid they could not lead to any increased cost to taxpayers. In fact, shesaid, department heads would have to cut total expenditures by $2 million.&quot;I am absolutely committed to avoiding an increase in the tax rate.&quot;<BR><BR>Other initiatives include:<BR>- Doing a better - and cheaper - job of neighborhood cleanups by coordinatingsanitation and street sweeping efforts. She said pilot projects were beingplanned for Central neighborhood in August, and Phillips in October.<BR>- Using untapped resources to help the city meet peak seasonal needs, suchas writing tickets during snow emergencies, cutting down weeds and removingrubbish. Resources include workers on light duty, summer youth workers.She said workers could be cross-trained and work year-round, instead ofbeing hired for summer work and laid off in the winter when they receiveunemployment and on-call bonuses. She stressed the need to work cooperativelywith organized labor to accomplish these goals.<BR>- Shifting the emphasis of School-Based Health Clinics to prevention inorder to improve student performance. <BR>- Investing in a program to reduce the &quot;slow leak&quot; of losses fromclaims and lawsuits, saving the City $200,000 in the first year and $500,000annually thereafter.<BR>- A preliminary plan for improvements needed in the City water system. <BR>- An Office of Citizen Services, a one-stop shop for citizens to obtaininformation and referrals, and an interdepartmental Task Force for Childrenand Families. <BR><BR><I>City Cable 34 will air videotape of the Mayor's address after taped repeatsof City Council meetings through September 11. Rebroadcasts of Council meetingsair Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays at 6 p.m. The full text of the addressis on the Internet - the City's home page address is http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us.Printed copies can be obtained from the Mayor's Office, 673-2100.</I><HR><H2>Town Meeting Set for September 19 </H2>Minneapolis city government will move from downtown to the neighborhoodson the evening of Thursday, Sept. 19. <BR><BR>The Minneapolis City Council and Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton will hold aMinneapolis Town Meeting at which citizens can obtain information aboutcity services and express their views on how city government is meetingits goals.<BR><BR>&quot;The Town Meeting is a unique chance for elected officials to hearfrom citizens about how we are doing in meeting our goals for Minneapolis,&quot;said City Council President Jackie Cherryhomes. &quot;We want to make iteasy and convenient for citizens to talk with us so we're getting out ofCity Hall and into a neighborhood.&quot;<BR><BR>The Open House featuring city departments will start at 6 p.m. Thursday,Sept. 19, and the Town Meeting will begin at 7 p.m. The event will be inthe Northeast Armory, 1025 Broadway Street NE, which is one block east ofCentral Avenue.<BR><BR>At the Open House, citizens will be able to pick up information and gettheir questions answered on a wide range of city services. City staff willhave information on everything from how to prevent crime to how to get ahome improvement loan. Citizens can learn how the city estimates the valueof their homes, how to get a job with the city and how to schedule an eventat the Convention Center. They can also register to vote.<BR><BR>At the Town Meeting, citizens will have an opportunity to tell City CouncilMembers and the Mayor how well they think the city is doing in meeting itseight official goals. The goals are livable neighborhoods that are safe,convenient transportation services, strong and healthy families and children,educational opportunities for all children through successful public schools,an economy that creates job opportunities, a strong and healthy downtown,protection of the natural and built environment, and a municipal governmentthat is efficient, effective and responsive to community needs. <H2><BR><HR>Selected August 9 Minneapolis City Council Actions <BR></H2><B>Appointments</B><BR>- Appointed Dorothy Balen to the Minneapolis Advisory Committee on Peoplewith Disabilities.<BR>- Concurred with Mayor's reappointment of E. Maurice Nakumbe to the CivilService Commission.<BR>- Approved Mayor's appointment of Joan Willshire to the Capital Long-RangeImprovements Committee.<BR><B>Community Development</B><BR>- Approved Focus MCDA - Future Directions and Priorities document.<BR>- Approved redevelopment agreement with Ryan Properties and other actionsfor Conservatory site, 800 Nicollet Mall.<BR>- Approved actions related to City assistance for the expansion of the WedgeCo-op, 2105 Lyndale Av S.<BR>- Approved revenue bonds for the renovation of Orchestra Hall and for HalperBox Co., 3552 and 3558 North 2nd St.<BR>- Approved offer to purchase City-owned land located in Plymouth.<BR><B>Public Safety &amp; Regulatory Services</B><BR>- Authorized submission of joint grant application with Hennepin Countyto the State to continue Hennepin County/Minneapolis Narcotics EnforcementTask Force.<BR>- Authorized submission of grant application to State for continuation ofcommunity volunteer coordinator at police/community substation located atLowry and Emerson Avs N.<BR>- Approved demolition of nuisance structures at 1601 Lincoln St NE, 907Morgan Av N and 3008 21st Av S.<BR>- Accepted $1.5 million Federal Law Enforcement Block Grant to be used toexpand community policing programs.<BR>Transportation &amp; Public Works<BR>- Approved several actions related to Nicollet Av S paving, lighting andstreetscape project.<BR>- Approved use of NRP transportation planning funds for stop signs in theCleveland neighborhood and crosswalks with flashers at Minnehaha Creek bikepath crossings located at 28th and Nokomis Avs S.<BR><B>Ways &amp; Means/Budget</B><BR>- Approved use of Standish Ericsson NRP funds for Hiawatha Camp project.<BR>- Accepted donation of funds from NSP for manufacturing lab at North Highand from Cargill Corporation and General Mills Foundation for employmentand training system.<BR>- Accepted donations for the Phillips Neighborhood Gateway from the MinneapolisFoundation, Baha'i Assembly of Minneapolis and Intermedia Arts Minnesota.<BR>- Approved agreement with Domestic Abuse Project (DAP) for provision ofdomestic abuse advocacy services.<BR><B>Zoning &amp; Planning</B><BR>- Approved a moratorium on the establishment or expansion of residential,commercial or industrial uses in the East Hennepin study area.<BR>- Found environmental assessment worksheet for Heritage Landing projectto be adequate. Heritage Landing is a multifamily housing development boundedby 1st and 2nd Sts N and 4th and 7th Avs N.<BR><B>Resolutions</B><BR>- Approved a resolution providing for assistance in the removal of treeson private property that were damaged by August 6 windstorms and enablingthe replacement of sidewalks.<BR><BR><I>This is partial list of Council actions. For a full list, or for detailson any action, call 673-3130. The minutes of City Council meetings can befound at http://www.finance-commerce.com. The next Council meeting beginsat 9:30 a.m. August 23. Watch live on City Cable 34 or repeats Mondays,Wednesdays and Fridays at 6 p.m. </I><HR><H2>September Events</H2><B>September 10 - Primary Election</B><BR>Voters can cast absentee ballots in person or by mail. Minneapolis residentscan vote in person at Room 1B City Hall between 8 a.m. and 4:30 p.m. Mondaythrough Friday, or from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. on Saturday, September 7, or until7 p.m. on Monday, September 9. To vote by mail, call 673-2070 before August30 for an application to obtain a ballot. <BR><BR><B>September 12 &amp; 13 - Vital Communities Conference</B><BR>Sponsored by the Neighborhood Revitalization Program and the MinneapolisPlanning Department, the conference will focus on ideas for creating strongercommunities and new methods for improving neighborhood planning. Call 673-5158for a complete conference announcement. <BR><BR><B>September 19 - Phillips Neighborhood Employment Fair</B><BR>The fair will be held at the American Indian Center, 1530 East FranklinAv, from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. Come ready to be interviewed on the spot; morethan 50 employers, many with job openings that are on&nbsp;a busline andpay more than $7 an hour will be there. For people not ready for employment,service agencies will be available with information on training. Call 871-2122for more information.<BR><BR><B>September 19 - Minneapolis Town Meeting<BR></B><I>See article in this On The Agenda.<BR><BR></I><B>September 21 - Northside Housing Fair</B><BR>Financing workshops, home improvement demonstrations, landscaping and paintingseminars - the Northside Housing Fair will have them all from 9:30 a.m.to 2 p.m. Saturday, September 21. Stop by the North Star Primary School,2410 Girard Av N. Call 673-2491 for more information. <HR><H2><BR>Board of Estimate Hearing</H2>As required by the City Charter, the Board of Estimate and Taxation willhold a public hearing on the proposed maximum property tax levies for 1997at 5 p.m. Thursday, September 5, in 319 City Hall. <BR><BR>The hearing provides citizens and organizations an opportunity to expresstheir views on proposed maximum 1997 property tax levies for the City Council,the Park and Recreation Board, the Library Board, and the Public HousingAuthority prior to the setting of the maximum amounts by the Board of Estimateand Taxation. <BR><BR><I>Call 673-2029 for information.</I><HR><H2>City Cable 34 Highlight</H2>Watch a new edition of Eye On Crime Tuesdays at 8:30 p.m., Thursdays at6:30 p.m., Saturdays at 7 p.m. or Sundays at 6:30 p.m. Deputy Chief GregHestness will discuss the Safe Streets program.<HR><H2>Council Committee Hearing</H2><B>Transportation &amp; Public Works<BR></B><I>Details from Jan Belsaas, 673 -3132</I><BR>Thursday, September 5, 9:30 a.m., Room 319:<BR>- Proposal to renew contract to hold Children's Grand Prix auto race indowntown Minneapolis for calendar years 1997 and 1998.<HR><H2>Open Appointments</H2><B>Previously Announced</B><BR>- Three positions on the Civil Rights Commission. Deadline is August 30.<BR>- Five vacancies on the Public Health Advisory Board to be filled by 