Minneapolis Firefighterstrained at Hennepin Technical College and first to complete Emergency MedicalTechnician and Hazardous Materials training before joining the department.<BR><BR>While the total number of Fire Department personnel decreased from 1981to 1996, the number of protected class employees increased from 43 to 133out of a current total of 441 employees. &quot;We're not underutilized inany male category,&quot; said Forte, &quot;and, in comparison to 12 othermajor metropolitan fire departments, we employ the largest percentage offemale firefighters - 9.5 percent.&quot; (Seattle is the closest competitorwith 8.2 percent; New York City's female firefighters compose 0.32 percentof the total force.) <BR><BR>Measured alone, protected class members hold 42 percent of all Firefighterpositions in Minneapolis. Forte said percentages for protected class Firefighterswould be even higher, but a record number of persons of protected classwere promoted in 1995 and 1996 from Firefighter to other positions in thedepartment.<HR> <H2>Consolidated Plan Meeting Set</H2>The City of Minneapolis will conduct a public meeting on the City's FY97Consolidated Plan on Wednesday September 18, beginning at 5 p.m. at theMCDA offices on the second floor of Crown Roller Mill,105 Fifth Avenue South.<BR><BR>Staff of the City of Minneapolis, the Minneapolis Community DevelopmentAgency (MCDA), and the Minneapolis Public Housing Authority (MPHA) inviteyou to participate in the development of the City's FY97 Consolidated Planfor Community Development Block Grant (CDBG), HOME Investment PartnershipsProgram (HOME), Emergency Shelter Grants Program (ESGP), and the HousingOpportunities for Persons with AIDS (HOPWA) federal entitlement funding.<BR><BR>The FY97 Consolidated Year is June 1, 1997 through May 31, 1998. Citizenscan participate by attending the meeting, by speaking at the meeting, and/orsubmitting written comments before, during, or after the meeting. If youare unable to attend this public meeting, you can send comments and relevantdata such as articles, reports, studies or surveys you feel should be consideredduring the development of the City's FY97 Consolidated Plan to the MinneapolisOffice of Grants &amp; Special Projects, 200 City Hall, 350 South FifthSt., 55415. If you have any questions, call Ken Brunsvold at 673-2348.<BR><BR>The FY95 and FY96 Consolidated Plans are available for review at the Grants&amp; Special Projects Office (200 City Hall), Municipal Information Library(300 City Hall), MCDA (700 Ceresota Mill), and Public Libraries. Copiesof FY95 plan (370 pages) or FY96 plan (207 pages) are available for purchaseat printing and mailing costs &shyp; pick up at Room 200 City Hall for $10or mailed first class for $15. Checks should be payable to Minneapolis FinanceDepartment. Please order from Grants &amp; Special Projects.<HR> <H2>Selected August 23 Minneapolis City Council Actions</H2><B>APPOINTMENTS</B><BR>&shyp; Concurred with Mayor's appointment of Randall Bradley to the CapitalLong-Range Improvement Committee.<BR><B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT</B><BR>&shyp; Approved FY95 Grantee Performance Report for Consolidated Plan andauthorized submission to HUD.<BR>&shyp; Approved modification to Windom NRP action plan and appropriatedfunds for community school.<BR>&shyp; Authorized Livable Communities grant application to MetropolitanCouncil for Franklin Avenue project.<BR>&shyp; Gave preliminary approval to issue revenue bonds for Ambassador Pressmanufacturing facility 14th &amp; Washington Avs N.<BR>&shyp; Gave final approval to issue revenue bonds for Turning Point chemicaldependency treatment facility, 1500 Golden Valley Rd.<BR><B>INTERGOVERNMENTAL</B> <B>RELATIONS</B><BR>&shyp; Set language for November 5 ballot on proposed charter amendmentseliminating staggered terms for City Council Members and providing winelicenses for neighborhood restaurants.<BR>&shyp; Transmitted City's position on license application submitted by CrownHydro to Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.<BR><B>PUBLIC SAFETY &amp; REGULATORY SERVICES</B><BR>&shyp; Approved assignment of police officer to the Drug Enforcement Administrationtask force for suppression of drug trafficking.<BR>&shyp; Approved demolition of nuisance structures at 1502 Thomas Av N, 2128Bryant Av N and 1700 Hillside Av.<BR>&shyp; Approved proceeding with design of new 5th Precinct Station and increasedcapital budget for project.<BR>&shyp; Passed an ordinance providing for a regulatory fee for contaminatedsites.<BR>&shyp; Accepted State award to the Police Cadet program for success of program,aggressive recruitment and hiring of protected classes.<BR>&shyp; Authorized contract with Hennepin Technical College to provide taxicabdriver training and directed staff to examine alternatives.<BR><B>TRANSPORTATION &amp; PUBLIC WORKS</B><BR>&shyp; Approved contract for disposal of contaminated soil from Bridal VeilCreek Watershed.<BR>&shyp; Renamed 250 S 4th St to &quot;City of Minneapolis, Public ServiceCenter.&quot;<BR>&shyp; Approved renegotiated contract for processing, transfer and/or disposalof City-collected yard waste.<BR>&shyp; Approved actions related to Healy Block street lighting project.<BR>&shyp; Approved agreement for the installation and maintenance of bicycleroutes, four-way stop and traffic circle test in Marcy-Holmes with coststo be reimbursed from NRP funds.<BR>&shyp; Authorized solicitation of proposals for engineering consultant servicesrelated to improvements to water system.<BR>&shyp; Established a fund to receive &amp; hold money reimbursed from environmentalclaims for remediation of environmental issues.<BR>&shyp; Approved contracts for Impound Lot towing services and increasedtowing fee from $65 to $70 and &quot;Bill of Sale&quot; fee from $3 to $10.<BR><B>WAYS &amp; MEANS/BUDGET</B><BR>&shyp; Approved contract with consultant to represent City regarding thirdparallel runway and other airport issues.<BR>&shyp; Authorized application for $490,000 to acquire properties adjacentto Central Park and Richard Green Central Park School under the Safe &amp;Drug-free Schools and Community Grant program.<BR><B>ZONING &amp; PLANNING</B><BR>&shyp; Granted a waiver from the East Hennepin development moratorium toenable leasing of space in the 200 block of East Hennepin.<BR>&shyp; Rezoned 2301 Dupont Av S to permit expansion of funeral chapel.<BR>&shyp; Passed ordinances regulating the establishment of telecommunicationantennas and transmission base sites, including personal communication networks.<BR><B>RESOLUTION</B><BR>&shyp; Approved a resolution recognizing the 25th anniversary of the Como-HarrietStreetcar.<BR><BR><I>This is partial list of Council actions. For a full list, or for detailson any action, call 673-3130. The minutes of City Council meetings can befound at http://www.finance-commerce.com. The next Council meeting beginsat 9:30 a.m. September 13. Watch live on City Cable 34 or repeats Mondays,Wednesdays and Fridays at 6 p.m. </I><HR><H2>Reminders</H2>&shyp; Tell the Mayor and Council how the City is doing in meeting its goalsat a <B>Town Meeting</B> at 7 p.m. Thursday, September 19 at the NortheastArmory, 1025 Broadway NE.<BR>&shyp; You can afford to buy a home or make needed repairs. Find out howat the <B>Northside Housing Fair</B>. It's free and will be held at theNorth Star School, 2410 Girard Avenue North, from 9:30 a.m. to 2 p.m. Saturday,September 21. <HR><H2>Planning Commission Agenda</H2>The commission will conduct public hearings starting at 4:30 p.m. Wednesday,September 11, on the following items:<BR>&shyp; Rezoning of 2024 Lyndale Av. N for Salvation Army church and corpsfacility.<BR>&shyp; Application for adult day care center at 4525 Aldrich Av. S.<BR>&shyp; Various actions including site plan review and rezoning to allowdevelopment of the &quot;Quarry&quot; sho