<H1>ON THE AGENDA</H1>
<H2>City of Minneapolis Actions & Issues<BR>
October 18, 1996</H2>
<I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions of
the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. This
is Issue 2, Volume 14. Next issue will be November 1. Please send address
corrections to 323M City Hall, 55415 or fax to 673-2011. ON THE AGENDA and
other City documents are available in alternative formats, call 673-2009.
The City provides sign language interpreting for City programs and services,
call TTY 673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity &shyp;
Affirmative Action Employer.</I><HR> 
<H2>Civil Rights Conducts Workshops </H2>
A series of upcoming workshops will help people learn about their civil
rights, understand the nature of discrimination, and see how the Minneapolis
Department of Civil Rights enforces the law. Residents and individuals or
organizations conducting business in the city of Minneapolis are encouraged
to attend. Elsa Batica, Deputy Civil Rights Director, will conduct the workshops
at the following times:  
<UL>
  <LI>Thurs., Oct. 31, 8:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. Understanding Personal and
Institutional Discrimination, with guest Yusef Mgeni, President, Urban Coalition
 
  <LI>Thurs., Nov. 14, 8:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. Racism and Sexism: How it
is Perpetuated in the Workplace and How to Prevent It, with guest Stephen
Schaffer, Assistant Professor, Saint Mary's University  
  <LI>Thurs., Dec. 5, 8:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. Anti-Semitism: Another Form
of Racism? With guest Carol Wirtschafter, Associate Director, Jewish Community
Relations Council of Minnesota and the Dakotas 
</UL>
<BR>
All three workshops will be held in 241 City Hall. The registration fee
is $40 per workshop. A limited number of scholarships are available. Sign
language service is available. For details, call Alanna S. Tyler at 673-3012.
For TTY service, call 673-2044. <BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H2>Call for Nominations: Outstanding Achievement in Civil Rights </H2>
The Minneapolis Civil Rights Commission is accepting nominations for its
annual Outstanding Achievement Award. The Commission presents this award
to an organization or individual who makes significant contributions in
civil or human rights. Past recipients worked in diverse areas such as education,
legal advocacy, the arts or politics to make Minneapolis a place that has
No Place for Prejudice. <BR>
<BR>
Deadline for nominations is Fri., Nov. 8. To get a form, call Jill Bryant
at 673-2146, TTY 673-2044. <BR>
<H2><HR></H2>
<H2>Lakes to Get Alum Dose </H2>
The cloudy waters of Cedar Lake and Lake of the Isles will dramatically
clear this fall and should remain that way for years to come following treatment
with a chemical that controls algae. The treatment in mid-October with aluminum
sulfate, commonly called alum, will help control algae by reducing the amount
of phosphorus in the water. The treatment is expected to take a week to
10 days. <BR>
<BR>
Alum is commonly used in water treatment plants and has been used around
the country in more than 100 lake restoration projects. The alum treatment
will help control internal phosphorus for 10 to 15 years. The treatment
is harmless to aquatic creatures, plants, and people. <BR>
<BR>
Once phosphorus controls are completed at Lake Calhoun, it also will undergo
an alum treatment. The Calhoun treatment is scheduled for 1998. <BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H2>Elections Information Now on Web </H2>
Minneapolis residents can now receive important elections information online.
The information is available on the City of Minneapolis web site.  <A HREF="/departments/city-council/clerk/elections/index.html">Click
here to jump</A> to the elections page.<BR>
<BR>
The site provides information about voting -- including how to preregister,
how to register on voting day, and how to vote by absentee ballot. Voters
may also find out where to vote using precinct maps. The five questions
voters will see on their ballots are also posted on the site. <BR>
<BR>
The web site is part of the voter information program &quot;Ready, Set,
Vote&quot; conducted by the Minneapolis Elections and Voter Registration
Department. Minneapolis voters can also call 673-2070 for information. <BR>
<BR>
The Minneapolis web site also offers other important City information, including
back issues of <I>On The Agenda</I>. People without home or business access
to the Internet can get online at select Minneapolis libraries. To find
the closest public access terminal, call 372-6633. <BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H2>City Calendar Published </H2>
Free Minneapolis calendars containing 1996-97 snow emergency rules, a list
of City telephone numbers, and other important information will soon be
delivered to Minneapolis households. The calendar covers Nov. 1996 through
Oct. 1997. It includes useful information about City services as well as
holidays and community events. <BR>
<BR>
The calendars will be in home-delivered copies of the Alley, Longfellow
Nokomis Messenger, Northeaster, North News, Seward Profile, Southeast Angle,
Southside Pride, Southwest Journal, Wedge, and Whittier Globe. <BR>
<BR>
People who do not receive a calendar in their paper may call 673-2491 to
get one. The calendars are available in alternative formats. Call 673-2491,
TTY 673-2157. <BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H2>&quot;Quality Stolen Merchandise&quot; Available at City Store </H2>
The City Store, a partnership of the Minneapolis Police Department and the
People of Phillips neighborhood organization, will introduce young people
to the business world and provide residents with bargains on unclaimed and
stolen property. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;If you're in the market for a car phone, television or snowblower,
you can find it here,&quot; Sayles Belton told those attending the store's
ribbon-cutting celebration. &quot;You'll also find opportunity here. An
opportunity for young people to learn and grow.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The store, which is located at 1037 East Franklin Av., opens for business
on Oct. 25. <BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H2>Street Sweeping Begins </H2>
Fall street sweeping begins in Minneapolis next week and will continue for
about a month. &quot;No Parking&quot; signs will be posted on streets the
day before they are swept, and any vehicles still on the streets will be
towed to the Municipal Impound Lot. <BR>
