<H1>ON THE AGENDA</H1>
<H2>City of Minneapolis Actions &amp; Issues - November 1, 1996</H2>
<BR>
<I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions of
the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. This
is Issue 3, Volume 13. Next issue will be November 15. ON THE AGENDA and
other City documents are available in alternative formats, call 673-2009.
The City provides sign language interpreting for its programs and services;
call TTY 673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity - Affirmative
Action Employer.</I><HR> 
<H2>Budget Address This Week</H2>
Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton will deliver her 1997 Budget Address at 2 p.m.
Thursday, November 7, in the City Council Chambers. Her address will focus
on public safety issues. The public is welcome to attend.<HR> 
<H2>City Gets Lead Control Grant</H2>
<BR>
A $5 million federal grant will allow Minneapolis to step up its lead-control
education program and replace or seal contaminated window frames to prevent
further lead poisoning in hundreds of city residences.<BR>
<BR>
More than 80 percent of the City's 177,000 housing units contain some lead-based
paint. Over the past five years, an average of 350 children annually have
undergone treatment for lead poisoning after blood tests indicated that
the metal had reached dangerous levels.<BR>
<BR>
Lead poisoning cases tend to be associated with older housing, where lead-based
paint was once used extensively. The City program, dubbed The 10,000 Windows
Project, will reduce lead exposure by replacing or sealing up to 10,000
sashes, jambs and other parts of contaminated windows.<BR>
<BR>
Part of the money also will be used to develop a system to track and manage
lead poisoning cases. Under the grant, financing will be made available
to help property owners in making what are often costly corrections. The
City anticipates that up to 200 residential properties will undergo extensive
lead reduction over the next two years.<HR> 
<H2>Open Appointments</H2>
<BR>
One position is vacant on the Minneapolis Advisory Committee on People With
Disabilities. Call Amy Stegora-Peterson at 673-2735 (TTY 673-3360) for information.
Deadline is November 8.<BR>
<BR>
Two positions are vacant on the Real Estate Advisory Board. More information
from Bill Carter, 673-2009. Deadline is November 22.<BR>
<BR>
Eight positions are vacant Minneapolis Arts Commission. The purposes of
the commission are to foster development of the arts, seek financial support
for the arts, advise the City Council with respect to arts-related matters,
and stimulate participation in and appreciation of the arts by all city
residents. For information call David Hanson, 673-3006. Deadline is December
13.<BR>
<BR>
<I>Call the City Clerk, 673-2735, for application materials. Appointees
must be residents unless exempted by Council action. Most boards do not
provide compensation.</I><HR> 
