<H2>Remembering Timothy Wegener</H2>
<BR>
Timothy Wegener, 38, loved being a carpenter. He was a member of the Brotherhood
of Carpenters Local 851 in Anoka. As a temporary employee of the City of
Minneapolis, Wegener was responsible for skilled carpentry work, a job in
which he took great pride. <BR>
<BR>
Sadly, on October 10, Wegener's life was cut short when a hydraulic lift
he was operating was struck by a train northwest of Cedar Lake. Wegener
was removing concrete forms from the Cedar Lake Parkway bridge when this
tragic incident occurred. He was the first City employee killed on the job
since Police Officer Jerry Haaf was killed in the line of duty in 1992.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Tim was an employee who impressed me, and I don't impress very easily,&quot;
said Rich Profaizer, the Bridge Maintenance Engineer who supervised Wegener.<BR>
<BR>
The Federal Railroad Administration is investigating the incident. It appears
that there was a communications breakdown. Under normal circumstances, a
rail dispatcher notifies any crews on the tracks several minutes before
a train arrives. However, Wegener's crew claims to have never received the
dispatch.<BR>
<BR>
Wegener moved to Brooklyn Center from Colorado about two years ago, and
is survived by his wife, Cindy, and four sons.<HR> 
