<H1><I>ON THE AGENDA </I></H1>
<H2><I>City of Minneapolis Actions &amp; Issues November 15, 1996</I></H2>
<BR>
<I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions of
the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250. This
is Issue 4, Volume 13. Next issue will be December 6. ON THE AGENDA and
other City documents are available in alternative formats, call 673-2009.
The City provides sign language interpreting for its programs and services;
call TTY 673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity Affirmative
Action Employer.<BR>
</I><HR>
<H2>Correction</H2>
The November 15 transmission of this issue of On The Agenda incorrectly
reported the November 8 City Council action concurring with the Mayors recommendation
to reappoint or appoint persons to the Minneapolis Commission on Civil Rights.
Lisa Albrecht, James F. Cannon, Robert B. Fine, Anne LaLonde Laux and Ophelia
Balcos were reappointed to the commission. Dianne G. Marsh and Ron Elwood
(not Ron Edwards as reported) are new appointees. <BR>
<BR>
The Office of Public Affairs regrets this error.<BR>
<H2>Mayor Sayles Belton Unveils 1997 Budget, Focus Is On Public Safety and
Infrastructure; Public Hearing Set for December 4</H2>
<BR>
On November 7, Minneapolis Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton unveiled a $194.6
million budget for 1997 that includes increases to fight crime and improve
the Citys neighborhoods and infrastructure, but no tax increases for the
third straight year. In presenting the budget to the City Council, Sayles
Belton, characterized the spending plan as a public safety budget. <BR>
<BR>
The Mayor also called it her first post-recovery budget, reflecting the
fact that Minneapolis has the second lowest office vacancy rate in the nation
at 3.9 percent and has seen an increase in commercial and residential property
values. We have the resources to make the necessary public safety investments,
she said. In this budget, I recommend new investments of nearly $10.3 million,
including $2.2 million in federal grants, to strengthen our ability to fight
and prevent crime. <BR>
<BR>
The Mayor also recommended the resumption of investment in neighborhood
and government infrastructure improvements that were postponed because of
rising costs and cuts in state and federal funds.<BR>
<BR>
She cautioned, however, that the fight against crime doesnt tell the entire
story. Citing the recent <I>Fortune</I> ranking of Minneapolis as the fourth
best city nationwide in which to do business, and a similar high ranking
by <I>Entrepreneur</I> magazine, the Mayor stressed the need to build upon
what is good about Minneapolis. Sayles Belton pointed to development in
the downtown area, which makes up 40 percent of the Citys tax base: construction
of a new Target Store, office towers and Riverfront development. She also
noted the new Quarry Retail Center in Northeast Minneapolis and a remodeled
Lunds grocery store in Uptown as signs of growth and development.<BR>
<BR>
Sayles Belton outlined initiatives to support major City priorities. Among
them were:<BR>
<BR>
<B>Safe Neighborhoods </B>By June, the Police Departments authorized strength
of 922 officers will be on the streets. The number an all-time high will
allow the zero-tolerance for gateway crimes that affect our residents and
their neighborhoods and lead to more serious offenses. <BR>
<BR>
The Mayor said better enforcement without aggressive prosecution would be
meaningless. In 1997, Minneapolis will start a one-year pilot program to
bolster the prosecution of misdemeanors, including domestic assault. Referring
to priorities being developed by the City and the Criminal Justice Coordinating
Committee, the Mayor cited a Hennepin County Drug Court and state supervision
of criminals on parole or probation. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Liveable Neighborhoods </B>Sayles Belton said that residents and businesses
should have an unprecedented voice in the decisions made about their neighborhoods.
We will consult them about where to put street lights and signs, how to
calm traffic, what kind of trees, plants and paving they prefer, the Mayor
said. Livablility doesnt come from a one-size-fits-all program. It comes
from respecting lifestyles, needs and desires of real people.<BR>
<BR>
The Mayor noted that the time has come for a plan to maintain the citys
streets during the upcoming decades now that 30 years of road construction
has been completed. The maintenance plan, still under development by Public
Works, has no effect on the 1997 budget but will affect the 1998 spending
plan.<BR>
<BR>
Sayles Belton proposed setting up a one-stop permit shop, where citizens
could have access to histories of all properties and information about them
from every City department. The service would cost $117,000 in 1997. She
also recommended boosting the snow removal budget by $200,000 to hire seasonal
workers during the winter months to help ease the negotiation of icy streets
and sidewalks. <BR>
<BR>
Neighborhood cleanups and graffiti-removal should be increased she said.
The budget contains a $100,000 boost in graffiti-removal funds.<BR>
<BR>
She also recommended spending $195,000 next year to conduct inspections
of South Minneapolis households to ensure that sound-insulated homes near
the Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport are up to code.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Health, Families and Children </B>The Mayor recommended a $159,000 increase
in the spending for Way to Grow, a program that helps parents find the resources
to care for their preschool children. She also announced that the City had
received a $5 million federal grant to help track and manage lead poisoning
in the citys children. The grant also will be used to eliminate dangerous
lead levels in 200 Minneapolis homes.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Economy </B>She recommended investing $430,175 in housekeeping and
production staffing to keep the Minneapolis Convention Center operating,
and spending $150,000 to begin a detailed plan to Downtown and Riverfront
development.<BR>
<BR>
<I>The full text of the Mayors Budget Address can be found on the Internet.
The Citys home page address is http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us. For a printed copy
call the Mayors Office, 673-2100. Or watch videotape of her address on City
Cable 34 at 9 p.m. Saturdays through November 30.<BR>
<BR>
City Council consideration of the Mayors proposed budget began with a general
review on November 13 and 15. The Council will review priorities and departmental
budgets the week of November 18. The Couincil will receive public comments
at the Truth in Taxation public hearing on Wednesday, December 4. The hearing
begins at 5:05 p.m. and will be held in Room 317 City Hall. (If necessary,
the hearing will be continued at 5:05 p.m. December 11.) Budget markup will
be December 5 and 6. The City Council will adopt the 1997 budget at a meeting
set for 5:05 p.m. December 12. <BR>
<BR>
The Truth in Taxation hearing (or hearings) and the December 12 City Council
meeting will be broadcast live on City Cable 34. Check the City Cable 34s
electronic schedule for days and times of repeats, or call 673-2234. For
information on the budget process, call Julie Norrid, 673-2296.</I><HR>
<H2>10,000 Diapers Needed</H2>
The second annual Minneapolis Police Department Diaper Drive will take place
December 16 to 22. Last year, the drive contributed more than 10,000 disposable
diapers to the 410 Homeless Shelter. Medium and large sizes are the most
needed. Drop off diapers at Precinct Stations or Police Administration,
130 City Hall.<HR> 
