<H1><I>ON THE AGENDA</I></H1>

<H2><I>City of Minneapolis Actions &amp; Issues -- December 6, 1996</I></H2>

<P><I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions
of the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250.
This is Issue 5, Volume 13. Next issue will be December 20. ON THE AGENDA
and other City documents are available in alternative formats, call 673-2009.
The City provides sign language interpreting for its programs ; call TTY
673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity &shy; Affirmative
Action Employer.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Animal Control, Vets Join For Licensing, Rabies Prevention</H2>

<P>Minneapolis Animal Control and local veterinarians have teamed up to
allow owners to buy pet licenses and get rabies shots for their dogs and
cats - all in one spot. The pet licensing and rabies shot campaign runs
through Sunday, December 15.</P>

<P>For neutered dogs and cats or pets that are less than eight months old,
the cost of the 1997 license and rabies shot is just $15. The cost is $20
for unaltered adult dogs and cats. Written proof that a pet has been neutered
is required.</P>

<P>Owners of dogs and cats that have wandered off often can be traced and
notified through license tags worn by their pets. Most times, a telephone
call is all that is necessary to reunite a licensed animal with its owner.
Without the tag, finding a lost pet can be much more difficult.</P>

<P>Locations, dates and times are:</P>

<P>- Animal Medical Clinic, 2603 Hennepin Avenue South, Saturday, December
7, 2 p.m. to 5 p.m..</P>

<P>- Camden Pet Hospital, 1401 44th Avenue North, Saturday, December 7,
2 p.m. to 5 p.m.</P>

<P>- Martin Luther King Neighborhood Center, 41st and Nicollet, Sunday,
December 8, 11:30 a.m. to 3 p.m.</P>

<P>- People's Veterinary Clinic, 2000 South 5th Street, Saturday, December
14, 8:30 a.m. to 11:30 a.m.</P>

<P>- Longfellow Community Center, East 35th Street and 36th Avenue South,
Saturday, December 14, 1 p.m. to 4 p.m.</P>

<P>- Harrison Neighborhood Center, 5th Avenue North and James Avenue North,
Sunday, December 15 11:30 a.m. to 3 p.m.</P>

<P><I>For more information call 348-4250.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Initiative Against Racism Hires Executive Director</H2>

<P>The Minneapolis Initiative Against Racism has hired Joanne Jackson, an
experienced community organizer, as its new executive director. Jackson
will be responsible for organizational development, implementation of a
long-range public relations campaign, fund-raising, and other efforts to
increase support for the Initiative. She assumed her responsibilities on
December 1.</P>

<P>&quot;I have dedicated myself personally and professionally to the eradication
of racism,&quot; Jackson says. &quot;In building on the MIAR's past successes,
I hope to increase awareness about institutional racism and marshal the
human and financial resources necessary to dismantle its devastating effects.&quot;</P>

<P>Among other things, Jackson plans to conduct training workshops for churches
and community organizations, strengthen fund-raising efforts, and raise
the visibility of the Initiative through billboards, public-service announcements,
and a cable television program.</P>

<P>Jackson's extensive management history includes directorships of highly
successful fund-raising campaigns, volunteer recruitment programs and design
of diversity-training curricula. Most recently, Jackson worked for the Mental
Health Division of the Minnesota Department of Human Services directing
the Multicultural Task Force and Advisory Committee.</P>

<P>From 1987 to 1989, she served as Director of Community Outreach for the
U.S. Department of Commerce. She was appointed in 1989 by Mayor Don Fraser
to direct the Minneapolis Census '90 Complete Count Campaign. In 1990, Jackson
was commended by then Mayor Don Fraser and City Council President Sharon
Sayles Belton for her leadership, which resulted in the City of Minneapolis
being cited as &quot;exemplary&quot; in its 1990 census count by the U.S.
Census Bureau.</P>

<P>Established in 1992, the Minneapolis Initiative Against Racism seeks
to break the cycle of racial misunderstanding, prejudice, and racism in
order to provide equal economic and social access to people of all cultures
and races. Nine task forces have been working to eliminate racism in the
media, housing, business, and other areas. Additional volunteers are welcome
and needed. For information, or to join a task force, call 962-4848.<HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>There's No Business Like Snow Business</H2>

<P>Minneapolis snow fighters come in all shapes and varieties,&quot; says
Brian Lokkesmoe, Director of Operations for Public Works. &quot;People always
think of the person in the plow, but there's an awful lot of support that
makes it all work.&quot;</P>

<P>Snow Emergencies typically involve 300 to 400 people. In addition to
about 160 drivers and operators, there are 50 or 60 mechanics and a half-dozen
dispatchers, plus supervisors and laborers, Impound Lot and enforcement
staff, street and bridge maintenance staff, and the people behind the scenes
answering phones, keeping track of payroll, and handling a slew of other
details.</P>

<P>Generally, four to six inches of snow needs to fall before the City declares
a Snow Emergency, but factors such as the condition of the streets before
the snowfall and the weather forecast must also be taken into consideration,
especially because every Snow Emergency costs at least $250,000. Lokkesmoe
recalls one March when it snowed 10 inches, but the City didn't declare
a Snow Emergency, because the forecast for the next day was 45 degrees and
sunny. The City lucked out, and the snow melted within two days.</P>

<P>Because back-to-back Snow Emergencies were declared on November 21 and
24, some City crews recently had to work 14 or more days in a row, many
of them 12-hour shifts each day. &quot;I'm always impressed by the responsiveness
of people,&quot; Lokkesmoe says. &quot;They're there when we need them.
They show up, get the work done, and don't complain.&quot;</P>

<P>For information on winter parking restrictions, call 348-SNOW, a 24-hour
hotline; pick up a brochure at a Tom Thumb Store; watch City Cable 34; or
visit the Minneapolis Home Page on the Internet at http://www.ci.mpls.mn.us.
<HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>City Provides Free Sand for Minneapolis Residents</H2>

<P>The City of Minneapolis provides free sand to residents to help keep
sidewalks safe for pedestrians. The sand is available at four street maintenance
yards. They are at 18th and Jefferson Street NE, 121 Glenwood Avenue North,
6036 Harriet Avenue South, and 4444 Snelling Avenue South.</P>

<P>The sand is furnished for the private use of residents only, not for
commercial use. It is accessible outside the yard gates 24 hours a day seven
days a week. Residents must bring their own shovel and bucket.</P>

<P>City ordinances require that sidewalks of single family homes and duplexes
be cleared within 24 hours after a snowfall. Sidewalks in commercial areas
and adjacent to apartment buildings must be cleared within four daylight
hours. Walks should be cleared to full width. To report unsafe sidewalks,
call 673-2441.<HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Selected November 22 City Council Actions</H2>

<P><B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT</B></P>

<P>- Approved sale of City-owned land located in Plymouth.</P>

<P>- Gave final approval to sale of bonds for the Community Home program.</P>

