and detached structures intended principally to be used for parking or vehicle
repair.</P>

<P><B>COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE</B></P>

<P>- Passed ordinance amendments related to the management of spaces beneath
public streets and sidewalks.</P>

<P><I>This is partial list of Council actions. For a full list, or for details
on any action, call 673-3130. The minutes of City Council meetings can be
found at http://www.finance-commerce.com. The next Council meeting begins
at 9:30 a.m. December 13. Watch live on City Cable 34 or repeats Mondays,
Wednesdays and Fridays at 6 p.m.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Corrections</H2>

<P>The November 15 issue of On The Agenda incorrectly reported the November
8 City Council action concurring with the Mayors recommendation to reappoint
or appoint persons to the Minneapolis Commission on Civil Rights. Lisa Albrecht,
James F. Cannon, Robert B. Fine, Anne LaLonde Laux and Ophelia Balcos were
reappointed to the commission. Dianne G. Marsh and Ron Elwood (not Ron Edwards
as reported) are new appointees. OTA also omitted the Council's appointment
of Duchess Harris to the commission.</P>

<P>The November issue also incorrectly reported an item from the Zoning
&amp; Planning committee. The moratorium applies only to correctional facilities
in residential districts. A proposed inclusion of elderly housing was deleted
before passage.</P>

<P>The Office of Public Affairs regrets these errors.<HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>City Cable 34 Highlights</H2>

<P>- The December 4 Truth in Taxation public hearings will be replayed at
approximately 8 p.m. Fridays, Mondays and Wednesdays following repeats of
City Council meetings.</P>

<P>- This month's Eye on Crime, hosted by Deputy Chief Bill Jones will feature
an interview with Lt. Val Wurster about the rise of domestic violence over
the holiday season and how to prevent it, along with a visit to the 4th
Precinct with Lt. Susan Piontek. Tuesdays at 8:30 p.m., Thursdays and Sundays
at 6:30 p.m., Saturdays at 7 p.m.</P>

<P>- City Beat, hosted by Kent Robbins, features a discussion of the new
Management of Public Right of Way Ordinance with Council Members Steve Minn
and Joe Biernat and Public Works Engineering Director Leonard Krumm. Tuesdays
at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 8:30 p.m., Saturdays at 7:30 p.m.</P>

<P><I>Call City Cable 34 Hotline at 673-2234 for information on other programs.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Watch Artifacts on Cable 34</H2>

<P><I>Patty Jane's House of Curl</I>, a nunnery that becomes an art center,
ghoulish movie props, and a quarter century of Gregorian chants - this month's
ho-hum bill on Artifacts.</P>

<P>Lorna Landvik's novel, Patty Jane's House of Curl, is set near Lake Nokomis.
Landvik reveals some of her writing and publishing adventures to co-host
Phill Lindsay.</P>

<P>Once a nunnery, then a women's shelter for 14 years, the Center for Performing
Arts in the King Field neighborhood is now home to numerous performing arts
companies, artists and creative folk. Entrepreneur Jackie Hayes outlines
her goals for the multidisciplinary resource.</P>

<P>Scenic artist Nance Derby has worked on some of the Hollywood movies
filmed in the Twin Cities. She and Artifacts co-host Janet Zahn talk about
her career, her company Acme Scenic Arts, and the industry, all the while
flanked by two tombstone props she created.</P>

<P>Lindsay then welcomes Monte Mason to the show. Mason is the founder and
director of The Gregorian Singers. The group was started in the early 70s
and performs regularly at St. Mark's Cathedral Church in Loring Park.</P>

<P><I>Artifacts is on the Metro Cable Network, Channel 6, at 10 p.m. Thursdays,
and Minneapolis City Cable 34 at 7:30 p.m. Tuesdays, 7 p.m. Thursdays and
5:30 p.m. Saturdays.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

