<H1><I>ON THE AGENDA</I></H1>

<H2><I>City of Minneapolis Actions &amp; Issues &shy; December 20, 1996</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H2>

<H2>			</H2>

<P><I>ON THE AGENDA provides information on issues, programs and actions
of the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX: 673-3250.
This is Issue 6, Volume 13. Next issue will be January 3. ON THE AGENDA
and other City documents are available in alternative formats, call 673-2009.
The City provides sign language interpreting for its programs; call TTY
673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity &shy; Affirmative
Action Employer.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>1997 Home Tour Seeks Nominations from Owners</H2>

<P>Now in its tenth year, the Minneapolis &amp; Saint Paul Home Tour is
a popular spring event for thousands of neighbors and remodeling enthusiasts.
The 1997 Home Tour will be held on Saturday, May 3 and Sunday, May  4.</P>

<P>Organized by the cities of Minneapolis and Saint Paul, the tour builds
community awareness, encourages home improvement, and promotes city living.
The cities invite owners to nominate their homes for the tour starting January
2. The closing date for nominations is February 14. </P>

<P>As in past years, a variety of homes will be showcased, from newly constructed
homes with modern amenities to turn-of-the-century landmarks featuring rich
woodwork or stained glass. Owners from neighborhoods throughout both cities
will proudly share their remodeling and decorating triumphs. Memorable homes
from past years include a geodesic dome and a houseboat. The tour is also
an opportunity for neighborhood organizations to communicate the strengths
of their neighborhoods to prospective home buyers.</P>

<P>The tour is fun and satisfying event for both visitors and home owners.
&quot;This was something we could do to promote where we live,&quot; said
Jonathan Riehle, whose home was on the 1993 Home Tour. &quot;The tour benefits
the entire city and benefits us as well.&quot; </P>

<P>All homes will be selected by mid-March. <I>To nominate your Minneapolis
home, call the Office of Public Affairs, 673-2491.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<H2>Civil Rights Award to be Presented January 17</H2>

<P>The Commission on Civil Rights will present its annual Award for Outstanding
Achievement at the 1997 Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Celebration.  The
celebration will be held from noon to 1 p.m. Friday, January 17, in the
atrium of the Hennepin County Government Center.</P>

<P>The commission presents this award to an organization or individual who
makes significant contributions in civil or human rights.  Past recipients
have worked in education, legal advocacy, the arts, and politics to help
make Minneapolis truly a city that has no place for prejudice.</P>

<P>Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton, City Council President Jackie Cherryhomes,
Hennepin County Commissioner Peter McLaughlin, and a representative of the
commission will be among the speakers at the celebration.  A sign-language
interpreter will also be present.</P>

<P>Following the program, the Minneapolis Commission on Civil Rights will
host a reception in the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Conference Room,
241 City Hall.  <HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<H2>Winter News Briefs</H2>

<H3>City Bans Parking on Even Side of Streets</H3>

<P>Due to high levels of snow accumulation, Minneapolis officials have determined
that it is necessary to ban parking on the even side of residential streets
for the remainder of the winter. The ban began at 8 a.m. Wednesday, December
18. It will remain in effect until April 1 or until the City is confident
that the snow season is over.</P>

<P>&quot;We realize this will inconvenience many Minneapolis residents,&quot;
said Public Works Director David Sonnenberg, &quot;but the welfare and safety
of the public in terms of our ability to get emergency vehicles through
the streets must take precedence over the inconvenience.&quot; Sonnenberg
adds that last winter was the first time since the winter of 1991-92 that
the City had to restrict parking to one side of the street. &quot;We have
already received as much snowfall this season as we had by mid-January last
winter,&quot; he says.</P>

<P>During Snow Emergencies, cars will be allowed to park on the even side
of the street on the odd-side plowing day. Vehicles parked on the even side
any other time will be subject to tagging and towing. Enforcement will continue
throughout the ban.</P>

<P>To ensure public safety after heavy snowfalls, Sonnenberg also reminds
residents and business owners to clear their sidewalks down to the pavement,
across the full width, and all the way to the corner after the plows have
gone by for the last time. City ordinances require that sidewalks of single-family
homes and duplexes be cleared within 24 hours after a snowfall. Sidewalks
in commercial areas and adjacent to apartment buildings must be cleared
within four daytime hours.</P>

<P><I>Complete Snow Emergency parking information is always available on
348-SNOW, the City's 24-hour hotline, as well as City Cable Channel 34 and
the City web site at www.ci.mpls.mn.us. </I></P>

<H3>Garbage Carts Need Shoveling</H3>

<P>Winter is a difficult time for Minneapolis sanitation crews. Moving snowed-
or iced-in garbage carts is hazardous and increases injuries. Please help
out by clearing a three-foot-wide path between your garbage cart and the
alley or street and remember to cut a path through the windrow left by snow
plows.</P>

<P>Households that do not provide a path for their garbage carts will receive
a warning. If no path is created by the next collection day, the carts will
be shovelled out by the City at a charge of $19 for each cart.</P>

<P><I>Community organizations provide shoveling assistance for a fee. Seniors
and persons physically unable to keep their sidewalks and garbage cart paths
in good winter condition can call 673-3004 for a referral. Solid Waste and
Recycling will answer other questions; call 673-2917.</I></P>

<H3>City Simplifies Christmas Tree Collection </H3>

<P>For Minneapolis residents with City garbage and recycling collection
services, disposing of Christmas trees is easier than ever this year. Just
place them next to your garbage cart by 6 a.m. on any garbage collection
day. Remember to remove ornaments and tinsel, and cut trees taller than
six feet in half. If you want your tree composted, save the tree in your
back yard (not in the alley) until yard waste collection begins in mid-April.</P>

<P>Residents are also reminded that the City cannot recycle gift wrap, gift
and toy boxes, tissue paper, ribbons or other holiday packaging even if
the products' labels say they are recyclable. </P>

<P>In 1997, make a New Year's resolution that helps everyone: Work to reduce
the amount of trash you generate and increase the amount you reuse or recycle.<HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>City Job Listings Now on Web</H2>

<P>Employment opportunities with the City have been added recently to the
City's web site. The address is www.ci.mpls.mn.us. You can also get weekly
updates by calling 673-CITY, Option 11.<HR ALIGN=LEFT>  </P>

<H2>December 12 Council Actions</H2>

<P>The Minneapolis City Council met on Thursday, December 12, to consider
various aspects of the City's 1997 budget.</P>

<P><B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT REPORTS</B></P>

<P>- Consolidated Plan: Approved with amendments the Mayor's recommendations
for FY97 CDBG allocation; approved HOME, ESG, &amp; HOPWA allocations; reaffirmed
Citizen Participation Plan amendments; and adopted revisions to FY95 Plan
in accordance with previous Council actions.</P>

<P>- Common Project: Approved Five-Year Redevelopment Plan and Common Project
priorities.</P>

<P>- MCDA Operating Budget: Approved MCDA Appropriation Resolution for 1997.</P>

<P>State-Orpheum Theater Operating Budget: Approved 1996 revised budget
and 1997 projected budget.</P>

<P>- Upper Harbor Terminal: Approved 1997 operating budget.</P>

<P><B>WAYS &amp; MEANS/BUDGET REPORTS</B></P>

<P>- Tax Levies: Set tax levies for 1996 property taxes payable in 1997.</P>

<P>- 1997 Budget: Approved with amendments the 1997 General Appropriation
Resolution as recommended by the Mayor. The resolution sets the maximum
amounts to be expended by departments under City Council jurisdiction.</P>

<P>- Public Housing Levy:  Authorized the Public Housing Authority to levy
a 1996 property tax payable in 1997.</P>

<P>- Capital Improvement Program:  Approved with amendments Mayor's recommended
1997 Capital Program allocations and requested issuance of various bonds.</P>

<P><I>Copies of these actions can be obtained from the City Clerk, 673-3130.
Copies of the Mayor's 1997 budget recommendations can be obtained by calling
673-2100.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<H2>Selected December 13 Minneapolis City Council Actions</H2>

<P><B>APPOINTMENTS</B></P>

<P>- Appointed Jay Heffern to the position of City Attorney for a term to
expire January 8, 1998.</P>

<P>- Reappointed Steve Chapman to the Public Housing Authority Board of
Commissioners.</P>

<P>- Concurred with Downtown Council on appointments to the Nicollet Mall
Advisory Board for two year terms: Thomas M. Clairmount, Gaviidae and City
Center; Jean Westberg, NSP Headquarters and Renaissance Square; David Sternberg,
IDS Center and Marquette Hotel; Dale Amondson, Dayton's; Kris Brandt, The
Conservatory; Edward Baker, Minnesota Law Center, Downtown Auto Park; David
Eisenman, Hyatt Regency Hotel; Robert D Greenberg, Young Quinlan Building;
Winifred Smith, three buildings at north end of The Mall; George Pennock
and Edward Gill (alternate), Orchestra Hall; Nancy Hite, YWCA; and Alice
Mortenson (alternate), Westminster Presbyterian Church.</P>

<P>- Appointed Dan Wozniak, President of Reliance Real Estate Services,
to fill unexpired term on the Skyway Advisory Committee.</P>

<P>- Reappointed Mark Frank; William Frothinger, Paul Sigurdson, and Patricia
Werner to the Real Estate Advisory Board; appointed Kim Douglas and Christine
Murphy as new members.</P>

<P><B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT</B></P>

<P>- Issued bonds for Nicollet Towers, 1350 Nicollet, and Minneapolis Society
of Fine Arts, 2400 3rd Avenue South.</P>

<P>- Made appropriations for 2% Revolving Loans.</P>

<P>- Neighborhood Revitalization Program actions:</P>

<P>- Approved First Step Plan and allocated funds for Lynnhurst and Victory
neighborhoods.</P>

<P>- Approved transfer of County NRP funds for Action Plan programs in Prospect
Park, Central and Elliot Park neighborhoods.</P>

<P>- Approved transfer of County NRP funds for employment program in Stevens
Square/Loring Heights neighborhood.</P>

<P>- Appropriated funds for the River City Trolley.</P>

<P><B>PUBLIC SAFETY &amp; REGULATORY SERVICES</B></P>

<P>- Passed an ordinance providing for vacation of dwelling units when an
owner has not obtained a Rental Housing License and citing absence of a
license as a misdemeanor.</P>

<P>- Approved New Year's Eve fireworks display for the central riverfront.</P>

<P>- Approved demolition of nuisance structures at  2931 Aldrich Av N, 
2404 Dupont Av N, and  2722 Bryant Av N.</P>

<P>- Authorized $110,000 contract with Children's Dental Services.</P>

<P>- Accepted a $126,424 Crime Prevention Grant. Most of the funds will
be used to hire a volunteer coordinator for the Lowry/Emerson substation,
who will work with the 4th Precinct, CCP/SAFE and seven neighborhood organizations
to shape the substation into a base for community-oriented policing. </P>

<P>- Accepted $12,500 donation from James Ballentine Post #246 to be used
for a School Patrol picnic and equipment for the 5th Precinct including
bicycles and bicycle repair. </P>

<P><B>TRANSPORTATION &amp; PUBLIC WORKS</B></P>

<P>- Established transient and monthly rates for the Municipal Parking System;
established valet rates at Centre Village and Loring ramps.</P>

<P>- Entered into an agreement to develop a mathematical computer model
of the Mississippi related to a  diversion dike that would divert known
contaminants away from the Water Works' intakes at Pump Station No 5.</P>

<P>- Authorized Mill City Music Festival to hold events over the Labor Day
weekends of 1997, 1998 and 1999 subject to conditions.</P>

<P><B>WAYS &amp; MEANS/BUDGET</B></P>

<P>- Authorized additional contract with consultant to assist the City in
precluding construction of a third parallel airport runway.</P>

<P>- Purchased properties at 312 &amp; 314 East 15th Street for Convention
Center completion.</P>

<P>- Accepted YouthWorks/Americorps grant from the Minnesota Department
of Economic Security to be used for a youth education and community service
initiative.</P>

<P>- Authorized contract with the Minnesota Housing Finance Agency to administer
a housing subsidy program for METP participants in conjunction with the
Minneapolis Public Housing Authority.</P>

<P><B>ZONING &amp; PLANNING</B></P>

<P>- Granted an appeal filed from a decision of the Planning Commission
that had denied an application for lattice-type antenna tower at 6000 Pleasant
Av S.</P>

<P>- Granted an appeal filed from decision of Heritage Preservation Commission
that had denied an application for personal communication system on roof
of Kenwood Water Tower, 1724 Kenwood Pkwy.</P>

<P><B>COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE</B></P>

<P>- Approved the committee's recommendation to not select specific site
for a new stadium until legislature determines what will be built and approves
a financing plan that contains significant private investment; also approved
exclusion of North Nicollet Mall and Warehouse District sites from consideration.</P>

<P><B>RESOLUTIONS</B></P>

<P>- Approved a resolution honoring Willard P. Jones for his service on
the Zoning Board of Adjustment since 1984 and other contributions to the
community. </P>

<P>- Approved a resolution honoring Brian Isaacson for his service on personnel
matters to the City of Minneapolis.</P>

<P>- Approved a resolution setting forth the City's legislative agenda on
sworn personnel pension reform and calling for pension enhancements that
reduce taxpayer liability.</P>

<P><B>MOTIONS</B></P>

<P>- Approved a motion that applicants for the Fire Cadet program who were
discharged because of their psychological profiles be placed on paid administrative
leave pending the completion of Affirmative Action investigations.</P>

<P><I>This is partial list of Council actions. For a full list, or for details
on any action, call 673-3130. The minutes of City Council meetings can be
found at http://www.finance-commerce.com. The next Council meeting begins
at 9:30 a.m. December 27. Watch live on City Cable 34 or repeats Mondays,
Wednesdays and Fridays at 6 p.m.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Council Committee Items</H2>

<P>- The Community Development Committee will conduct a public hearing at
9:30 a.m. Monday, December 30, in Room 319 City Hall to consider Amendment
No 8 to the South Nicollet Mall Development Program, Amendment No 5 to the
Greater Hennepin Avenue Development Program, and Modification No 45 to the
Common Plan which authorize public redevelopment activities related to parking
facilities, office, institutional, commercial and related infrastructure
and skyways.</P>

<P><I>For information, call 673-5010; hearing impaired, call 673-2626 TTY.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Meetings on I-35W Plans Set for January 7 and 14</H2>

<P>The Minnesota Department of Transportation (Mn/DOT) will hold a community
meeting at 7 p.m. Tuesday, January 7, at the Sabathani Community Center,
310 East 38th Street, to inform citizens of plans for safety improvements
and congestion relief for sections of I-35W in Minneapolis and Richfield.
</P>

<P>Mn/DOT will also host an open house from 4 to 8 p.m. Tuesday, January
14, at Richfield Lutheran Church, 60th Street at Nicollet, on the same topic.
 </P>

<P>Mn/DOT has submitted project plans to the cities of Minneapolis and Richfield
for approval and has completed an addendum to the 1995 Final Environmental
Impact Statement for the proposed improvements. Representatives of Mn/DOT
and the city governments of Minneapolis and Richfield will answer questions
at the two meetings on these plans and on the impact statement.</P>

<P>Construction is scheduled to begin in the spring of 1999 with completion
in 2003. The planned $75 million project will include reconstruction of
the commons between I-35W and Highway 62 and the addition of a high occupancy
vehicle lane in each direction between the intersection of I-35W and I-494
and 46th Street.</P>

<P><I>Additional information, which includes a conceptual plan for the new
I-35W/Highway 62 commons, is available from Mn/DOT. Call 582-1320, fax a
request to 582-1368, or visit www,dot.state.mn.us.</I><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>City Cable 34 Highlights</H2>

<P>- The current City Beat, hosted by Kent Robbins, features a discussion
of the City's 1997 budget with Ways &amp; Means Chair Joan Campbell and
Budget Director Don Siggelkow. Tuesdays at 7 p.m., Thursdays at 8:30 p.m.,
Saturdays at 7:30 p.m.</P>

<P>- Tape of the City Council's December 4 public hearing on the budget
can be seen Mondays and Fridays at 8 p.m.</P>

<P>- Watch City Cable 34 for coverage of the December 12 Committee of the
Whole discussion of a proposed new baseball stadium. Wednesdays at 8 p.m.<HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Training Worksites Needed</H2>

<P>The City of Minneapolis Employment and Training Program (METP) is seeking
vendors to serve as worksites for youth training through the Summer Youth
Employment and Training Program (SYETP).  The program will operate from
June 9 to August 15, 1997.  </P>

<P>Request for proposal specifications may be obtained at the METP office,
Room 310 1/2 City Hall, 350 South 5th Street, Minneapolis MN 55415-1388,
or by calling 673-5700.  METP reserves the right to reject all proposals
in response to the request.  Proposals must be received in the METP office
by 4:30 p.m. Friday, January 10.<HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Planning Commission Agenda</H2>

<P>The commission will hold hearings at 4:30 p.m. on Wednesday, January
8, in Room 317 City Hall, on the following items.</P>

<P>- Subdivision plat by MCDA in the vicinity of 3747-3756 Pillsbury Av
S.</P>

<P>- Ordinance amendment concerning the spacing requirements for secondhand
stores and rummage shops.</P>

<P>- Conditional use permit for extension of the operating hours at 6004
Penn Av S.</P>

<P>- Conditional use permit for a child day care center at 5522 Garfield
Av S</P>

<P>- Expansion of a nonconforming use to permit addition to an existing
industrial building at 315 1st Av NE.</P>

<P>- Expansion of a nonconforming use to permit a loading berth at 3000
University Av SE.</P>

<P>- Expansion of a nonconforming use to permit the construction of a building
for metal storage and for relocation of a beverage can receiving area for
a metal recycling facility at 1728 North 2nd St. </P>

<P>- Change of a nonconforming use to permit an office and eight dwelling
units at 212 11th Av S. </P>

<P><I>For more information call 673-5836.</I></P>

<P><BR>
<B><HR ALIGN=LEFT></B></P>

