<H1><I>ON THE AGENDA</I> </H1>

<H2><I>City of Minneapolis Actions &amp; Issues - January 3, 1997</I></H2>

<P><B><I>ON THE AGENDA </I></B><I>provides information on issues, programs
and actions of the City of Minneapolis. Editor: Bill Carter, 673-2009. FAX:
673-3250. This is Issue 7, Volume 1. Next issue will be January 17. <B>.
ON THE AGENDA</B> and other City documents are available in alternative
formats, call 673-2009. The City provides sign language interpreting for
its programs; call TTY 673-2626. The City of Minneapolis is an Equal Opportunity
Affirmative Action Employer. </I></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>City Outlines 1997 Legislative Agenda</B> </P>

<P>At the December 27 City Council meeting, the Council adopted its agenda
for the upcoming state legislative session. The City's Intergovernmental
Relations Department, which represents the city's interests at state, local
and federal levels, will pursue the agenda. Major points include: </P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>- Obtain State of Minnesota funding for completion of the Convention
  Center. </P>
  <P>- Endorse a metro-wide sales tax to adequately fund transit and replace
  the current property tax devoted to transit. </P>
  <P>- Participate in planning efforts facilitated by Hennepin County regarding
  the short- and long-term effects of welfare reform. </P>
  <P>- Obtain state funding for continuation of Phat Summer program. </P>
  <P>- Endorse current multi-jurisdictional effort regarding management of
  public rights-of-way for telecommunications uses. </P>
  <P>- Endorse multi-jurisdictional efforts related to state funding for
  police overtime and for portion of costs of a Hennepin County drug court.
  </P>
  <P>- Obtain state funding for clean up of pollution on sites for industrial
  development. </P>
  <P>- Endorse continuation of current Local Government Aid distribution.
  </P>
  <P>- Pursue property tax relief for apartments and business, provided that
  tax burdens are not shifted to homeowners or that local government revenues
  are not reduced. </P>
  <P>- Increase the share of K-12 expenditures funded by sales taxes. </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>For a copy of the entire program approved December 30, call Intergovernmental
Relations, 673-2043. The City's legislative program is subject to change.
</P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>Civil Rights Presents Award</B> </P>

<P>Mort Ryweck has been chosen as the recipient of the 1997 Award for Outstanding
Achievement sponsored by the Commission on Civil Rights. </P>

<P>Ryweck has worked professionally in the intergroup relations and civil
rights fields since 1961, including sixteen years as regional director of
the Jewish Community Relations Council/Anti-Defamation League of Minnesota
and the Dakotas. He is being recognized for his continued dedication to
countering all forms of bigotry and extremism and promoting interfaith understanding.
</P>

<P>The presentation of the award will take place at the 1997 Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. Celebration. The celebration will be held from noon to 1
p.m. Friday, January 17, in the atrium of the Hennepin County Government
Center. </P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><B></B></P>

<P><B>Convention Center Honored</B> </P>

<P>The Minneapolis Convention &amp; Visitors Association was recently recognized
for excellence in servicing meetings and conventions. </P>

<P><I>Meeting News Magazine </I>named the GMCVA and the Minneapolis Convention
Center as a 1996 recipient of the coveted Planners Choice Award. Criteria
used to name the GMCVA and the Convention Center as a winner included helpfulness
and efficiency of on-site convention center staff, design and quality of
conference rooms, food service and facility location. </P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>NRP Policy Board Elections</B> </P>

<P>Elections to the Neighborhood Revitalization Programs Policy Board will
be held at 7 p.m. on Wed., January 22, at the Hennepin Avenue Methodist
Church art gallery, 511 Groveland Av. Only neighborhood electors, chosen
in the past few months in each of Minneapolis NRP neighborhoods, will vote
in this election. </P>

<P>The Policy Board is the governing body of the NRP. Its members provide
overall direction to the program and are responsible for the review and
approval of neighborhood plans. Neighborhood representatives hold four of
the 19 seats on the board -- one from each of the types of NRP neighborhoods
and one at-large representative -- and serve one-year terms. For more information,
call 673-5158. </P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>Council Committee Items</B> </P>

<P>The Committee of the Whole will meet on Tuesday, January 7 at 2 p.m.
in Room 317 City Hall, to consider the congregate living ordinances which
were referred to Council from the Zoning &amp; Planning Committee. </P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>Planning Commission Agenda</B> </P>

<P>The commission will hold a public hearing on Wednesday, January 22, at
4:30 p.m., in Room 317 City Hall, to consider an amendment to the maps of
the Minneapolis Zoning Code to provide office space for Pacer Center at
4821-23 Chicago Av S. For more information, call 673-5836. </P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>Open Appointments</B> </P>

<P>The <B>Civil Rights Commission </B>implements the Citys Civil Rights
policies through public information and education; mediation and conciliation;
and enforcement. The commission's members serve on standing committees and
panels that hear allegations of citizens regarding violations of their civil
rights. A minimum of six members and a maximum of eight members must be
lawyers. Commission members serve three year terms. Commission members are
compensated $35 per monthly meeting. Two positions are currently open. For
more information, call Elsa Batica at 673-3012. Applications are due by
4:30 p.m. on Friday, January 10. </P>

<P>The <B>Metropolitan Aircraft Sound Abatement Council</B> studies aircraft
noise issues and advises on problems. The council has 33 members, who serve
two-year terms. For more information, call Perry Thorvig at 673-2036. There
are six regular and two alternate positions vacant. Applications are due
by 4:30 p.m. on Friday, January 24. </P>

<P>The <B>Minneapolis Television Network </B>(MTN) promotes cable communication
and cultural richness in the city of Minneapolis. Each of the nine board
members serve four year terms and must live or work in the City of Minneapolis.
In addition, directors must not have a financial interest in any entity
engaged in, or doing business with, cable television in Minnesota. Meetings
are held the second Thursday of the month. Members also participate in monthly
committee activities. For more information, call Edie French at 673-2911.
Three positions are currently vacant. Applications must be received by 4:30
p.m. on Friday, January 17. </P>

<P><B>The Senior Citizen Advisory Committee to the Mayor and City Council
</B>advises on senior citizens concerns and acts as a link to the senior
citizen community<B>. </B>The committee's 20 members are Minneapolis residents
55 years or older. All appointees serve two-year terms. Meetings are the
second Thursday of each month. For more information, call Ruth Kildow, 673-3004.
Four positions are currently vacant. Applications are due at 4:30 pm on
Friday, January 17. </P>

<P><I>Call the City Clerk, 673-2735, for application materials. Appointees
must be residents unless otherwise noted or unless exempted by Council action.
</I></P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>Selected Recent City Council Actions</B> </P>

<P><B>December 27</B></P>

<P><B>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT</B> </P>

<P>- Approved implementation plan for Weed &amp; Seed crime prevention program.
</P>

<P>- Approved financial assistance for 900 Hennepin project; Central Care
Nursing Home, 1600 Fillmore St NE; BW Development, 2640-2700 Minnehaha;
and STS Enterprises Inc., 700 East Lake St. </P>

<P>- Accepted staff report on MCDA relocation procedures. </P>

<P><B>INTERGOVERNMENTAL RELATIONS</B> </P>

<P>- Supported the City's bid to host International City/County Management
Association's annual conference in the year 2005. </P>

<P>- Approved contracts for general legislative liaison services and for
services related to the completion of the Convention Center. </P>

<P>- Approved transit planning and funding strategies. </P>

<P>- Approved the City's 1997 legislative program. See the article on previous
page<I>.</I> </P>

<P><B>PUBLIC SAFETY &amp; REGULATORY SERVICES</B> </P>

<P>- Authorized agreement with Youth Express for the City to provide scrap
bicycle parts for bicycle repair in 1998 at no cost to the City. </P>

<P>- Accepted $352,000 State of Minnesota grant for the Hennepin County/Minneapolis
Multi-Jurisdictional Narcotics Enforcement Task Force. </P>

<P>- Approved demolition of nuisance structures at 2400-02 13th Av S, 622
East 24th St and 3430 First Av S. </P>

<P>- Approved City participation in the Middle Mississippi River Watershed
Management Organization in order to manage, protect, enhance &amp; restore
waters in Minneapolis. </P>

<P>- Approved emergency demolition of 121 Washington Av N. </P>

<P>- Accepted state grants for the Immunization Action Plan and for ImmuLink
which will track immunizations nationally. </P>

<P>- Accepted state grant to conduct training and outreach to landlords
regarding lead safety. </P>

<P>- Authorized funds for a building information and inspections information
systems project. </P>

<P><B>TRANSPORTATION &amp; PUBLIC WORKS</B> </P>

<P>- Agreed to finance any costs for the 14th Avenue SE bridge in excess
of funds received from a state grant. </P>

<P>- Approved University of Minnesota plans for relocation of 22nd Av S
in the vicinity of West River Pkwy. </P>

<P>- Directed staff to explore public/private partnership option and to
explore, evaluate and implement cost saving measures for the City's ready-mix
concrete plant. </P>

<P>- Established an interagency task force to consider possible sites for
a new downtown station for Greyhound and Jefferson lines. </P>

<P>- Appropriated funds for final phase of the Cedar Lake Bicycle Trail
including connection to West River Road. </P>

<P>- Took actions related to the design of a new 40-million gallon finished
water reservoir at the Hilltop Reservoir. </P>

<P><B>WAYS &amp; MEANS/BUDGET</B> </P>

<P>- Authorized an application for Innovations in American Government award
on behalf of the City's Job Bank Program. </P>

<P>- Made technical year-end adjustments to the 1996 budget and authorized
appropriation/transfer of additional funds for snow removal costs. </P>

<P><B>ZONING &amp; PLANNING</B> </P>

<P>- Approved ordinance amendment related to on-sale wine license charter
amendment approved in the November general election. The charter amendment
expanded the locations where wine and strong beer licenses may be obtained
to include many areas near residential neighborhoods. The ordinance amendment
is a temporary moratorium on new applications. </P>

<P>- Granted a waiver from the moratorium on establishment and expansion
of residential, commercial and industrial uses in the East Hennepin Study
Area to allow a residence at 400 East Hennepin Av. </P>

<P>- Granted a waiver from the moratorium on auto service and sales uses
along Lake Street to allow an auto repair facility at 3010 East Lake St.
</P>

<P>- Extended the storefront ordinance to include the block bounded by Park,
Portland and East Franklin Avs and East 19th St. </P>

<P>- Approved rezonings at 1700-2000 Elm St SE, 506 East 24th St, 2825-45
Harriet Av S and 624 1/2 E Franklin Av. </P>

<P><BR>
<B>December 30</B> </P>

<P>The Council held a special meeting on December 30. </P>

<P>- Set 1997 water and sewer rates. Water rates increase from $1.29 to
$1.35 per 100 cubic feet. Sewer rates increase from $2.19 to $2.35 per 100
cubic feet. </P>

<P><I>This is partial list of Council actions. For a full list, or for details
on any action, call 673-3130. The minutes of City Council meetings can be
found at http://www.finance-commerce.com. The next Council meeting begins
at 9:30 a.m. January 10 in City Hall 317. Watch live on City Cable 34 or
repeats Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays at 6 p.m.</I></P>

<P><B><HR ALIGN=LEFT></B></P>

