| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P><B><I>City Retains AAA Rating</I></B><BR>
Minneapolis is proud to be one of only two cities with a population over 200,000
to receive the highest possible credit rating from both of the major rating
services. Moody's Investor's Service and Standard and Poor's gave Minneapolis a
rating of AAA, which translates to millions of dollars in lower interest costs,
because it assures bond buyers that Minneapolis is a financially safe and
attractive investment. Last year, the only other city of similar size to hold the
AAA rating from both rating services was Charlotte, North Carolina.

<P><B><I>The City of Minneapolis Is No Place for Prejudice</I></B><BR>
The programs and services of the City of Minneapolis are available to all
citizens. The Minneapolis Civil Rights Ordinance protects against discrimination
treatment based on race, color, creed, religion, ancestry, national origin, sex
(including sexual harassment), affectional preference, disability, age, marital
status, and status with regard to public assistance. The ordinance also protects
families with children in the rental and purchase of housing. For educational
materials and programs, or for information on how to file a discrimination
complaint, call the Minneapolis Department of Civil Rights, 673-3012.

<P><B><I>Call 673-LINK for Business Information and Services</I></B><BR>
When Kirk's Mobil, a service station at 46th Street and Fourth Avenue South,
wanted to install gas pumps, co-owner Kirk Anderson turned to BusinessLink for
assistance. BusinessLink, a business referral network at the MCDA, helped the
station apply for the necessary zoning changes and locate affordable financing to
remodel. BusinessLink can make it easier you to do business in Minneapolis, too,
by connecting you with professionals who can offer valuable financing and
technical assistance. Whenever you need to navigate City regulatory procedures
(licensing, zoning, and permits), locate a new office or industrial site, secure
affordable financing, or write a business or marketing plan, BusinessLink can
help. Call 673-LINK (5465).

<P><B><I>Council Meets on Fridays</I></B><BR>
Minneapolis City Council meetings take place at 9:30 a.m. every other Friday,
with the exception of four weeks a year. Meetings take place in Room 317 City
Hall. They are open to the public and aired live on <STRONG>City Cable
34</STRONG>. For a 1996 Council meeting schedule, call 673-3130. For a ward map,
call 673-2070.

<P><B><I>Mayor, Council Set Priorities to Guide City Spending</I></B><BR>
The Mayor and City Council have developed seven policy goals as part of their
effort to determine what the City's 1996 service priorities and budget
allocations ought to be:

<OL TYPE="1">
	<LI>Strong and healthy families and children.
	<LI>Livable neighborhoods that are safe.
	<LI>Education opportunities for all children through successful public schools.
	<LI>Access to convenient transportation services.
	<LI>Diverse, resilient economy that creates needed job opportunities.
	<LI>Strong, healthy downtown area for housing, commerce, employment, and entertainment.
	<LI>A municipal government that is efficient and effective, responsive to the needs of citizens and neighborhoods, and ensures quality service.
</OL>

<P><B><I>Advisory Committee Makes Minneapolis More Accessible</I></B><BR>
With help from residents, Minneapolis is striving to become a barrier-free city.
A 15-member Advisory Committee on People with Disabilities provides advice and
guidance to the Mayor and City Council regarding architectural and program
accessibility, employment, transportation, and housing. Anyone with an interest
in accessibility or disability issues is welcome to attend the committee's
monthly meetings. For more information, or to report a problem with
accessibility, call 673-3343 (TTY 673-3360).

<P><B><I>Home Tour Showcases City Living</I></B><BR>
The South Minneapolis home of Skeet Kelly and Diana Richards used to be a
single-story summer home on the river.  By the time they finished with the second
story, the home had become a unique statement on the diversity of city housing. 
To show off their pride in city life, Diana and Skeet welcomed visitors during
the 1995 Minneapolis-Saint Paul Home Tour.  In all, 50 homes in the two cities
were featured. The 1996 tour will be May 4 and 5. To nominate a home, call
673-2491.

<P><B><I>Vote for School Board on November 7, 1995</I></B><BR>
Minneapolis voters will elect School Board members on Tuesday, Nov. 7. The next
election for Mayor and City Council will be in 1997, when Council Members will
begin serving staggered terms. Members of odd-numbered wards will be elected to
two-year terms in 1997 and to four-year terms in 1999. Members of even-numbered
wards will be elected in 1997 and 2001. You can register to vote on or before
Election Day. If you don't know where to vote, or if you have other questions,
call 673-2070.

<P><B><I>City Honors Special Citizens</I></B><BR>
The Mayor and City Council present Minneapolis Awards every fall to citizens who
have &quot;gone the extra mile&quot; to enrich the arts, education, business, or
some other aspect of the city. Anyone who lives or works in Minneapolis is
eligible to receive one of these awards. For nomination forms, call 673-2491.

<P><B><I>Visit City Hall on City Cable 34</I></B><BR>
When you can't get to City Hall, City Cable 34 brings City Hall to you. Council
Meetings air live at 9:15 a.m. Council Fridays and are rerun at 6 p.m. Fridays,
Mondays, and Wednesdays. City Beat recaps decisions made at Council meetings and
examines issues currently before the Council. Artifacts covers the local arts
scene and features interviews with local artists and arts policy makers. Twin
Cities 10 Most Wanted profiles local criminals and offers rewards for information
leading to their arrest. Mayor's Roundtable, hosted by the Mayor, explores issues
facing Minneapolis.

<P>Check round-the-clock videotext for job openings, program schedules, snow
emergencies, and other news. For a quarterly program guide, call 673-2234. For
cable installation and subscription rates, call 522-2000.

<P><B><I>City's Share of Your Property Tax Bill Is Only 17 Percent</I></B><BR>
Nearly half of your property taxes help support the Minneapolis Public Schools.
About one-quarter of them pay for municipal services, including parks and
libraries. Police service receives the largest share of municipal property taxes,
followed by Fire, Parks, and Public Works. Property taxes are based on estimated
market value as determined by the City Assessor and a formula established by the
State.

<P>Where Your Municipal Property Tax Dollars Go:
<PRE>
     Police        (29%)
     Fire          (15%)
     Public Works  (14%)
     Other         (20%)
     Parks         (15%)
     Libraries      (7%)
</PRE>

<P>Where Your Property Taxes Go:
<PRE>
     City          (17%)
     Libraries      (2%)
     Parks          (5%)
     Other          (4%)
     County        (23%)
     Schools       (49%)
</PRE>

<P><I>Lend A Hand: State law allows you to take time off with 
pay to be an election judge. Please help on Election 
Days. Call 673-2070.</I>

<P><A HREF="index.html">(Table of Contents)</A>


