<HEAD>

<TITLE>Next Generation</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Next Generation"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Next Generation</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P><B><I>Jobs, Training Available to Teens</I></B><BR>
Several City-sponsored programs offer full-time, part-time, permanent, and
seasonal job opportunities for Minneapolis youth. For example, the Youth Program
provides part-time jobs to disadvantaged high-school students; the Minneapolis
Youth Work Internship Program provides paid business internships to 16- to
21-year-olds; the Summer Youth Employment Program links 14- to 21-year-olds with
jobs in nonprofit agencies; and Teen Teamworks offers summer park-maintenance
jobs to at-risk youth. For more information about Teen Teamworks, call 661-4883.
For other programs, call 673-5700.

<P><B><I>Libraries Provide Homework Help and More to City Youth</I></B><BR>
After-school &quot;homework helper&quot; centers and a new Bookmobile are two
ways the Minneapolis Public Library works to serve youth and build a literate
society. To meet the needs of our increasingly diverse community, the library
provides adaptive equipment for people with disabilities as well as materials in
languages other than English. While preserving a rich history of recorded
knowledge, the library is also on the cutting edge of the digital age, ensuring
that electronic information is accessible to all. To find a library branch or
Bookmobile stop near you, call 372-6500.

<P><B><I>The Education and Health of Children Are Top City Priorities</I></B><BR>
The City is nurturing the next generation through programs and services such as
the Immunization Action Plan, an effort by the City and County to protect kids
from childhood diseases; Dancin' in the Streets, a September event that
celebrates youth with entertainment and mentorships; the City Children's
Nutcracker, which stars more than 300 boys and girls in a performance at Northrop
Auditorium every December; and the new Bookmobile, which makes regular stops in
30 Minneapolis neighborhoods.

<P><B><I>Sign Up for Child Care, Recreation</I></B><BR>
<STRONG>Recreation Plus</STRONG>, the Park Board's school-age childcare program,
offers safe fun and affordable care with an emphasis on the development of
positive recreation skills. For more information, call 661-4892.
<STRONG>Youthline</STRONG>, a program for 12- to 16-year-olds, involves youth in
activities, field trips, and leadership development. It is available at 11 parks
year-round and at an additional 26 parks in the summer. For more information,
call 661-4880. The Youth in Minneapolis After-school Program
(<STRONG>Y-MAP</STRONG>), serves more than 4,000 middle-school youth each
quarter. For more information, call 661-4885. <STRONG>Phat Summer</STRONG> (slang
for &quot;cool summer&quot;) is a free evening recreation program for 12- to
18-year-olds. It offers art, music, sports, life skills, and special events at 24
park and school sites during the summer. For more information, call 673-2060.
<STRONG>Club Fed</STRONG>, one of the Governor's Star Youth Service Programs,
coordinates free family events that provide educational, cultural, and
recreational enrichment. For more information, call 377-9441.

<P><I>Lend A Hand: You can give city youth a great advantage 
through United Way mentoring programs. Call 340-7621.</I>

<P><A HREF="index.html">(Table of Contents)</A>


