<HEAD>

<TITLE>Family Neighborhoods</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Family Neighborhoods"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Family Neighborhoods</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P><B><I>MCDA Offers Business Loans</I></B><BR>
Neighborhood businesses bring goods, services, and jobs close to residents and
make Minneapolis a better place to live and work. That's why the Minneapolis
Community Development Agency offers business loans with below-market-rate terms
to finance operations, purchase inventory, or make building improvements.
Minneapolis also has more than 30 business associations, which meet to share
ideas, learn about expansion and improvement programs, and discuss strategies for
strengthening their commercial areas. To learn more about MCDA business loans or
to connect with your nearest business association, call 673-5071.

<P><B><I>NRP Makes a Difference</I></B><BR>
Thousands of your neighbors are working with local government, businesses, and
nonprofit organizations to make Minneapolis a better place to live, work, learn,
and play. With help from the Minneapolis Neighborhood Revitalization Program
(NRP), they are meeting their housing, safety, economic development, recreation,
health, social service, environment, and transportation needs. Currently, 80 of
the city's 81 neighborhoods are involved in the NRP. Get involved in the NRP
activities in your neighborhood; call 673-5140.

<P><B><I>City Inspectors Help Preserve Quality Neighborhoods</I></B><BR>
City inspectors help ensure that Minneapolis homes and businesses are safe and
properly maintained. They also inspect construction sites and check for
compliance with environmental and zoning regulations. You can help, too. If you
witness illegal dumping, try to get a license number and description of the
driver, then call 673-2895. If you see graffiti, report it to 673-2090.

<P><B><I>Valuing Diversity</I></B><BR>
Like other major cities across the country, Minneapolis is becoming increasingly
diverse. Signs of our changing demographics are all around us: diverse
publications on our newsstands, non-traditional performances at our theaters,
ethnic restaurants in our neighborhoods. Minneapolis values this diversity, and
many citizens are working to ensure equal treatment and opportunity for all
through their involvement in the Advisory Committee on People with Disabilities,
the Minneapolis Initiative Against Racism, and other volunteer groups.

<P><I>Lend A Hand: Join the Minneapolis Initiative Against Racism, which fights
discrimination in business, housing, the media, and other areas. Call 730-6256
for more information.</I>

