<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Falls &amp; Fountains</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Falls &amp; Fountains"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Falls &amp; Fountains</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P><B><I>Get to Know Minneapolis' Finest Natural Resource</I></B><BR>
From the natural beauty of Minnehaha Falls to the serenity of the Berger fountain
in Loring Park and the inexorable movement of the mighty Mississippi, Minneapolis
is truly a city made beautiful by water. With more than 80 miles of parkways
winding along the shores of the city's lakes and rivers, you'll always be able to
get lost in the serenity of a gurgling stream or relish in the driving thunder of
a waterfall.

<P><B><I>SPEEDREAD Installation Nears Completion</I></B><BR>
Most Minneapolis residents now have their water meters read automatically by a
new system called SPEEDREAD. Since January 1992, the Water Works has installed
SPEEDREAD in more than 80 percent of Minneapolis homes. SPEEDREAD consists of a
new water meter and a meter interface unit (MIU), which is connected to
residents' telephone lines. The MIU is programmed to read meters once a month,
convert the data into a digital format, and send the information over the phone
line to a central computer in the downtown Utility Billing Office. SPEEDREAD
eliminates the need to send meter readers door-to-door and estimate bills when
residents are not home. If you do not yet have SPEEDREAD, call 1-800-648-3244 to
have it installed, free of charge.

<P><B><I>Monthly Utility Billing Begins</I></B><BR>
To assist residents with budgeting, the City is switching from quarterly to
monthly billing for water, sewer, and solid waste. The changeover began in August
1995 and was expected to take five months. Monthly billing is available only to
customers with SPEEDREAD, the City's automatic water meter reading system.
Residents without SPEEDREAD will continue to be billed quarterly.

<P><B><I>Separating Sewers Stops Pollution, Saves Money</I></B><BR>
A 10-year effort to stop pollution of the Mississippi River will conclude in
1996. This effort has involved separating storm and sanitary sewers to prevent
the overflow of untreated sewage during large rainstorms and snow melts.
Separating the sewers has saved the City an average of $625,000 a year by
reducing the amount of water requiring purification at the treatment plant by
millions of gallons a year.

<P><B><I>Clean Water Takes Partnership</I></B><BR>
Even if you don't live by a lake, what you do at home affects the water in the
lakes and creeks. The water that drains off your yard and driveway is carried to
the lakes and creeks by the storm-sewer system. Landscaping that reduces erosion
and lawn care that is kind to the environment help protect water quality. Avoid
raking leaves into the street and never pour oil and antifreeze down the storm
drains harm local waters. The City of Minneapolis is part of an innovative Clean
Water Partnership that is improving water quality in the Chain of Lakes. The
partnership is one of the largest urban water restoration programs in the
country. It is restoring wetlands, including Cedar Meadows; building stormwater
ponds; and constructing grit chambers to remove pollutants from stormwater. The
City's partners include the City of St. Louis Park, Hennepin County, the
Minneapolis Park and Recreation Board, the Minnehaha Creek Watershed District,
and the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency. To learn how to help improve water
quality, call 348-4448.

<P><I>Lend A Hand: Help stencil storm drains to remind people that what they put
down the storm drain flows directly to lakes and streams. Call 927-8563.</I>

<P><A HREF="index.html">(Table of Contents)</A>


