<HEAD>

<TITLE>Community Safety</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<!-- #include "city_head.incl"
	#MY_BGCOLOR#="ffffff"
	#MY_HEADER#="Community Safety"
-->
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<TABLE border=0>
<TR>
	<TD valign=top><IMG SRC="/pict/sails.gif" alt="logo"></TD>
	<TD valign=center><H1 align=right>City of Minneapolis</H1>
	<H2 align=right>Community Safety</H2></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<!-- end include -->

<!-- #include "city_navbar.incl" -->
<P><HR>

<A HREF="/index.html">Home</A>
| <A HREF="/hot/index.html">What's Hot</A>
| <A HREF="/events.html">Events</A>
| <A HREF="/topics/index.html">Topics</A>
| <A HREF="/departments/index.html">Departments</A>
| <A HREF="/publications/index.html">Publications</A>
| <A HREF="/related.html">Other Sites</A>

<HR>
<!-- end include -->

<P><B><I>National Night Out Helps Build Community</I></B><BR>
Each year in August, neighbors across the city fill their streets for National
Night Out. Locally-planned events are as diverse as the neighborhoods and include
parades, concerts and entertainment for kids. The evening provides opportunities
to get to know your neighbors and underscores that strong neighborhoods, where
people are involved and know one another, are consistently safer and more stable.

<P><B><I>Firefighters Respond to Calls in an Average of 3.5 Minutes</I></B><BR>
With 20 well-equipped stations located throughout the city, the Fire Department
responds to approximately 30,000 calls a year, arriving in an average of 3.5
minutes. Fighting fires is just part of a firefighter's service to citizens. They
also respond to medical emergencies, check blood pressure at all stations,
inspect commercial buildings, drop off fire-safety information to residents
annually, and teach children about fire safety during fire safety camps. You can
help by reading fire-safety information, checking your home for unsafe wiring or
flammable items, replacing the old battery in your smoke detector, and properly
storing flammable items. For more information call 673-3290.

<P><B><I>Police Officers Meet the Public, Maintain Safety</I></B><BR>
Community policing, the philosophy that guides the Minneapolis Police Department,
means police cooperate with other agencies, departments, businesses, and
residents to identify priority problems as well as long-term solutions. The
regular contact with citizens achieved through permanent shifts, bike patrols,
the mounted patrol, and other community policing strategies builds trust and
facilitates the exchange of information, which results in better service and
stronger neighborhoods. The creation of the downtown mounted patrol is a result
of the cooperative efforts between the City and the Downtown Council. The City
agreed to provide the Police officers, and the Council agreed to provide the
funds necessary to implement the program and cover monthly operational costs.

<P><B><I>Knowing Your Neighbors Is Key to Keeping Crime Down</I></B><BR>
Neighbors are more effective deterrents to crime than expensive security systems,
according to the experts. People who connect with each other, take ownership in
the quality of life on their block, and work to solve problems that arise are
crucial to safe, stable neighborhoods. The Police Department's Community Crime
Prevention/SAFE office provides resources and support to block and apartment
clubs, including workshops and printed materials on personal and home safety,
property management, and other neighborhood safety issues. Another important
resource, the McGruff House program, recruits residents who can offer safe places
for children to go in emergencies. Teams of civilian crime-prevention specialists
and police officers coordinate neighborhood crime-prevention activities
throughout the city. To get involved in making your neighborhood safer, call the
CCP/SAFE office, 673-3015.

<P><I>Lend A Hand: Keep your neighborhood safe and meet your neighbors by joining
a block club. Call 673-3015 for information.</I>

<P><I>The City-sponsored safety camp is a great way for kids to learn safe
habits. Call 348-2183.</I>

<P><A HREF="index.html">(Table of Contents)</A>


