<HEAD>
<TITLE>Research Concerning Changes On A Global Scale</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="GlobalScale"> </A> 
<PRE><img src="/images/planete.gif">  <img src="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE><P>
<H1>Research Concerning Changes On A Global Scale</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>Table of contents</H2>
<UL> 
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="glob_scale.html#Intro"> Introduction </A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B> <A HREF="ocean.html">Ocean and Climate : WOCE, CLIVAR and GCOS </A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="gewex.html"> Aerosol-cloud-radiation interactions and GEWEX </A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="cont_bio.html#ContBiosph">Continental biosphere</A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="polder.html"> A multidisciplinary program POLDER</A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="atmos_che.html# AtmChem"> Middle-atmosphere and atmospheric chemistry</A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B></UL>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<A NAME="Intro">
<H2> Introduction </H2>

This programme includes two complementary parts, devoted respectively to the World Climate Research Programme (WCRP) and the International Geosphere - Biosphere Programme (IGBP). <P>

The study of the ocean, of the meteorological atmosphere and of their interactions is broached within the framework of the first part which concentrates on the physical aspects of the climate. This part includes the Franco-American altimetric mission, <A HREF="/topex/Mission.html">TOPEX/POSEIDON</A> which constitutes the reference element of the space system for observation set up for the World Ocean Circulation Experiment (<A HREF="#OceanClimate">WOCE</A>). France is also participating in this system by its contribution to ESA's ERS programme. The study of the aerosol-clouds-radiation-dynamic interactions, one of the priorities of the Global Energy and Water cycle EXperiment (<A HREF="#Gewex">GEWEX</A>) Programme, is the  objective of a specific instrument programme which comprises the <A HREF="/scarab/Mission.html">SCARAB</A> radiometer for observing the radiation budget, the ALISSA altimetric lidar and the Infrared Atmospheric Sounding Interferometer (<A HREF="/iasi/Mission.html">IASI</A>). The POLarization and Directionality of Earth Reflectances (<A HREF="/polder/Mission.html">POLDER</A>) imaging radiometer-polarimeter, designed for the <A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/satdata/adeos_e.html">ADEOS mission</A> is also an element in this instrument programme. It constitutes a link between the two parts of the french programme to the degree that the study of the biosphere and of aerosol cycle, two themes of the IGBP, will also be benefiting from the richness of its measurements.  Shared between the goals of WCRP and IGBP, the stratospheric research programme also contributes to both parts. It owes its originality to a balloon-borne observation programme, open to the international community. <P>

The second part, devoted to the International Geosphere-Biosphere Programme, is centered on the study of the biosphere. It is based on the continuity and on the evolution of the SPOT Programme, on the complementarity of the <A HREF="http://www-projet.cnes.fr:8050/">VEGETATION</A> and POLDER instruments and on a set of airborne systems.<P> 
<A HREF="#index">Back to index</A><P>

