<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ocean climate</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<PRE><img src="/images/p6205.gif">    <img src="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE>
<P>
<H5><I>Topography of seas surfaces</I></H5>
<H1>Ocean and Climate : WOCE, CLIVAR and GCOS</H1>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_whale.gif"><BR>
<H2>Mission list</H2><P>

<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF="/topex/Mission.html">TOPEX/POSEIDON</A> <BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF="/tp-follow/Mission.html">TOPEX/POSEIDON Follow On</A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF="/doris/Mission.html">DORIS</A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B></UL>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_whale.gif"><P>
ERS and <A HREF="/topex/Mission.html">TOPEX/POSEIDON</A> are the space components of the observation system of WOCE, which, in a pre-operational configuration, makes it possible to characterize ocean circulation at various space-time scales and the atmospheric forcing at the ocean-atmospheric interface. The TOPEX/POSEIDON altimetric programme is conducted in cooperation by CNES and NASA. The spacecraft was launched by ARIANE on August 10, 1992. Defined by the international oceanographic community, the mission was entirely optimized to meet the requirements of the WOCE programme. In addition to the launcher, CNES supplied the POSEIDON solid state compact altimeter, the <A HREF="/doris/Mission.html">DORIS</A> POSEIDON control and processing center and the AVISO system for post-processing and distribution of all the mission's data. AVISO/EDDIE completes the <A HREF="http://www.ifremer.fr/cersat/english/">CERSAT system operated by IFREMER</A>, to benefit ESA with the production and distribution of oceanic low rate data from the ERS-1 and 2 missions. <P>

 Since January 1993, the total technical success of the TOPEX/POSEIDON mission has been demonstrated. The excellent performance of the two altimeters, the subdecimetric precision of the orbit calculated by the DORIS system and the excellent operation of the data processing and distribution system confirmed the pertinence of the choice of the Science Working Team of NASA and of CNES.  The results obtained attest that the mission's goal was largely exceeded, and they open new scientific prospects and orient the definition of future altimetric systems. <P>

Henceforth, what is needed is continuity of an altimetric observation system including a TOPEX/POSEIDON class reference mission plus at least one other satellite - ideally two - in order to best observe the marine geoid, the whirlpools, the major currents such as the Gulfstream, the Kuro Shivo and the Antarctic Circumpolar Current, the "El Nino" climatic anomalies, the tides and the Waves, the ice and the level variations sea. Given the maturity of the technologies, that of the community of users and the anticipated scientific and operational, advantages involved such as system would naturally fit within the ocean component, Global Ocean Observing System (GOOS) of the worldwide climate observation system. To contribute to this undertaking, CNES is participating in the ENVISAT altimetric mission, providing the DORIS orbitography service and CNES is carrying out the design of a series of operational altimetric mini-satellites, destined to continue the TOPEX/POSEIDON observations at least cost and at the same performancelevel. <P>

Two major surveys at sea, devoted to the study of the ocean-atmosphere exchanges and the medium scale ocean circulation, SOFIA and SEMAPHORE, were organized in 1992 and 1993. They supply an integrating framework for researches and make it possible to establish the contribution of the ERS and TOPEX/POSEIDON measurements and to reinforce the validation of the reversal techniques and to assess the representativity of the space measurements. Like the works validating the ERS-1 data, they benefited from the availability of original onboard instruments such as the RESSAC conical sounding radar or the PORTOS hyperfrequency radiometer. <P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
