<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>GEWEX</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<PRE><IMG SRC="/images/p4745.gif">       <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE><P>
</A>
<H5><I>space view of earth. cloudy strata</I></H5>

<H1>Aerosol-cloud-radiation interactions and GEWEX</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>Missions list</H2><P>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF="/scarab/Mission.html">SCARAB</A> :
 Radiative budget experiment<BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF="/polder/Mission2.html">POLDER</A> : POLarization and Directionality Of the Earth's Reflectances<BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 4, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF="/iasi/Mission.html">IASI</A> : Infrared Atmospheric Sounding Interferometer; Humidity and temperatures profiles<BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B >
<IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF="http://www.cais.com:80/gewex/gewex.html">IGPO</A>: International GEWEX Project Office<P>
</B >
</UL>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
Research on this theme is mobilizing many laboratories and organizations and is supported by the joint use of globally oriented space systems, airborne equipment which is indispensable to the study of mesoscale processes and to a hierarchy of digital models. <P>

France is developing a series of dedicated instruments for GEWEX, to observe the radiation budget, the three-dimensional thermodynamic structure of the atmosphere, the clouds and the aerosols. The radiation pattern observation programme is based upon the <A HREF="/scarab/Mission.html">SCARAB</A> instrument, designed by the Laboratoire de M&eacute;t&eacute;orologie Dynamique and ROSHYDROMET (Russia) and is also based on <A HREF="../CNESaction/polder.html">POLDER</A>.  An initial series of two to three instruments will be used on Russian meteorological satellites of the METEOR series, as part of the Franco-Russian cooperation. The first was launched on 25 January 1994 from the Plessetsk cosmodrome. An international annoucement of opportunities for proposals involving the validation and scientific use of the data has been released on January, 1995. The second flight model is expected to be launched in 1997 onboard the RESSURS satellite. With time, the <A HREF="../scarab/Mission.html">SCARAB</A> instrument might find its natural place on the METOP operational meteorological missions, developped by ESA and EUMETSAT for a launching at the beginning of the next century. The POLDER imaging polarimeter radiometer is an instrument which complements SCARAB and whose function is to study the radiation impact of aerosols, the physical properties of clouds and the two-directional distribution functions of short waves fluxes. The franco-russian lidar, ALISSA, will make it possible, within the framework of a short duration exploration experiment on the MIR space station, to analyze the potential contribution of cloud altimetry to the study of the interactions between clouds and radiation. <P> 

The Infrared Atmospheric Sounding Interferometer (IASI) is now being studied in Phase B as part of an european cooperation.  Its performances, particularly in terms of space resolution and radiometric budget will enable to observe the temperature and humidity profiles in the troposphere with a vertical precision and resolution beyond the possibility of the present operational probes, and to obtain measurements of the integrated contents of ozone, methane and carbon monoxide which play key roles in the troposphere's chemistry and in the additional greenhouse effect. IAS is designed for the METOP polar meteorological mission. It will be used for the joint needs of climate research and operational meteorological forecasts. <P>

 The airborne programme, developed in cooperation with INSU, METEO-FRANCE, IGN and CNET is part of the PATOM (Meso-scale Oceanography ATmosphere Programme). <P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
