<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Description</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<PRE>
<IMG SRC="/images/polder-crau.gif">                 <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif">
</PRE>
<H1>POLDER on ADEOS : a multi-disciplinary program</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_forest.gif"><P>
<H2>Missions list</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF="/polder/Mission2.html">POLDER</A>: POLarization and Directionnality of the Earth's Reflectances <BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 4, 1996</EM><P></B></UL>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_forest.gif"><P>

The <A HREF="/polder/Mission2.html">POLDER</A> on ADEOS program is an initial Franco-Japanese space cooperation in the field of the Earth and Environmental sciences. The POLDER instrument is a wide viewing imaging polarimeter radiometer designed for the ADEOS japanese mission which will be launched in 1996 and which collect, during at least three years and over the whole globe, observations of solar radiation reflected by clouds, aerosols and marine or continental surfaces. Thanks to an original instrument concept, POLDER will be the first space instrument to simultaneously observe the polarization and the multi-spectral and directional signatures of reflected radiation. Its observations will make it possible to reach certain physical-optical characteristics of aerosols and clouds, to observe oceanic phytoplankton, the continental biosphere, the directional distribution of short wave radiation as well as the water vapor content.<P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
