<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Middle atmosphere and atmospheric chemistry</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="AtmChem">
<PRE><IMG SRC="/images/p6277.gif">        <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE>
</A>
<H5><I>KIRUNA: stratospheric balloon</I></H5>

<H1>Middle atmosphere and atmospheric chemistry</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>Missions list</H2><P>

<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF ="/windii/Mission.html">WINDII</A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B><IMG SRC="/images/balljaun.gif"><B> <A HREF ="/poam/Mission.html">POAM-2</A><BR>
<EM> Latest Update: April 2, 1996</EM><P></B></UL>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

French research work concerning dynamics, physico-chemistry of the stratosphere and the mesosphere remains centered on the study of the processes of ozone destruction, the chemical-dynamic inter-actions, the troposphere-stratosphere exchanges as well as on the analysis of trends and balances at regional and global scale. For observation, it relies on stratospheric balloons, instrument equipped aircraft and space systems, the combination of which is necessary to study the complex processes and the mechanisms of inter-actions and of integration of scales. These activities complete France's contribution to ESA's ENVISAT-1 programme. <P>

The balloon programme is based on a set of vehicles and operational services developed and operated by CNES. The Open stratospheric balloons (Bso), capable of carrying multi-instrumented gondola weighing 500 kg, are widely used for short duration flights, while the infrared Montgolfieres (MIR) have shown their ability to fly 50 kg instrumented gondolas during more than 60 days above convective tropical zones with vertical displacements, sufficient for the study of troposphere-stratosphere exchanges. These facilities and services are made available to the international scientific community, on a commercial basis which make it possible to ensure their permanence and their evolution. In this way, many Bso launches by CNES have widely contributed to the success of the European Union's European Arctic Stratospheric Ozone Experiment (EASOE) and to that of the French component of the UARS correlative measurement programme. The MIR have also made it possible to study the water vapor flux between the equatorial stratosphere and troposhere.  <P>

A long duration, international scope balloon survey, STRATEOLE is also in Phase B. Its goal is to study the stratospheric dynamic-chemical inter-actions, associated with the Antarctic polar vortex, using 200 high pressure drifting balloons, traveling at two different altitudes (70 hPa and 50 hPa) at the periphery and within the vortex. The payload of these balloons will be composed of 10 kg gondolas equipped with miniaturized instruments for position determination and measuring pressure, temperature, wind and minor constituents including ozone. During the survey, planned for the year 2000, the balloon observations will be combined with the profiles of constituents, aerosols and temperature produced by ENVISAT and with digital models, in order to follow a complete cycle of the evolution of the Antarctic vortex. STRATEOLE will make it possible to perform a large scale validation of the ENVISAT observations. <P>

The strictly space component of this programme is conducted within the framework of various cooperations. It concerns a set of instruments intended for the study of solar forcing, of the dynamics, thermodynamic structure and constituents in the stratosphere. The SPECSOL spectrometer, developed by two laboratories, the Service d'A&eacute;ronomie (SA) and the IASB and flown several times in the ATLAS and EURECA missions, characterizes the variability of the UV solar spectrum. <A HREF ="../uars/descript.html#Windii">WINDII</A>, a Canadian-French interferometer, measures temperature and wind profiles in the stratosphere and mesosphere on board UARS. In the field of stratospheric chemistry, CNES and the French community are concentrating their efforts on occultation techniques, by participating in the France-belgium (GRILLE on ATLAS) and Belgium-France-Russia (MIRAS on MIR) infrared spectrometry experiments and in the United States <A HREF ="../poam/Mission.html">POAM-2</A> experiment carried on SPOT-3. <P>

In parallel, the study of the tropospheric chemistry is growing considerably from the theoritical and experimental point of view, with, particularly, research accompanying the development of the IASI infrared spectrometer. <P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
