<HEAD>
<TITLE>Site de Landers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<IMG SRC="/icones/logo_radar.gif" ALIGN=LEFT> 
<H1>LANDERS : The displacement field of the Landers earthquake mapped by radar interferometry</H1>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

The Landers, California earthquake sequence of June 28 1992, produced large displacements of the ground, reaching maxima along the surface rupture, where up to 6.7 m of right-lateral slip has been measured. <P>

Synthetic Aperture  Radar (SAR) images acquired before and after the earthquakes (M = 7.3) by the <A HREF="http://gds.esrin.esa.it:80/">European ERS-1</A> satellite were analyzed by interferometry to measure the coseismic surface displacement field over an area of 100 km by 250 km. <P>

After removing effects due to topography and orbits, the residual fringes depict changes in the ground surface between the acquisition times of the two images. <P>

This approach provides a denser sampling than surveying methods and a better precision than previous space imaging techniques. <P>

This new geodetic technique can detect centimetre-sized changes in the ground surface. The accuracy of the measurement is better than 4 cm in range, based on comparisons with ground surveys. <P>

For a pair of images taken before and after the earthquake, the interferogram shows clear lobes with long axes oriented approximately 45&#176; from the fault trace, consistent with predictions of an elastic dislocation <A HREF="model_landers.html">model</A>. <P>

<A HREF="landers1.html"><IMG SRC="/images/icone_landers.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A><BR>
  First interferogram :<BR>
  Post processing interferometry fringes obtained with the pair of ERS-1 images taken before (24 April 92 ) and after(7 August 92) the earthquake. <P><BR>

<A HREF="landers2.html"><IMG SRC="/images/icone_landers2.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A><BR>
  Second interferogram :<BR>
  Post processing interferometry fringes obtained with the pair of ERS-1 images taken before (24 April 92) and the year after(18 June 93) the earthquake. <P><BR>

<A NAME="Fawnskin"></A>
<A HREF="fawnskin.html"><IMG SRC="/images/icone_zoom_landers.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A><BR>
  Zoom of the second interferogram :<BR>
  Fawnskin area, a zone of 8 km wide, the concentric fringes shows an earth inflating (M = 5.4). One cycle of colour corresponds to one interferometric fringe equivalent to 28 mm of change in the range between the satellite and the reflector on the ground. <P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
