<HEAD>
<TITLE>Site de l'Etna</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<IMG SRC="/icones/logo_radar.gif" ALIGN=LEFT> 
<H1>ETNA : Volcano deflation monitored by spaceborne radar interferometry</H1>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

Spaceborne radar interferometry can be used to monitor long-term volcano deformation. Two families of Synthetic Aperture Radar images, acquired from ascending and descending orbits by the <A HREF="http://gds.esrin.esa.it:80/">satellite ERS-1</A>, and looking at mount Etna from opposite sides, cover the time period from May 17 1992 to October 24 1993, and include the second half of Etna's most recent eruption. <P>

With the interferometric technique, a volcano-wide deflation has been observed, which is an expected consequence of the eruption, but which had not previously been appreciated. The <A HREF="etnamodl.html">modelled deformation</A>, based on the change of pressure in a sphere located in an elastic half-space, increases linearly with time until the end of the eruption. <P>

Examples of interferograms showing the subsidence of the volcano at different stages : <P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/etna1.gif">  
<IMG SRC="/images/etna2.gif"> 
<IMG SRC="/images/etna3.gif"> 
<IMG SRC="/images/etna4.gif"> <BR>
<IMG SRC="/images/etna5.gif"> 
<IMG SRC="/images/etna6.gif"> 
<IMG SRC="/images/etna7.gif"> 
<IMG SRC="/images/etna8.gif"> <P>
</CENTER>

The longer the time between image acquisition the larger the deflation, expressed by the number of fringes. The first figure shows less than 1 fringe. The last figure shows up to 5 fringes. Artefact structure due to atmospheric heterogeneity can be seen. Noisy areas occured where the conditions for surface preservation between data acquisition were not met, mainly due to vegetation or climate changes. <P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
