<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The POAM Mission</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<PRE><IMG SRC="/images/p6284.gif">  <IMG SRC="/images/nrl.gif"> Logo NRL</PRE>
<H5><I>ozone studies</I></H5>  
<H1>POAM II : Polar Ozone Aerosol Measurement</H1>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>Table of contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#objectives">Mission objectives</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#description">Instrument description</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#contribution">CNES contribution</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#results">Scientist results</A></B><P>
</UL><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>


POAM II is a National Research Laboratory (USA) experiment. <P>

The instrument is flown on the CNES SPOT 3 spacecraft. It has been launched on september 1993, and its life time is 3 years minimum.<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/p7995.gif"></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2><A NAME="objectives">Mission objectives</A></H2>
The POAM II experiment is intended to measure the concentration of ozone and aerosols in the atmosphere by observing the atmospheric extinction of the solar disk at selected spectral wavelengths. In addition, information on aerosol characteristics and the vertical temperature profile can be determined from the data : <P>
<UL>
<LI> Measure long-term trends in stratopheric ozone abundance at high latitudes, and examine the morphologie of spring-time ozone depletions in the solar regions.<BR>
<LI> Measure stratospheric aerosol extinction profiles and obtain a climatology of polar stratospheric clouds<BR>
<LI> Make zonal average measurements of H2O and NO2 in the stratosphere and characterize seasonal and latitudinal variations in the polar regions.<BR>
<LI> Measure ozone abundance in the upper troposphere.<BR>
<LI> Make observations of the frequency of occurrence and optical thickness high cirrus clouds<BR>
<LI> Characterize atmospheric propagation at 1059 nm in the polar regions.
</UL><P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>
<HR><P>

<H2><A NAME="description">Instrument description</A></H2>

POAM II is composed of three subsystems :  <P>
<OL>
<LI> An optical head housing nine telescopes each of which has an aperture defining a common field-of-view, a narrow-band interference filter, and a detector. The telescopes are coaligned and mounted on a gimbal with sufficient movement in elevation and azimuth so that they can be pointed at the sun at sunrise and sunset.
<LI> An electronic module which controls the optical head, collects and stores the data from these sensors, processes the commands, and controls all equipment operations.
<LI> A telemetry subsystem which transmits data to the the ground through a filter and a antenna
</OL><P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2><A NAME="contribution">CNES contribution</A></H2>
CNES controls the instruments, on behalf of NRL. Those remote actions are done through the systems set up to control the <A HREF="/spot/Mission.html">SPOT 3</A> satellite.<P>

CNES leads a french scientific group included in the Science Team POAM II. Those people are involved in the POAM II results validation, both through theoretical studies and through data correlation with non-satellite-based experiments.<P>

CNES will set up, for the french scientific community, the <A HREF="/ether/Ether.html">Ether</A> access service to POAM II data.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2><A NAME="results">Scientist results</A></H2>
<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

