<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The ODIN Mission</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<CENTER> <img src="/images/cnes.gif"></CENTER><P>
<H1>ODIN</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
<H2> Table of contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="#objectives">Mission Objectives</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="#experiment">Aeronomy experiment</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="#payload">Payload Composition</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <B><A HREF="#contribution">CNES Contribution</A></B>
<P>
</UL>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="objectives">Mission Objectives</A></H2>

Odin is a dual purpose project dedicated to the study of both astronomical objects and the Earth's atmosphere. The Odin Payload is a common resource and approximately half of the available spacecraft time shall be used for each scientific discipline. <P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2><A NAME="experiment">Aeronomy experiment</A></H2>

Odin will be used to infer the abundance and spatial distributions of important atmospheric species such as water vapour, chlorine monoxide, ozone, molecular oxygen, mitrogen and hydrogen compounds as well as atmospheric aerosol particles. A limb scanning mode will be employed between 15 and 120 km to observe spectral signatures in the mm, submm and ultraviolet-near infrared wavelength regions of the spectrum. Odin will be the first aeronomy satellite to perform spectroscopic measurements at submm wavelengths and will be operationnal during a period when a serious lack of satellite surveillance of the Earth's atmophere is expected to exist. <P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2><A NAME="payload">Payload composition</A></H2>

The payload will comprise a heterodyne radiometer system and a spectrograph with an ultraviolet near infraed spectroscopy capability. The radiometer is fed by a 1.1 m telescope and will be used for both the astronomy and aeronomy parts of the mission. <P>
By designing the radiometer to have a frequency coverage of approximately 118.25 - 119.25 GHz, 486 - 502 Ghz and 541 - 579 Ghz it can fulfill the rquirements of both scientific disciplines. The receiver will be equipped with one acusto-optical and two hybrid correlator spectrometers. The maximum instantaneous banswidth is 1 Ghz. There will be two selectable frequency resolutions, 1 Mhz and 150 Khz, respectively. <P>
The ultraviolet-near infrard spectrograph will only used for the aeronomy observations. The design assumes as a goal a wavelength coverage between 200 - 800 nm, 1.19 - 1.39 &#181;m and 1.43 - 1.60 &#181;m. The resolving power is assumed to be between 55 and 900. <P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2><A NAME="contribution">CNES Contribution</A></H2>

ODIN data should  be available for the french scientific community through <A HREF="/ether/Ether.html">Ether</A> service.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

