</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Description</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/logo_polder.gif"></CENTER>
<H1>Polder Instrument And Mission Concept Description</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

The POLDER instrument concept is based on wide-field-of-view telecentric optics, a rotating wheel carrying spectral and polarizing filters and a charged coupled device (CDD) detector array. With its aperture of 43&#176; along-track, 51&#176; across-track and 57&#176; in the diagonal, the instantaneous field of view of the optics intercepts a two-dimensional Earth scene imaged and partitioned into 244 x 274 elementary pixels by the CCD matrix. This geometry produces a swath width of about 2400 km, allowing for near-complete daily coverage of the Earth, while the arrangement of the CCD matrix pixels yields a quasi-constant horizontal resolution throughout the swath, only distorted by Earth curvature and equal to 6 x 7 km2 at nadir. <P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/p9824.gif"></CENTER><P>

Multi-angle viewing is achieved by the along-track migration at spacecraft velocity of the two dimensional field of view, as illustrated on the following schema. Thus, over a single pass any target within the instrument swath can be observed quasi-simultaneously under up to 13 different viewing angles. Combining multi-pass observations obtained at short time intervals in taking advantage of the 4 day quasi-subcycle of the ADEOS orbit allows a more complete sampling of the bidirectional reflectance and polarization distribution functions (BRDF and BPDF). On the other hand, the polarization and multispectral capability is produced the rotation of the filter/polarizer wheel. The selection of the fifteen filters mounted on the wheel, determined by mission requirements, results in POLDER's capacity to observe reflectances in eight narrow spectral bands of the visible and near infrared spectrum and, for three of these channels, respectively centred on 443, 670 and 865 nm, at three different polarization angles 60 degrees apart. A sixteenth, opaque filter is mounted on the wheel for frequent measurements of the CCD dark current and control of its stability. <P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/p8623.gif"></CENTER><P>


The list hereafter displays the characteristics of POLDER spectral bands. High and low limits of the dynamic range correspond to worst case saturation (considering that both the sun and the sensor are aligned at zenith) and to the minimal observable reflectances (molecular scattering only) respectively. <P>
<UL>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 443 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 20
No Polarization
Low dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.05 ~ 0.22
No High dynamic range (reflectance)
Main mission : Ocean colour
</PRE>
</LI>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 443 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 20
Polarization : 3 angles
No Low dynamic range (reflectance)
High dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.05 ~ 1.1
Main mission : Aerosols, ERB
</PRE>
</LI>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 490 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 20
No Polarization
Low dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.034 ~ 0.17
No High dynamic range (reflectance)
Main mission : Ocean colour
</PRE>
</LI>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 565 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 20
No Polarization
Low dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.019 ~ 0.11
No High dynamic range (reflectance)
Main mission : Ocean colour
</PRE>
</LI>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 670 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 20
Polarization : 3 angles
Low dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.013 ~ 0.25
High dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.013 ~ 1.1
Main mission : Vegetation, Aerosols, ERB
</PRE>
</LI>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 763 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 10
No Polarization
Low dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.007 ~ 0.25
High dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.007 ~ 1.1
Main mission : Cloud top pressure
</PRE>
</LI>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 765 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 40
No Polarization
Low dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.007 ~ 0.25
High dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.007 ~ 1.1
Main mission : Aerosols, Cloud top pressure
</PRE>
</LI>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 865 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 40
Polarization : 3 angles
Low dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.007 ~ 0.25
High dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.007 ~ 1.1
Main mission : Vegetation, Aerosols, ERB
</PRE>
</LI>
<LI>
Central wavelength (nm) : 910 nm
<PRE>
Band width (nm) : 20
No Polarization
Low dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.007 ~ 0.25
High dynamic range (reflectance) : 0.007 ~ 1.1
Main mission : Water vapour
</PRE>
</LI>
</UL>
In order to accommodate both the large dynamic range required by the observation of clouds and the high radiometric sensitivity needed at low signal level for the ocean colour mission, short and long integration/exposure times are interleaved as a result of the optimisation of the CCD reading sequence, leading to a Noise equivalent Differential Reflectance (NeDR) increasing from 10E-4 at low reflectance values up to about 10E-3 for a reflectance of 1. All spectral channels from 670 to 910 nm have dual dynamics/sensitivity. 

An accuracy of 2 % and 3 % is targeted for the estimation of the calibration coefficient for shorter (< 565 nm) and longer (> 565 nm) wavelengths respectively, while a 1 % accuracy is expected for the interband calibration coefficient. These error budgets are considered within reach of a calibration approach based on both pre-launch calibration with an integrating sphere and on in-flight, external calibration based on modelling and observation of reference Earth targets of known reflectance signatures. A pre-launch POLDER-OCTS intercalibration procedure is also planned, with an expected accuracy of 2 %. <P>
POLDER observations are acquired continuously in the sun-illuminated part of the orbit, for solar zenith angles lower than 75&#176; with respect to nadir viewing. This implies that the geographic zones observed by POLDER change according to the season. <P>

