<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>TOPEX/POSEIDON: Mission Description</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<PRE><IMG SRC="/images/topex2.gif">       <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE>
<H1>TOPEX/POSEIDON: Mission Description</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2>Table of Contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B><A HREF="#satellite">The TOPEX/POSEIDON satellite</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B><A HREF="#payload">The TOPEX/POSEIDON Payload</A></B><P>
</UL>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<A NAME="satellite"><H2>
The TOPEX/POSEIDON satellite
</H2></A>

The TOPEX/POSEIDON satellite is an adaptation by Fairchild Space of the existing Multimission Modular Spacecraft (MMS), which has successfully carried the payloads of the Solar Maximum Mission, Landsat 4 and Landsat 5. The MMS design was modified to meet the TOPEX/POSEIDON requirements.<BR>

The satellite carries 6 science instruments, 4 from NASA, 2 from CNES. A dual frequency radar altimeter (ALT, NASA), a TOPEX microwave radiometer (TMR, NASA), a Laser Retroreflector Array (LRA, NASA) and the Doppler Orbitography and Radiopositioning Integrated by Satellite (DORIS, CNES) dual Doppler tracking system receiver are the operational sensors. The single frequency solid-state radar altimeter (SSALT, CNES) and the Global Positioning System Demonstration Receiver (GPSDR, NASA) are the experimental ones.<BR>

The orbit configuration has been chosen to avoid undesirable aliased tidal frequencies such as 0, annual and semi-annual, and avoid that different tidal constituents be aliased to the same frequency. To satisfy these constraints and yet cover most of the world's ocean (~ 90%), an inclination of 66&#176; was selected. A repeat period of 9.916 days has been chosen to compromise best between spatial and temporal resolutions, resulting in a 316 km cross-track separation at the equator. Finally, a high orbit altitude was selected to maximise the accuracy of orbit determination, because of the reduced atmospheric drag and gravity forces acting on the satellite. The exact altitude that allows the orbit satisfy these constraints and fly over 2 verification sites located in the Mediterranean Sea (Lampedusa Island, Italy) and at the Harvest Platform (California, USA)  is 1336 km.<BR>

The TOPEX/POSEIDON satellite has a 2500 kg mass and is expected to have a 5 year lifetime. It has been launched in August 1992 with an european ARIANE 42P launcher.<P>



<P><A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>


<A NAME="payload"><H2>
The TOPEX/POSEIDON Payload
</H2></A>

The ALT is the first spaceborne dual frequency altimeter. The measurements are made at 2 frequencies (5.3 and 13.6 GHz) and are combined to minimize the errors caused by the ionospheric free electrons. The ALT design is based on the previous SEASAT and GEOSAT altimeters with significant improvements including the 5.3 Ghz channel for the ionospheric measurement, a more precise height measurement and longer lifetime.<BR>
The TMR makes use of the measurement of sea-surface microwave emissivity at three frequencies (18, 21 and 37 GHz) to estimate the total water vapor content in the atmosphere. The 21 GHz is the primary channel for water vapor measurement. The 18 GHz and 37 GHz channels are respectively used to remove the effects of wind speed and cloud cover on the water vapor measurement.<BR>

The LRA is used with a network of Satellite Laser Ranging (SLR) stations to provide satellite tracking data for precision orbit determination and calibration of the altimeter bias.<BR>

The DORIS system of CNES provides another type of satellite tracking data using microwave Doppler techniques. The system is composed with an onboard receiver and a network of ground transmitting beacons. These beacons provide a quasi-continuous tracking of the satellite. They are equipped with meteorological sensors measuring temperature, humidity, and atmospheric pressure to correct for the atmospheric effects on the transmitted signals. The DORIS signals are transmitted at 2 frequencies (401.25 and 2036.25 MHz) to allow the removal of the effects of the ionospheric free electrons on the tracking data.<BR>

The SSALT is a solid-state Ku-band (13.65 GHz) altimeter. It is a new technology low power, low weight altimeter.<BR>

The GPSDR receives signals from the GPS constellation. With a combination of the GPSDR data and a number of GPS receivers on the Earth's surface, precise tracking of the satellite is made possible by using the technique of Kalman filtering and differential ranging. <P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

