<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The orbit determination</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<PRE><IMG SRC="/images/doris.gif">    <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE><P>
<H1>Orbit determination</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>The DORIS system provides three orbit restitution products.
<UL>
<LI> Type : Real time
<UL>
<LI> Processing center: On-board package
<LI> Precision achieved    :
<UL>
<LI> Position : < 4 m RMS all axes
<LI> Velocity : < 0.4 cm/s
</UL>
<LI> Delay            : none
</UL>
<LI> Type : Operational
<UL>
<LI> Processing center: DORIS control and data processing center (CNES, TOULOUSE, FRANCE)
<LI> Accuracy achieveds    : < 20 cm RMS on the radial component
<LI> Delay            : 48 hours
</UL>
<LI> Type : Precise
<UL>
<LI> Processing center: Precise Orbit Determination Service (CNES, TOULOUSE, FRANCE)
<LI> Accuracy achieved    : < 5 cm RMS on the radial component
<LI> Delay            : 1 month
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
The system was originally designed to perform very precise orbit restitution of low Earth orbiting satellites, in support of the POSEIDON ocean altimetry experiment, providing an orbit altitude reference for radar altimeter data processing, with an accuracy goal of 10 cm or less on the radial component of the orbit. As such, it was embarked on the TOPEX satellite which was launched in August 1992, but it was also validated earlier in flight, on the SPOT2 Earth observation satellite, launched in February 1990. This precise orbit determination requires a certain amount of processing of the measurements performed by the DORIS on-board package, with a software model of a certain number of parameters. The orbit data is available within 1 month, the delay resulting mainly from external data availability (solar flux, earth rotation parameters).<P>

As far as the Precise Orbit Determination (POD) is concerned, operational computation has been performed on SPOT2 data since January 1992, TOPEX data since September 1992 and SPOT3 (launched in September 1993) data since October 1993. Thanks to the very good coverage of the orbit determination beacons network, which increases with the spacecraft orbit altitude, the amount of data acquired daily is very important. Moreover, data production is very reliable, the TOPEX precise orbit having been produced 100 % of the time since the beginning of the mission.<P>

For DORIS on SPOT satellites, only internal criteria can be used, for the orbit restitution quality assessment, such as residuals after orbit restitution and comparisons of solutions with overlapping data. For DORIS on TOPEX, external criteria can be used, on top of the previous ones, such as comparison of the POD performed by CNES with DORIS data and performed by NASA-GSFC with SLR, or altimetric crossovers. All these results show that the radial accuracy of precise orbit restitution using the DORIS system is in the order of 2 to 3 centimeters with DORIS/TOPEX data and 5 to 6 cm with DORIS/SPOT data, well within the 10 cm accuracy goal that was set initially for the system.<P>

Other analysis have been performed also by groups outside of CNES, using DORIS data, which also demonstrate very good performance (Willis et al, 1994 ; Tapley et al, 1993).<P>

The DORIS control and data processing center provides an operational orbit with a 20 cm RMS accuracy on the radial component within 48 hours, also well within the 1 meter accuracy design goal.<P>

The on-board package provides, at the interface with the spacecraft, an orbit calculated in real time, computed by a navigation software designed to an accuracy goal of 25 meters RMS 3D. This may typically be of interest for other instruments or experiments on-board the spacecraft that need the provision of an orbit in such a class of accuracy. This feature has been incorporated in the DORIS receiver to fly with the SPOT4 satellite in 1998, and has been tested on ground with SPOT2 and SPOT3 data. It shows very good performance when compared to the precise orbit calculated with the same data, the 4 meters accuracy results being well within the design goal of 25 m RMS.<P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
