<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Positioning</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<PRE><IMG SRC="/images/doris.gif">    <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE><P>
<H1>Positioning</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
Similar measurements can be performed to determine the location of a ground beacon for point positioning, whether it is a beacon of the permanent network or a dedicated location beacon.<P>

Location of ground beacons is performed either by a quasi-geometric method using the precise orbit ephemeris and measurements over the considered beacon, or by a dynamical method using the whole set of measurements and estimation of beacon locations as well as orbit and dynamical parameters. This enables high accuracy absolute or relative location.<P>

The worldwide coverage of the system makes it most suitable for monitoring of natural phenomena such as continental drift, sea level, earth rotation. The good accuracy, the field packaging of the location beacons and the fact that the system is centralised, which enables automated operation of the location beacons, even for long durations, and does without the usual significant cost for data communications, are all important points that make DORIS a very useful tool for precise geodesy and monitoring of glaciers, landslides, volcanoes, construction sites, tectonic plates...<P>

A positioning service, based on dedicated location beacons, is offered by CLS (Collecte et Localisation par Satellite) a CNES subsidiary in Toulouse, France, which also operates the ARGOS search and rescue system. It includes rent of equipment, installation help, personnel training, maintenance, processing and archiving, reporting. Location of the beacons of the permanent network is performed by several groups for scientific purposes : GRGS (Groupe de Recherche en G&eacute;od&eacute;sie Spatiale), IGN (Institut G&eacute;ographique National), University of Texas.<P>

Depending on the processing strategy of the data, several classes of accuracy can be achieved. The service offered by CLS achieves the performances quoted in fig. 1, with respect to the ITRF international reference, for absolute location. For relative location, performances are given in fig. 2 for 26 days of observation. This service has already been applied in geodesy to the determination of a point coordinates, e.g. for a 2 GHz satellite ground station or for airport equipment, for the tying in of a local geodetic network to a reference network, for the determination of a geodetic network itself. In geophysics, it has been or is being used for local tectonic monitoring, geodynamics applications, seismology, glaciology, vulcanology. It has also been used for landslide monitoring.<P>

<PRE><B>data gathering duration       Accuracy achieved</B>

        1 hour                      1  m 
        1 day                      30 cm
        5 days                     15 cm
       26 days                      5 cm

        Fig. 1 : Absolute location (CLS)



</PRE>
<P>
<P>
<PRE><B>     baseline                Accuracy achieved</B>

        10 km                        3 cm
     <1000 km                   3 to 5 cm
     >1000 km                  5 to 10 cm

        Fig. 2 : relative location (CLS)

</PRE>

Absolute location performed by scientific groups yields precision in the order of 5 cm for solutions with a 1 month repeatibility, and it goes down to 2 cm for solutions with all DORIS data (fig. 3 and 4) with respect to ITRF'92.<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH><TH>3-D RMS (cm)</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Case 1<TD ALIGN=CENTER>2.2</TR>
