Case 3 : Combination of 3 satellites<BR></EM><P>
fig. 4 : Comparison between the monthly DORIS solutions and the global DORIS solution for 45 beacons. (GRGS)</CENTER><P>
<P>
Based on the good stability of the location of the beacons of the DORIS permanent network, and on the fact that the latter covers the nine major lithospheric plates, velocity solutions enable to derive global plate motions. Fig. 5 shows the relative velocities of 331 interplate baselines based on three years of DORIS data on SPOT2, SPOT3 and TOPEX/POSEIDON for 28 beacons on 8 plates, as compared with the NUVEL1-A model predictions for global plate motions. The correlation of 0.975 is quite impressive.<P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/fig5_doris.gif"><P>
Fig. 5</A> : Relative velocities of 331 interplate baselines (mm / year). (GRGS)</CENTER><P>

 Fig. 6 gives the relative velocity between Fairbanks (Alaska) and Kokee Park (Hawaii) and between Easter Island and Huahine (French Polynesia) for DORIS data, VLBI estimates, ITRF'92 combinations and NUVEL1-A prediction, and shows again a good correlation. <P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH><TH>DORIS<TH>VLBI<TH>ITRF'92<TH>NUVEL-1</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Fairbanks-Kokee Park<TD ALIGN=CENTER>-5.3 &#177; 0.3<BR>(Soudarin, 1994)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>-4.6 &#177; 0.15<BR>(Ward, 1990)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>-4.82 &#177; 0.14<BR>(Boucher,1993)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>-4.9</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Easter Island-Huahine<TD ALIGN=CENTER>13.2 &#177; 0.8<BR>(Soudarin, 1994)<TD ALIGN=CENTER> <TD ALIGN=CENTER>14.63 &#177; 0.46<BR>(Boucher, 1993)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>15.7</TR>
</TABLE><P>
Fig. 6 : Comparisons of different relative velocities estimates (mm / year). (GRGS)</CENTER><P>

 Fig. 7 also shows good correlation between NUVEL1-A and DORIS data processing. <P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/plaques.gif"><P>
Fig. 7</A> : Tectonic plate velocities based on NUVEL-1 and DORIS data compared. (GRGS)</CENTER><P>

The DORIS system has been used also for polar motion determination. Fig. 8 shows the polar motion from 1990 to 1994, clusters of points representing the DORIS data. It can be seen that the correlation is very good and that it even increases with the availability of DORIS/TOPEX data in addition to DORIS/SPOT2 data from mid-1992, and again with DORIS/SPOT3 data from end 1993.<P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/dep_pole2.gif"><P>
Fig. 8</A> : Polar motions estimated from 1990 to 1994 and correlation with DORIS data. (GRGS)</CENTER><P>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><P>
<H2>MODELS</H2>
Due to the fact that processing of DORIS data calls for use of mathematical models for physical forces involved, such models as Earth gravity field model, geo&iuml;dmodel, ionosphere model and air drag models can be improved implicitly.<P>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><P>
<H2>SYSTEM EVOLUTIONS AND OTHER APPLICATIONS</H2>
The DORIS system will be used as a new technique in the international Earth Reference System (IERS). DORIS data, which is already processed by several groups around the world, will be even more abundant in the future since a DORIS receiver will be part of the European Space Agency (ESA) ENVISAT satellite payload complement, and since the data produced during that mission will be part of the ENVISAT science data base.<P>

Evolutions currently under development to make the present system and its performances even more attractive include : self programming of the on-board instrument, using the on-board calculated orbit data,in view of autonomous navigation ; self initialisation of the on-board orbit determination software ; improvement of on-board orbit determination accuracy, with a 1 meter objective ; processing two channels (and therefor two beacons) simultaneously in the on-board instrument, which would enable to have one channel dedicated to precise orbit determination and the other to precise location for example ; provision of datation on board of the carrier satellite with respect to UTC.<P>

Moreover, the DORIS results have justified the will to perpetuate the system and the service it provides, taking into account potential new applications with increased performance requirements such as : navigation for satellite cluster colocation, constellation management or GEO satellite control, autonomous satellite navigation and even control, satellite to satellite tracking, time transfer, ground clocks comparison, ground beacon position determination on-board of the satellite, attitude determination, ... This is leading CNES to study new developments with an objective of reduction of the DORIS on-board package in term of mass, volume, cost, by using MMIC and digital signal processing technology, with the possibility to add a spread spectrum ranging capability to the system.<P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
