<HEAD>
<TITLE>SCARAB Science</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></CENTER>
<H1>ScaRaB Science: Radiation Budget, Nebulosity, Climate</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2>Radiation Budget</H2>
It is the difference between :
<UL>
<LI> the part of the incident solar radiation (short waves) absorbed by the Earth and its atmosphere, which warms it,<BR>
<LI> the thermal infrared radiation (long waves) sent back in space, which cools it.
</UL>
The mean radiation budget (on a global scale and annual period) is very near 0. But on short time scale, it is a function of latitude.

<H2>Nebulosity</H2>
<IMG SRC="/images/img_scar1.gif"> <P>
<IMG SRC="/images/img_scar2.gif"> <P>
Variations with time and space of radiation budget are dipending on various factors but in peculiar of nebulosity. <P>
A cloud reflects locally the incident solar radiation and decreases the absorption. On the other hand, a cloud creates locally a greenhouse effect and decreases the thermal radiation re emitted back towards space.  <P>
Nebulosity is a critical parameter in modelizing climatic evolution.
<P>
<H2>Climate</H2>
<IMG SRC="/images/result4_scarab.gif"><P>
The radiation budget variations drive global circulation of atmosphere and ocean but at the same time, give evidence of this circulation, which is a key of climate evolution.<P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
