<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>&Oslash;RSTED Scientific objectives</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
image du satellite a inserer
<H1>&Oslash;RSTED Scientific objectives</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2>Background</H2>
 Scientifically, the objectives has been defined to answer the need to resume measurements of the earth's magnetic field more than a decade after the Magsat mission. A unique combination of Magnetometers and a compact star imager has simplified the collection of data, and the special boom design will minimize the intrinsic magnetic contamination from satellite.<P>
<H2>Primary Science Objectives</H2>
 The two primary science objectives are to measure the main magnetic field from the Earth, and to study its interaction with the Solar wind plasma.<P>
<A HREF="/images/chmpmag1.gif"><H2>Earth Magnetic Field</H2></A>
 The Earth's main magnetic field is determined by the Earth's own inner structure. The aim is therefore to :<BR>
<UL>
<LI> determine models of the main magnetic field and its secular variation
<LI> study physical properties of fluid core
<LI> study electrical conductivity of the mantle
<LI> investigate correlation between the geomagnetic field and variations in the length of day
<LI> study lithospheric structure and evolution.
</UL><P>
<A HREF="/images/chmpmag2.gif"><H2>Solar Wind/Magnetosphere Interaction</H2></A>
 The other main objective focuses on the interaction between the Solar wind plasma and the Earth's magnetosphere, entailing studies of :<BR>
<UL>
<LI> structure and variability of high-latitude fields and currents
<LI> relationships between field-aligned and ionospheric currents in the cleft and cusp
<LI> external magnetic fields as functions of local time, season, and solar wind conditions
<LI> ionospheric signatures of localized processes in the outer magnetosphere
<LI> substorm processes.
</UL><P>
<H2>Secondary Science Objectives</H2>
 In addition, the &Oslash;rsted mission has several secondary science objectives, namely to study <BR>
<UL>
<LI> ionospheric currents including the equatorial electrojet and the Sq current system
<LI> energetic particles, which includes research on the energetic particle environment and geomagnetic morphology, and a study on correlations between energetic particle precipitation and ionospheric absorption seen in ground-based imaging riometer observations.
</UL><P>

 Data on GPS satellite occultaion will also be provided which may subsequently be used to derive information on temperature and humidity profiles in the atmosphere.<P>
<H2>Orbit</H2>
 To optimize conditions to fulfil these various scientific objectives, an orbit has been chosen with the following characteristics :
<UL>
<LI> Elliptical Polar Orbit
<LI> Apogee at 850 km
<LI> Perigee at 400 km
<LI> Inclination at 96.1&#176;
<LI> Nodal drift at 0.77&#176;/day.
</UL><P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
