<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The &Oslash;RTED Space Segment</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></CENTER>
<A HREF="/images/schema1.gif"><H1>&Oslash;RSTED Space Segment</H1></A>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif">
<P>
<H2>Configuration</H2>
The &Oslash;rsted satellite is shaped as a box with a long boom carrying the magnetic instruments and the star imager, with solar panels on its five sides. It has a height of 68 cm, a width of 45 cm and a depth of 34 cm.<P>

Interface with the launch vehicle adapter is through a satellite separation mechanism mounted on the underside of the satellite body. Mounted above it are the lower platform, the vertical 'H' beam primary structure, a cable tray and an upper platform.<P>

<H2>Primary Structure</H2>
The main structural 'H' beam configuration forms two vertical compartments, one on each side of a centre web of the 'H' beam. Two rows of modular electronic boxes for the satellite and payload functions are mounted in one of these compartments. The other contains the boom assembly which during launch is packed in a caniser. All main structures are fabricated of aluminium.<P>

<A HREF="/images/bras_intr_oerst.gif"><H2>Boom Structure</H2></A>
The deployable boom consists of three coilable longerons, separated by radial spacers and tensioned by cross-wires. Redundant release mechanisms are provided, and deployment is controlled by a restraining lanyard. Total length is 8 meters, divided into two sections of 6 and 2 meters each.<P>

During launch the hingeless boom is coiled like a spiral. In orbit the boom deploys slowly (1m/min) with a screw-shaped motion.<P>

<H2>GPS receivers</H2>
The satellite position is determined by two GPS receivers with the following specifications :<P>
<UL>
<LI> The primary GPS receiver is a six channel TAN GPS from Trimble Navigation. It uses C/A mode on L1 frequencies, and gives an accuracy of position better than &#177; 50 m.
<LI> The secondary GPS receiver isTurboRogue receiver from JPL. It uses P-mode on L1 and L2 frequencies for GPS occultation measurements, but uses C/A mode on L1 frequency for position back-up.
<LI> Universal Time Coordinated accuracy is within 1 microsec, and velocity determination is within 0.5 m/sec.
</UL><P>

<H2>Power subsystem</H2>
The Power subsystem is compromised of the following elements :<P>
<UL>
<LI> A solar array, consisting of five solar panels. Each panel is composed of 2 x 4 cm GaAs solar cells with micro-sheet cover glass. The array delivers 54 watts average at End-of-Mission.
<LI> Two NiCd battery units, each with a 6 Amp/h capacity. A 15% depth of discharge is forseen during eclipse operations.
<LI> Two power control units are included with redundant battery charge regulators, central DC/DC converters, and load control/protection devices.
<LI> Available outputs : &#177; 5 V, &#177; 8V, &#177; 15 V and the unregulated power bus. Controlled disconnection of loads is included for the protection of the power subsystem itself.
</UL><P>

<H2>Communication</H2>
The communication system is redundant in order to ensure communication to and from the satellite with a very high reliability. Its characteristics are :<P>
<UL>
<LI> S-band communication (down link 2039.6 MHz, up link 2215 MHz) with two turnstile communication antennas mounted on the downwards side of the satellite.
<LI> Science data accumulation rates are approximately 1 kbit/sec in normal mode, and 6 kbits/sec in burst mode.
<LI> Telemetry down link is equipped with Reed-Solomon concatenated and convolutional encoding.
<LI> Telecommand up link includes Bose-Chaudhury - Hocquenghem encoding.
<LI> ESA packet standards PSS-04-106 (Telemetry) and PSS-04-107 (Telecommand) have been adopted for the &Oslash;rsted mission.
</UL><P>

<H2>Command and Data Handling</H2>
The Command and Data Handling (CDH) subsystem is responsible for all onboard data processing, performing<P>
<UL>
<LI> housekeeping data acquisition and processing
<LI> science data acquisition and storage
<LI> time management
<LI> data memory management
<LI> data compression
<LI> TM and TC format management
<LI> TC validation, distribution and execution
<LI> attitude control processing
</UL><P>

The CDH subsystem is compromised of two Central Processing Units each equipped with an Intel 80186, 16 MHz processor. It contains 16 Mbytes of RAM data storage which is sufficient for 13 hours of continuous operation. Data error detection and correction circuitry are included in the CDH.<P>

<H2>Attitude control</H2>
Attitude control is provided to perform detumbling after separation from the launch vehicle and to ensure stabilization during the operational phases of the mission. Attitude determination is based on inputs from the star imager, sun sensors, the CSC magnetomater and GPS receiver. Attitude control is performed in a way which creates minimum disturbances to magnetic field measurements.<P>

Stabilization of the satellite attitude is accomplished by passive and active techniques. The passive technique employs gravity-gradient stabilization using the deployed boom with a tipmass of 3.1 kg from the two magnetometers and the star imager. The active technique uses three-axis magnetorquer coils interacting with the Earth's magnetic field. The ACS maintains a yaw angle variation of &#177; 10&#176; to optimize the power output of the solar panels.<P>

<H2>Ground Equipment</H2>
Ground Support Equipment used for &Oslash;rsted has been designed whith the following key considerations :<P>
<UL>
<LI> The Core EGSE is build from a commercial product (EasyMAP)
<LI> Subsystem specific test equipment is to be integrated via standardized I/Fs
<LI> Adoption of ESA Space Standards
 <UL>
 - Packet TM/TC standards<BR>
 - Packet Utlization Standards (PUS)
 </UL>
</UL><P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
