<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The IASI Mission</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<PRE><IMG SRC="/icones/logo_iasi.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM>      <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE>
<H1>Introduction</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif">
<P>
IASI (Infrared Atmospheric Sounding Interferometer) is part of the core payload of EUMETSAT Polar System (EPS)<A HREF="/images/metop.gif"> METOP-1</A> and will contribute to the primary mission objective of EPS which is the assessment of meteorological parameters. The AMSU-A and MHS microwave sounding systems, the HIRS/3 infrared sounder and the AVHRR/3 imager are companion instruments of the meteorological payload. <A HREF="/images/sensor2.gif">IASI</A>, AMSU-A, MHS, HIRS/3 and AVHRR/3 will operate from a low altitude, sun-synchronous polar orbit, over a 2000 km wide swath.<P>

The main focus of IASI on the provision of temperature profiles with improved accuracy and vertical resolution compared to the currently existing infrared temperature sounder HIRS on NOAA polar satellites. To achieve this goal a high spectral resolution is required, and a novel instrument was designed based on a Michelson inetrferometer. It will cover the spectral range from 645 to 2760 cm&#175; &#185; with a spectral resolution (unapodised) between 0.25 and 0.5 cm&#175; &#185;. Beyond the technical challenge to realise this instrument the analysis of the IASI data is demanding, and it will be required to modify existing or develop new algorithms to retrieve all desired information from IASI data.<P>

Among the parameters that will be measured with IASI either in a stand-alone or in a synergistic mode with other EPS instruments are, in addition to profiles of the temperature, water vapour profiles, surface characteristics (temperature, emissivity,...), cloud parameters (top pressure and temperature, effective amount) and column integrated and vertical information of some minor constituents (<MATH>O<SUB>3</SUB>, CO, CH<SUB>4</SUB>, N<SUB>2</SUB>O, SO<SUB>2</SUB></MATH>).<P>

Although the objectives of the EPS mission are primarily aimed at fulfilling the needs of operational meteorology and climate monitoring, the system will also be able to support research oriented applications in the area of meteorology and global change. Through its capability to monitor trace gases EPS will be at the same time of value for studies in the field of atmospheric chemistry. <P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
