<HEAD>
<TITLE>The IASI Mission Objectives</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="objectives"></A>
<PRE><IMG SRC="/icones/logo_iasi.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM>      <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE>
<H1>Mission Objectives</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>Table of Contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Remote">Remote sounding with high spectral resolution instruments</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#mission">The IASI Mission : Operational and Research Objectives</A></B><P>
  <UL>
  <IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Introduction">Introduction</A></B><P>
  <IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Meteorology">Meteorology</A></B><P>
  <IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Climate">Climate Monitoring and Global Change</A></B><P>
    <UL>
    <IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Monitoring">Climate Monitoring</A></B><P>
    <IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Global">Global Change</A></B><P>
    </UL>
  <IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Chemistry">Atmospheric Chemistry</A></B><P>
  </UL>
<P>  
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Flight">Flight opportunity</A></B><P>
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif">
<P>
<A NAME="Remote"><H2>Remote sounding with high spectral resolution instruments</H2></A>

The infrared portion of the atmospheric spectrum can be divied into three broad regions :<BR>
<UL>
<LI> The near infrared (2,500 to 20,000 cm&#175; &#185;) is dominated by solar radiation scattered by the atmosphere and reflected at the Earth's surface.
<LI> The middle infrared (500 to 2,500 cm&#175; &#185;) is characterised by thermal emission of atmospheric molecules in the vibrational-rotational bands. This range has been extensively used for atmospheric sounding.
<LI> In the far infrared (50 to 500 cm&#175; &#185;) rotational lines are present in the thermal emission of atmospheric molecules and radicals. This region has not been exploited yet as extensively as the previous one by space-borne remote sounding systems.
</UL><P>

Line widths in vibrational-rotational bands vary by several orders of magnitude. The bands are typically 10 to 100 cm&#175; &#185; wide, consisting of several thousands of spectral lines, which have halfwidths from 0.1 cm&#175; &#185; near the surface (collision broadening) to 10&#175; &#179; or 10&#175;<SMALL><MATH><SUP>4</SUP></MATH></SMALL> cm&#175; &#185; (Doppler broadening) at the top of the atmosphere.<P>

The concept of using narrow channels in the 15 &#181;m (~670 cm&#175; &#185;) vibrational-rotational bands of <MATH>CO<SUB>2</SUB></MATH> was experimentally tested on-board the NIMBUS 3 spacecraft using the SIRS instrument. The first instrument designed to provide temperature profiles on an operational basis was VTPR launched on NOAA-2 in 1972.<P>

Technology achievements have now enabled observations of the surface and the atmosphere at a resolution of parts of cm&#175; &#185;. This higher spectral resolution is required to gain deeper insight into the physical and chemical behaviour of the atmosphere by measuring more parameters with higher accuracy and better vertical resolution. Studies have shown that a system based on high spectral resolution may provide, with respect to temperature profiles, a precision of 1 K and a vertical resolution ranging from 1 km near the surface to 3 km at the tropopause.<P>

The present space-borne systems are far from meeting the instrumental requirements to achieve these goals. The ATOVS sounder planned by NOAA for launch in 1996 will provide improved temperature and water vapour profiling. However, it will not advance significantly the vertical resolution in the troposphere, which will remain the major weakness of the present operational temperature and humidity sounders. The IASI instrument has been designed to fulfil the need for a high spectral resolution in order to achieve the mission requirements of EPS (see <A HREF="/iasi/Annexe1.html">Meteorological payload</A> for a description of IASI and companion instruments).<P>

Numerical weather prediction, climate studies and atmospheric chemistry will benefit from the new capabilities of such hight spectral resolution instruments. For the optimal use of data from infrared sounders complementary measurements in the microwave domain should be available.<P>

<A NAME="mission"><H2>The IASI Mission : Operational and Research Objectives</H2></A>

<A NAME="Introduction"><H3>Introduction</H3></A>

To date, a lot of experience has been gained with the operational meteorological satellites of the NOAA series (from TIROS-N to NOAA-12). NOAA has produced in real time global sounding of temperature and moisture profiles determined from TOVS radiances since the instruments became operational in January 1979. Besides this pioneer operational approach parallel research efforts have been devoted to improve the quality of the retrieved products and derive additional products from measurements.<P>

The weakness of the current TOVS vertical sounding for operational numerical weather prediction and climate research is now well recognised. The primary shortcomings are insufficient vertical resolution and limited precision, namely 2 K for temperature and 20 to 30 % for water vapour profiles.<P>

To meet the specifications issued by the World Meteorological Organisation (i.e. temperature with an average error of 1 K ; humidity with an average error of 10 % ; vertical resolution of 1 km, at least in lower troposphere), an improvement of the spectral resolution by typically one order of magnitude is need. IASI will be the first space-borne operational instrument which is expected to meet these requirements.<P>

The mission objectives assigned to IASI will primarily serve on an operational level the meteorological and climate monitoring communities. However, the nature of data provided from IASI allows also for more research orientated objectives in the fields of meteorology, global climate change and atmospheric chemistry. Many of the geophysical products which can potentially be derived from IASI will indeed be of common interest to both operational and research users. Tentatively the following products could be targets for retrievals from IASI either in a stand-alone or in a synergistic mode : <P>

<UL>
<LI> temperature profiles with an average accuracy of 1 K and 1 km vertical resolution,
<LI> humidity profiles with an average accuracy of 10% and a vertical resolution of about 2 km,
<LI> cloud parameters (cover, cloud top temperature, characterisation, total precipitable water),
<LI> ozone column amounts and profiles,
<LI> column amounts of CH<MATH><SUB>4</SUB></MATH>, CO, N<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>O and potentially CFCs, possibly in several layers,
<LI> sea surface temperature with an average accuracy better than 1&#176;C,
<LI> land surface temperature,
<LI> outgoing longwave radiation.
</UL> <P>

For a more complete list of products which could be derived from IASI we refer to Table A. <P>

Operational and research oriented IASI mission objectives which can be served by the assessment of these products are presented in the following in some more detail. A brief description of some relevant international programmes which will benefit from IASI is included in the discution. <P>

<A NAME="Meteorology"><H3>Meteorology</H3></A>

Operational meteorology covers a wide spectrum of activities related to predicting the way the atmosphere will change with time on regional and global scales. These activities are coordinated through the World Weather Watch (WWW) of the World Meteorological Organisation (WMO). While the needs of very short-range forecasting and nowcasting can be served by geostationary satellites, forecasting beyond 12 hours and up to 14 days relies on global input from polar orbiting satellites. Of paramount importance for NWP in this context are three dimensional fields of temperature, humidity and winds. <P>

As a result of the significant advances of operational NWP models (assimilation techniques, computing facilities) the current spaceborne sounding systems, despite their unique spatial and temporal sampling capabilities are now appearing as a limiting element of the forecast accuracy. Amajor improvement of satellite systems in terms of all weather prediction especially for the Northern Hemisphere where radiosonde networks over continental areas usually provide satisfactory data. Even over the oceans of the Northern Hemisphere, the accuracy of 6 hours forecasts using information from continental radiosondes which has propagated downstream is comparable to the accuracy of forecasts based on satellite data. <P>

The inversion and use of simultaneous co-located infrared and microwave sounding on METOP is deemed essential to exlpoit the capabilities of the system up to its limits, namely under cloudy conditions. Due to the high spectral resolution of the IASI instrument and the coupling with AMSU-A and MHS, temperature and humidity profiles of improved accuracy and vertical resolution can be provided which will significantly advance the potential of the current NWP. <P>

To make full use of the information that will be provided by IASI and companion instruments, significant evolution of the assimilation methods may be necessary. Examples are the influence of stratospheric wind information derived from ozone distributions and the direc use of raw (and cloudy) radiances. <P>

<A NAME="Climate"><H3>Climate Monitoring and Global Change</H3></A>

The requirement to monitor and understand the global changes of climate has been widely recognised in the last decade. Current satellite observations while having many desirable characteristics are by no means ideal for diagnosis of the climate system. An advance as the one offered by IASI and companion instruments on METOP is highly welcome because of the enhanced accuracy and increased number of parameters which can be retrieved. <P>

EPS will especially contribute to an improved understanding of the planetary boundary layer, the analysis of changes due to greenhouse gases, the investigation of climate processes such as the interaction between clouds and radiation and the validation of climate models. Global climate models, presently limited by their spatial resolution and by the parameterisation schemes used to represent complex physical processes, still meet difficulties in describing the full variability ofthe atmosphere. The evaluation of their strengths and shortcomings will clearly benefit from improved satellite observations. <P>

<A NAME="Monitoring"><H4>Climate Monitoring</H4></A>

While climate related activities have been more on a scientific level in the past the need for the transition to an operational scheme for global monitoring has been more and more recognised. WMO and UNEP (UN Environmental Program) took the initiative to reorganise the exchange between the scientific community and the policy makers through the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). The report by this panel highlighted the need for systematic observations of key climate related parameters which include the sources and sinks of greenhouse gases, clouds which influence the radiative transfer, oceans, land surfaces and the hydrology cycle. <P>

The programme GCOS (Global Change Observing System) was established to ensure that consistent and high quality data are systematically provied for climate studies and applications. Satellite data will be a fundamental component of this operational climate monitoring system, and the GCOS Space Plan is inteded to identify and prioritise the requirements for spacebased observations in the context of an operational climate monitoring system. An initial Observing System (IOS) is planned to be established by the year 2005.<P>

A rpovisional list of productshas been defined which will be needed as input for the IOS and follow-on systems. IASI, in combination with the other instruments on EPS, can contribute to the product requirements through its potential to yield temperature and humidity, monitor ozone and possibly aerosols, detect and analyse clouds, provide information about the surface temperature, surface emissivity and radiation budget. <P>

EPS will continue the long term monitoring of climate relevant parameters from NOAA/TIROS satellites whose observations are currently being reanalysed in the context of the PathFinder programme (organised by NOAA and NASA). It is aimed at the reprocessing the whole NOAA/TIROS observations since 1979 and started with a reprocessing of a two-year benchmark period. <P>

<A NAME="Global"><H4>Global Change</H4></A>

A number of research oriented programmes complementing GCOS have been initiated with the aim to improve our general understanding of global changes. Two of the major programmes are the World Climate Research Program (WCRP) and the International Geosphere-Biosphere Program (IGBP). <P>

The general objective of the WCRP is to determine to what extet climate and man's influence on climate can be predicted. Within WCRP four international core projects have been given the highest priorities, and contributions from IASI can be expected to two of them. The first is the Global Energy and Water Cycle Experiment (GEWEX). The aim of GEWEX is to further our understanding of the impact of greenhouse gases on global climate and the response of the hydrology cycle to climatic changes. The second project is Climate Variability and Predictability (CLIVAR) whose goal is the description, modelling and prediction of global climate variations on seasonal, inter-annual and mult-decadal time scales. There are a number of parallel programmes or sub-programmes which will also benefit from the global and long-term monitoring capabilities of satellite instruments such as IASI on EPS. <P>

In closecooperation to WRCP, the IGBP programme has the objective to describe and understand the physical, chemical and biological processes that regulate the total Earth system, the changes that are occuring in this system and the impact of man's activities. The sub-programme Global Change and Terrestrial Ecosystems (GCTE) is aimed at developing an understanding of the effects of climate changes, the atmospheris composition and land use on eco-systems and determining the feedback to the physical climate system. There are a number of other sub-programmes within GCTE which will rely on instruments like IASI for the provision of data which are relevant to climate issues. <P>

<A NAME="Chemistry"><H3>Atmospheric Chemistry</H3></A>

The study of atmospheric chemistry is a secondary mission objective for IASI and companion meteorological instruments. While activities related to meteorology are on an advanced operational level and climate monitoring is progressing in this direction, the study of the complex chemical processes in the atmosphere using satellite data is a research subject. <P>

Observations show that due to human activities, both industrial and agricultural, the chemical composition of the atmosphere is changing on all spatial scales. Of special importance from a global point of view are increased concentrations of trace gases with long atmospheric residence times which affect the climate and chemical equilibrium such as CH<MATH><SUB>4</SUB></MATH>, N<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>O and O<MATH><SUB>3</SUB></MATH> and chlorofluorocarbons (CFC). As there are still large uncertainties, especially regarding the temporal and spatial distribution of trace gases it is important to apply advanced space-borne techniques for monitoring on a global scale. <P>

IASI will enable the observation of CH<MATH><SUB>4</SUB></MATH>, O<MATH><SUB>3</SUB></MATH> and CO and possibly also of SO<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>, NO<MATH><SUB>x</SUB></MATH> and CFCs and can thus provide valuable information about some of the key trace gases which are involved in the chain of chemical reactions. Especially the importance of O<MATH><SUB>3</SUB></MATH> is to be stressed as a precursor of OH radicals which are strongly reactive with almost all gases emitted into the troposphere by natural or anthropogenic processes. IASI might ultimately contribute to the monitoring and analysis of events such as industrial pollution, biomass burning and stratospheric ozone depletion. <P>

Several international projects are dedicated to the advancement of our understanding of atmospheric chemistry. Especially the International Global Atmospheric Chemistry Project (IGAC) has to be mentioned which is a component of IGBP and has the aim to improve our insight into the processes the determine the chemical composition of the atmosphere and to understand the interactions between the chemical composition of the atmosphere and climate processes.<P>

<A NAME="Table1"></A>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH>Product<TH>IASI<TH>HIRS<TH>AMSU-A<BR>MHS<TH>AVHRR</TR>
