<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<PRE><IMG SRC="/icones/logo_iasi.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM>      <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"></PRE>
<H1>Constraints</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
<H2>Table of Contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#constraints">Operational and programatic constraints</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Availability">Availability of IASI data</A></B><P>
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<A NAME="constraints"><H2>Operational and programatic constraints</H2></A>

The global sounding and imaging mission has been recognised as having the highest priority for the EUMETSAT Polar System (EPS). IASI is a key for element of the meteorological sounding package, and it is forseen that IASI will, after successful demonstration, replace the HIRS infrared sounding instrument. Accordingly, IASI is the prototype instrument of a sries of advanced operational infrared sounders. <P>

The design, configuration and operation of IASI has to comply with the complete METOP-1 spacecraft and payload. This refers to mechanical, thermal and electrical interfaces, data rates and management, mass and power budgets and the operation of the instrument. <P>

Some of the IASI features are forseen to be adjusted to the accompanying meteorological payload. This refers to the simultaneous operation and identical coverage for all instruments and co-registration between the infrared (IASI, HIRS/3) and microwave (AMSU-A, MHS) units. Furthermore, co-registration of typically 1 km is required between the IASI sounder and the AVHRR/3 imager. The IASI scan pattern will be synchronised with those of MHS and AMSU-A. <P>

IASI will also be, to the extent feasible, compatible with the afternoon satellite to be developed within the US converged satellite system. This NPOESS satellite is expected to form together with its METOP/EPS counterpart the polar component of the next generation of meteorological space observing system. <P>

The currently difined target life time for IASI is four years (with a planned in-orbit commissioning and operation phase for METOP-1 of five years). The probability of IASI to be fully functional and operational without significant loss in performance after four years in orbit operation must be at least 0.8. During this time IASI should be available without interruptions 24 hours a day. All IASI expendables must be designed for a life-time of six years. <P>

The operation of IASI will include three distinct phases after the launch. The first is the commissioning and validation phase which is anticipated to last less than six months. The pre-operational assessment phase follows. It is forseen that this second phase covers up to 18 months. It will be succeeded by the third, operational phase for the rest of the life-time of METOP-1. <P>

Under nominal conditions starting with the pre-operational assessment phase the IASI system, composed of the IASI instrument and its ground segment, should allow permanent coverage of at least 95 % of the earth without any significant systematic gap in coverage. <P>

Over the Atlantic Ocean, Europe and the Mediterranean Sea the objective is to reach 99 % coverage. <P>

The operational processinf of IASI data on-ground has to comply with the requirement to provide the user community with sounding data not later than 135 minutes after reception. The software for this processing will be used in an operational environment by EUMETSAT and has to follow operational constraints and principles.

<A NAME="Availability"><H2>Availability of IASI data</H2></A>

During the commissioning and validation phase the performance of the instrument and the level 0 to 1 processing algorithms will be validated. With the start of the pre-operational assessment phase validated level 1 data will be processed and archived. At present, it is expected that IASI data will be distributed to operational users at level 1c (i.e., radiance spectra, obtained by Fourier Transform of the interferograms plus apodisation : see <A HREF="/iasi/Annexe1.html">Meteorological payload</A> for the definition of data levels). The pre-operational assessment phase is dedicated to the validation of level 2 products (temperature and humidity profiles, cloud parameters, trace gas amounts, etc.). <P>

Selected investigators will have access to IASI data necessary for their investigations. The provision of all data will be subject to operational constraints which will be inherent in the ground segment. As the ground segement is still in the planning stage the constraints cannot be completely specifiedat this time. <P>

