<A NAME="Chaine"><H3><A HREF="/images/funchain.gif">Functional Chain</A></H3></A>

<A NAME="Description"><H3><A HREF="/images/funcdes2.gif">Functional Description</A></H3></A>

<A NAME="Optical"><H3><A HREF="/images/optiq.gif">Optical Configuration</A></H3></A>

<A NAME="Spectral"><H3>Spectral Specifications</H3></A>

The <A HREF="/images/sensor2.gif">IASI instrument</A> covers the spectral range from the CH<MATH><SUB>4</SUB></MATH> absorption band at 3.62 &#181;m (2760 cm&#175; &#185;) to the CO<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH> absorption band at 15.5 &#181;m (645 cm&#175; &#185;). Within this range the following regions contain useful information : <P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>650<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>770<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>CO<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH> temperature sounding</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>770<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>980<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>surfaces and cloud properites</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>1000<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>1070<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>O<MATH><SUB>3</SUB></MATH> sounding</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>1080<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>1150<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>surfaces and cloud properites</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>1210<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>1650<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>watervapour sounding ; N<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>O and CH<MATH><SUB>4</SUB></MATH> column amounts</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>2100<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>2150<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>CO column amount</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>2150<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>2250<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>CO<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH> temperature sounding ; N<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>O column amount</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>2350<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>2420<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>CO<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH> temperature sounding</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>2420<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>2700<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>surfaces and cloud properites</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT>2700<TD ALIGN=CENTER> to <TD ALIGN=CENTER>2760<TD ALIGN=CENTER> cm&#175; &#185; : <TD ALIGN=LEFT>CH<MATH><SUB>4</SUB></MATH> column amount</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><P>

To optimise the performance of the IASI instrument the full spectral range has been subdivised into three spectral bands. The boundaries and spectral resolution for these bands are given in Table ! . IASI has a constant spectral sampling interval of 0.25 cm&#175; &#185;. <P>

Band 1 is mainly contributing to retrievals of temperature profiles and ozone, band 2 to retrievals of humidity and som trace gases and band 3 to retrievals of temperature and some trace gases. <P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH>Band<TH>Range (cm&#175; &#185;)<TH>range (&#181;m)<TH>apodised resolution<BR>(cm&#175; &#185;)</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>1<TD ALIGN=CENTER>645 to 1210<TD ALIGN=CENTER>15.5 to 8.26<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.5</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>2<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1210 to 2000<TD ALIGN=CENTER>8.26 to 5<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.5</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>3<TD ALIGN=CENTER>2000 to 2760<TD ALIGN=CENTER>5 to 3.62<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.5</TR>
</TABLE><P>
<STRONG>Table 1 : IASI Spectral Bands and Resolution</STRONG></CENTER><P>

<A NAME="Radiometric"><H3>Radiometric Specifications</H3></A>

For the spectral resolutions defined in Table 1 IASI shall measure equivalent temperatures between 2 (cold space) and 315 K. The quality of the measuerement is determined by the radiometric noise and radiometric calibration accuracy. <P>

Radiometric noise has been specified for IASI in terms of the noise equivalent temperature difference, NEDT, for a given reference temperature of 280 K. The NEDT requirements apply to pseudo-channels defined as average of individual samples (0.25 cm&#175; &#185;), having widths of 0.5 cm&#175; &#185; in band 1, 1.0 cm&#175; &#185; in band 2 and 1.5 cm&#175; &#185; in band 3. A requirement of &lt; 0.2 K has been established which will be met close to the channel boundaries and at the centers (TBC). This includes all noise contributions (detectors, amplifiers, A/D converters, processing) and all errors sources which do not result in a bias (e.g., errors due to field-of-view motion, fluctuations of wavelength calibration, knowledge of the spectral response function, fluctuations of the radiometric calibration). <P>

Table 2 indicates for the example of band 1 how the specifications for the noise have to be modified if two different reference temperatures, 250 K and 220 K , are chosen. <P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH>Wave number (cm&#175; &#185;)<TH>T = 280 K<TH>T = 250 K<TH>T = 220 K</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>650<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.2<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.243<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.320</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>750<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.2<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.257<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.363</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>850<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.2<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.272<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.414</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>950<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.2<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.288<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.473</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>1050<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.2<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.306<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.542</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>1150<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.2<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.325<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.622</TR>
</TABLE><P>
<STRONG>Table 2 : IASI Noise Requirements at Different Reference Temperatures</STRONG></CENTER><P>

The specifications for the on-board radiometric calibration are as follows :<P>
<UL>
<LI> The accuracy is &lt; 1 K in the range from 200 to 300 K (the goal is 0.5 K).
<LI> The stability is &lt; 0.3 K in the range from 200 to 300 K.
<LI> The relative accuracy between bands, different scan angles and different ground pixels for targets at the same equivalent temperature is &lt; 0.2 K.
</UL><P>

<A NAME="imager"><H3>The integrated imager</H3></A>

In order to improve the processing of partly cloudy pixels the IASI instrument will comprise a built-in imager to enable precise collocation between IASI and AVHRR and also some stand-alone mean for cloud analysis. The field-of-view of the imager will coincide with that of the IASI sounding unit (3.3333&#176; by 3.3333&#176;). The field-of-view will be covered by a raster of 64 by 64 imager pixels. <P>

The imager will have a single spectral channel ranging from 3.7 to 4.0 &#181;m. The radiometric performance is characterised by NEDT of less than 0.5 K at 280 K and calibration accuracy of better than 1 K at 280 K. The positionning error of imager pixels with respect to the pixels of the sounding unit will be less than 0.05&#176;. <P>

<A NAME="characteristics"><H3>Instrument field-of-view and scanning characteristics</H3></A>

IASI is <A HREF="/images/geom.gif">scanning</A> across track with a swath width of approximately &#177; 1100 km in a "step and dwell" mode. Over the scan width the scan mirror moves to 30 positions, one every 216 ms. During the dwell time of 150 ms for each pixel the movement of the satellite is compensated for by the mirror. The field-of-view corresponding to each pixel is 3.3333&#176; by 3.3333&#176;, which is about 48 by 48 km at the sub-satellite point. Within each pixel four sub-pixels, arranged in form of 2x2 matrix, are imagedonto four detectors of the IASI instrument. Each sub-pixel corresponds to a circular field-of-view of 0.84&#176;, which results in a sub-pixel diameter of 12 km at the sub-satellite point. The total scan period is 8 sec, including the 30 "step and dwells", calibration measurements and the retracing to the starting position. <P>

The IASI scan cycle of 8 sec is synchronised to the AMSU-A scan cycle. While IASI samples four sub-pixels in each 3.3333&#176; by 3.3333&#176; pixel, AMSU-A only performs one measurement of the full pixel. IASI is also synchronised with MHS in sense that three MHS scans are performed during one IASI scan. MHS samples with a circular field-of-view every 1.1&#176;, so that after three MHS scans in each basic IASI pixel (3.3333&#176; by 3.3333&#176;) nine MHS pixels have been sampled. The sampling and scanning characteristics of IASI and the companion instruments of the meteorological core payload are collated in Table 3. <P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH>Instrument<TH>IASI<BR>pixel<TH>IASI<BR>sub-pixel<TH>AMSU-A<TH>MHS<TH>AVHRR/3<TH>HIRS/3</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>scan type<TD ALIGN=CENTER>step and<BR>dwell<TD ALIGN=CENTER>step and<BR>dwell<TD ALIGN=CENTER>step and<BR>dwell<TD ALIGN=CENTER>continuous<TD ALIGN=CENTER>continuous<TD ALIGN=CENTER>step and<BR>dwell</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>scan rate<BR>(sec)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>8<TD ALIGN=CENTER>8<TD ALIGN=CENTER>8<TD ALIGN=CENTER>8/3=2.667<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.1667<TD ALIGN=CENTER>6.4</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>IFOV<BR>(degrees)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>3.3333<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.84<BR>(circular)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>3.3<BR>(circular)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1.1<BR>(circular)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.0745<BR>(square)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.69<BR>(circular)</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>sampling<BR>interval<BR>(msec)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>216<TD ALIGN=CENTER>216<TD ALIGN=CENTER>200<TD ALIGN=CENTER>19<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.025<TD ALIGN=CENTER>100</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>sampling<BR>interval<BR>(degrees)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>3.3333<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1.65<TD ALIGN=CENTER>3.3333<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1.1111<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.0541<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1.8</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>pixels/scan<TD ALIGN=CENTER>30<TD ALIGN=CENTER>120<TD ALIGN=CENTER>30<TD ALIGN=CENTER>90<TD ALIGN=CENTER>2048<TD ALIGN=CENTER>56</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>swath<BR>(&#177; degrees)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>48.33<TD ALIGN=CENTER>49.16<TD ALIGN=CENTER>48.33<TD ALIGN=CENTER>49.44<TD ALIGN=CENTER>55.37<TD ALIGN=CENTER>49.5</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>swath<BR>(&#177;km)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1026.31<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1064.07<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1026.31<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1077.68<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1446.58<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1080.35</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>IFOV size<BR>nadir (km)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>47.63<TD ALIGN=CENTER>12.0<TD ALIGN=CENTER>47.63<TD ALIGN=CENTER>15.88<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1.08<TD ALIGN=CENTER>10.0</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>IFOV size<BR>edge (km)<BR>across track<TD ALIGN=CENTER>146.89<TD ALIGN=CENTER>39.14<TD ALIGN=CENTER>146.89<TD ALIGN=CENTER>52.83<TD ALIGN=CENTER>6.15<TD ALIGN=CENTER>33.27</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>along track<TD ALIGN=CENTER>78.79<TD ALIGN=CENTER>20.31<TD ALIGN=CENTER>78.79<TD ALIGN=CENTER>27.10<TD ALIGN=CENTER>2.27<TD ALIGN=CENTER>17.03</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>scan<BR>separation<BR>(km)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>52.69<TD ALIGN=CENTER>23.81<TD ALIGN=CENTER>52.69<TD ALIGN=CENTER>17.56<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1.1<TD ALIGN=CENTER>42.15</TR>
</TABLE><P>
<STRONG>Table 3 : Field-of-View and Scanning Characteristics for IASI and Companion Instruments</STRONG></CENTER><P>

<A NAME="levels"><H3>Data and Product Levels</H3></A>

The following description of IASI data and product levels follows results of the IASI Phase A Study and should therefore only be considered as preliminary. <P>

<DL>
<DT> Level 0 :
<DD> Raw IASI telemetry data, including housekeeping, on-board calibration and verification data, after demultiplexing, time re-ordering, elimination of redundant information and addition of METOP-1 housekeeping data. <P>

<DT> Level 1a:
<DD> Unapodised radiance spectra and imager data with quality flags, obtained in the nominal operating mode ; corrected from geometrical and instrumental effects by an interim calibration procedure ; merged with time and geolocation information ; with all information needed for the further processing of IASI data, including flags, IASI and METOP-1 housekeeping data and the instrument transfer function ; level 1a data should be processed from level 0 without loss of information. <P>

<DT> Level 1b :
<DD> Unapodised, resampled radiance spectra and imager data corrected from all geometrical and instrumental effects based on the ultimate calibration procedure ; including quality flags, merged with time and geolocation information ; with all information needed for the furtherprocessing of IASI data, including flags, ISAI and METOP-1 housekeeping data and the instrument transfer function. <P>

<DT> Level 1c :
<DD> Level 1b data after apodisation ; expected real time input for NWP models. <P>

<DT> Level 2a :
<DD> Geophysical products derived from IASI in a self-standing mode (profiles of temperature, humidity, surface temperature, trace gas distribution, cloud parameters, etc.). <P>
Level 2a data may exist as interim geophysical products during the commissioning and pre-operational IASI mission phases and as geophysical products after upgrading of the processing software at the end of the pre-operational phase. Some of them might be merged into a more limited number of geophysical product records depending on the processing architecture and needs of users. <P>

<DT> Level 2b :
<DD> Geophysical products derived after co-processing of data from IASI and the companion meteorological instruments. These products may be similar to level 2a products but with higher accuracy, resolution and/or representative for a wider range of cloudiness. Or they are additional geophysical products which can only be derived in a synergistic mode. <P>

<DT> Level 3 :
<DD> Gridded and time-averaged geophysical products derived from level 2b products possibly in combination with information not obtained from EPS but from other sources.
</DL><P>

<A NAME="Companion"><H2>The companion : meteorological payload</H2></A>

The meteorological core payload comprises, in addition to IASI, the following instruments : <P>

<UL>
<LI> <STRONG>AMSU-A</STRONG> (Advanced Microwave Sounding Unit) : a microwave temperature sounder with 15 channels. AMSU-A is an upgrade of the MSU currently providing the microwave component of the TIROS Operational Sounder (TOVS). The prime role is to yield temperature sounding over completely oveercast conditions and to aid cloud detection for the companion infrared sounding instruments. The temperature sounding exploits the oxygen band at 50 GHz. <P>

<LI> <STRONG>MHS</STRONG> (Microwave Humidity Sounder) : a microwave humidity sounder with 5 channels. MHS is the upgrade of AMSU-B currently flying with AMSU-A on the NOAA spacecrafts. As MHS is sensitive to liquid water in clouds and graupel in precipitating clouds it can also provide a qualitative estimate of the precipitation rate. The calibration repeatability is 0.3 K. The inter-channel calibration accuracy is 0.5 K. <P>

<LI> <STRONG>AVHRR/3</STRONG> (advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer) : a multispectral imager with 6 channels in the visible and infrared. The focus is on cloud parameters (distribution, top height, emissivity, etc.), sea surface temperatures and ice, snow and vegetation cover. The instrumentis currently flying on the NOAA series of spacecraft. The absolute calibration accuracy is 2% in the visible and 1 K (at 273 K scene temperature) in the infrared, the in-orbit stability 2% in the visible and 0.2 K in the infrared, and the inter-channel accuracy 0.2 K. (Please note that channel 3a will presumably only be used during daytime, 3b only during nighttime.) <P>

<LI> <STRONG>HIRS</STRONG> (High Resolution Infrared Radiation Sounder) : a sounder with 19 channels in the infrared and 1 in the visible. HIRS will fly on NOAA K to N satellites and will as part, of the TOVS units, provide temperature and humidity profiles. The calibration repeatability is specified to be better than 0.3 K with an inter-channel accuracy of better than 0.2 K.
</UL> <P>

For a more detailed description of these instruments we refer to the appropriate technical documents. <P>

