<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>TOPEX/POSEIDON Follow On</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<H1>TOPEX/POSEIDON Follow On</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2> TPFO, MISSION OBJECTIVES </H2>

Given the difficulties to observe the ocean in situ, the satellites are part and parcel of any regional or global ocean observing system, for their unique capabilities to provide homogeneous quantitative measurements with appropriate sampling, coverage and availability. <P>

Radar altimetry from space is the only proven technique for observing ocean circulation and sea level on a global, quantitative and systematic basis. The accurate measurement of the shape of the sea surface is the only physical variable measurable from space that is directly and simply connected to the large scale movement of water and the total mass and volume of the ocean. <P>

Altimetry has also the unique advantage to give access to homogeneous long term series of co-located measurements of wind speed and significant wave height, in any region of the ocean. These parameters are derived from the analysis of the shape of the returned echo. <P>

<STRONG>Recall of the measurement techniques</STRONG> <P>

The ocean dynamic topography is obtained through two basic measurements, first the satellite altitude above the sea surface using the altimeter and then the radial distance from the satellite to the reference ellipsoide using precise orbit determination system. <P>

The altimeter uses radar pulses to measure precisely the distance from the satellite antenna to the ocean surface by measuring the time it takes for the emitting pulse to return to the spacecraft. <P>

Geophysical corrections are then applied to compensate for the measurements errors introduced by propagation through the troposphere, this is the aim of the radiometer, and by ionospheric electrons, directly obtained when using a two-frequency altimeter. Other corrections related to tides and pressure effects are also applied. <P>

The satellite precise  position is calculated using data coming from precise orbit determination system like <A HREF="doris/Mission.html">Doris</A> (Doppler Orbitography and Radiopositionning Integrated by Satellite) or laser system. <P>

<STRONG>TOPEX-POSEIDON continuity</STRONG> <P>

Since August 1992, The Topex/Poseidon system marked a new era in altimetry by providing on a permanent basis high quality data of the global ocean circulation signal and its variability. <P>

One major challenge of the space oceanography programmes of the next decade is therefore to transition from the successful programs of the nineties (ie ERS and <A HREF="topex/Mission.html">TOPEX/POSEIDON) to operational systems designed to ensure the continuity of a service with the best compromise in terms of performance and cost. This transition is justified by the stake and the sustainable demand from the research and operational communities, as stressed in the following. <P>

<EM>Research and climate monitoring</EM> <P>

Prototype systems for EL NINO early detection and prediction have already been developed, based on the combination of <A HREF="topex/Mission.html">TOPEX/POSEIDON</A> measurements, sub-surface observations arrays and numerical models. A number of models are now run in pre-operational mode in the tropical ocean but need to be extensively validated over long periods and for a representative set of distinct events. Moreover, just like numerical weather prediction models, these ocean models produce extrapolations from a realistic description of the initial state of the ocean, which will ever be determined in using observations like those provided by altimeter systems. <P>

Other interannual phenomena involving air-sea-ice interactions have been observed, like slow fluctuations in the northern Atlantic and Pacific oceans. These phenomena remain poorly understood due to the lack of adequate observations over long enough periods, but seem to be connected with significant climate variability over Europe. Altimeter measurements at centimetric accuracy are necessary to quantitatively describe the ocean processes involved. <P>

The secular variations of global mean sea level, currently estimated to 4.5 mm per year thanks to the Topex/Posidon measurements, may also have important societal impact in the long run, but are currently poorly sampled by few highly accurate tide gauges, whose measurements are difficult to reference to a common absolute terrestrial frame. As demonstarted by the analysis of TOPEX/POSEIDON data, altimetry can overcome these shortcomings and difficulties. <P>

The continuity of TOPEX/POSEIDON-class measurements is thus essential. It is in particular indispensable for applications which are out of reach of mesoscale-oriented missions like ERS or GEOSAT, namely : <P>

<UL>
- early detection and prediction of EL NINO anomalies which develop over a period over about 2 years and repeat in a variable configuration every two to six years, <P>

- quantitative studies of seasonal and interannual variability of the ocean circulation, including the fluctuations on scales of decades which have signatures of a few centimeters over thousands of kilometers, and their impact on climate, <P>

- analysis and monitoring of the slow and subtle variations of mean sea level of a few mm per year, in the context of additional greenhouse effect. <P>
</UL>

<EM>Ocean and meteorological applications</EM> <P>

The meteorological services produce sea state analyses and predictions used in real time in order to maintain the security of personnels and goods at sea, to assist navigation and operation of off-shore facilities or to perform ship routing. Such products are also elaborated and/or used by the public and private sectors to compute the wind/wave statistics necessary to design and size marine infrastructures in any region of the ocean. The altimetric measurements are already integrated into these services and used for marine predictions at regional or global scale, directly or after assimilation into sea state numerical prediction models, or for statistical and climatological applications. The long term continuity of data is also indispensable to the sustainable development of these applications. <P>

<STRONG>From demonstration to operational altimeter systems</STRONG> <P>

Transitioning from a demonstration programme to an operational service requires that technologies, mission concepts and applications are mature enough and that a long term need be expressed by a well-structured user community. Most of those conditions are now met, since the TOPEX/POSEIDON programme has demonstrated the validity and value of an optimum mission concept and qualified the advanced technologies needed to manufacture light-weight, compact, low consumption sensors with high performances and reliability. Meanwhile, the TOPEX/POSEIDON and ERS missions have met the challenge of quantitative space oceanography, stimulated the structuration of the user community, the development of methods and the demonstration of tools, models and know-how, which now serve as the basis for operational organizations to demonstrate the viability of a number of applications. As a result, the sustainable and consistent development of research and application is possible, including the implementation of an operational global ocean circulation monitoring system. <P>

<STRONG>TPFO AS THE FIRST ELEMENT OF A FRENCH SMALL SATELLITE PROGRAMME</STRONG> <P>

CNES started to initiate studies on a multi-mission platform dedicated to scientific or operational missions compatible with a small satellite in 1993. This program is now named " PROTEUS " (Plateforme Reconfigurable pour l'Observation, les Tlcommunications et les Usages Scientifiques) for reconfigurable platform for observation, telecommunications and scientific uses. The objectif of PROTEUS is to provide the necessary means to design and build satellites (excluding the payload sensors) with  low cost and short delays objectives and adapted to all types of low earth orbiting missions with a launch mass between 300 and 500 Kg. <P>

PROTEUS shall thus include the development of non recurring equipments, functional assemblies or platforms as well as the required methodology and tools to fulfill the cost and schedule requirements. <P>

In parallel, PROTEUS, leaning on industry, develop the satellite and integrate the sensors of the various missions. <P>

The phase A studies have been successfully completed in May 1995 and have demonstrated the technical feasability of this concept. <P>

TOPEX-POSEIDON FOLLOW ON is the baseline candidate for the first mission in this small satellite program. It was selected among a number of focussed, research-dedicated or operational missions, on the basis of scientific, technical and programmatic arguments described hereafter. <P>

The first basic justification is that a dedicated small satellite appears the definite right choice for altimetry. The space programmes of the last decade have amply demonstrated the superiority of dedicated altimetric satellites over complex multi-mission systems with altimetric capabilities. TOPEX/POSEIDON has been demonstrating since 1992 the invaluable capabilities of a fully optimized mission tailored to the needs of the World Ocean Circulation Experiment. Indeed, the choice of a dedicated non-synchronous, high altitude orbit proved essential to cut the error budget down to below 5 cm RMS and to reduce the geographically correlated orbit errors. Such performances are required to quantitatively assess the seasonal and interannual variability of the large scale ocean circulation, including EL NINO events and basin scale fluctuations, and to monitor the subtle variations of the global mean sea level in the context of additional greenhouse effect. <P>

The feasibility of compact, low power, light weight sensors like the French solid state KU band POSEIDON altimeter qualified on board TOPEX/POSEIDON, confirms that a TOPEX/POSEIDON-class mission can now be implemented at much lower cost by small satellites in the 400-600 kg range. This opens new perspectives for operational systems with recurring costs compatible with the resources of user organizations. <P>

From a more general standpoint, an altimetry mission was deemed technically representative of a large set of the small satellite missions which justify the PROTEUS program development, and the planned continuity of the TPFO series was found very attractive for the long term assessment of the small satellite " product line " and its evolution. In addition, the successful TOPEX/POSEIDON heritage makes TPFO a first class scientific programme with low technological risk at payload level, which is an ideal situation for assessing the product line. <P>

