<HEAD>
<TITLE>TOPEX/POSEIDON Follow On</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<H1>TOPEX/POSEIDON Follow On</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2> TPFO, FROM OBJECTIVES TO MISSION REQUIREMENTS</H2>

<STRONG>Error budget</STRONG> <P>

The fundamental objective of the TPFO mission is to ensure the continuity of TOPEX/POSEIDON measurements over two decades starting in 1999, with at least the same level of accuracy and the addition of a real time service tailored to the needs of the operational users. The performance requirements are therefore equal to the proven performances of T/P (see table hereafter) with a local absolute error budget on instantaneous (one-second average) sea level measurements below 5 cm RMS, the goal being to reach the centimeter level. <P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TH><TH>TPFO requirements<TH>TPFO anticipated
<TR><TH ROWSPAN=6>Altimeter<TD>Altimeter noise<TD>2.0<TD>1.7
<TR><TD>EM bias<TD>2.0<TD>2.0
<TR><TD>Skewness<TD>1.2<TD>1.0
<TR><TD>Ionosphere<TD>0.5<TD>0.5
<TR><TD>Dry troposphere<TD>0.7<TD>0.7
<TR><TD>Wet troposphere<TD>1.5<TD>1.1
<TR><TH>Total altimeter range<TD>3.5 cm<TD>3.1 cm
<TR><TH>Precision orbit (radial)<TD>3.5 cm<TD>2.2-2.9 cm
<TR><TH>Sea surface height (single pass)<TD>5.0 cm (RMS)<TD>3.9-4.3 cm
</TABLE><P>

Table 1 : TOPEX/POSEIDON flight proven performances // TPFO requirements </CENTER><P>

<STRONG>Orbit selection</STRONG> <P>

Repeating the TOPEX/POSEIDON orbit was deemed necessary by the Science Working Team in order to maintain the T/P performances. This choice is also essential to avoid any disruption or degradation in the use of the data, since it allows to use the T/P-dedicated gravity field for orbit determination, to cross-calibrate T/P and TPFO over the same sites, and to interpret the TPFO measurements without any delay, with explicit reference to TOPEX/POSEIDON altimetric mean profiles. <P>

The main characteristics of this non-synchronous orbit are: <P>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD>altitude :<TD>1336 km circular
<TR><TD>inclination<TD>66 degrees
<TR><TD>repeat cycle<TD>9.9 days (127 rev.)
<TR><TD>ground track repeatability<TD>&#177; 1 km crosstrack at the equator
</TABLE> <P>

<STRONG>Payload requirements and definition</STRONG> <P>

The TPFO sensor payload is composed of a compact, light weight, low power, solid-state dual frequency (Ku and C Band) altimeter derived from POSEIDON, a second generation miniaturized DORIS receiver, a three-channel microwave sounder and a laser reflector. A GPS receiver is also considered as an option. <P>

A dual frequency altimeter is necessary for correcting range measurements from ionospheric path delay. The comparison of altimeter signals at two frequencies yields an estimate of total electron content co-located with and simultaneous to the range measurements, which allows the ionospheric correction to be obtained directly from the altimeter data. Such corrections would be otherwise known from ionospheric models, but with insufficient accuracy, in particular in the equatorial regions under high solar activity. <P>

The three-frequency, nadir viewing microwave radiometer is also needed to measure the water vapour column with an accuracy compatible with the 1.1 cm error allocated to the "wet" tropospheric correction applied to the range measurements. <P>

The <A HREF="doris/Mission.html">DORIS</A> (Doppler Orbitography and Radiopositionning Integrated by Satellite) two-channel Doppler tracking system is compliant with the 3.5 cm allocated to the radial orbit error, as demonstrated on TOPEX/POSEIDON. Doris also allows the production of real time onboard ephemeris accurate to 5 meters. The DORIS POD service is based on measurements of Doppler shifts of radiofrequency signals transmitted to the spacecraft by ground beacons. The DORIS network includes about 50 beacons and its worldwide coverage and homogeneous distribution are optimized to produce homogeneous orbit quality and to minimize error correlations. A laser retroreflector array consisting of quartz corner cubes is also accommodated on TPFO for use as a calibration source for the orbit determination. <P>

<STRONG>Products definition</STRONG> <P>

As for TOPEX/POSEIDON, an Interim Geophysical Data Record (IGDR) will be available within 10 days for mesoscale and El Nino event studies, with an orbit in the 10 cm accuracy range. The final Geophysical Data Record (GDR), to be delivered within 30 days with an orbit precision of 3.5 cm or better, are dedicated to large scale ocean circulation and mean sea level studies. For TPFO, an additional Operational Science Data Record (OSDR), including wind, wave and topography information with an associated orbit precision of 5 m, will be made available within three hours for real time use/assimilation by operational services/users. Moreover, the feasibility of a real time data downlink to remote sites such as ships at sea is under investigation. <P>

<STRONG> FLIGHT SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS</STRONG> <P>

<STRONG>Orbit-driven requirements</STRONG> <P>

The TPFO ground-track pattern repeats every 9.9 days, with 127 orbits in each cycle and must be phased so as to overfly one calibration site. An on-board propulsion system is necessary to reach the operational orbit after injection by the launcher and to maintain it within +/- 1 km at the equator. The orbit being non-synchronous, has an inertial nodal rate of -2.06  per day. The orbit thus rotates two times in approximately one year in a westerly direction relative to inertial spacewhich means that the sun-orbit plane angle varies through three cycles per year, and the spacecraft must periodically operate over periods during which the sun is occulted at each orbit, up to 35 minutes per orbit. This is a driver of the design and sizing of the electrical power and solar array subsystems, and led in the case of TOPEX/POSEIDON to adopt a yaw steering mode in order to keep the solar array pointed towards the sun. A similar approach is envisaged for TPFO but with a view to simplifying the attitude control law as much as possible whilst keeping the level of available power sufficient. <P>

The TPFO orbit induced radiation environment has also been identified as a dimensionning constraints for the electronic components. The total cumulated dose after five years behind  a shielding equivalent to 1 g/cm2 of Aluminium has been estimated at 36 Krad. <P>

<STRONG>Pointing requirements</STRONG> <P>

The sensors pointing reference is the geodetic nadir defined as the perpendicular to the local goid, as opposed to geocentric pointing. The altimeter is pointed to nadir with an uncertainty budget below 0.30 (conical, 3 sigma), with 0.28 allocated to the satellite bus and 0.1 to the altimeter/radiometer antenna electrical boresight misalignment with respect to the mechanical reference. These relatively stringent pointing requirements are driven by the need to preserve the altimeter return signal (waveform) from antenna pattern disturbances and to keep the measurement accuracy within specifications. Special care should be taken to limit medium frequency (1 minute to 1 day) errors which would neither be filtered by the altimeter nor easily calibrated and removed  by ground processing. On the contrary, altimeter pointing calibration can be used to remove very low frequency components of the pointing errors such as misalignments and the attitude control system of the satellite shall allow these calibration maneuvers (periodically roll and pitch mispointing command of 0.3  amplitude). <P>

<STRONG>Precise Orbit Determination (POD) requirements</STRONG> <P>

In order to meet the 3.5 cm requirement, the level of pertubating accelerations must be minimized. Although the POD system can partially estimate unmodelled accelerations using DORIS measurements, the requirement implies some constraints onto the satellite design, in terms of knowledge on surface to mass ratio, on-orbit mass,, satellite projected surface and thermal model, relative motion of the satellite with respect to the DORIS phase center and residual acceleration level between manoeuvres. <P>

As one of the objective of the TPFO mission is to measure long term variation of the mean sea level of a few mm per year, special care should also be taken on the knowledge of the position of the satellite center of  mass location and its evolution along the mission time. <P>

<STRONG>Command control and ground interface requirements</STRONG> <P>

The only particular TPFO requirement is the three-hour latency imposed by the operational real time service. One acquisition per day is necessary, which drives the definition of the ground station network. <P>

