<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>TOPEX/POSEIDON Follow On</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<H1>TOPEX/POSEIDON Follow On</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2> TPFO, STATUS AND DESIGN REQUIREMENTS </H2>

The satellite bus design status presented hereafter is based on internal CNES studies and industrial Phase A studies performed by two industrial subcontractors, AEROSPATIALE and MATRA MARCONI SPACE. <P>

<STRONG> Satellite bus design status</STRONG> <P>

Its structure is monobloc with unique load path and its thermal control is software driven for single cavity using thermistances and heaters, the more sensitive equipments like the battery being installed on the Earth-looking face. <P>

The TPFO satellite design is based on the multi mission platform designed in the frame of the PROTEUS project. Its baseline solar array configuration is based on a satellite yaw manoeuvre, which provides sufficient power and a relatively stable thermal environment, whilst keeping low the complexity of the driving mechanics and attitude control law. The required solar array surface is around 7 m2 consisting in two three-panel wings using Si cells. <P>

The attitude control system is based on a classical gyro compassing technique using reaction wheels and magnetotorquers as actuators and magnetometers, sun and earth sensors and gyros as sensors. <P>

The propulsion system uses a reference hydrazine module with a spherical tanks of around 30 liters to allow final orbit acquisition and maintenance with a comfortable margin with respect to the foreseen operational lifetime. <P>

The data handling is centralized, built around a MA 31750 micro-processor and uses modular packaging (stacked cards) and a 1553 data bus for payload interfaces. The on-board storage requirement (4 orbits) of about 0.7 Gbits is met by existing solid state recorders. An all S-band configuration for science and housekeeping telemetry is the current baseline for telecommunications, for it reduces the spacecraft equipment mass and power at the expense of minor ground stations modifications. <P>

The current baseline launcher, the NASA Med-Lite (using a Taurus or a Delta-lite configuration), has a 2 m-diameter shroud, which leaves enough volume margin to accommodate a two-antenna configuration. <P>

 Although the contractors do not consider the 1336 km orbit as critical in terms of radiation environment, it will be necessary to carefully select the parts in order to reduce as much as possible the Single Event Upset probability, to select Latch up free parts and to perform evaluation tests on some parts/components and to use adequate shielding. <P>

As in Europe like in the US, components manufacturers are progressively closing their dedicated " space  " product line, due to the very small market amount associated, we are currently investigating the adequacy of Commercial space part or Plastic Encapsulated Microcircuit to our application. <P>

Recent studies tend to show that this type of components have now reached an equivalent and sometimes even better reliability level than usual space qualified parts because of the large effort which has been payed mainly in the computer and car industry. Moreover, the number of available parts type will increased by about 30% and the cost will be much lower, so the potential advantages for our small satellite, low cost approach is obvious. But this type of components also show a great variability in time and also from one manufacturer to another one, they are not well known by the usual space community and their adequacy to the TPFO radiation induced environment is also questionnable and needs to be assessed. <P>

In order to be in a position, by the end of 1995 for schedule compatibility, to decide whether this approach is adequate for TPFO or not, a set of actions are in progress. These actions aim at defining a procurement approach, building a preliminary preferred parts list from selected best commercial suppliers, evaluate the specific space related constraints and their impact on the commercial parts availability and selection and assessing the assembling technologies. <P>

The 0.9 reliability objective will probably require to implement some redundancy in order to minimize single point failures. Nevertheless, some functional redundant modes with degraded but still acceptable performances for the mission are foreseen (eg for attitude control). The current baseline for payload integration is to accommodate all the sensors inside an instrument module provided by the satellite bus contractor. <P>

The overall mass and power budgets are the following for the dual string, single antenna configuration : <P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TH><TH><TH>Mass<TH>Margin (included)
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Platform<TD>257 kg		
<TR><TH ROWSPAN=9 ALIGN=LEFT>Payload<TD><TD><TD ROWSPAN=9>153 kg
<TR><TD>Altimeter (dual string)<TD>50<TD>
<TR><TD>Altimeter antenna<TD>17<TD>
<TR><TD>Radiometer (internally redunded)<TD>18<TD>
<TR><TD>Radiometer antenna (deployable)<TD>10<TD>			
<TR><TD>DORIS (dual string)<TD>41<TD>			
<TR><TD>Laser retroreflector<TD>2<TD>			
<TR><TD>GPS (option)<TD>10<TD>			
<TR><TD>Real time downlink (option)<TD>5<TD>			
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Payload structure/mechanisms<TD>30 kg		
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Payload thermal<TD>6 kg		
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Dry mass<TD>446 kg
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Fuel<TD>15 kg
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Launch mass<TD>461 kg
</TABLE> <P>

<STRONG>TPFO mass budget (Dual antenna confguration)</STRONG> <P>

<TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TH><TH><TH>Power<TH>Margin (included)
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Platform<TD>187 W		
<TR><TH ROWSPAN=6 ALIGN=LEFT>Payload<TD><TD><TD ROWSPAN=6>146 W
<TR><TD>Altimeter<TD>62	<TD>	
<TR><TD>Radiometer<TD>18<TD>		
<TR><TD>DORIS<TD>24<TD>		
<TR><TD>GPS (option)<TD>18<TD>		
<TR><TD>Real time downlink (option)<TD>24<TD>		
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Payload thermal<TD>12 W		
<TR><TH COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=LEFT>Satellite basic power<TD>345 W
</TABLE> <P>

<STRONG>TPFO power budget</STRONG></CENTER> <P>

<STRONG> Payload design</STRONG> <P>

The estimated total <A HREF="/images/TPFOPAYLOAD.GIF">nominal payload</A> mass assuming a dual string configuration is around 140 kg with a power consumption of 105 W. <P>

<EM>DORIS</EM> <P>

The DORIS flight segment consists of a two-channel, two-frequency (401.25 MHz and 2036.25 MHz) Doppler receiver capable of tracking signals from a worldwide network of about 50 ground beacons. The TPFO DORIS receiver is the same second generation device as the one developed for the ESA ENVISAT mission at the exception of the data interfaces. Its main functional improvements over first generation receivers are its capability to receive two beacons simultaneouly and to produce on board in real time orbit ephemeris with a precision of 5 m. The receiver is controlled by an ultra stable oscillator delivering the reference frequency with a stability of 5 10-13 over 10 to 100 seconds and delivers an on-board real time UTC time output accurate to within 0.1 ms. Its mass and power consumption are reduced and it is equipped with a new, more powerful processing unit which is more tolerant to radiations and single event upsets. It is compatible with a 1553 data bus interface and configured with redunded USOs and receivers connected through a switching unit to a single omni-directionnal dual frequency antenna. <P>

<EM>Altimeter and radiometer</EM> <P>

The two-frequency solid state altimeter (SSALT), derived from the single frequency POSEIDON altimeter, is under phase B at ALCATEL and consists of two synchronized radar altimeters, operating at 13.575 GHz and 5.3 GHz respectively. The altimeter electronics is split into two boxes, the processing unit and the RF unit. The processing unit includes the digital chirp generator, baseband demodulator, spectrum analyzer, instrument control unit and interfaces. The RF unit performs the up-conversion to Ku and C bands, the high power solid state amplification, the low noise amplification of the received echoes and its mixing with a reference chirp. The peak output power of the two channels are 6 to 8 W in Ku band and 30 to 40 W in C band. The radars operate at pulse repetition frequencies of 1800 and 300 Hz respectively, corresponding to 6 Ku-band pulses for 1 C-band pulse. <P>

The major evolutions of the altimeter with respect to Poseidon are : <P>
<UL>
	-Addition of the second frequency (C Band) to obtain direct ionospheric correction. Using models, the ionospheric correction induces errors which are not compatible with the TPFO error budget mainly during the high intensity period of the solar cycle. <P>

	-The digital chirp generator to allow a selectable bandwidth necessary for the C band channel and a better phase knowledge. <P>

	-Increase of the emitting power to keep an acceptable link budget (the size of the antenna has been decreased wrt Topex/Poseidon). <P>

	-A 128 points FFT transform to obtain a better mispointing evaluation and then reduce the pointing requirements. <P>

	-Use of a rad hard microprocessor to provide a better radiation tolerance and thus increase the operational availability of the sensor. This microprocessor will also be more powerful to increase the on-board processing capability of the altimeter. <P>
</UL>

The phase B study, which will end in March 1996 includes some pre-developments. The housekeeping telemetry is also extended to improve the sensor monitoring capability and the instrument control unit is modified for compatibility with the 1553 data bus. This impacts primarily on the processing unit, the RF unit which includes almost all analog hardware being only modified by the addition of the C-band channel. The preliminary reliability estimations show that a dual string (without cross-coupling) altimeter will probably be the optimum approach for meeting the 0.9 payload reliability objective. Both channels will be connected to a single dual frequency antenna through a switching unit. <P>

The radiometer consists of three separate channels at 18, 23.8 and 34 GHz and is based on MMIC technologies, leading to reduced weight and power consumption. This design does not need for a cold horn for the calibration, which is performed using a noise diode. The electronics of the 23.8 GHz channel is fully redunded. <P>

Both sensors will use a dedicated antenna (deployable for the radiometer) but a common antenna with a multi- frequency feed system is still considered as an option. <P>

<STRONG>Flight / Ground interfaces</STRONG> <P>

A time multiplexing approach is adopted for simultaneous downlink of housekeeping and scientific telemetry, using the aforementioned all S-band configuration. The baseline ground network includes the NOAA Fairbanks and Wallops stations and a third station located in Europe. The latter is needed to acquire the blind orbits in line with the real time service requirement. The baseline is to use a dedicated, low-cost ground station to be developed by CNES in the frame of  the PROTEUS program. The antenna has a two-meter diameter, which requires an increased in on-board transmitter power (5 W), the use of convolutional coding to achieve an acceptable data link budget and QPSK modulation to cope with power flux density modulation. <P>

The telemetry system is based on a packetized approach which allows to differentiate engineering telemetry from scientific one. Each packet includes an header identifying the associated type of informations (including time tagging) which allow to process the packet without any external informations. <P>

The packet TM approach allows to use several virtual channels supported by the same physical link. One channel will be allocated to the real time telemetry, a second one to the play back engineering telemetry, a minimum of two channels will be allocated to the payload scientific telemetry. For TPFO, the first one will be dedicated to the fast delivery data and includes the Doris real time ephemeris, the radiometer data and the altimeter  on board estimated parameters. The second one will include tha altimeter raw data , the Doris and radiometer data and wiil be used to generate the IGDR and GDR products. <P>

<STRONG>CONCLUSION</STRONG> <P>

The TPFO program aims at ensuring the continuity of TOPEX/POSEIDON measurements over twenty years from 1999 onwards, with the same accuracy, using a series of low-cost, high performance small satellites operating on the same non-synchronous orbit. This initiative is part and parcel of an attempt to extend the World Weather Watch in the framework of the GOOS, recommended by the Second World Climate Conference and the Rio UNCED conference. It is justified by the maturity of the mission concept, advanced sensor technologies and the user communities and by a sustainable demand in the fields of research, monitoring and applications in the open sea and coastal zone. <P>

The results available from the satellite phase A study and sensor phase B studies confirms that the approach is technically feasible within the programmatic, cost and schedule constraints. Particular attention is being paid to the recurring cost, since it determines the affordability of the transfer of the programme to user organizations, which is considered as a medium term goal. <P>

Figure 1 :  <A HREF="/images/TPFOPAYLOAD.GIF">TPFO payload module configuration</A> <P>

