<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The STRATEOLE Mission Objectives</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/cnes.gif"></CENTER>
<H1>STRAT&Eacute;OLE Mission Objectives</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
Solving the main scientific problems in stratospheric dynamics and ozone chemistry requires not only ozone, water vapour and other trace gases observations but also accurate measurements of wind and temperature with high resolution sampling, as well as the capacity to detect polar stratospheric clouds. At present, only instrumented drifting balloons are capable of provinding the required accurate measurements with the appropriate sampling of diurnal variations - not accessible from heliosynchronous satellites. These observations, combined with present meteorological analyses and trace constituent soundings obtained from satellites, would lead to significant improvement in our understanding of the basic processes which couple dynamics with photochemistry. The trajectography of a sufficient number of constant level drifting balloons equipped with currently available precise positioning devices can give an accurate description of the velocity field at their drifting level, resolving horizontal scales as small as 600 km every 15 minutes. The optimum number of balloons and their lifetime must be determined in order to secure the horizontal coverage needed to document the filamentation or injection of small isolated coherent vortices from the main vortex and give valuable information on the mixing properties of air masses. Simultaneous measurements of chemical species, temperature and wind on board the same gondola is particularly interesting for documentating the complex chemical processes involved in ozone depletion and their coupling with dynamics. Finally, simultaneous radiation measurements and in situ observations of dynamical variables will allow to document the vortex evolution.<P>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>STRAT&Eacute;OLE : The Scientific Objectives </H2>
The scientific objectives are the study of :<BR>
<UL>
<LI> the structure and evolution of the antarctic polar vortex,
<LI> the diffusion and mixing properties of the vortex,
<LI> the evolution of the ozone deficit and its dilution after the vortex breakdown,
<LI> the permeability of the vortex edge to chemical constituent fluxes,
<LI> the impact of gravity waves and turbulence on the mixing properties of the vortex.
</UL>

<P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>Complementary Measurements</H2>
Complementary measurements of wind and chemical species at different time and space scale from ground-based, aircraft and space borne instruments are planned or will be available during STRAT&Eacute;OLE.<BR>
The ENVISAT mission of the European Space Agency, includes among other sensors three profiling instruments (SCIAMACHY, MIPAS, GOMOS) devoted to the observation of minor constituents, as well as temperature and aerosols. STRAT&Eacute;OLE will bring the detailed dynamical information necessary fir explaining the large scale transport and distribution of these aerosols and minor constituents. Hence the synergy between these two programmes appears to be a unique opportunity for the research community.<BR>
The use of airborne facilities developed by different countries, instrumented Infrared Montgolfi&egrave;res, ground-bases instruments, radiosondes and ozone sondes at stations existing on the Antarctic continent will also provide complementary measurements documenting to stratospheric chemistry, vortex permeability and turbulence.<BR>
International cooperations will be sought to organize such intensive observing campaing during the STRAT&Eacute;OLE experiment.<P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
