Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 5529
Last-Modified: Thursday, 28-Nov-96 16:17:13 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The STRATEOLE Mission Description</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/cnes.gif"></CENTER>
<H1>STRAT&Eacute;OLE Mission Description</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
<H2>The Observing System</H2>
The main element of the STRAT&Eacute;OLE observing system is a set of approximately 200 balloons drifting at two different constant density level (about 50 and 70 hPa), equipped with instrumented gondolas weighting about 10 kg.<P>

<STRONG>The gondolas</STRONG> are designed by LMD (CNRS); their structure consists in a 70 cm long and 40 cm diameter polystyrene tubes which allows thermal conditioning of the different elements. Three solar panels are set vertically around the central tube.<BR>
The basic payload includes :<BR>
<UL>
<LI> temperature and pressure sensors,
<LI> precise positioning GPS receivers,
<LI> an ARGOS beacon for data collection.
</UL><BR>
The total mass of tha basic payload is 5.5 kg. In addition, some gondolas will host supplementary sensors :<BR>
<UL>
<LI> TDDR (TOTAL DIRECT DIFFUSE RADIOMETER) to measure O<MATH><SUB>3</SUB></MATH> and N<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>O column amounts and aerosols,
<LI> IRBBR (INFRARED BROAD BAND RADIOMETER) to measure upwelling IR fluxes.
</UL>
these two instruments are developed by the NASA-AMES RESEARCH CENTER,<BR>
<UL>
<LI> a light weight, near infrared diode laser spectrometer to measure CH<MATH><SUB>4</SUB></MATH> and H<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>O mixing ratio, developed under the responsibility of the LPMA (CNRS-UNIV. OF PARIS 6).
</UL><BR>
The energy is supplied by Cd-Ni batteries, heated and reloaded by the solar panels. The energy budget of the gondola is determined by the duration of the solar day : at its minimum (15 of August at 65&#176; latitude south), the daily energy available is 40 Wh and the internal temperature is between -40 and +20&#176;. After this date, each additional solar hour gives an added energy of 20 Wh. The onboard processing is performed using an electronic device which controls also the interface with the ARGOS system and the GPS receiver. The data are transmitted to ground using the ARGOS system.<P>


<STRONG>The balloons</STRONG> developed by CNES are small overpressurized balloons, with a closed "no-leak" envelope, able to carry a payload of about 10 kg, with an expected life time of three months.<BR>
Before launch, the balloon is inflated with an amount of helium which is a function of the targetted flight altitude and gondola mass. When the balloon reaches flight level, the envelope must be overpressurized to prevent deformation in order to keep a constant volume (in particular at sunset, when the balloon cools down) and hence a constant density level. The balloon is spherical in order to better resist to pressure. It is made with bilaminated polyester material with a final thickness of 50 microns. The life time of these balloons is mainly limited by their pearmeability to hellium. This point requires careful tests and verifications at all stages from manufacturing to launching.<P>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>SUMMARY</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Number of Balloons</STRONG><BR>
Balloon trajectory simulations have shown that balloons should spread in the 50-70&#176; latitude band. In order to secure a description of velocity field with horizontal scales of the order of 600 km, it is necessary to have 100 evenly distributed balloons drifting simultaneously at each level. This means that at least 200 balloons must be launched.<P>
<STRONG>Launch Frequency</STRONG><BR>
Mixing properties of air masses will tend to homogenize the <A HREF="/images/strateo3.gif">distribution</A> of balloons after a sufficient period of time. Consequently, a ramdom launch strategy is acceptable with a launch rate from 1 up to 3 balloons per day. The objective is to have most of the balloons well inside or very near the vortex edge.<P>
<STRONG>Dates</STRONG><BR>
The balloons devoted to measurement of chemical species will be launched well inside the vortex around August 15. Those devoted to the study of the vortex in winter time and during the spring breakdown will be launched later, after September 1st, close to the vortex edge.<P>
<STRONG>Constraints</STRONG><BR>
The balloon envelope is fragile and conditions for a safe launch require that winds at ground level be no more than 2 m/s. This is a very stringent condition on the Antarctic continent. Thus, meteorology will play a central role in launching operations.<P>
<STRONG>Launch Sites</STRONG><BR>
This finding and its constraints have guided the Scientific Steering Committee and CNES in their optimum choice of appropriate balloon launch stations. At least three launch stations are necessary in order to secure launchings at the edge and well inside of the vortex. Today, the nomianl scenario considered by CNES is to use <A HREF="/images/site1_strateole.gif">Marambio</A> and <A HREF="/images/site2_strateole.gif">Ushuaia</A> (Argentina) as the main stations and <A HREF="/images/site3_strateole.gif">McMurdo</A> (USA) as the secondary station. <P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
