<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The ADEOS Mission Description</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<IMG SRC="/images/adeos.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"><H1>The ADEOS Description</H1></A>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2> Table of contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <A HREF="#satellite">The ADEOS satellite</A><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <A HREF="#payload">The ADEOS payload</A>
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
<H2><A NAME ="satellite">The ADEOS satellite</A></H2>
ADEOS is a 3.5 ton polar orbiting satellite following on from earlier Japanese satellites such as MOS-1, MOS-1b and JERS-1. It is scheduled for launch mid-1996 from Tanegashima, Japan, by the new H2 launcher developed by NASDA. The design life time of the mission is three years with expendables available for another two years of on-orbit operations. <P>

ADEOS will be flying at an altitude of 797 km on a sun-synchronous orbit with an inclination of 98&#176;, an exact repeat period of 41 days and a quasi-subcycle of 4 days. In addition to <A HREF="/polder/Mission.html">POLDER</A>, it will carry advanced optical sensors (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/avnir_e.html">AVNIR</A> and <A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/octs_e.html">OCTS</A>) developed by NASDA and other sensors provided by the National Administration for Space and Aeronautics, NASA, of the USA (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/toms_e.html">TOMS</A> and <A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/nscat_e.html">NSCAT</A>), the Ministry for International Trade and Industry, MITI, of Japan (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/img_e.html">IMG</A>) and the Japanese Environment Agency, JEA (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/ris_e.html">RIS</A> and <A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/ilas_e.html">ILAS</A>). <P>

Observations from these sensors will be recorded on board ADEOS by three Mission Data Recorders (MDR) and two Low speed Mission Data Recorders (LMDR) and dumped at high speed to ground stations such as the Hatoyama Earth Observation Centre (EOC). EOC, in interaction with the NASDA Tracking and Control Centre (TACC) will generate operation plans for the instruments, mission data recorders and ground stations. These plans are based on requests from sensor-providing organizations, end-users and foreign ground stations. <P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2><A NAME="payload">The ADEOS Payload</A></H2>
The ADEOS Platform will carry :
<UL>
<LI> the Ocean Colour and Thermal Scanner (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/octs_e.html">OCTS</A>) for observing ocean colour and sea surface temperature,
<BR><LI> the Advanced Visible and Near Infrared Radiometer (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/avnir_e.html">AVNIR</A>), a visible/near infrared, high-resolution, narrow-swath, multispectral imager,
<BR><LI> the NASA Scatterometer (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/nscat_e.html">NSCAT</A>) for observing wind vector patterns at the air-sea interface,
<BR><LI> the Total Ozone Mapping Spectrometer (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/toms_e.html">TOMS</A>) for mapping atmospheric total ozone,
<BR><LI> the Interferometric Monitor for greenhouse Gases (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/img_e.html">IMG</A>), a nadir viewing Fourier Transform Spectrometer for sounding temperature, moisture and some greenhouse/trace gases in the thermal infrared,
<BR><LI> the Improved Limb Atmospheric Spectrometer (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/ilas_e.html">ILAS</A>) a limb-viewing visible/infrared spectrometer operating in solar occultation mode for sounding stratospheric ozone and other species over high latitude areas,
<BR><LI> the Retroreflector In Space (<A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/sendata/ris_e.html">RIS</A>) for atmospheric absorption and trace gases studies,
<BR><LI> the POLarization and Directionality of Earth Reflectances (<A HREF="/polder/Mission.html">POLDER</A>), a multispectral imaging radiometer/polarimeter designed to collect global and repetitive observations of the solar radiation.
</UL><P>
<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

