<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The POLDER Instrument</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<IMG SRC="/images/instrument_Polder3.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<BR><BR><H1>The POLDER Instrument</H1><BR><BR><BR>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<STRONG><EM>Main Features</EM></STRONG><P>

<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <A HREF="#Multidirectionality">Multidirectionality</A> <P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <A HREF="#Multispectral">Multispectral and Polarized</A> <P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <A HREF="#Performances">Performances</A> <P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"> <A HREF="#Technical">Technical Features</A> <P>
</UL><P>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<IMG SRC="/images/optique.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><BR><BR><BR>
<STRONG>The POLDER instrument is a camera composed of a two-dimensional CCD
detector array, wide field of view telecentric optics and a rotating wheel
carrying spectral and polarized filters.</STRONG> <P><BR><BR>

<A NAME="Multidirectionality"><H2>Multidirectionality :</H2> <P>
<IMG SRC="/images/afrique1.gif" ALIGN=LEFT> 
An image sequence is taken every 20 s. Meanwhile, the satellite moves about 140 km. Any target on Earth therefore stays in POLDER's field of view for several successive imaging sequences (up to 14 for a single satellite pass). From one day to the next, the satellite's ground track shifts the target is therefore viewed under various geometric conditions. After four days, due to the <A HREF="http://">ADEOS</A> subcycle, the situation is similar to that on the first day. In this way that POLDER samples the bidirectional reflectance function of the targets. <P>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/cible.gif"><TD><EM>Representation in polar coordinates (zenith viewing angle, azimuth viewing angle, in degrees) of the successive viewing geometries for a target at latitude 40N, observed between March 19th and 23rd (days are numbered from 1 to 5). (LMCE simulation)</EM>
</TABLE> <P>

<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD><A HREF="/images/imgsnb.gif"> <IMG SRC="/images/icone_Ref_Cr90.gif"></A><TD>Image sequence taken with the airborne POLDER instrument over the La Crau site. The instrument's field of view is such that the same target (here shifting from left to right) is observed from different angles. Surface patterns can be recognized on the reflectance measurements (left). And the same sequence seen by POLDER through a polarization filter (right).<TD><A HREF="/images/imgspola.gif"><IMG SRC="/images/icone_RefPol_Cr90.gif"></A>
</TABLE></CENTER> <P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to the top </A><P>

<A NAME="Multispectral"><H2>Multispectral and Polarized :</H2> <P>

The observation of the same scene in polarized and natural light provides two quite different series of images (see above). On the polarized images, surface details can no longer be recognized and an atmospheric signal, almost independent of the underlying surface, appears. The isolines of the polarized radiance form kind of ellipses which match the isocontours of the scattering angle, thus confirming that the polarized signal results from atmospheric scattering. <P>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/roue1.gif"><TD><EM>POLDER has 9 spectral bands, 3 of which (443, 670 and 865 nm) are associated with polarized filters (P1, P2 and P3). 3 bands are dedicated to the observation of ocean color (443, 490, 565 nm). Apart from the 763 and 910 nm bands, chosen to estimate absorption by oxygen and water vapor, POLDER's non-polarized channels were designed to allow direct comparison with OCTS observations. </EM></TABLE><P>
<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to the top </A><P>

<A NAME="Performances"><H2>Performances :</H2> <P>

Radiometric performance is expressed in term of signal to noise ratio for a reflectance of 0.1 assuming the sun is at the zenith. <P>

  <UL>
  <LI> <STRONG>Geometrical :</STRONG> <BR>
With a field of view of &#177; 43 along track and &#177; 51 cross track, POLDER  as a 2400 km swath which allows a daily coverage of almost the whole Earth. <P>

The instrument resolution is 6 km x 7 km at nadir, increasing at higher incidence angles due to the Earth's curvature. A pixel size of 6 km x 6 km is obtained after resampling on the geocoded POLDER grid. <P>

<TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><STRONG>REGISTRATION PERFORMANCE</STRONG>
<TR><TD>0.1 of a pixel for the 3 polarized components in the same spectral band.
<TR><TD>0.1 of a pixel for different spectral bands in the same sequence.
<TR><TD>0.2 of a pixels for multidirectional registration.
<TR><TD>0.4 pixels for multitemporal registration.
<TR><TD>1 pixel for absolute registration. 
</TABLE> <P>

  <LI> <STRONG>Radiometrical :</STRONG> <BR>
In order to optimize the radiometric quality of measurements, two exposure times may be programmed: the short exposure time for high-reflectance targets (High Dynamic Mode) and the long one for low-reflectance targets (Low Dynamic Mode). <P>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TH><TH>Mode<TH>443P<TH>443NP<TH>490<TH>565<TH>670P<TH>763<TH>765<TH>865P<TH>910
<TR><TH>Bandwidth (nm)<TD><TD>20<TD>20<TD>20<TD>20<TD>20<TD>10<TD>40<TD>40<TD>20
<TR><TH ROWSPAN=2>Reflectance<BR>range<TD>high<BR>dynamic<TD>0.05 - 1.1<TD>NA<TD>NA<TD>NA<TD>0.1 - 1.1<TD>0.07 - 1.1<TD>0.07 - 1.1<TD>0.07 - 1.1<TD>0.1 - 1.1
<TR><TD>low<BR>dynamic<TD>NA<TD>0.05 - 0.22<TD>0.034 - 0.17<TD>0.019 - 0.11<TD>0.013 - 0.25<TD>0.008 - 0.25<TD>0.008 - 0.25<TD>0.008 - 0.25<TD>0.007 - 0.25
<TR><TH ROWSPAN=2>Signal to<BR>noise ratio<TD>high<BR>dynamic<TD>189<TD>NA<TD>NA<TD>NA<TD>196<TD>149<TD>196<TD>196<TD>188
<TR><TD>low<BR>dynamic<TD>NA<TD>400<TD>500<TD>714<TD>500<TD>385<TD>476<TD>476<TD>357
</TABLE>
</CENTER> <P>

NA: Not Applicable <P>

  <LI> <STRONG>Calibration Performance</STRONG> <BR>
2 to 3 % for absolute calibration (Rayleigh scattering).<BR>
1 % for interband calibration (in glitter conditions).<BR>
1 % for low frequency interpixel calibration (over deserts and in glitter conditions).<BR>
0.1% for high frequency interpixel calibration (over spatially homogeneous cloud cover).<BR>
the polarization ratio is calibrated over targets, applying both high and low polarization, with an expected accuracy of 1 %. <P>

  </UL>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/prepasat.gif"><TD><EM> Final preparations on the POLDER instrument before its integration on <A HREF="http://hdsn.eoc.nasda.go.jp/guide/guide/satellite/satdata/adeos_e.html">ADEOS</A>. </EM></TABLE><P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to the top </A><P>

<A NAME="Tecnical"><H2>Technical Features :</H2> <P>

<TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TD ROWSPAN=10><IMG SRC="/images/instrument_Polder2.gif"><TD>MASS<TD ALIGN=CENTER>32 kg
<TR><TD>VOLUME<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.8 x 0.5 x 0.25 m&#179;
<TR><TD>POWER CONSUMPTION<TD ALIGN=CENTER>50 W (IMAGE MODE)
<TR><TD>ENCODING<TD ALIGN=CENTER>12 BITS
<TR><TD>DATA RATE<TD ALIGN=CENTER>883 kbps
<TR><TD ROWSPAN=2>FIELD OF VIEW<TD ALIGN=CENTER>&#177; 43 along track
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>&#177; 51 cross track
<TR><TD>SWATH<TD ALIGN=CENTER>2400 KM
<TR><TD>PIXEL (at nadir)<TD ALIGN=CENTER>6 KM x 7 KM
<TR><TD>MISSION LIFETIME<TD ALIGN=CENTER>3 YEARS
</TABLE> <P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to the top </A><P>

