<HEAD>
<TITLE>MERIS</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"><H1>MERIS - MEdium Resolution Imaging Spectometer</H1></A>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
<H2>Table of contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#description">Description and characteristics</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#synergism">Synergism with other ENVISAT - 1 instrument</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#dependance">Dependance on other data</A></B>

</UL><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2><A NAME="description">Description and characteristics </A></H2>
MERIS is a passive optical pushbroom instrument intended to perform radiance measurements with high spectral resolution in the spectral range from 0.40 to 1.05 &#181;m. up to 15 band can be selected at any time.<P>
The swath width of MERIS is 1450 km, providing a global coverage of the Earh's surface every 3 days, with a spatial resolution of 250 m (full resolution) or 1000 m (low resolution) at subsatellite point.<P>
The main goal of MERIS is to monitor marine biophysical and biochemical parameters on a large scale and with a very high resolution. Secondary objectives are related to atmospheric parameters, such as cloud properties and water vapour, and to vegetation conditions on land surfaces. As a moderate spatial resolution, wide swath sensor, MERIS should provide data useful as inputs to global climatological and ecosystem models on a long term basis.<P>
DATA will be collected only during daylight, and geophysical validation will be achieved by correlation with in situ measurements.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<H2><A NAME="synergism">Synergism with other ENVISAT - 1 instruments</A></H2>
The high resolution data of MERIS will complementor benefit measurements from many other instruments such as AATSR, SCARAB, SCIAMACHY, and , to a lesser extend, ASAR. For the former group, the complementarity will come from their capability to obtain data on bi-directional reflectance to achieve good correctionsfor the atmospheric effects, as well as additional information regarding angular dependance of target albedos, aerosol and cloud properties.<P>
With the ASAR, useful correlations will be made for the observation of oceanic surface patterns such as current, front, eddies. The same will be true, to a lesser extend, of AATSR.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<H2><A NAME="dependance">Dependance on other data </A></H2>
Knowledge of atmospheric attenuation and cloud fields is important for correcting atmospheric effects. Data from AATSR will be very useful for this purpose.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
