<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ASAR</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"><H1>ASAR - Advanced Synthetic Aperture Radar</H1></A>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
<H2>Table of contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#description">Description and characteristics</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#synergism">Synergism with other ENVISAT - 1 instruments</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#dependance">Dependance on other data</A></B><P>
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><P>

<H2><A NAME="description">Description and characteristics</A></H2>

ASAR belongs to a new generation of SARs. While the principle of operation is the same as in ERS - 1, the technology is different. ASAR is an active antenna which allows changing the antenna beam position in orbit. The advantage is that the observed swath can be changed in position. While ERS - 1 takes images in only one swath of 100 km width, ASAR allows the choice of seven different swaths (with widths between 60 and 100 km) inside a total swath of 500 km. On one handhis allows higher flexibility in observing a given area from different satellite passes; on the other hand it allows observation under different incidence angles. ASAR also allows to image a full swath of more than 400 km, at one time, but a reduced spatial resolution (100 m)<P>

Another major difference between the AMI/SAR and ASAR is the availability of a second polarisation. ERS - 1 operates only with vertical polarisation, ASAR with both vertical and horizontal polarisation. A special mode allows quasi-simultaneous imaging in both polarisation. In addition, ASAR has a low resolution mode (1 km) which allows images of more than 400 km swath width to be taken from anywhere on the Earth and stored on the on-board tape recorder.<P> 
The operating frequency of ASAR is 5.3 GHz as on ERS - 1. Continuity between ERS - 1 and ASAR is ensured as the ASAR performance characteristics include the capability of ERS - 1.<P> 

The scientific objectives of the ASAR includes:
<UL>
<LI>Oceanography: ocean circulation, (current, fronts, eddies, internal waves, bathymetry); 
<LI>Land processes: Soil moisture, surface roughness, geomorphology, vegetation science (moisture, geometry, biomass); 
<LI>Cryospheric sciences:
<UL><LI>Sea-ice dynamics and dissemination;
<LI>Ice sheets and shelf dynamics; 
<LI>Snowpack properties.
</UL></UL>
The parameters are derived from interpretation/analysis of images elaborated from doppler-shifted radar echoes processed through a coherent ASAR image processor.<P> 
ASAR is designed for five modes:
<UL>
<LI>Image mode: it provides High resolution images (resolution < 30 m) in any subswaths inside a total swath of 500 km. The polarisation is either vertical or horizontal. A direct data transmission is required because of the high data rate (about 100 Mbit/).<P>
<LI>Wave mode: it provides Radar imaging of one or two imagettes of 5 x 5 km anywhere inside the total swath of 500 km. The repetition distance for imagette (pair) to imagette (pair) along track is 100 km or 200 km respectively. No ground contact is required during operation.<P>
<LI>Alternating polarisation mode: it provides Hig Resolution imaging in any subswath as in Image mode but with polarisation changing from subaperture to subaperture. The results are images of the same scene in HH and VV polarisation with better than 30 m resolution. Radiometric resolution is reduced compared to Image mode, but the data rate is equivalent. Ground contact is thus required for data transmission.<P>
<LI>Wide swath mode: it provides a Medium Resolution imaging (resolution < 100 m) of a full swath of more than 400 km. The data rate/ transmission is similar to Image mode.<P>
<LI>Global monitoring mode: it provides a Low Resolution imaging (resolution < 1000 m) of a full swath of more than 400 km. This mode has a reduced data rate, so that the data can be stored on-board for global monitoring.
</UL>
Additional support modes are also used for ease of operations and for in-orbit calibration and validation.<P>
ASAR is an instrument for which operational and/or commercial applications are already identifid (e.g. ice, geology, mapping) and are anticipated in the medium term (agriculture, forestry, vegetation). ASAR is furthermore independent of weather and daylight.<P> 

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<H2><A NAME="synergism">Synergism with other ENVISAT - 1 instruments</A></H2>
ASAR data will be of major synergistic use for data originated from maby other instruments on European and US polar platforms, including:
<UL>
<LI>MERIS and AATSR for studies of vegetation status (growth, soil moisture stress), snow/ice energy transfers and sea-ice dynamics, as well as oceanic features (front, boundaries, currents); 
<LI>RA - 2 for ice topography (ASAR providing fine detailed information on sea-ice morphology) and large-scale ocean dynamics (ocean currents)
</UL><P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<H2><A NAME="dependance">Dependance on other data</A></H2>
ASAR does not depend on other instruments.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
