<HEAD>
<TITLE>GOMOS</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<H1>GOMOS - Global Ozone Monitoring by Occultation of Stars</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<H2>Table of contents</H2>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#description">Description and characteristics</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#synergism">Synergism with other ENVISAT - 1 instruments</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#dependance">Dependance on other data</A></B><P>
</UL><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<H2><A NAME="description">Description and characteristics</A></H2> 
The primary function of GOMOS is to monitor ozone and ozone trends to high accuracy using stellar occultation by observing the UV/visible/near infrared spectra of stars as they set through the atmosphere. It capitalises on the inherent strenghts of te occultation technique. The high measurement accuracy, stability and vertical resolution are unique features.<P>

About 25 stars can be monitored systematically over many orbits in the course of a day, providing enough coverage for the production of word-wide, daily maps of ozone concentrations at each altitude above 20 km.<P>

In addition to ozone, it may also produce simultaneous observations of other species including  H<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>O, NO<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>, NO<MATH><SUB>3</SUB></MATH>, OClO and aerosol. Thus in addition to monitoring ozone it should be capable of providing new information on the composition, the dynamics and the radiation balance in the middle atmosphere. GOMOS will provide data not only of relevance to "chemical" investigations but also to radiative studies.<P> 
GOMOS consists of two bore-sighted spectrometers. Spectrometer A covers the spectral range 2250 to 675 nm (O<MATH><SUB>3</SUB></MATH>). Spectrometer B covers the range 758 to 772 nm (O<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>) and 926 to 943 nm ( H<MATH><SUB>2</SUB></MATH>O). The spectral resolutions of the two instruments is 1 nm for spectrometer A and 0.1 nm for spectrometer B.<P>
In the limb viewing mode it is intended to operate over a vertical height range of about 10 km to about 100 km. In this mode it will have a resolution in the vertical of about 1.7 km.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<H2><A NAME="synergism">Synergism with other ENVISAT - 1 instruments</A></H2>
MIPAS an SCIAMACHY both provide data which could complement that from GOMOS as they can cover other relevant species simultaneously at different times in the diurnal cycle. For ozone monitoring, GOMOS can provide stable reference datas.<P> 

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<H2><A NAME="dependance">Dependance on other data</A></H2>
GOMOS does not depend on other instruments to observe the spectra of chemical species in the middle atmosphere or to monitor trends.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<!--<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>-->
