<HTML>
<HEAD> 
<TITLE>AATSR</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">

<A NAME="TOP"><H1>AATSR - Advanced Along Tracks Scanning Radiometer</H1></A>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#description">Description and characteristics</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#synergism">Synergism with other ENVISAT - 1 instruments</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#dependance">Dependance on other data</A></B><P>
</UL><P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><P>

<H2><A NAME="description">Description and characteristics</A></H2>
AATSR will provide data of relevance to a wide span of disciplines including:
<UL>
<LI>Climate studies (sea surface temperature) 
<LI>Biological oceanography (productivity)  
<LI>Physical oceanography (oceanic variability) 
<LI>Cloud detection/radiation processes 
<LI>Vegetation monitoring (index, leaf moisture content) 
<LI>Bi-directional reflectance 
</UL>
It is also intended to use AATSR for operational and commercial applications (meteorology and derived applications, land applications related to vegetation monitoring).<P>

AATSR is an imaging radiometer operaing in the infrared (4 channels at 1.6, 3.7, 10.7 and 12.0 &#181;m) and in the visible (3 channels at 0.55, 0.67 and 1.37 &#181;m) part of the spectrum. The AATSR retains the conceptual design of the ATSR to be flown on ERS - 2, namely that a 500 km swath width, centred on the subsatellite ground track is imaged at a number of wavelengths and two views of each surface sample are provided, at different angles of incidence. By comparing the measurements for each view, the effects of the atmospheric attenuation can be removed. This principla offers a unique method of significantly improving the accuracy of sea surface temperature (SST) retrievals and of measuring surface properties. The measurements occur within a time (typically 150 s) over which atmospheric and illumination levelsare unlikely to change significantly. AATSR is designed to operate continuously. Channel 3 (3.7 &#181;m) is used  at night and Channel 4 (1.6 &#181;m) is used or day measurements.<P> 

The different viewing directions are achieved by employing a plane inclined mirror in the which rotates and produces a conical SCAN of the instrument instantaneous field of view (IFOV), the scan being centred about a line of sight approximately 23&#176;, i.e. along track of nadir. The two views therefore are at angles approximately parallel to an 46&#176; from nadir. Pixel size for the ocean IR channels 1 km x 1 km and 500 m x 500 m for the land visible channels.<P>
The two principle objectives for the AATSR are:
<OL>
<LI>To extend the ATSR/ERS - 1, 2 data set, and continue to develop and exploit the operational (and also scientific) applications of precise SST data that will have been initiated and demonstrated by ATSR.<P>
<LI>To develop new land applications of the bi-directional reflectance measurements which are made by AATSR using the Along Track Scanning Techniques. This objective will be achieved through the use of visible/reflected IR channels additional to those in the ATSR/ERS - 1, 2 instrument design.
</OL><P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<H2><A NAME="synergism">Synergism with other ENVISAT - 1 instruments</A></H2>
Biologicla and physical oceanography will benefit from synergism between AATSR and MERIS data.<P>
 
<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

<H2><A NAME="dependance">Dependance on other data</A></H2>
AATSR does not depend on other instruments.<P>

<A HREF="#TOP"> Back to index </A><P>

