<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Description</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="Description"></A>
<PRE><IMG SRC="/images/uars2.gif">   <IMG SRC="/images/cnes.gif"><P></PRE>
<H1>Mission Description</H1>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
<H2>Table of contents</H2>
<P>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="#Instrum">Instruments presentation</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="/windii/Mission.html#AtmW">Atmospheric Winds</A></B><P>
<IMG SRC="/images/ballroug.gif"><B> <A HREF="/windii/Windii.html">Wind Imaging Interferometer (WINDII)</A></B>
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>
<P>
<H2><A NAME="Instrum">Instruments presentation</A></H2>
The UARS operational altitude is 330 miles and its inclination is 57&#176; to the Earth's equator. <P>

The four instruments that measure and record atmospheric chemical composition and temperature include the Cryogenic Limb Array Etalon Spectrometer (CLAES), Improved Stratospheric and Mesospheric Sounder (ISAMS), Microwave Limb Sounder (MLS) and the Halogen OccultationExperiment (HALOE). <P>

These instruments determine the amounts of ozone, chlorine, methane hydrofluoric and hydrochloric acids, carbon dioxide and other chemical compounds implicated in ozone depletion and suspected greenhouse effects, along with temperature fluctuations at various atmospheric levels. <P>

The first direct measurements of horizontal winds in the upper atmosphere are made by the High Resolution Doppler Imager (HRDI) and the Wind Imaging Interferometer<A HREF="/windii/Windii.html">(WINDII)</A> Indirect measurement are taken by the CLAES ans ISAMS instrument. <P>

The measurement of ultraviolet radiation as the major energy source for the upper atmosphere are conducted by the Solar Ultraviolet Spectral Irradiance Monitor (SUSIM) and the Solar/Stellar Irradiance Comparison Experiment (SOLSTICE). <P>

The Particle Environment Monitor (PEM) detects the characteristics, amount and distribution of electrically charged particles that enter the upper atmosphere. <P>

The Active Cavity Radiometer Irradiance Monitor (ACRIM II) measures the total amount of radiation from the sun to help provide an insigth as to how increased solar activity may affect the Earth's weather and climate. <P>

<A HREF="#Description"">Back to index </A><P>

