<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Interferometry RADAR</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/icones/back8.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<H1>RADAR INTERFEROMETRY METHOD</H1>

<IMG SRC="/icones/line_fusee.gif"><BR>

<STRONG>Radar interferometry is a recent technique that uses the phase difference between two radar images as a measurement of the distance between the ground and a satellite. This measurement is to scale with the wavelength used, i.e. to within centimeters and thus highly accurate.</STRONG> <P>

We can also use the technique to measure relief (with accuracy to within 10 m) or possible movements on the ground (to within millimeters). <P>

<H2>RADAR IMAGERY</H2>

Each pixel of a radar image carries two items of data : a radiometric characteristic and a phase. Radiometry represents the ground's reflectivity to hyperfrequency waves, provinding the image as such. The phase is the sum of the phase specific to the pixel and dephasing due to the there and back path of the wave used. The pixel's specific phase is random from one pixel to another but does not change from one shot to another. Dephasing depends only on the relative distance between the point observed and the satellite. <P>

<H2>RADAR INTERFEROMETRY</H2>

Once the two radar images have been made superimposable by geometric processing, the pixel to pixel phase difference is carried out. The specific phase for each pixel, related to the physical nature of the ground, is thus eliminated, leaving only purely geometrical data for changes in distance between the point observed and two satellite passes. This measurement is highly accurate, but will only be known as modulo of wavelength (a few centimeters). The image for these phase differences will thus show "fringes". This will be the image we have come to call an "interferogram". <P>

An interferogram can be broken down into three distinct items of data : <P>

<UL>
<LI> A shape created by the viewing geometrical configuration and the possible non-parallelism of the two orbits. This latter effect can be eliminated with prior knowledge of the relative position between the orbits and the image. <P>

<LI> By a slight stroboscopic effect, the relief will impress a network of fringes similar to that for iso-altitude curves on the interferogram. The difference in altitude between two of these fringes (and thus the accuracy of the altimetric measurement) will depend on imaging accuracy (stereo base). <P>

<LI> Finally, any movement on the ground between two shots will be measured by interferogram on the scale of the wavelength, and thus to within very high accuracy. To obtain this image for movements (also made up of fringes comparables to iso-movement curves), we must be able to eliminate relief's effects or choose an image couple where the stereo effect is non-existent. <P>
</UL> <P>

<H2>LIMITATIONS</H2>

<UL>
<LI> <EM>Geometrical</EM> :<BR>
Dephasing related to the ground's physical nature will depend on the wave's incidence on the ground. This dephasing must be the same for both SAR images. The two satellite passes must thus be close enough (to within about a few hundred meters), which is often the case. <P>

<LI> <EM>Temporal</EM> : <BR>
The surface state of the ground must remain unchanged between two viewings. This excludes seas, but also highly agricultural regions dues to harvests, ploughing or simply changes in the vegetation. Where possible, it is preferable to avoid over long intervals between image acquisitions or regions with a dense cover of vegetation. <P>
</UL> <P>

<H2>APPLICATIONS</H2>

<UL>
<LI> <EM>Terrain Digital Model</EM> : <BR>
A Terrain Digital Model can be computed from a raw interferogram and prior knowledge of satellite orbital positions. Levels of accuracy obtained are comparable with those obtained by stereo optics from SPOT images. <P>

<LI> <EM>Ground movements</EM> : <BR>
If we can remove the effect of relief or where this effect is of low significance, the interferogram can show ground movements between two viewings to within centimeters. CNES was the first to validate this technique when it published a cartography for ground co-seismic movements during the Landers earthquake in June 1992 (<EM>Nature</EM>, July 93). Other applications include the following : <P>

<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="landers.html">studying earthquakes</A> and detection of pre- and post seismic movements,
<LI> <A HREF="etna.html">detecting volcano swellings</A> before eruption,
<LI> <A HREF="mexique.html">measuring landslides</A>,
<LI> measuring the rate of progress of glaciers,
<LI> monitoring land subsidence where gas or oil are being extracted,
<LI> <A HREF="mexique2.html">classification of agricultural land</A> according to vegetation growth rate.
</UL> <P>
</UL>

