<P>
<H1>The Shetland News Appeal Fund</H1>
<H2>Please help us defeat this unprecedented legal attack <BR>on the freedom of the Internet</H2>
<HR>

<IMG SRC="/pics/redpost.jpg" align=left height=55><IMG SRC="/pics/redpost.jpg" align=right height=55>

<font size=-1>
We regret that part of our service to readers has been censored by unprecedented court action<BR>  at the instigation of Robert Wishart, managing director of The Shetland Times Ltd. 
<BR>
He can be reached by e-mail at <A href="mailto:r.wishart@shetland-times.co.uk">r.wishart@shetland-times.co.uk</A>.
</font>
<br clear=all>

<HR>
<P>
</center>
<CENTER><H2>A letter from <A HREF="mailto:editor@shetland-news.co.uk">the Editor</A></H2></CENTER>

11th November 1996
<P>
Dear Reader,
<P>
As you may know, The Shetland Times Ltd have obtained a temporary court order preventing The Shetland News from making free HTML links to pages on their website. 
<P>
They claim we breached their copyright by doing so. This case has enormous implications for the future of the World Wide Web and has attracted international concern because, if The Shetland Times succeeds at the full hearing in the Court of Session in Edinburgh, it will become illegal in Scotland (and possibly throughout the UK) to make a hypertext link to a page without the permission of the website operator. 
<P>
The action also has serious implications for me personally. I have already incurred legal fees of 1,831.50p for lodging defences in a court 400 miles away. My professional association, the <A HREF="http://gnew.gn.apc.org/media/nuj.html">National Union of Journalists</A>, has now taken up the case and we have instructed a specialist law firm in Edinburgh to fight it. But I still have to pay my initial costs.
<P>
1,831.50p is chickenfeed to a business like The Shetland Times Ltd, which has a near-monopoly on print media in Shetland, but I run a one-man news agency business and I don't have the spare cash to settle this account, which is now due. Nor does Zetnews Ltd, the publisher of The Shetland News, because it is a new company, still in the development stage. 
<P>
A bill of this size would mean firing our first paid member of staff, whom we hired only last week to help expand our free service to readers. The rest of us are currently working for nothing on this project.
<P>
I don't like asking you for charity but I have no alternative. If you will make a donation, however small, to The Shetland News Appeal Fund, my colleagues and I will be very grateful. We will not publicise individual donations without the donors' permission.
<P>
The fund will be controlled and administered by Messrs. Tait & Peterson, solicitors, of Commercial Street, Lerwick, Shetland. They will be the sole signatories on the bank account, in trust for me and Zetnews Ltd. The money will be used to pay our legal expenses. If there is a surplus, we propose that it should go to the National Union of Journalists, to help the costs of fighting this case and any similar cases which may arise in future. The accounts of the fund will be open to public inspection and in due course will be published on our website.
<P>
Thank you for your help,
<p>
(Jonathan Wills)
 <BR> <BR> 
<P>
