<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - The Bressay Essay</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>The Bressay Essay</H1>
<H3>A new script for 'Tory Story'</H3>
<P>
by Jonathan Wills, 9th January 1997
<H4>(This feature also appears in <I>The Orcadian</I> newspaper, published at Kirkwall, Orkney.)</H4>
<HR>
</center>
<P>
Last year it was too snowy for first-footing, although Lord knows I tried. Remind me to tell you the story, sometime, of how I fought my way out of that drift in the park below Raymond's house, armed with only a broken ski stick and an empty half-bottle. The year before it was too icy and the year before that it was so windy that people were blown over on the ice before they reached their neighbours' full bottles. Some of us bear the scars to this day.
<P>
But this year the summer weather was with us - those calm, sunny days and still, frosty nights having arrived four months late but some weeks before Christmas and, most remarkably, persisting throughout the festies. So it was not surprising that normal first footery was resumed with a vengeance in Beautiful Downtown Bressa. There was a lot of catching up to do and no-one was astonished when I became sleepy around five a.m. and a kindly neighbour offered a sofa to 'lay me by for a start'. Anything to stop me singing.
<P>
I awoke, with a start, to find yet another sunny afternoon breaking - and set off with a light foot and a heavy head for the second footing. Bressa being a sociable place, it was not long before I found myself sidetracked. With just five minutes to the oven-timer dinner deadline I tumbled in the door of the old homestead, only to find I had been despaired of and that, rather than call out the rescue helicopter with that infra-red thing that can spot lukewarm half-bottles in roadside ditches, someone had got their priorities right and put the turkey in to roast early. It was some time later before we realised that the foul giblets were still in their plastic bag, inside the hapless fowl. Entirely my fault, of course
<P>
Let us draw a veil over these distressing events. I really should have gone to Stromness for a sober New Year, as intended. The second day of 1997 was, let us say, somewhat subdued. But good cheer was restored on the morning of the third when the radio alarm went off right on time (there having, quite unaccountably, been no power cuts overnight) and dear old Radio England told us, as the lead story, that Mr Major had decided to make 'The Family' his theme in the run-up to the General Election.
<P>
'Gosh!' I said to my partner in our vale of four feet. 'That's jolly good news, Dear, isn't it?' She sniffed, gave me a look of withering distaste and left to catch the Bressa wage-slaves' Red-Eye Special to Lerwick, where the streets are paved with PAYE slips.
<P>
I mean, I'd been expecting Mr Major to say: 'Look here, voters. Who needs families? Isn't it time we did away with such outmoded and often embarrassing social concepts, oh yes? 
<P>
'So I say to Mr Blair, the Devil Incarnadine, why don't we just do away with trade union rights, put millions of men on the dole and force on millions of women the freedom to go out to work for lower wages than the men used to get, my goodness me, yes? With the grown-ups working all the time, or filling in forms at Jobseekercentres, pre-school children will have three or four different child-minders every week, so they'll hardly ever see their parents and will soon forget who they are. 
<P>
'Then they'll grow up to be economic individuals, as the Blessed Margaret intended, not socialised members of old-fashioned families with all the restrictive practices that entails, and it'll be so much easier for my friends in the Confederation of British Industry to hire them for peanuts on short-term, part-time contracts. Soon we'll be the most successful economy in the world and we'll be able to undercut South Korea, so who needs Europe? And I shall be remembered, Oh yes, I will!'
<P>
But that's not what Mr Major's saying at all. The mind boggles, as Mr Blair's surely must have when he heard what the Prime Minister had to say in the forward to his new book of speeches. He'll surely win by a landslide on these novel, family-friendly policies. With the Tories at last converted to family values, their platform must surely include: a minimum hourly wage; restoration of trade union rights; no discrimination by race, creed, gender or age; doubling the old age pension; a social wage for home-makers and carers; free nursery schools on demand; a ban on the purchase of privilege in education, health and social services; and, of course, a sensible defence policy for a small archipelago, in order to free up the funds to pay for the rest.
<P>
Readers, we may at last be about to emerge onto the sunny uplands, after 18 years in the dark canyons of despair. For I now see that I may have misunderstood Mr Major for the past six years. He is actually a double agent, like Kim Philby, Aldrich Ames, Oleg Gordievsky and all the other rentaspooks in the 'Boys' Own Book of Spies' my wife gave me for Christmas. While pretending to be a loyal Thatcherite, he has secretly been preparing for the day when he can lead us triumphantly back to the sanity of a properly-funded welfare state where we are all one big, and not too unhappy, family.
<P>
Chance would be a fine thing. Some ironic genius in the 'Today' programme production team slotted in a package about childminding a few minutes after the announcer's deadpan recital of Mr Major's tawdry old election slogans. 
<P>
This disturbing report explained that many young children really do see so little of their parents these days that they're in danger of growing up not knowing who they, let alone their parents, really are. The reason is that most families can only survive financially by having both parents working, because wages are so low. 
<P>
With regular, professional childcare almost impossible to buy, even if you have the money, thousands of children's lives have to be fitted into complicated daily arrangements, often involving several childminders. They see less of either parent than any previous generation, and at six o'clock, when their mummies and daddies (particularly the single ones) finally get home from work, they're too exhausted to play with them.
<P>
The BBC reporter asked listeners: 'Are we doing right by our children?' The question might more properly have been put a few minutes earlier to the head Con-man who helped to bring our society so low and who still resists the efforts of the European Union to force the Government of Sweatshop Britain plc to conform to at least some minimum standards of civilised social policy.
<P>
Radio England was still on as I moved into the living room, to start collecting wine and beer glasses left by revellers under the table, behind the Christmas Tree, on top of the piano and in other ingenious places. It being the Parliamentary Recess, they were broadcasting a fairy tale in place of Prime Minister's Questions. I was just about to switch on the vacuum cleaner when I realised that another BBC producer, no doubt hoping for preferment under an incoming administration, had hired (apparently for ready money) the wholly unremarkable Carol Thatcher to read out loud her trite biography of her even more unremarkable father. 
<P>
The potboiler's plot, such as it was, was that Dennis Thatcher was 'the golden thread of love' in the life of That Bloody Woman, the author's mother (who, in a just and civilised society, would now be doing porridge in Holloway). How absolutely astonishing. Who ever would have thought it? But there was more - rich, reliable old Dennis had been moved to tears when Maggie the Terrible was overthrown in November 1990, by disloyal underlings as bigoted as herself. Get away! I was so amazed that I switched on the vacuum cleaner and shifted an armchair, to collect more pine needles and shards of broken whisky tumblers.
<P>
It was then that I saw the 'Toy Story' video for which I had been hunting ever since I visited my incredibly famous (and extremely hospitable) friend 'Gospel Tom' Morton over Christmas and he allowed me to play for an hour on his computer with the 'Toy Story' Inter-active CD Rom which he had bought for his bairns (well, that was his story). 
<P>
My taste in films is simple: I like a nice, happy ending after a good car chase but not too much excitement and no murders. I have to watch the old ticker, after all. It helps if the characters are not cardboard cut-outs, which is why I hated 'Four Weddings and Hugh Grant's Funeral in Los Angeles'. Movies must also be funny if I am to watch them for more than a few minutes, which is why I always avoid Woody Allen and never miss a Shell promotional video about the environment. I am also partial to special effects, which is why I so much enjoy Labour Party conferences on the telly, or Jim Wallace on horseback.
<P>
So I left the housekeeping until the afternoon and settled down to watch 'Toy Story', after a helpful child had shown me how to work the video machine. If you haven't yet seen it, all I can say is do so, soon. If you have, then why not watch it all over again?  This film has everything. I take back all I ever said about the Disney Corporation. They finally did it. Eat your heart out, 'Magic Roundabout'!
<P>
Disney executives and their many competitors must already be worrying about how they can follow a blockbuster like this. It's obvious that human actors are a thing of the past. The computer creations are now so much more attractive and interesting and, no doubt, easier to direct and produce. And so much less likely to compromise themselves with Los Angeles ladies of the night, or indeed the middle of the afternoon.
<P>
The answer may well be 'Tory Story'. It can only be a matter of time before 'House of Cards' and 'Our Friends Up North' are superceded by a computerised version of Parliamentary papers and capers. Better still, the inter-active CD Rom version would allow voters the chance to design the politicians they want and make them do things the electorate would like them to do, rather than what vested interests lobby them for.
<P>
I am already working on a screenplay which, for copyright reasons, I dare not expose to your vulgar gaze until I've flogged it to Shetland Times Global Media Monopolies plc. But I can tell you one of the storylines: in 'Toy Story' Sheriff Woody marshals his troops in preparation for the imminent house removal of their owner, one Andy (a child whose working mother appears to lavish him with expensive gifts in lieu of meaningful inter-familial relationships).
<P>
Woody asks each toy to make sure he, she or it has a 'Moving Buddy' - a colleague to look after them on the journey. The question must be - who should John Major's moving buddy be? Not Michael 'Mr Wobbly' Hassletime, surely? Certainly not Michael 'Action Man' Portaloo or Michael Forsyth, the pet rat. Rather too many Michaels there for a single script, in any case.
<P>
His old buddy, Peerie Norrie Lamont, aka 'My Little Shetland Pony', might not be welcome on a long pantechnicon journey these days. Possibly Ken 'Mr Potato' Clarke, being the Little Lead Major's next-door neighbour, might chum our unlamented First Lord of the Treasury into oblivion on the Huntingdonshire tundra or the Bank of England board. More likely, I suggest, it will be Virginia 'Bo Peep' Bottomley, who has lost her sheep - and the place.
<P>
Whoever is chosen, I hope they lose their buddy on the way. We desperately need a new script, suitable for all ages. Alas, 'Bambi' Blair's production team seem all too likely to seek parental guidance. His Dad was a Tory, after all.
<P>


<P>
<BR>
<HR>

