<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Foinaven wreck mystery may be solved
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">
<BR>
<font size=-1>
<A HREF="/appeal.html">Help fight the legal battle for free WWW links</A>
</font>
<P>
<H1>Foinaven wreck mystery may be solved
</H1>
<H2></H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt5.gif">
<HR>
</center>
<P>

<P>
9th January 1997
<P>
A Fife historian believes he has solved the mystery of the wreck  discovered on the seabed less than a mile from Britain's first  Atlantic oilfield.
<P>
Dunfermline author and businessman Bob Baird said yesterday [WED] he  was 'extremely confident' that the ship lying 1,400 feet below the  surface is the Norwegian steamer 'Navarra', torpedoed with the loss  of 11 men on April 6, 1940, just three days before the Nazi invasion of Norway.
<P>
Now Mr Baird (55) is trying to find out what happened to the 14  survivors who were picked up from lifeboats by the Finnish steamship  'Atlas' and landed at Kirkwall.
<P>
The wreck, at the Foinaven oilfield 100 miles west of Shetland, was  found two years ago by a remotely-operated vehicle (ROV) during  seabed surveys by McDermotts, working for British Petroleum. 
<P>
BP made available 13 hours of ROV video footage for Mr Baird to study  and, after an 11-month trawl through libraries and wartime archives  in Britain, Norway and Germany, he said the wreck exactly fitted the  'Navarra', built at Sunderland in 1921.
<P>
It was the right size, in the right position and its cargo of coal  matched records showing the 'Navarra's' last voyage was from Swansea  to Oslo with 3,000 tonnes of Welsh coal - and also what appear to be  some tracked military vehicles.
<P>
'BP have been brilliant,' Mr Baird said. 'They couldn't have been  more helpful. They even arranged for a re-survey of the wreck a few  weeks ago. I feel highly privileged.'
<P>
BP's Foinaven operations manager, Les Thomson, has taken a keen  personal interest in the discovery. On his Aberdeen office desk sits  a lump of coal brought up from the wreck by a ROV, which also  recovered the serial number plate 105675 from the ship's Marconi  radio, now being checked for positve identification. There are plans  to send to coal for chemical analysis and to try to recover one of  the tracked vehicles on board.
<P>
Mr Thomson said his one remaining doubt was that the wreck appeared  to have a gun on the stern. As Norway was still neutral at the time,  this did not seem to tally. But yesterday [WED] Mr Baird said he  thought he had solved that problem: 'There was an agreement under the  rules of war that allowed neutral shipping under contract to  belligerent states to be armed defensively... 
<P>
'I suspect the 'Navarra' was under contract to a British company,  bringing pit props from Norway and taking coal back, so that's the  obvious explanation for the gun, which the Imperial War Museum have  identified as a 12-pounder,' he said.
<P>
'The 'Navarra' was torpedoed by Oberleutnant Hans Jurst of the U-59  in a horrendous northerly gale at 2.30 in the morning. I don't think  Jurst made any attempt to communicate with the ship before he sank  her. In those conditions it would have been very difficult. The fact  that she was a neutral vessel trading with the enemy would have  justified him sinking her. On the video you can see the ship's plates  bent 90 degrees by the force of the explosion.'
<P>
Chris Olsson of Foinaven oilfield operators Golar-Nor is helping with  the research. He said yesterday: 'What became of those 14 men who  landed in Kirkwall on April 7, 1940? If their vessel had not been  sunk then they would have been steaming up Oslo Fjord on the morning  of April 9, surrounded by most of the German surface fleet which was  attacking Norway.
<P>
'The U-boat which torpedoed 'Navarra' continued a successful career  throughout the remainder of the war until she was scrapped in Kiel in  the summer of 1945. 
<P>
'The commander of U-59 was transferred to the newly built U-104 in  August 1940 and was killed, together with all his crew, when they  were depth-charged by 'HMS Rhododendron' north-west of Ireland three  months later.' 
<P>
Mr Olsson found the details on an excellent Icelandic site  <A HREF="http://rvik.ismennt.is/~gummihe/Uboats/u-boats.htm">http://rvik.ismennt.is/~gummihe/Uboats/u-boats.htm</A>  which readers may like to visit.
<P>
Mr Baird and Mr Olsson would like to hear from any survivors of the  'Navarra', or their descendants, so they can piece together the full  story of the 'Navarra's' last voyage, 57 years ago.
<P>
Mr Baird can be contacted at: <BR>39 Woodlands Drive, <BR>Crossford,  <BR>Dunfermline, <BR>Fife, <BR>KY12 8QE; <BR>tel: +44 (0)1383 728307.
<P>
Mr Olsson is at <A HREF="mailto:101470.1100@compuserve.com">101470.1100@compuserve.com</A>. 
<P><CENTER><B><A HREF="/intray/intray.html">See his appeal for  information at The In Tray</A></B></CENTER>                                                                          
<P>



<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1997.

