<P>
<H1>The In Tray</H1>
<H2>Letters to the Editor
</H2>
<HR>
Feel free to <A HREF="mailto:editor@shetland-news.co.uk"><img src="/pics/bigemail.gif"></a> us with your comments.
<P>

(Most recent letters are at the top)
</center>

<P>
<HR>
<P>

<B>Can any of our readers help with the 'Navarra' investigation? </B>
<P>
Chris Olsson <A HREF="mailto:101470.1100@compuserve.com">101470.1100@compuserve.com</A> writes:
<P>
 The Norwegian Steamship "Navarra" was torpedoed by a German U-Boat (U-59, Captain Jurst) on 6th April 1940 while carrying a cargo of 3,000 tons of Welsh steam coal from Swansea to Oslo.  It is believed that she now lies in  400 metres of water near the Foinaven oilfield.  I understand that 11 men perished, but 14 others were rescued by a Finnish vessel (Atlas) and were delivered to Kirkwall in Orkney on the 7th.  This event occurred just 3 days before the German invasion of Norway and those men may have subsequently joined the  Free Norwegian Merchant Navy.
<P>
I have been in touch with the researcher and author Bob Baird who has established that she was sunk at 02:30hrs during a Northerly Gale.  A Royal Air Force Coastal Command aircraft sighted a lifeboat on that same day  some distance to the South and it was subsequently established that this  boat  was from Navarra and which was saved by "Atlas".  
<P>
On the 9th of April one of Navarra's lifeboats was found in North Ronaldsay Sound  and on the 2nd of May a liferaft from Navarra was found at Ness Point, Burray, Orkney.  On the 3rd of  May another was found at Old Head, South Ronaldsay and on the 4th of May  a lifebuoy from Navarra was found at Stew Haven on the East side of South Ronaldsay.
<P>
An excellent Website in Iceland <A HREF="http://rvik.ismennt.is/~gummihe/Uboats/u-boats.htm">http://rvik.ismennt.is/~gummihe/Uboats/u-boats.htm</A>  shows that the  U-boat which torpedoed Navarra continued a successful career throughout the remainder of the war until she was scrapped in Kiel in the summer of '45. The commander of U-59 at the time of the sinking  of Navarra was transferred to the newly built U-104 in August '40 and was killed together with all his crew when they were depth-charged by HMS Rhododendron North West of Ireland three months later.
<P>
What became of those 14 men who landed in Kirkwall on the 7th of April 1940? If their vessel had not been sunk then they would have been steaming up Oslo Fjord on the morning of the 9th of April surrounded by most of the German surface fleet which was attacking Norway! 
<P>
Presumably records were made in Kirkwall of the arrival of 14 ship-wrecked sailor even if they were nationals of a then neutral state.  Perhaps the Kirkwall Harbour Masters office recorded their names.  Perhaps the Norwegian Vice-Consulate in Orkney documented their arrival and their onward  departure for Aberdeen?  Would the local Police have been involved?  I presume that during wartime the local newspaper would have been forbidden from printing casualty information which could have been of value to the enemy, but perhaps unnamed witnesses of the sinking were interviewed for a suitably censored report.
<P>
I would be most interested to find a list of the names of those 14 men and any other information about them which may still be available.  It is unlikely that any of them are still alive today, but that possibility does exist and I would like to try to find out what happened to them.
<P>

<I><A HREF="/headline/navarra/navarra.html">[See The Shetland News story about the 'Navarra']</A></I>




<P>
<HR>
<P>

<P>
<B>The Dan Lawn judgment - Stan Stephens writes:</B>
<P>
Valdez, Alaska, 
<BR>28th December 1996
<P>
The Alaska Supreme Court has handed state environmental regulator Dan  Lawn a victory in his wrongful-demotion lawsuit.
<P>
This demotion occurred on July 31, 1989 - four months after the  'Exxon Valdez' ran aground on Bligh Reef.  Dan was removed as  District Supervisor of the Prince William Sound District and relieved  of all oversight responsibilities dealing with the Alyeska Pipeline  Service Company and the oil industry.  
<P>
Before the oil spill Dan had constantly warned the State of problems  with the shipment of oil.  The State of Alaska ignored his pleas  before the spill and failed to listen to their senior most  knowledgeable person at the time of the spill.  
<P>
Dan Lawn's hard work was rewarded by a job demotion. This December,  almost eight years after the spill, the State told Dan Lawn that they  no longer had work for him and said he would be laid off as of  February 1997. This early Christmas present by the State was their  way of saying thanks to a dedicated employee of 19 years, who did his job.
<P>
On December 27 the Alaska Supreme Court ruled that Dan Lawn was  wrongfully demoted in July of 1989. This decision gave Dan back his  old job duties, overseeing the Alyeska Pipeline Terminal in Valdez  for the Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation.
<P>
Will the State of Alaska do the right thing and honor the Supreme  Court decision? We are all hoping so. The citizens of Alaska have  everything to gain by putting Dan back in his old job.  The citizens  of this State have always said that Dan was wrongfully demoted. Now  the Supreme Court of the State of Alaska agrees.
<P>
It will be interesting to see if a Supreme Court decision will be  upheld by the State administration or if they will continue to try to  abuse his rights.
<P>
Stan Stephens <BR>Valdez <BR>Alaska 
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:ssc@alaska.net">ssc@alaska.net</A>
<P>






<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Back The Tory Government, Whatever It Does? </B>
<p>
2nd December 1996
<P>
Dear Sir,
<P>
The tendency of Tory prospective candidates, for Orkney and Shetland, to criticise Tory government policy has again been exemplified by Mr Hope Vere  Anderson's attack on Mr Clarke's airport tax.
<P>
To show one's independence is all very well and we must thank Mr Anderson for so doing but, it is fair to ask, for whom should local Tory supporters vote if they happen genuinely to support Mr Clarke on this matter - as they have every right to do ?
<P>
This, may I say, is not a problem for me as I shall not vote Tory, however many criticisms Mr Anderson may make of bigger and better Tories than he. Were I a mischievous old fellow, I would put up as a 'Back The Tory Government Whatever It Does' candidate. I reckon I could split the Tory vote rather neatly.
<P>
Anyone for Election Agent for the BTTGWID Party?
<P>
Yours more or less sincerely,
<P>
 Eric Stockton,  West Cott, Sanday, Orkney,  KW17 2BW,  UK 
<BR>
e-mail  <A HREF="mailto:stockton.sanday.orkney@zetnet.co.uk">stockton.sanday.orkney@zetnet.co.uk</A> 
<P>




<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Folly beyond belief does incalculable damage to Web culture</B>
<P>
16th November 1996
<P>
It is intensely sad that Shetland Times publisher, Robert Wishart, in  his attempted gagging of the Shetland News has infringed the very  principles of free access, co-operation and interdependence that the  WWW community has espoused since its inception.
<P>
He has demonstrated, in an astonishing outburst of almost Maxwellian  bile, a fear of anything which could remotely threaten his  monopolistic ambitions in Shetland's news gathering and publishing arena.
<P>
The Shetland News was set up to inform, educate  and entertain the Shetland public and the world at large, on a medium  which, though in its infancy, is generally free of the kind of  cut-throat commercialism more appropriate to the Robber Barons of the  publishing world. In one fell swoop Wishart has ended the unwritten  code that permeates Internet culture - Free Speech is genuinely free.
<P>
And why? Because the Shetland News, a small company existing on  sponsorship and goodwill, makes an open-handed gesture in the spirit  of the Web's emerging culture by offering a link to the Shetland  Times' pages. Wishart, by obtaining an unprecedented court  injunction (at great expense, no doubt) to remove this link,  astonishingly says to the world: 'Here's my foot, here's the pistol - bang!'
<P>
The damage to Web culture in general and Shetland credibility is  incalculable. No-one benefits from airing dirty washing in public, we  know, but to make an issue of what is, after all, clean washing  is folly beyond belief. 
<P>
I hope that the inevitable spotlight that Wishart's decision will  bring to bear on Shetland's Internet presence, will, in the end, help  to show that some of us in Shetland have the vision and ability to  shrug off such petty rivalry. I hope also that Robert Wishart will  eventually understand that the Internet is no place to flex  commercial muscle in the pursuit of personal profit.
<P>
Dave Hammond <BR><A HREF="mailto:shetland.smokehouse@zetnet.co.uk">shetland.smokehouse@zetnet.co.uk</A>
<P>



<P>
<HR>
<P>



<P>
<B>Concern about Academic ramifications of the case</B>
<P>
15th November 1996
<P>
I am a little concerned about the potential implications of the 'links' case for academic citations. 
<P>
A link in the WWW is, after all, a 'pointer' to another source in the same  medium. A foonote is, similiarly, a pointer to another source in the same medium (print). If a WWW link becomes something which requires permission from the copyright holder, and which might be charged for, could not publishers then appply the same principle to print?
<P>
Conversely, of course, as publishers do not insist that one have permission to cite in print, and I imagine no publisher would dream of demanding copyright permission or payment for citations in print on paper, how can citation in print on the WWW be treated any differently?
<P>
Mike Cosgrave History Dept. University College, Cork Ireland
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:m.cosgrave@ucc.ie">m.cosgrave@ucc.ie</A>
<P>



<P>
<HR>
<P>




<P>
<B> The Internet for Dummies</B>
<P>
15 November 1996
<P>
Dear Sir,
<P>
I have just read about this situation in our copy of New Scientist  and, out of curiosity,  have looked at the pages of Shetland Times and Shetland News.  And I  am a bit confused.
<P>
I fully expected the Shetland Times pages to be viewable only by  membership, i.e. that  the publisher charges money for a web user to read the pages.  If  this were true however  then hyperlinks from Shetland News could not bypass any membership  security on the Times  server, so there would be no argument.  If on the other hand the  Shetland Times pages are  free (as indeed it appears) then hyperlinks from Shetland News merely  has the effect of  diverting readers to those pages - a benefit to the Times and a loss  to the News.
<P>
So what is the problem?  Ok, I suppose you could argue that in a  community as close as  Shetland a courtesy call might be better but hey, this is the World  Wide Web.  The whole  *point* is that you want as many readers as possible and as many  links to your pages as  possible to justify the development cost.  If other sites point to  yours then surely it  is because yours is worth reading?  And isn't this why you do it?
<P>
We have recently launched our own Web site and, frankly, if Shetland  News posted  hyperlinks to our material we would be delighted.  It would be  different if the News  copied material from our pages without our permission but as I  understand it this is not  what happened.
<P>
This is all totally ridiculous.  The editor of the Shetland Times  clearly does not  understand the basic principles of Internet publishing and his court  action is at best  ill-advised and at worst (given the potential implications) irresponsible.
<P>
To help with his confusion perhaps you could send him some background  reading.  How about  "The Internet for Dummies"?
<P>
Best wishes and good luck!
<P>
Tony Tipping <A HREF="mailto:tony.tipping@ewos.com">tony.tipping@ewos.com </A>
<BR><A HREF="http://www.fishlink.com/ewosv">http://www.fishlink.com/ewos</A>
<P>
P.S.  Why was the judge who imposed the Interdict so poorly briefed?   Technically this  should never have got this far surely?



<P>
<HR>
<P>

<B>World Wide Web under threat</B>
<P>
10th November 1996
<P>
 Dear Sir,
<P>
As an Internet user, I was horrified to hear of the Shetland Times'  assault on the whole concept of the World Wide Web.  
<P>
As any Net user will know, links to one's site are a much  sought-after commodity; this is how people find it.  Any normal  person would be grateful to find another organisation - especially  one which he views as a rival - including a link to his site.
<P>
Quite what possessed Mr. Wishart to launch a judicial task force over  this piece of professional courtesy is a mystery to me. It is only to  be hoped that, when his case is thrown out of court, his legal bill  is suitably crippling.
<P>
I am more than willing to donate to any defence fund for the Shetland  News, should this become necessary.  It is unfortunate that I do not  live in Shetland, otherwise I could boycott the Shetland Times.
<P>
Yours,          <BR>Graham Pearson <BR>Edinburgh.         <BR><A HREF="G.R.Pearson@hw.ac.uk">G.R.Pearson@hw.ac.uk </A><BR><A HREF="http://www.cee.hw.ac.uk/~ceegrp">http://www.cee.hw.ac.uk/~ceegrp</A>
<P>
(I promise not to sue anyone if they publish links to my homepage!)
<P>









<P>
<HR>
<P>

<B>Is the Shetland surf too cold?</B>
<P>
Dear Sir,
<P>
Isn't the entire point of the Internet the fact that you can move  from site to site to site? It's called 'surfing', as any schoolchild  with a modicum of intelligence will tell you. I can only presume that  Mr Wishart's total loss of marbles is due to the surf up Shetland way  being so damn cold, especially at this time of year.
<P>
There couldn't be another reason, could there? Could it possibly be  that Mr Wishart's ire is up because The Shetland News is the far  superior and livelier newspaper and its editor the best journalist  the islands have produced in a generation or more?
<P>
Peter Denton <BR>
Teddington <BR>
Middlesex <BR>
England




<P>
<HR>
<P>

<B>Shetland Times loses a link from Glasgow</B>
<P>
7th November 1996
<P>
Sheila Webber <A HREF="mailto:sheila@dis.strath.ac.uk">sheila@dis.strath.ac.uk</A> writes: 
<P>
May you and the Shetland News prosper! As has been pointed out by other  correspondents, people are normally flattered (and may be prepared to  pay) to have a link to their site. And as you yourself say, to invoke  the Copyright Act seems curious where no copying is involved. 
<P>
For some time I have had a link to your excellent site from my <A HREF="http://www.dis.strath.ac.uk/business/newsuk.html"> UK news page</A>  (part of a site of links to business sources) - I have removed the link  to the Shetland Times...
<P>
Sheila Webber  <BR>Strathclyde University, <BR>Glasgow
<P>
 



<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Something funny in the water, perhaps?</B>
<P>
David Rothman writes from Alexandria, Virginia:
<P>
 Has anyone checked some local water supplies for lead or perhaps something more lively, in the Timothy Leary vein? Just how else to explain Robert Wishart's bizarrely obtuse crusade against easy linking, the very glory of the World Wide Web? Only one other possiblity (<A HREF="http://www.shetland-news.co.uk/editorial/guested2.html">http://www.shetland-news.co.uk/editorial/guested2.html</A>) comes to mind.
<P>
Whatever the reason, I'm amazed that anybody could be so dim-witted, so blind to the basic principles here. 
<P>
Just now I dropped by the Web site of the Shetland Times and saw that Mr Wishart publishes books, not just the newspaper. Let's hope that he doesn't feel the same way about this other medium. If so, perhaps a judge will go along with Mr. Wishart's certain-to-be-made suggestion that library catalogues be declared illegal. 
<P>
At least the controversy has introduced me and others to your newspaper's wonderful, quirky writing -the Shetland Islands aren't exactly at the center of most conversation in my suburb of Washington, D.C. 
<P>
Now some second thoughts: Could Mr. Wishart actually be a secret investor in The Shetland News? If you two are in cahoots to boost your publication's readership, I'll say: 'Jolly well done.' 
<P>
Seriously, the very best of luck in court.
<P>
David Rothman
<BR>Author, NetWorld!
<BR><A HREF="mailto:rothman@clark.net">rothman@clark.net </A>
<BR><A HREF="http://www.clark.net/pub/rothman/networld.html">http://www.clark.net/pub/rothman/networld.html </A>
<BR><A HREF="http://www.clark.net/pub/rothman/telhome.html">http://www.clark.net/pub/rothman/telhome.html</A>
<P>
<I><B>The Editor writes:</B> I've checked the share certificates and Mr  Wishart's money is not with us yet, alas.  Thank you, David, for some  most entertaining suggestions and welcome to the Washington DC  section of the Shetland expats club!</I>
<P>








<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Shocked at victimisation of The Shetland News</B>
<P>
1st November 1996
<P>
Dear Editor
<P>
I have just returned from a visit to Russia, and am shocked to  discover that The Shetland News, a website I read daily when in the  UK, is being victimised by someone who clearly doesn't understand what the World Wide Web is about. 
<P>
This is just a line to wish you all the best in the important legal  battle that is to come. Post details of where to send money for your  legal fighting fund and you'll certainly get a contribution from me.
<P>
And thanks for a thoughtful, literate, provocative and entertaining  paper. Could it be that the Shetland Times people are jealous?
<P>
David Warnes
<BR>  <A HREF="mailto:dj.warnes@zetnet.co.uk">dj.warnes@zetnet.co.uk</A>
<P>
<I><B>The Editor writes:</B> Good Lord! What a bizarre suggestion! (tee hee).  We are looking at the costs of the case right now and will let  readers know if and when we need to launch an appeal.</I>
<P>






<P>
<HR>
<P>

<B>A stab in the heart of the Internet community</B>
<P>
31st October 1996
<P>
Dear Editor,
<P>
I have read the reports of what has been happening in the Scottish  Court vis-a-vis the outrageous claim that the links you made to  another island newspaper, The Shetland Times, were illegal and a  breach of copyright law!
<P>
Why should I be interested? I have no links with the Shetland Islands  other than a few friends I've made over the Internet.
<P>
Well, I'm an expatriate Welshman, and I know what links with home  mean. It's been such a pleasure to read publications from a small  community that still has heart - or so I thought. The actions of your  rival seem to me to stab at that heart, and extremely viciously. I  can think of no occasion when I was unaware of which newspaper I was  reading. Anyone who is interested enough to read the two publications  must be aware that they are different.
<P>
The action taken is against the free spirit of the Internet. Anybody  who has only two or three hours worth of experience of "Net surfing"  would realise this. I have two small web-sites on which I'm  encouraged to make world-wide links. In other words, I'm supposed to  give a free ad. to other contributors to this medium, provided of  course that they are not engaged in anything unsavoury or illegal.
<P>
One of them is in the course of revision right now. It's in the  States, and the whole site gets many visitors. I shall, in my  revision, put a link to "The Shetland News", and when it's in place,  later next week, I'll let you have full details with the address.  Please note. I'm not asking your permission to do this. I hope you  won't take me to court for it!
<P>
So far as I'm concerned a blow against free speech of this sort on  the Internet is a blow against the Freedom of the Press.
<P>
Yours sincerely,
<P>
Ian Ballard. 
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:ballard@zetnet.co.uk">ballard@zetnet.co.uk</A>
<P>
<I>
<B>The Editor writes:</B> Thank you for your support, Ian. It is very much appreciated by our embattled crew here at The Shetland News, as we prepare to fight The Shetland Times' legal action all the way. We'll be more than happy if you or anyone else cares to put up a link or links to any of our web pages. And we'll be equally happy to link to yours. That's what it's all about, after all.</I>


<P>
<HR>
<P>

<P>
<B>Strong reaction from Shetland expatriates Down Under </B>
<P>
<I><B>Editor's note:</B> at the risk of further interdicts from the Man Who  Would Be Sheltiecyberking, we reprint the following letter sent to  The Sh*tl*nd T*m*s from two islanders living in Australia:</I>
<P>
30th October 1996
<P>
Dear Mr Wishart,
<P>
As expat Shetlanders with many relatives around the world we are  appalled at your recent action against the Shetland News.
<P>
You obviously have no understanding of the World Wide Web. Your  behaviour is ridiculous  and pathetic. What is worse is that it brings down the name of The  Shetland Times and questions the intelligence of Shetland islanders  re the outside world!
<P>
For God's sake, stop being so stupid. A great many people, including  ourselves, will no longer be accessing the Shetland Times pages if  this idiotic childishness continues.
<P>
Rob and Ian Leask
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:leaskrob@acr.net.au">leaskrob@acr.net.au</A>




<P>
<HR>
<P>

<P>
29th October 1996
<P>
 Dear Shetland News,
<P>
I am writing in to support your right to be able to freely show links  to other Web sites (inc. Shetland Times). A link to a Shetland Times  story is in my estimation the equivalent of reading one newspaper,  and it telling you to read "headline" on page xxx of other newspaper. 
<P>
In simple terms you are just referencing their material, not  reproducing it, therefore keeping within the bounds of copyright law.
<P>
If you can use this letter of support to help your case, then please  feel free to do so.
<P>
Tony Walker.
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:tony.walker@zetnet.co.uk">tony.walker@zetnet.co.uk</A>
<P>






<P>
<HR>
<P>

28th October 1996
<P>
Dear Sir
<P>
I heard with dismay about the current conflict between you and the  Shetland Times.  Such a thing in a small community seems absurd  especially considering the ramifications which come to bear on the  whole idea of the internet being a medium with a free exchange of  information.  What a shame that this could not have been settled  between the two parties without resorting to the courts.
<P>
I should like to draw your attention to links which we have set up  which show what a ridiculous situation this is.  Several months ago,  William Sandison from Shetland Litho/The Shetland Times asked me if I  would set up a link from our knitwear brochure (which acknowledges  that it is printed by Shetland Litho (part of the Shetland Times  organisation) and in return they would link from their publicity to  us.  They must have been aware that the Shetland News had a link to  us so by extrapolation the links run as follows: Shetland News linked  to us, we are linked to Shetland Litho and Shetland Litho is linked to  the Shetland Times. Or at least, as far as I am aware all these links  are in place and if not, they were intended to be.
<P>
In addition, if the system of linking is ruled to be causing a breach  of copyright then will we have to sue all those people who put links,  unbeknownst to us, to our brochure? Surely the system of links is  meant to draw people's attention to your web-site and not to detract from it?
<P>
I trust that this situation is clarified soon,..., otherwise the free exchange of information  will not be able to continue.
<P>
Yours sincerely
 <p>
Louise Irvine<BR> - speaking from a personal point of view but with a  business interest.
<P>


<P>
<HR>
<P>
27th October 1996
<P>
Dear Editor,
<P>
   As you know, I've been following with interest your dispute with the Shetland Times about your past inclusion of Web links to that newspaper.  In response to your query about precedents in America, I know of no interdiction of Web linking except in the "Dilbert" case, in which the Web author actually incorporated the copyrighted contents of another site into his own Web page format, giving the appearance that the content resided at his own site.  I am not an expert on U.K. copyright regulations, but it is my view that in the U.S., copyright law simply would not apply to a situation such as yours, since no copying was done by you or your newspaper.
<P>
   In one of your editorials, you mentioned your concern that a threatened action against your paper might be intended to cause unbearable legal expenses, even if unsuccessful.  Over here, such an action is known as a SLAPP suit, which stands for Strategic Lawsuit Against Public Participation.  Such suits are frequently filed against individuals and small businesses in order to prevent the publication of letters to newspapers, presentations at public meetings of legislative bodies, etc.  The billboard industry ("outdoor advertizing" in its own terminology) is notorious for filing such suits to suppress community support for billboard-banning local ordinances.  If you've traveled in America, you'll no doubt appreciate how widespread and successful this tactic has become.
<P>
   As a faithful reader of both Shetland newspapers, let me express my hope that this dispute can be settled quickly and on a basis rooted in the realities of the Internet.
<P>
Sincerely,
<P>
James Thompson
<BR>
E-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:Thompson@ucrac1.ucr.edu">Thompson@ucrac1.ucr.edu</A>

<P>
<HR>
<P>

<P>
<B>Cyberwars: 'Puzzled of Sanday' writes</B>
<P>
25th October 1996

<P>
Dear Dr Wills,
<P>
I am rather new to the Internet and so perhaps I have misunderstood what has been happening between you and the management of The Shetland Times. As I see it, you have included in the SN one or more links to the ST and that this action has been construed, by them, as breach, by you, of the ST's copyright.
<P>
Irrespective of legal technicalities (of which I am in even greater ignorance than of the Internet) it appears to me that you have actually provided, by way of these links, two useful services: you have given your readers easy access to another, no less valuable, net site and you have given the ST a little more publicity than it would otherwise have had.
<P>
It would be pressing matters too far perhaps for you actually to ask the ST to pay for what amounts to free advertising but, were I the operator of a major independent website, I would be glad of, and encouraged by, any links to my site that other interested operators might put in theirs.
<P>
I write as one who values both the SN and the ST and indeed I have been a regular reader and intermittent contributor to the ST for a good many years.
<P>
I hope that this matter is soon to be resolved to the satisfaction of all concerned - especially the readers upon whom both publications depend.
<P>
Yours sincerely,
<P>
 Eric Stockton, <BR>West Cott, Sanday, Orkney,  KW17 2BW,  UK 
<BR>e-mail  <A HREF="mailto:stockton.sanday.orkney@zetnet.co.uk">stockton.sanday.orkney@zetnet.co.uk</A> 
<P>
<I><B>The Editor writes: </B>We also hope it will be resolved soon. We have  asked our lawyers to tell The Shetland Times that, if they care to  ask the court to lift the interdict, and if they pay all costs, we  are happy to let byegones be byegones. There is room for both  publications and scope for co-operation (and friendly rivalry)  between them. But we cannot and will not give up the right to post  links to the pages of other publications. This practice is the  essence of the Internet and a founding principle which should guide  all internet publishers.</I>
<P>

<P>
<HR>
<P>


<B>Fond memories of USCG Scatsta</B>

<P>
Vern Mace writes: 
<P>
  I have just made one of the most enjoyable connections on the internet I  could ever imagine; a connection to Shetland. You can't imagine how  fantastic it feels to be able to re-connect with the greatest experience in  all my life.
<P>
 In 1970, I was assigned to duty at the US Coast Guard Base in Scatsta Brae  near Sullom Voe. I lived with my wife, Elizabeth, in a small cottage called  Boden in Stromfirth. We absolutely loved (and still love) your wonderful  islands and all our wonderful Shetland friends. The Hunters, the Robertsons,  and all our neighbors in Stromfirth were without a doubt the warmest and  most endearing friends I have ever met. The fourteen months we lived in  Shetland are still fresh in my mind, and so wonderful that they are almost  dreamlike today. When I received my orders to return to the US, I was faced  with the most difficult task I have ever had to perform - leaving Shetland.  Even though I physically left, my heart has always remained in Shetland. 
<P>
 Many years have gone by, as have many failed plans to return to Shetland.  And now I have a chance to once again return to your beautiful islands. It  is not quite the same as being there, but through the internet, your  newspaper articles and pictures have again made that connection to my heart.  I am forever grateful. Thank you, your web page, all the wonderful people of  Shetland, and all the wonderful memories of Shetland that I hold so dearly.
<P>
 If anyone would like to contact me, feel free to email me at  teltecmace@worldnet.att.net. I would greatly appreciate the opportunity to  renew contact with old friends and meet new ones as well. I am also  interested in any information concerning what happened to the US Coast Guard  base at Scatsta, as well as the whereabouts of any others who were stationed  there in 1970-71.
<P>
Vern Mace<BR>  
TelTec Communications Corp<BR>  
Griffiss Technology Park <BR> 
255 Hill Road  <BR>
Rome, <BR>
NY 13441  <BR> 
phone: 508-677-0133, 315-337-2002  <BR>
fax  : 508-677-0134, 315-337-2010<BR>
email: <A HREF="mailto:TELTECMACE@postoffice.worldnet.att.net">TELTECMACE@postoffice.worldnet.att.net</A>
<P>







<P>
