<HR>

<A name="GenSit"></A>

<STRONG>General Situation at 12:00 UTC 08/01/97, with Inference</STRONG><BR>

An anticyclone of 1018 mb over Scotland is expected Faeroe, with little change, by midday Thursday. A large area of high pressure extending from Iceland into eastern Europe will persist. 
<p>

A low of 988 mb in Finisterre is expected 1002 mb southern France by the same time.  An Atlantic low will move rapidly east, expected north-east Spain also by the same time. Later in the day, as an occluding Atlantic frontal system pushes north-east across Biscay, SE'ly winds are expected to strengthen across southern areas.
<p>

Pressure is expected to remain high across northern areas during Thursday and Friday.
<p>

There is the likelihood that, during Friday and Saturday, southern areas may see a period of snow - or possibly freezing rain - as the occlusion pushes on into England and Wales. This should gradually turn to rain as much milder conditions move in. The north of Scotland should stay fine and dry, though with a freshening E'ly wind, until late on Saturday.
<p>

Over the weekend the high pressure may transfer south-east into eastern Europe and, with pressure low over the eastern Atlantic, mild S'ly winds are likely across much of the UK.
<p>

<A HREF="#Top"><IMG SRC="/pics/up.gif"></A>

<center><HR width=80%></center>

<p><A name="3-day"></A>

<STRONG>3-day outlook for the Northern Isles (Thursday - Saturday)</STRONG><BR>

Daytime temperatures 3&#176; to 5&#176; Celsius, 0&#176; to 2&#176; Celsius overnight. Coastal areas are likely to remain virtually frost-free, but a ground frost is likely to be widespread inland. Areas of 'black ice' may develop on untreated roads left wet by any overnight showers - especially should skies clear. 
<p>

<B>THURSDAY:</B> Remaining generally settled with variable amounts of cloud and a few scattered showers over the North Isles. Winds are expected to be F1-3 NE'ly.
<br>
<B>Swell</B> - N'ly at 1 metre.
<p>

<B>FRIDAY:</B> A fine, frosty start with bright periods, scattered wintry showers and light winds. Becoming cloudier during the afternoon and evening as the wind increases F4 SE'ly by the end of the day.
<br>
<B>Swell</B> - N'ly at 2 to 3 metres.
<p>

<B>SATURDAY:</B> Cloudy, but mostly dry at first with a F4 SE'ly wind. Rain and sleet, preceeded by snow over the higher hills, spreading north through Caithness around midday. At the same time the SE'ly winds, backing ESE'ly, will be increasing F6-7, possibly touching gale F8 over exposed hills and headlands.
<p>

<A HREF="#Top"><IMG SRC="/pics/up.gif"></A>

<center><HR width=80%></center>

<p><A name="extended"></A>



<STRONG>Extended Outlook for the Northern Isles (Sunday - Saturday)</STRONG> - <I>Confidence level is low.</I>
<br>
Mild, with temperatures around 6&#176; to 8&#176; Celsius.
<p>

<B>SUNDAY:</B> Mild and cloudy with mist, periods of rain and a F5-7 ESE'ly wind at first. Becoming a little drier and brighter later as the wind veers S to SW'ly.
<p>

<B>MONDAY - SATURDAY:</B> Generally cloudy, with outbreaks of rain at times and a strong S to SW'ly wind. Continuing mild.
<p>

<A name="disclaimer"></A>
<p>

<A HREF="#Top"><IMG SRC="/pics/up.gif"></A>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/nph-count?width=5&link=/brock/weather.html&show=NO">

<HR>

Weather page provided by, and words copyright of <A HREF="mailto:weatherman@zetnet.co.uk">Dave Wheeler</A>, Fair Isle Weather Services.

<HR>

<H5><STRONG>

DISCLAIMER

<br>

Be aware that the weather over north-west Europe - and especially around the Northern Isles - is part of an ever changing and dynamic system.  Therefore regard the 'Extended Outlook' as a guide only - there are times when any outlook going beyond about 36 to 48 hours is likely to prove uncertain.

<p>

All forecasts are for planning purposes only.  The Shetland News, or Dave Wheeler, do not accept any liability for the accuracy of this forecast.</STRONG></CENTER></H5>

