<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - The Ken Speckle Papers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>The Ken Speckle Papers</H1>
<H2>Mr Black Mekkie's star wanes
</H2>
<HR>

<P>

</center>
<P><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="speckbig.jpg" hspace=10 vspace=5>
<I>



</I>
<P>
Being further extracts from the papers of the Reverend Kenneth Speckle BD (failed), Edin, (1747 - ?), sometime incumbent of the disjoined parish of Stobister and pendicles, edited and prepared for the press, at no inconsiderable pains, by Dr Jonathan Wills.
<P>
(This feature also appears in the Yule number of <B>The New Shetlander</B> magazine, on sale now.)
</I>
<P>

<br clear=all>

<HR>
<P>
<I>
<STRONG>
My journal, kept at ye Manse of Stobister, Breezey Isle, Zetland.  ye 15th day of December, yr. of our Lord 1796.
</STRONG>
</I>
<br clear=all>
<P>
<P>
Mistress Mana Berg being in a great 'stoor' in her pantry this morning, a-preparing of sweetmeats, sundry victuals and ale for the feast of Our Blessed Saviour's Nativity, I did not at first remark upon an unusual noise emanating from the brigstanes. But at length the commotion became so clamorous that I was obliged to rise from my escritoire and open the door of my study, intending gently to reprove the good woman and inquire whether she would be so kind as to refrain from her labours for an hour's length, that I might compose my sermon without further distraction, my topick for Christmas Eve being the folly and vanity of all our striving in this sorry world, and the spiritual necessity of preparing oneself for the Day of Judgment.
<P>
The scene that I beheld resembled the Day of Judgment itself. For there, in a cloud of dust, stood the unmistakable figures of Young Grinnyskull and Dicka Nastigirth, each bearing a monstrous flagstone upon his back, to add to the growing pile of slabs resting in my vestibule. Mistress Berg was remonstrating with them, gesticulating, and adamantly repulsing their insistent demands for 'wan peerie moothlufter'.
<P>
Interposing myself betwixt the combatants, I bade Mistress Berg fetch a  flagon of porter and indicated to the two young rascals that I wished to interview them privily in my chambers. Meek as lambs, they followed.
<P>
Young Grinnyskull presently explained: 'Da Commeeshnersis wantinstonn furdastritta Lerook an da young mesteraKeldybuster's kerryinonlikk smokk afforda Nesseens irda Hollanders winninapoda tredd.'
<P>
'Yea, feth,' his accomplice vouchsafed, 'Anwirrbin biddenta oppinda aald wharry idda Hollada Boogers pa' Bard. Datsda verrrabest stonnfurda chob, dusees.'
<P>
'Anwirrhockit ankerried aamoarneen anwitowtwi widdchoost laywis byfrastert aside dee, bitshoosno waantinwis,' Young Grinnyskull added, indicating the glowering form of my housekeeper who, despite her manifest displeasure, had indeed borne two flagons of refreshment from the cellar.
<P>
'Biddalooksa yuntwa lippers, meenister, wanill likklyno be anyoch!' she  said, and turned on her heel, slamming the door with such force that a domestic ornament - a painted clay figurine of an Eider Duck, given me by the good Cap'n Dooswelfrimsel, to mark the launch of his new bark 'Denter' - fell from its shelf and shattered upon the floor.
<P>
Mistress Berg's prediction proved accurate. It was late evening before the fifth flagon was consumed and the lads staggered away down the sheeps' gait with their back burdens, in the general direction of the noost below Mistress Lindatimber's establishment, whence the precious cargo was to be ferried to the great works upon the main thoroughfare of our county town.
<P>
I did not regret their visit for, having been much at Lerook upon their errands with samples of the Breezey flagstones over the past weeks, they were able to impart many intelligences concerning publick affairs, which might otherwise have escaped me, I having been confined to my manse with a fit of the vapours of late.
<P>
What they had to tell was alarming in the extreme. It appears that the junto of seditious malcontents who for so long have vexed our wise and benevolent governor, Mr Black Mekkie, have now succeeded so far in their turbulent scheming as to induce him to consider resigning his benefice. Sir Jas Bloob, ever Mr Black Mekkie's closest confidant, is said to be arranging a suitably handsome <I>ex gratia </I>honorarium to ensure that the great man shall not be quartered upon the parish in his dotage.
<P>
An aura of gloom and despond surrounds the once lightsome halls of the local authority, where in happier times mummers and fiddlers were frequent guests of Mr Black Mekkie, the most notable patron of the musical arts these islands have ever known. 
<P>
All of Mr Black Mekkie's personal retinue are concerned anent their future employment with the Commissioners of Supply. Messrs Smeeg and Risible bear the look of hunted men. Other flunkeys, once upon familiar terms with the Omnipotent, now avoid his gaze and scuttle around the skirts of Mistress Lorta Carnaptions, the Commissioner for Whalesahoy and Pendicles, whose favour they hope to gain under the new administration. 
<P>
Mr Pall, who formerly regulated the emptying of slop buckets, the cleansing of the publick wells and the inspection of cooked viands, is entirely disaffected and has lost all interest in his duties, or such duties as were left him after King George's men of business had appropriated sundry responsibilities to their retainers in the rotten burgh of Noswasepa, upon the continent of Scotland.  Mr Pall has expressed himself desirous of departing the Commissioners' service, if appropriate terms can be arranged. It is understood that there is some enthusiasm for this upon the part of the Commissioners, who had already decided to dispense with Mr Pall's services and hire but a single clerk to administer the wells, stanks, cart roads and applications for commercial alms.
<P>
I am informed that Mistress Hazel Nethergreen, the keeper of the Privy Chambers, was visibly distressed when her superior was impertinently called to account by Mr Bertram Blackguard, the Commissioner for Helliness, who dared to demand that he be furnished with details of the elaborate arrangements for preventing eavesdropping at the Toon Hoose, where matters of great moment are oft discussed in seclusion when Mr Black Mekkie grants audience to principals in His Majesty's Ministry and, indeed, to the gentlemen adventurers of the British Peat Oil Company and the Shalloot Corporation, to the incalculable, if necessarily unseen, advantage of the commons of Zetland.
<P>
It is being put about, by Sir Jas Bloob's serving wenches below the Toon Hoose stairs, that Canon Shand was entirely ignorant of the 27,000 pounds Scots expended by Mr Black Mekkie upon ear trumpets, trip-wires, man-traps, night-watchmen and concealed scribes. The authority for the works was entirely that of Sir Aidie Pleep, now out of office and compiling a memoir of his decades in the cockpit of political oeconomy, which is expected to be a massive quarto of some 800,000 wise words.
<P>
Sir Adie Pleep, being accosted and questioned upon Da Stritt by some vulgar and disrespectful septuagenarians, is said to have replied: 'Manmanman, dukeens, wichoost heddta duit, brrrm, hmmph, whitwi'dat Dr Garlick rinnin' amok. Daboggerwis gettincloss, aafilcloss. Rrmph. Wididna keen whit he micht du neist!'
<P>
This is taken to be a reference to the panick induced in the Toon Hoose by the elevation to a commissionership, ephemeral as it turned out, of the notorious Dr Witney Garlick, some years past. Dr Garlick is but rarely seen these days, Dicka Nastigirth confided, being entirely taken up with his new 'evanescent publishing machine' which employs the latest calculating engines, new-brought from our former American colonies. My printers and I trust this venture will founder in the same impecuniary confusion as his previous incarnations, and have taken certain measures at law to ensure that this comes about.
<P>
Young Grinnyskull's opinion was that Commissioner Blackguard had been emboldened in his attack on the viceroy by the sudden appearance in publick office of the but recently disgraced Mr Nicol Jonpy, whose spendthrift profligacy, masquerading as benevolence to the poorer classes, Mr Black Mekkie had been obliged to rein in, lest the coffers be entirely emptied and no specie remain to support indigent carp-farmers, such as Mr Francis Fishybizz, the Master of Laxfirth and Skattland Point.
<P>
Last month Mr Jonpy, brazen as ever, had the impudence to present himself to the electors of Soothyale for a casual vacancy upon the Commission of Supply. The island being remote from reliable political intelligences and wanting a licensed town crier of its own, the inhabitants were naturally insensible of the true condition of our Zetland commonwealth and, foolishly, were induced to return Mr Jonpy with a handsome plurality of the ballots. 
<P>
The calculated offence was compounded by the irksome necessity of Mr Black Mekkie counting the votes in person at the rude bothy or 'side school' which served as polling place for that tiresome and depopulated district. Upon the result being declared, he was further constrained by constitional propriety actually to shake the hand of the unwelcome interloper. 
<P>
Mr Black Mekkie's words of congratulation were suitably muted and inaudible to the throng of bonnet lairds and idle peasantry who had assembled to witness this extraordinary reverse in his fortunes.  One ignorant boor, employed in the Commissioners' service upon the bigging up of brigs and slaps, was even heard to remark: 'Disseldoofurda aald deevilnoo! Fur Mester Chonnpy keenswhaarda bonns is hoided.' It is greatly to be regretted that the rancelman in attendance was unable to identify and apprehend the offender, who will undoubtedly have his publick emoluments terminated, should he be taken before the Committee of Discipline. 
<P>
I would despair of our prospects of civil government, were it not for the efforts of Commissioner Wullamandra Whitret, who grows daily in stature and <I>gravitas</I> and may soon be estimated amongst the true worthies of our society. His custodianship of the Common Good Fund has been exemplary, with vast quantities of treasure bestowed liberally upon every gentleman merchant and manufacturer who will bestir himself to append his signature to the necessary parchments. Commissioner Whitret's conduct, on those occasions when his ministrations were questioned by vulgar scribblers such as Mr Garry Luss, the Olsterman, has been much admired by those of the Quality.
<P>
Only last week, when interrogated anent the desperate condition of the poor's dwellings, the parochial schools and the Lerook Wet Docks Commission, Mr Whitret responded unhesitatingly: 'Weel, weel, I dunnakeen bit feth dey'll choost haeta makkda bestoa beddchob an dirnaethin mairtabi seddabootit, du keens.'
<P>
Methinks I detect a budding greatness in Mr Whitret, whose full flowering I trust we shall shortly see, after Mr Black Mekkie goes to enjoy his well-earned rest at Fort Acolyte where, I am told, a company of wandering minstrels, Darridvans, has already been engaged to serenade his declining years.
<P>


<HR>



