<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - 'Am I a Sheltie?'</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>'Am I a Sheltie?'</H1>
<H2>How to trace your island ancestors and long-lost cousins</H2>
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>Readers often ask if we can help them trace relations in Shetland. 
This is not surprising because there are probably as many people with 
Shetland connections living outside the islands as there are in 
Shetland. And more and more of them are on the Net.
<P>They don't have the knowledge, skills or resources (yet!) to give your 
queries the detailed attention they deserve. But we know people who do.
<P>The Shetland Family History Society is a group of enthusiastic but 
entirely unpaid volunteers. They'll help you if and when they can 
but, because of the huge interest in Shetland genealogy worldwide, 
they can't promise a reply by return.
<P>You can reach the society, by snail-mail only , at the following address:
<P>Shetland Family History Society<BR>
6 Hillhead<BR>LERWICK<BR>Shetland<BR> ZE1 0ED<BR>Scotland

<P>Another place on the 'Net that might be of interest is<BR>Orkney Shetland Expatriate Network<BR> 
<STRONG>Contact:-</STRONG> E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:tmanson@mindlink.bc.ca">Thomas Manson</A>
<BR>
Tel: (604) 631-4725 
<BR>
Fax: (604) 631-3131<BR> 
This site was established in February 1996 to assist expatriates from Shetland and Orkney to maintain links to "the Old Country". The site is maintained by volunteers. 




<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

