<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - 'Shetland News' deluged with support </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">
<BR>
<font size=-1>
<A HREF="/appeal.html">Help fight the legal battle for free WWW links</A>
</font>
<P>
<H1>'Shetland News' deluged with support </H1>
<H2>in  global campaign against WWW legal curbs</H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
</center>
<P>
<P>
2nd December 1996
<P>
Hundreds of messages of support are flooding into 'The Shetland News'  offices from all over the world, as outraged readers protest against  court action taken by 'The Shetland Times' to ban links from our  pages to theirs.
<P>
'Shetland News' editor Jonathan Wills said last night (SUN): 'From  Australia to North America, and throughout Britain and Europe, the  message has been unanimous - deploring the resort to legal action.
<P>
'People are telling us that if 'The Shetland Times' wants to restrict  access to its pages and make all visitors pass through the home page  first, then all it has to do is put up a normal gateway on the site,  not drag us though a financially damaging action in the Court of Session.
<P>
'The Shetland Times Ltd say we've breached their copyright and they  maintain other Internet publishers support them. We've done no such  thing and not a single Internet publisher has come out publicly in  favour of the legal action,' Dr Wills said.
<P>
The UK <A HREF="http://gnew.gn.apc.org/media/nuj.html">National Union of Journalists</A> is backing Dr Wills, managing  director of 'Shetland News' publishers Zetnews Ltd, in defence of the  legal action, which is expected to be debated in court early next  year. But Dr Wills still has to pay personal legal bills of over  1,800 for initial court defences when the Court of Session in  Edinburgh ordered a temporary ban on links on October 24.
<P>
Donations to the legal defence fund have been coming in as  international media pick up on the story and its serious implications  for the future of free links on the World Wide Web.
<P>
'If this were just a personal spat, no-one would be interested,' Dr  Wills said. 'We're fighting this case for the important principle  involved and it's now clear we have overwhelming support from Net  users who know what they're talking about.
<P>
'Unfortunately, the workload of replying to every e-mail is now so  great that I can no longer cope with it and attend to my work on our  news site at the same time, quite apart from my other job as Shetland  correspondent for the national media. So I hope the many kind people  who write to me will understand if I don't reply immediately.
<P>
'The letters have been a great boost to all of us on 'The Shetland  News' during a very trying time. We didn't seek this conflict and  we've tried to settle it amicably, out of court, so we can get on  with developing our site and improving the service to readers.
<P>
'The response from the United States after<A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/"> 'The New York Times' </A> carried our story has been particularly heartwarming. It's good to  know we have so many friends and I thank them all sincerely on this  Thanksgiving weekend.'
<P>
Dr Wills asked supporters not to do anything 'provocative', such as  putting up their own protest links to 'The Shetland Times' and  challenging them to take more legal action.
<P>
'We're happy to let the law take its course and have no doubt we must  win. In any case, we've no intention of resuming regular links to  'The Shetland Times', whatever the outcome of the case. We were  growing rapidly without linking to them and they were always an  optional accessory to our pages. Now they've alienated so many  surfers, we don't feel like giving their website any more free hits.'
<P>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="/appeal.html">'The court ban(!) on our WWW links and how you can help fight it'</A></CENTER>
<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

