<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Internet publishing boom in Shetland

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Internet publishing boom in Shetland  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
1st November 1996
<P>
Statistics published on the Internet yesterday (Thursday) show that  Shetland is becoming a major electronic publishing centre.
<P>
The islands' two electronic newspapers, <I>The Shetland News</I> and <I>The  Shetland Times</I>, are gaining more than 10,000 'hits' between them  every day. The larger of the two, The Shetland News, is heading for  two million hits by its first anniversary on November 23.
<P>
A 'hit' is a single visit to a page on a computer newspaper and  10,000 hits equates to around 6,800 readers - because many readers go  to more than one page.
<P>
The figures, compiled independently, are the Internet's equivalent of  the Audit Bureau of Circulation reports used by conventional newspapers.
<P>
Dr Jonathan Wills, managing director of Zetnews Ltd, which publishes  <I>The Shetland News</I>, said yesterday: 'What these figures show is the  amazing growth in readership since we started <I>The Shetland News </I>as an  experiment, just under a year ago. The figures are an under-estimate  because many central computers on the Internet store our pages for  quicker access and this does not show up in the records.
<P>
'The secret of success is updating our 250-page news magazine every  day. Surprisingly, only about five per cent of our readers live in  Shetland. Because of emigration from the islands over the past  century and a half, there are now hundreds of thousands of people  with Shetland connections all over the world and they're a big part  of our audience.'
<P>
He said <I>The Shetland News</I> accounted for 83 per cent of Shetland's  daily hits and three quarters of the information downloaded by  surfers, to read on their own home or office computers. 
<P>
'Interestingly, it appears that we trebled the <I>Shetland Times'</I> much  smaller readership when we began making links from our pages to  theirs early in October,' Dr Wills said. 'Unfortunately, they took  this as an assault on their copyright rather than the friendly  gesture which it was, and they've obtained an interim interdict  preventing us giving them an even wider audience.'
<P>
A hearing in the test case, which will decide for the first time  whether links between Internet sites are legal, is expected in the New Year at the Court of Session in Edinburgh.
<P>
Both papers rely on the services of <A HREF="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/">Zetnet Services, Ltd,</A> the  nationwide, local-call-rate access provider run from Lerwick, Shetland.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
