<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>Funny Old World</H1>
<H2>Meet Robert Wishart, <BR>the man who took The Shetland News to court</H2>

</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>


<B>He did WHAT?</B><BR>
As managing director of The Shetland Times Ltd, he complained on 23rd October 1996 to Scotland's supreme civil court, the Court of Session in Edinburgh, that <I>The Shetland News</I> (which he, but no-one else, regards as a rival) was making direct links to the pages of his on-line edition.
<P>
<B>So what was his problem?</B><BR>
Breach of copyright, dear child. <I>Shetland News</I> links via his headlines to his stories apparently amounted to stealing the hard work of his six journalists and 'passing off' their stories as <I>Shetland News</I> reports.
<P><A HREF="wishart.jpg"><IMG SRC="wisharts.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=163 HEIGHT=216 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
<B>This ridiculous allegation was some sort of joke?</B><BR>
Not at all. Mr Wishart intends to be Shetland's main Internet entrepreneur and regarded the alleged breach of copyright as a very serious matter indeed.
<P>
<B>But, but, but surely he realised that a link does not involve making a copy?</B><BR>
That's not Mr Wishart's view and he is a very important person in the Shetland media world. His thoughts on Life, the Internet and Everything are of great consequence. He publishes and/or prints almost all the islands' magazines and his weekly <I>Shetland Times </I>(founded 1872, circulation 11,000+ copies among 23,000 islanders) has a profitable monopoly in its tiny paddock.
<P>
<B>But, as I said, no unlicensed copy is made by a link, so how can the question of copyright arise?</B><BR>
I'm glad you asked that. Only Mr Wishart knows the answer. Everyone else who knows anything about it thinks he's up a gum tree.
<P>
<B>I thought there were no trees in Shetland?</B><BR>
Not many, but a person of Mr Wishart's stature can afford to buy what he likes.
<P>
<B>Like lawyers?</B><BR>
Oh, yes, lots of them.
<P>
<B>But surely <I>they</I> know this is nonsense and doomed to fail?</B><BR>
I don't think we ought to talk about that. It might upset their client.
<P>
<B>I take it the court told him to get lost?</B><BR>
Not exactly. Lord Hamilton, the judge, listened to three hours of legal arguments and then went to avizandum.
<P>
<B>He went on <I>holiday</I> to Turkey? In the middle of a test case which will decide the whole future of the Internet in the UK?</B><BR>
No, you fool. Going to avizandum means returning to your chambers, having a nice cup of tea, putting your feet up and having a long think about things, before sleeping on it.
<P>
<B>And what <I>did </I>Lord Hamilton think when he woke up next morning?</B><BR>
He thought it fairest to all concerned to order a temporary ban - what we rocket scientists call an interim interdict - which would restore the situation to what it was before Mr Wishart complained.
<P>
<B>So that's that, then? Internet links are illegal unless you have the website operator's approval to make them?</B><BR>
Not yet. That's what Mr Wishart thinks Lord Hamilton means but in fact there won't be a full hearing of all the evidence in the Court of Session until the New Year. Only after that will the court decide one way or the other.
<P>
<B>I see. So what sort of fellow is this Wishart?</B><BR>
Perfectly charming, according to those who are close to him. Worshipped by his staff, welcome in any dockside watering hole, always bubbling over with <I>bonhomie</I> and <I>joie de vivre</I>, he was educated at Gordonstoun (where Prince Charles went) and has his own yacht, so he must be a thoroughly good egg.
<P>
<B>Not, er, subject to tantrums at all? Flying off the handle, that sort of thing?</B><BR>
Perish the thought! A man of supremely equable temperament, skilled in the arts of quiet diplomacy and charitable to a fault, it says here.
<P>
<B>Qualifications for current position?</B><BR>
Oodles. In fact, his dad was so impressed with his c.v. that he asked him to be MD for life.
<P>
<B>Gosh, that's pretty impressive!</B><BR>
Yes, isn't it?
<P>
<B>But, wait a minute, weren't these chaps at <I>The Shetland News</I> doing him a favour by giving him readers, at their own expense, for his not terribly popular website?</B><BR>
That's what<I> they</I> thought, pathetic idealists and free communicators that they are. But don't take their word for it: e-mail the great man yourself at <A href="mailto:r.wishart@shetland-times.co.uk">r.wishart@shetland-times.co.uk</A>
<P>
<I>(A word of warning, though - he regards unsolicited correspondence on this subject as 'nuisance mail')</I>
<P>

<hr width=50%>


<I>
<P>
Decide for yourself if the 
<A HREF="/headline/olive/olive.html">olive branch</A>  we offered was fair and reasonable.

<P>
