<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Treasures to return
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">
<BR>
<font size=-1>
<A HREF="/appeal.html">Help fight the legal battle for free WWW links</A>
</font>
<P>
<H1> Treasures to return
</H1>
<H2></H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt5.gif">
<HR>
</center>
<P>

<P>
10th January 1997
<P>
Treasures from two major archaeological digs in Shetland are to  return to the islands.
<P>
Shetland Museum curator Tommy Watt said yesterday [THUR] the Finds  Disposal Panel of Historic Scotland had awarded the museum finds from  excavations at Upper Scalloway and Kebister, near Lerwick.
<P>
'I'm very pleased these artefacts are coming home,' he said. 'They've  been undergoing extensive study in Scotland and now that the final  reports are nearing publication, they've been released.'
<P>
Kebister was excavated between 1985 and 1987, revealing a site dating  from the Neolithic to the 19th century.  Among the Kebister finds is  a large armorial slab, believed to have belonged to Henry Phankouth,  archdeacon of Shetland (1501-29), who had a teind barn or warehouse  at Kebister, for rents paid in butter and cloth. 
<P>
Mr Watt said: 'The Upper Scalloway material is a vast collection of  artefacts which where excavated from a settlement and medieval  cemetery.  A late Bronze Age cremation was discovered under a broch  and associated Late  Iron Age structures.
<P>
'Exciting finds include several carved bone playing pieces, painted  pebbles which have an unknown unique use, crucible fragments and many  other smaller items from a site with a long human occupation.'
<P>
He hoped to display the items once they are returned to Shetland in April.
<P>




<P>
<BR clear=all>
